<L>Whan She herde / myn Orysoun,</L>
<L>And Saugh / by n&omacr;&omacr;n Occasyoun</L>
<L N="17040">I wolde nat leue / my Bordoun</L>
<L>Nor my Skryppe / ffor no manace;</L>
<L>And sawh how / In the sam&euml; place</L>
<L>I hadd&euml; Chose / to myn Entent /</L>
<L N="17044">Reffuge / that was Suffycyent,</L>
<L>In alle Trouble and dysese,</L>
<L>Myn hertly Sorwys / to apese,</L>
<L>And stynte / alle myn Aduersyte,</L>
<L N="17048">An&omacr;&omacr;n she seyd&euml; / thus to me:</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>Trybulacion. /</HEAD>
<L>&para; 'I am,' quod she / 'lyk off manere</L>
<L>To thylk&euml; wynde / (as thow shalt here,)</L>
<L>That with his blast / maketh fful offte</L>
<L N="17052">The levys Ryse / and fflen aloffte</L>
<L>Toward the Skyes / hyh in the heyr. /</L>
<L>Thus haue I / causyd thy Repeyr /</L>
<L>Thurgh my Trowble / pryked tho,</L>
<L N="17056">Vn-to Reffuge / ffor to ffle. /</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>'Caste thy look / toward the hevene /<MILESTONE UNIT="Stowe folio" N="301b"></L>
<L>ffer abowe / the Sterrys Sevene /</L>
<L>In thy Contemplac&iuml;on /</L>
<L N="17060">That wer but / as a leff her doun,</L>
<L>ffor-welkyd / and caste a-way,</L>
<L>Wych by the ground ful low&euml; lay,<NOTE PLACE="marg">[<B>Cotton MS.</B> <I>begins again</I>.]</NOTE><MILESTONE N="242a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>But, thorgh my commyss&iuml;oun,</L>
<L N="17064">I ha tournd the vp-se<NOTE PLACE="marg">[so St.]</NOTE>-doun,</L>
<L>And many a-nother ek also,</L>
<L>With my trouble and with my wo;</L>
<L>And with my toong&euml;s I hem chace,</L>
<L N="17068">Ageyn the lord whan they trespace,</L>
<L>That I cause hem for to ffle</L>
<L>To god, on hem to han pyte.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>'And somme I have ek causyd offte</L>
<L N="17072">To fflen vn-to the sterre aloffte,</L>
<L>To whom thow fleddyst with gret labour,
<PB REF="00000566.tif" N="458"></L>
<L>'ffor to have off hyre, socour,</L>
<L>Confort and consolac&iuml;oun,</L>
<L N="17076">Ageyn al tribulac&iuml;oun;</L>
<L>Wher-in thow erryst neueradel,</L>
<L>But wrouhtest prudently and wel.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>'Kep the wel in hyr presence,</L>
<L N="17080">ffor, by verray experyence,</L>
<L>As sone as thow art from hyr go,</L>
<L>I shal nat long&euml; be the fro,</L>
<L>By vertu off my commyss&iuml;oun,</L>
<L N="17084">ffor to don execuc&iuml;oun,</L>
<L>As I ha don to many on;</L>
<L>With my toong&euml;s made hem gon,</L>
<L>That wer out off the wey&euml; ferre,<MILESTONE UNIT="Stowe folio" N="302a"></L>
<L N="17088">Resorte ageyn vn-to that sterre,</L>
<L>Ther to haue protecc&iuml;oun</L>
<L>In euery trybulac&iuml;oun.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>'And thus I kan, in many wyse,</L>
<L N="17092">With my yerd&euml; wel chastyse</L>
<L>Swych folkys as be dyssolut,</L>
<L>And chace at hem in my pursut,</L>
<L>Namly, folk predestynaat,</L>
<L N="17096">And swych as be preordynaat</L>
<L>To kome vn-to savac&iuml;oun,</L>
<L>That kan in trybulacioun</L>
<L>Suffren, and have pacyence.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="17100">'And yiff that thow, for thyn offence,<MILESTONE N="242b" UNIT="folio"><NOTE PLACE="marg">[C. &amp; St.]</NOTE></L>
<L>Hast her-to-forn haad nede off me,<NOTE PLACE="marg">[C. &amp; St.]</NOTE></L>
<L>And, in partye, I ha to th&egrave;<NOTE PLACE="marg">[C. &amp; St.]</NOTE></L>
<L>Parcel declaryd off myn offys,<NOTE PLACE="marg">[C. &amp; St.]</NOTE></L>
<L N="17104">As thow mayst fele (yiff thow be wys)</L>
<L>With-outen any gret owtrage</L>
<L>Don to the, or gret damage,</L>
<L>With-outen many wordys mo,</L>
<L N="17108">A dieu! farwel! for I wyl go.</L>
<L>And be war, in thy passage,</L>
<L>That thow do wel thy pylgrymage,</L>
<L>And in thy way be iust and stable,</L>
<L N="17112">Lych a pylgrym good and hable.'</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>The Pylgrym:<NOTE PLACE="marg">[St., <I>om</I>. C.]</NOTE>
</HEAD>
<PB REF="00000567.tif" N="459">
<L>And as I stood allone, al sool,<MILESTONE UNIT="Stowe folio" N="302b"></L>
<L>Gan compleyne, and mak&euml; dool,</L>
<L>Havyng no thyng vp-on to reste,</L>
<L N="17116">Saue (as me sempt&euml; for the beste)</L>
<L>I lenede me on my bordoun;</L>
<L>ffor thogh that Trybulac&iuml;oun</L>
<L>Wer departyd in certeyn,</L>
<L N="17120">She sayde she wold&euml; kome ageyn.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>But I (wherso I wooke or slepte,)</L>
<L>With my refuge, ay I me kepte,<NOTE PLACE="marg">[slepe . . kepe St.]</NOTE></L>
<L>To have, by hyre, protecc&iuml;oun</L>
<L N="17124">Ageyn ech trybulac&iuml;oun,</L>
<L>But for that I, by gret owtrage,</L>
<L>Was off my port, wylde and savage,</L>
<L>Dyuers off my condyc&iuml;oun,</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="17128">And al day turnynge vp <I>and</I> doun,</L>
<L>fful off chaung and doubylnesse,</L>
<L>Havyng in me no stabylnesse.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>And whyl I went&euml; thus musynge,</L>
<L N="17132">With-Inne my sylff ymagynynge,</L>
<L>I ffyl a-noon, in my passage,</L>
<L>In-to a wood&euml; ful savage;</L>
<L>Me thouhte the wey&euml; peryllous,</L>
<L N="17136">And by to pass&euml;, Encombrous;<MILESTONE N="243a" UNIT="folio"><NOTE PLACE="marg">[C. &amp; St.]</NOTE></L>
<L>I knew nat what was best to done,<NOTE PLACE="marg">[C. &amp; St.]</NOTE></L>
<L>ffor, in a woode, a man may soone<NOTE PLACE="marg">[C. &amp; St.]</NOTE></L>
<L>Lese his weye, and gon amys,<NOTE PLACE="marg">[C. &amp; St.]</NOTE></L>
<L N="17140">Or he be war; and thus yt ys,<NOTE PLACE="marg">[C. &amp; St.]</NOTE></L>
<L>As pylgrymes know&euml; wel echon,</L>
<L>That on pylgrymag&euml; gon:</L>
<L>Passage they fynde, narwh and streyth;<MILESTONE UNIT="Stowe folio" N="303a"></L>
<L N="17144">Brygauntys lyn<NOTE PLACE="marg">[lyen St.]</NOTE> ek in a-wayt,</L>
<L>And wylde bestys many on,</L>
<L>Tassayll&euml; pylgrymes, wher they gon:</L>
<L>ffolk expert, the trouth&euml; knowe.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="17148">And in a valey that stood lowe,</L>
<L>I sawh on stonden in my way,</L>
<L>Old and owgly, off array</L>
<L>Dysguysed wonder queynt&euml;ly,</L>
<L N="17152">Off port and chere ryht vngoodly,
<PB REF="00000568.tif" N="460"></L>
<L>Semyng to me (yt ys no faylle)</L>
<L>That she wold&euml; me assaylle;</L>
<L>Yt sempt&euml; so, as by hyr cher;</L>
<L N="17156">And al my lyff, fer or<NOTE PLACE="marg">[nor St.]</NOTE> ner,</L>
<L>Radde I neuer, in book nor geste,</L>
<L>Off so merveyllous a beste;</L>
<L>Nat in the Book off Danyel,</L>
<L N="17160">Nouther in Ezechyel,</L>
<L>Nor in Thapocalyps off Iohan,</L>
<L>Swych a best&euml; fond I noon.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>I was abaysshed a-noon ryht,</L>
<L N="17164">Whan fyrst off hyre I hadde a syht;</L>
<L>In hyre I fond so many a lak:</L>
<L>ffyrst, she hadde a brook&euml; bak,</L>
<L>Corbyd and haltyng, both&euml; two;</L>
<L N="17168">Off rowh frese, she hadde also</L>
<L>A garn&euml;ment shape lyk a sak,</L>
<L>Wych she werede vp-on<NOTE PLACE="marg">[weryde on St.]</NOTE> hyr bak:</L>
<L>Gret noumbre ther-on I tolde,</L>
<L N="17172">Off cloutys and off pachchys olde.<MILESTONE N="243b" UNIT="folio"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Aboute hyr necke, I sawh ek wel,<MILESTONE UNIT="Stowe folio" N="303b"></L>
<L>That ther heng a gret sachel;<NOTE PLACE="marg">[C. &amp; St.]</NOTE></L>
<L>She shop hyr no-thyng for the flyht;</L>
<L N="17176">ffor, that poket (to my syht,)</L>
<L>She felde yt ful (in &eacute;specyal)</L>
<L>Off Coper, yren, <I>and</I> off metal.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>And as yt sempte to me also,</L>
<L N="17180">Hyr own&euml; tonge halp wel ther-to,</L>
<L>Wych heng out at hyr mouth ful<NOTE PLACE="marg">[ful <I>om</I>. St.]</NOTE> long.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>And aboute hyr neck&euml; strong,</L>
<L>Thys lady, with hyr corbyd bak,</L>
<L N="17184">Was y-moselyd with that sak,</L>
<L>Sowyd sore, that nyht nor day</L>
<L>Yt myghte nat wel falle A-way.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>In noumbre she hadde (I gan beholde<NOTE PLACE="marg">[as I . . holde St.]</NOTE>)</L>
<L N="17188">Syx&euml; handys, for I hem tolde;</L>
<L>And tweyne (to myn Inspecc&iuml;oun)</L>
<L>Wer the pawmys off A gryffoun.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>And I beheld the sam&euml; whyle,</L>
<L N="17192">In On hand she held<NOTE PLACE="marg">[hadde St.]</NOTE> a ffyle,
<PB REF="00000569.tif" N="461"></L>
<L>fforgyd off ful myghty stel;</L>
<L>And (as fer as I koude fel,)</L>
<L>The ffyl&euml; was ymad <I>and</I> ment</L>
<L N="17196">To ffyl&euml; brydles, off entent.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Touchynge hyr other gouernaunce,<NOTE PLACE="foot">Here the 15th century hand in the Stowe MS. 952 stops, and old John Stowe's handwriting begins, and goes on to the end.</NOTE></L>
<L>She held also a gret ballaunce,</L>
<L>Only off purpos (yiff she konne,)</L>
<L N="17200">To peyse the sodyak<NOTE PLACE="marg">[zodiak St.]</NOTE> and the sonne,</L>
<L>And caste hem in the wynd in veyn,</L>
<L>And neuere to callyn hem ageyn:</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>A larg&euml; dyssh, ek I beheld,</L>
<L N="17204">In hyr hand how that she held.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>And in hyr ffyffthe hand a kroket;</L>
<L>And on hyr hed a gret mawmet.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Hyr syxth&euml; hand she gan to launche</L>
<L N="17208">Low&euml; doun vn-to hyr haunche,</L>
<L>Wych caus&euml; was (vn-to my syht)<MILESTONE UNIT="Stowe folio" N="304a"><MILESTONE N="244a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>She haltede, and went&euml; nat vp-ryht,</L>
<L>Lyk as a crepyl, with potente;</L>
<L N="17212">Evene me thouht&euml; so she wente.<NOTE PLACE="inter">[9 <I>lines blank in MS. for an Illumination.</I>]</NOTE></L>
<L>And, by maner off bataylle,</L>
<L>Thys vekk&euml; gan me to assaylle,<MILESTONE UNIT="prose cap" N="iii"></L>
<L>Off malys and inyquyte,<NOTE PLACE="marg">[Cap. ii. is omitted.]</NOTE></L>
<L N="17216">And felly sayd&euml; thus to me:</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>The old Avarice:<NOTE PLACE="marg">[St., <I>om</I>. C.]</NOTE></HEAD>
<L>'I swer to the, by my mawmet</L>
<L>Wych vp-on myn hed ys set,</L>
<L>In whom ys holy my plesaunce,</L>
<L N="17220">My trust pleynly, <I>and</I> my creaunce,</L>
<L>I have abyde vp-on thys way</L>
<L>Tawayte on th&egrave; ful many a day.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>'Ley doun thy skryppe and thy bordoun,</L>
<L N="17224">And do homage to my Mahown!</L>
<L>ffor yt ys he (thow shalt wel knowe)</L>
<L>By whom that I, off hih and lowe</L>
<L>Allowyd am, and off gret prys.
<PB REF="00000570.tif" N="462"></L>
<L N="17228">Yhold&euml; prudent, and ryht wys.</L>
<L>ffor no man hath, with-out&euml; me,</L>
<L>Worshepe nor no dygnyte;</L>
<L>In hih estat ys no whyht Set,</L>
<L N="17232">But thorgh favour off my mawmet,</L>
<L>To whom thow mvst submytt&euml; the,</L>
<L>Or thow shalt deye; so mot I the!'</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>Pilgrim:<NOTE PLACE="marg">[St., <I>om</I>. C.]</NOTE></HEAD>
<L>"ffyrst, thow mvst declar&euml; me<MILESTONE N="244b" UNIT="folio"><NOTE PLACE="marg">[St. &amp; C.]</NOTE></L>
<L N="17236">Thy power and thyn Auctoryte,<MILESTONE UNIT="prose cap" N="iv"><NOTE PLACE="marg">[St. &amp; C.]</NOTE></L>
<L>Thow old&euml;, ryvelyd off vysage,<NOTE PLACE="marg">[St. &amp; C.]</NOTE></L>
<L>Thy kynrede, and thy lyn&aacute;ge,<NOTE PLACE="marg">[St. &amp; C.]</NOTE></L>
<L>Thy contre and thy nac&iuml;oun,</L>
<L N="17240">And also off what reg&iuml;oun</L>
<L>That thow art born, (I wyl ffyrst knowe,)</L>
<L>With bak and chyn&euml; courbyd lowe;</L>
<L>The maner ek off thy mawmet,</L>
<L N="17244">Shap&euml; lyk a marmoset:</L>
<L>Tel me hys condic&iuml;oun;</L>
<L>ffor me thynketh yt no resoun</L>
<L>Off equyte, nor by no ryht,</L>
<L N="17248">Syth he ys dowmb, and blynd off syht,</L>
<L>I that am born off good lynage,</L>
<L>Sholde vn-to hym do now homage."</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>Avarice:<NOTE PLACE="marg">[St., <I>om</I>. C.]</NOTE></HEAD>
<L>'Syth thow wylt fyrst yse,<MILESTONE UNIT="prose cap" N="v"></L>
<L N="17252">And what my nam&euml; shold&euml; be,</L>
<L>I wyl, as now, no thyng spare;</L>
<L>But the trouthe to th&egrave; declare,</L>
<L>That thow shalt (with-oute offence)</L>
<L N="17256">Yive to me the mor credence.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>'Yiff thow lyst the trouth&euml; se,</L>
<L>Kom on a-noon, and folwe me,</L>
<L>And thow shalt (yiff thow kanst espye)</L>
<L N="17260">Her&euml; me ful lowd&euml; crye;</L>
<L>ffor I shall<NOTE PLACE="marg">[shall St., shan C.]</NOTE> sen, duryng my lyff,<MILESTONE UNIT="Stowe folio" N="304b"></L>
<L>The vale off sorwen<NOTE PLACE="marg">[sorow St.]</NOTE> and off stryff,</L>
<L>The woful Interiecc&iuml;oun</L>
<L N="17264">Most ful off lamentac&iuml;oun.'</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>Pilgrim:<NOTE PLACE="marg">[St., <I>om</I>. C.]</NOTE>
</HEAD>
<PB REF="00000571.tif" N="463">
<L>And trew&euml;ly<NOTE PLACE="marg">[trewly C., truly St.]</NOTE> (I took good kep,)</L>
<L>She wente vp to a fosse kaue dep;</L>
<L>And ther she bad me lok&euml; doun;<MILESTONE UNIT="prose cap" N="vi"></L>
<L N="17268">Wher I hadde inspecc&iuml;oun</L>
<L>Off an abbey, wych euerydel</L>
<L>(As I beheld the maner wel)<MILESTONE N="245a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Was foundyd besyden a cheker,<NOTE PLACE="marg">[C. &amp; St.]</NOTE></L>
<L N="17272">Squar as ys a Tabler.<NOTE PLACE="inter">[8 <I>lines blank in MS. for an Illumination</I>.]</NOTE></L>
<L>And I beheld<NOTE PLACE="marg">[lokyd St.]</NOTE> also with-al,</L>
<L>Ther wer esches, bothe gret and smal,</L>
<L>fful wel ywrouht in all&euml; thynges.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="17276">Ther sawh I rookys <I>and</I> ek kynges,</L>
<L>And knyhtys (ek in verray soth)</L>
<L>Drawen, as a ffers y-doth</L>
<L>In travers wys&euml;, by bataylle,</L>
<L N="17280">Euerych other gan assaylle</L>
<L>Wyth sharp&euml; swerdys, thus thauht&euml; me,</L>
<L>A dysguys&euml; thyng to se;</L>
<L>ffor at the ches, in al my lyff,</L>
<L N="17284">Sawh I neuere swych a stryff,</L>
<L>Nor so fers A contenaunce;</L>
<L>ffor everyche gan hym sylff avaunce,</L>
<L>Whan ther bataylle was ado,</L>
<L N="17288">To make hem redy for to go</L>
<L>To that abbay ther besyde,</L>
<L>And, be surquedye and pryde,</L>
<L>Ther to forreye, what they may,</L>
<L N="17292">Robbe and spoylle, and ber a-way,</L>
<L>And rev&euml; hem off ther rychesse,</L>
<L>And brouhten hem in swych dystresse,</L>
<L>That no thyng leffte to ther refut,</L>
<L N="17296">But made al bare and destytut.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Whan I hadde al thys yseyn,<MILESTONE N="245b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>How al was makyd wast and pleyn,<NOTE PLACE="marg">[C. &amp; St.]</NOTE></L>
<L>Quod I, "what thyng meneth thys,<MILESTONE UNIT="prose cap" N="vii"><NOTE PLACE="marg">[C. &amp; St.]</NOTE></L>
<L N="17300">That thys cherche destroyed ys?<NOTE PLACE="marg">[C. &amp; St.]</NOTE></L>
<L>Thys ys (to myn oppynyoun)</L>
<L>The woful Interiecc&iuml;oun,</L>
<L>Wher-off pleynly (me semeth so)
<PB REF="00000572.tif" N="464"></L>
<L N="17304">Euerych wyse man sholde ha wo,</L>
<L>And compleyne (I the ensure)</L>
<L>Thys vnhappy &aacute;venture."</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>Avarice:<NOTE PLACE="marg">[St., <I>om</I>. C.]</NOTE></HEAD>
<L>'Wher thow be wel or evele apayd,<MILESTONE UNIT="prose cap" N="viii"></L>
<L N="17308">Lo her ys al that I ha sayd.</L>
<L>Thys mescheff (yiff thow kanst yt se)</L>
<L>Ys ydon and wrouht by me,</L>
<L>And acomplysshed vp in dede,</L>
<L N="17312">Al-thogh that yt be no nede;<MILESTONE UNIT="Stowe folio" N="305a"></L>
<L>Wher-off, in hys prophesye,</L>
<L>The nobyle prophete Ieremye</L>
<L>(As he that lyst no thyng to feyne)</L>
<L N="17316">Wept&euml; sore, and gan compleyne:</L>
<L>'Allas!' quod he, 'how the pryncesse,</L>
<L>Off folkys all&euml; cheff maystresse,</L>
<L>Ys trybutarye, and bor doun,</L>
<L N="17320">And brouhte in-to subiecc&iuml;oun!'</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>'The prophete wyste aforn ryht wel,</L>
<L>That I sholde causen euerydel</L>
<L>Thys gret&euml; desolac&iuml;on</L>
<L N="17324">And thys habomynac&iuml;on.</L>
<L>I and myne (yiff yt be souht)</L>
<L>Have thys gret&euml; mescheff wrouht.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>'Thys the custom (in substaunce),</L>
<L N="17328">Holy the maner and vsaunce,</L>
<L>Off al that to my scol&euml; go,</L>
<L>By my doctryn&euml; to do so,</L>
<L>And so to werke, by my techyng;</L>
<L N="17332">ffor ther ys nouther rook nor kyng,<MILESTONE N="246a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>But ech off hem (for ther part)<MILESTONE UNIT="prose cap" N="ix"></L>
<L>Sor&euml; studyen in that art,</L>
<L>Euerych off hem to fynde a waye,</L>
<L N="17336">How they may to me obeye.</L>
<L>Thow mayst me leve in sykernesse;</L>
<L>Ther own&euml; werkys ber wytnesse.'</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>Pilgrim:<NOTE PLACE="marg">[St., <I>om</I>. C.]</NOTE></HEAD>
<L>"I may nat levyn (fer nor ner)<MILESTONE UNIT="prose cap" N="x"></L>
<L N="17340">Thow sholdest han so gret power,</L>
<L>Wych that art so poryly
<PB REF="00000573.tif" N="465"></L>
<L>"Arrayed, and so dysguesyly;</L>
<L>Halt and lame, (as semeth me)</L>
<L N="17344">Brok&euml;-bakkyd, and foul to se.</L>
<L>And with al thys (I the ensure),</L>
<L>A verray monstre in nature,</L>
<L>(Who lyst looke, he shal yt fynde,)</L>
<L N="17348">And engendryd a-geyn kynde.</L>
<L>How sholdystow, with al thys thynges,</L>
<L>Ouer erlys, dukys,<NOTE PLACE="marg">[dukes earls St.]</NOTE> kynges,</L>
<L>Have power or domynac&iuml;on</L>
<L N="17352">To brynge hem in subiecc&iuml;on,</L>
<L>Sythen they, by gret noblesse,</L>
<L>Haven off kynd&euml; swych fayrnesse,</L>
<L>And brouht forth by engendrure,</L>
<L N="17356">Kynd&euml;ly, as by nature?"</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>Avarice:<NOTE PLACE="marg">[St., <I>om</I>. C.]</NOTE></HEAD>
<L>'Yiff thow wylt a whyl&euml; dwelle,<MILESTONE UNIT="prose cap" N="xi"></L>
<L>A good exaumple I shal the telle,</L>
<L>Reporte me wel in euery thyng:</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="17360">'Ther was onys a myghty kyng,</L>
<L>Wych that hadde, to hys plesaunce,</L>
<L>A lady in hys governaunce,</L>
<L>Whom that he louede paramour,</L>
<L N="17364">And took to hyre al hys tresour,<MILESTONE UNIT="Stowe folio" N="305b"></L>
<L>Good<NOTE PLACE="marg">[goods St.]</NOTE> and Iowelles euerydel,</L>
<L>Be-cause that he louede hyr so wel.<MILESTONE N="246b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>And shortly, thus with hym stood,</L>
<L N="17368">She gou&eacute;rnede al hys good,</L>
<L>Whos name was Lyberalyte:</L>
<L>She was benygn&euml;, large and fre,</L>
<L>Wych, in euery reg&iuml;oun,</L>
<L N="17372">Hadde gret fame and gret Renoun.</L>
<L>And she dyde euere hyr labour,</L>
<L>So to dyspendyn hys tresour,</L>
<L>That hys worshepe on euery syde</L>
<L N="17376">Gan encrece and spred&euml; wyde;</L>
<L>Gat hym honour and gret ffame,</L>
<L>And with al thys, a ryht good name.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>'The story doth also specefye,</L>
<L N="17380">She made hys goodys multeplye,
<PB REF="00000574.tif" N="466"></L>
<L>'And causede also, how that he</L>
<L>Was wel belovyd in hys contre;</L>
<L>ffor love excellyth in worthynesse</L>
<L N="17384">Euery tresour and rychesse.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>'But whan that I thys dyde<NOTE PLACE="marg">[dyd this St.]</NOTE> espye,<MILESTONE UNIT="prose cap" N="xii"></L>
<L>I hadde ther-off ful gret envye,</L>
<L>And caste to fynde occas&iuml;oun</L>
<L N="17388">ffor to tourne al vp-so-doun.</L>
<L>I gan taproche the court ful ner,</L>
<L>A-queyntede me with the porter</L>
<L>And with thoffycerys euerychon;</L>
<L N="17392">And in-to chaumbre I kam a-noon,</L>
<L>Wher as the kyng a bedd&euml; lay.</L>
<L>Whyl he slepte, I stal away</L>
<L>(Throgh my sleyhte in prevyte,)</L>
<L N="17396">Hys paramour Lyberalyte;</L>
<L>And or the kyng yt koude espye,</L>
<L>Benchaunt&euml;ment And sorcerye</L>
<L>I gan at hyr&euml; so enchace,<NOTE PLACE="marg">[tenchase St.]</NOTE></L>
<L N="17400">That she was voyded fro that place;</L>
<L>And, by fals collus&iuml;oun,<MILESTONE N="247a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>I shet hyre in a strong prysoun,</L>
<L>Wher I ha cast, (shortly to telle,)</L>
<L N="17404">Whyl that I lyve, she shal ther dwelle;</L>
<L>And in hyr sted&euml; (off entente,)</L>
<L>To bedde vn-to the kyng I wente,</L>
<L>Whyl that he slept&euml; vnwarly.<NOTE PLACE="marg">[slept vnwarely St.]</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="17408">'And whan he wook al sodeynly,</L>
<L>In stede off Lyberalyte,</L>
<L>In hys Armys he took me;</L>
<L>At wych tyme, by sorcerye,</L>
<L N="17412">I blent&euml; so the kyng&euml;s Eye,</L>
<L>That I be-kam hys paramour,</L>
<L>And hadde in guarde al hys tresour.</L>
<L>Wherso that he wook or slep,</L>
<L N="17416">Off hys worshepe I took no kep;<MILESTONE UNIT="Stowe folio" N="306a"></L>
<L>Hys honour, gold, hys good&euml; fame,</L>
<L>Al I tournede yt to shame;</L>
<L>ffor he ne myghte (who-so me knewe)</L>
<L N="17420">ffynde noon offycere mor vntrewe.
<PB REF="00000575.tif" N="467"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>'I am the sam&euml; (thys the cas,)</L>
<L>Off whom that whylom wrot Esdras,</L>
<L>Apemenen, wych, hyr sylff al sool,</L>
<L N="17424">Made the kyng so gret a fool:</L>
<L>Whan she was hevy, he was sad;</L>
<L>Whan she lowh, than he was glad;</L>
<L>She took hys crowne, <I>and</I> leyd yt doun,</L>
<L N="17428">And he, by lowh subiecc&iuml;oun,</L>
<L>Al hyr lustys dyde obeye,</L>
<L>ffor he durste hyr nat with-seye:</L>
<L>Thus yt stood, and thus yt was,</L>
<L N="17432">As thow shalt fynden in Esdras.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>'By wych exaumple, thow mayst se</L>
<L>That yt fareth thus by me;</L>
<L>ffor I kan, by my werkynges,<MILESTONE N="247b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="17436">Deceyu&euml; prynces and ek kynges;</L>
<L>And al the meyne off the cheker,</L>
<L>I kan make off herte enter,</L>
<L>To robben abbeys euerychon,</L>
<L N="17440">And to dyspoylle hem, on by on,</L>
<L>With-outen any compass&iuml;oun.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>'And touchyng ek my nac&iuml;oun,<MILESTONE UNIT="prose cap" N="xiii"></L>
<L>And my name (yiff I shal telle,)</L>
<L N="17444">I was engendryd fyrst in helle;</L>
<L>And ther the prync&euml; Sathanas</L>
<L>(Yiff thow wylt wyte,) my fader was;</L>
<L>And in that Valey Infernal</L>
<L N="17448">I was begete: lo her ys al.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>'And my name ek to devyse,</L>
<L>I am callyd Covetyse</L>
<L>(Off verray ryht, and nat off wrong,)</L>
<L N="17452">And Avaryce, somwhyle Among;</L>
<L>But Coveytys&euml;, men calle me</L>
<L>Off verray ryht and equyte,</L>
<L>Whan I am mevyd in<NOTE PLACE="marg">[<I>om</I>. C., St.]</NOTE> my blood</L>
<L N="17456">To coueyte other mennys good.</L>
<L>And Avaryc&euml; men me calle,</L>
<L>Whan that I fro folkys alle</L>
<L>Kepe al that euere I get&euml; kan,</L>
<L N="17460">And wyl depart&euml; with no man,
<PB REF="00000576.tif" N="468"></L>
<L>'Wher they be wel or evele apayed.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>'And that I am thus evele arrayed,</L>
<L>I do yt only off entent</L>
<L N="17464">That my gold ne be nat spent,</L>
<L>On clothys wastyd, nor my good.</L>
<L>And levere me were, bothe gowne and hood</L>
<L>Wer with wermys day be day</L>
<L N="17468">Conswmyd, and yffret a-way,<MILESTONE UNIT="Stowe folio" N="306b"></L>
<L>Than por&euml; folk (so god me spede,)</L>
<L>Shold&euml; were hem in ther nede;</L>
<L>ffor I caste me nat at al,<MILESTONE N="248a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="17472">Neuere for to be lyberal</L>
<L>Whyl I may walken on the ground;</L>
<L>ffor I resemble vn-to that hound</L>
<L>Wych lyggeth in a stak off hay,</L>
<L N="17476">Groynynge al the long&euml; day,</L>
<L>Wyl suffre no beste ther-to to gon,</L>
<L>And yet hym sylff wyl et&euml; noon.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>'Myn handys off merveyllous fasoun,<MILESTONE UNIT="prose cap" N="xiv"></L>
<L N="17480">Lyk the pawmys off a gryffoun,</L>
<L>Be mad (wher-so I slepe or wake,)</L>
<L>Nat to yive, but for to take.</L>
<L>To axe me good, wer gret foly;</L>
<L N="17484">ffor thys my purpos, (fynaly,</L>
<L>And as me semeth for the beste)</L>
<L>To shette my gold vp in my cheste:</L>
<L>Thys al myn hool entenc&iuml;on,</L>
<L N="17488">Offys and occupac&iuml;on.</L>
<L>Al good, wher yt be grene or rype,</L>
<L>I kan wel glenyn, I kan wel grype,</L>
<L>Bothe to-forn and at the bak:</L>
<L N="17492">What I may gete, goth in-to sak,</L>
<L>Off entent (be wel certeyn)</L>
<L>Neuere to taken yt out ageyn.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>'My wyl ys euere vnstaunchable,</L>
<L N="17496">And my desyr in-sacyable;</L>
<L>My thouht nor myn affecc&iuml;oun</L>
<L>Ha neuere ful replec&iuml;oun.</L>
<L>I am the swolwh (who lyst to se)</L>
<L N="17500">Wych that in the salt&euml; see,
<PB REF="00000577.tif" N="469"></L>
<L>'Al that euere goth forth by,</L>
<L>He devoureth yt Outterly,</L>
<L>And neuere ne sent no thyng ageyn.</L>
<L N="17504">Tawayte ther affter wer but veyn,</L>
<L>ffor shortly, he devoureth al,</L>
<L>Coper, yren, and metal;</L>
<L>Al that peyseth or yiveth soun,<MILESTONE N="248b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="17508">To the botm&euml; yt goth<NOTE PLACE="marg">[botome it goythe St.]</NOTE></L>
<L>To gretter wrak than on a rok.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>'And as an Ape vn-to a blok</L>
<L>Or to a clog, tyed with a cheyne,</L>
<L N="17512">Ryht so I do my bysy peyne;</L>
<L>I teye my sylff (by gret dystresse)</L>
<L>And bynd&euml; me to my rychesse;</L>
<L>I bynde yt nat; yt byndeth me,</L>
<L N="17516">That I am bonde, and nothyng fre,</L>
<L>ffor to have theroff plesaunce.</L>
<L>ffor lak only off suffysaunce,</L>
<L>I am so teyd (I may nat skape,)</L>
<L N="17520">With a clog, ryht as an Ape,<MILESTONE UNIT="Stowe folio" N="307a"></L>
<L>Wych in soth so letteth me,</L>
<L>That I ha no lyberte</L>
<L>To gon at larg&euml; hih nor lowe.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="17524">'And yiff thow lyst also to knowe<MILESTONE UNIT="prose cap" N="xv"></L>
<L>What my vj<NOTE PLACE="marg">[syx&euml; 473/17666]</NOTE> handys be,</L>
<L>I shal declare a-noon to the,</L>
<L>And make a demonstrac&iuml;on:</L>
<L N="17528">I Gryppe <I>and</I> streyne lyk a Gryffoun,</L>
<L>And faste I hold&euml; ther-with-al</L>
<L>Coper, yren, and ech metal;</L>
<L>Streyhtly kepe yt in myn hond,</L>
<L N="17532">Bothe in water and on lond.</L>
<L>And thow aforn dyst neuere se</L>
<L>So cursyd handys as they be;</L>
<L>Enarmyd abouten Envyroun</L>
<L N="17536">With the pawmys off a Gryffoun.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>'The fyrst&euml; hand (for to dyffyne)</L>
<L>By ryht ycallyd ys 'Ravyne,'</L>
<L>That sheweth Gentyl outward alway,</L>
<L N="17540">Tyl that he<NOTE PLACE="marg">[it St.]</NOTE> may cachche hys pray;
<PB REF="00000578.tif" N="470"></L>
<L>'Dyspoylleth<NOTE PLACE="marg">[dispoylyn St.]</NOTE> pylgrymes est and west,</L>
<L>Bothe in woode and in fforest,</L>
<L>With-outen any excepc&iuml;on:<MILESTONE N="249a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="17544">Thys ys my condyc&iuml;on,</L>
<L>To robbe and reue with al my myght.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>'I cleym&euml; al thyng myn off ryht;</L>
<L>Myn hand ys lyk vnto<NOTE PLACE="marg">[lyk to C., lyke to St.]</NOTE> a kyte:</L>
<L N="17548">I tak&euml; chykenys that be lyte;</L>
<L>Wher I ham fynd&euml;, fer or ner,</L>
<L>I ber hem hoom to my dyner.</L>
<L>Gret robbery, on folk I make;</L>
<L N="17552">Hors and cart&euml;, bothe I take,</L>
<L>With porvyaunce and wyth vytaylle.</L>
<L>And off malys I wyl nat faylle:</L>
<L>Yiff a pore man haue a kowh,</L>
<L N="17556">Oxe or mare that draweth hys plowh,</L>
<L>I make hem selle hem by duresse,</L>
<L>ffor to staunche my gredynesse,</L>
<L>Wher any swych I kan espye.</L>
<L N="17560">And as an yreyne sowketh the flye,<MILESTONE UNIT="prose cap" N="xvi"></L>
<L>And hyr entroyll&euml;s<NOTE PLACE="marg">[entralls St.]</NOTE> draweth oute,</L>
<L>Evene lyk I renne aboute,</L>
<L>And cesse nat, whan I ha be-gonne,</L>
<L N="17564">Tyl that I my pray ha wonne.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>'The tother hand, to do gret wrak,</L>
<L>Ys set behynden at the bak,<MILESTONE UNIT="prose cap" N="xvii"></L>
<L>That no man ne sholde espye</L>
<L N="17568">The maner off my roberye.</L>
<L>So secretly I kan yt vse,</L>
<L>Outward my falsnesse to exeuse.</L>
<L>Thys hand ful hih vp-on A tre</L>
<L N="17572">Maketh many on enhangyd be;<MILESTONE UNIT="Stowe folio" N="307b"></L>
<L>And with hys ffeet (wych ys nat fayr,)</L>
<L>ffor to waggen in the hayr<NOTE PLACE="marg">[ayre St.]</NOTE></L>
<L>fful hih a-loffte, yt ys no dred.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="17576">'Thys hand, fro many manhys hed,</L>
<L>Causeth the Erys be kut away;</L>
<L>And thys hand, fro day to day,</L>
<L>Ys the hand off gret dyffame,<MILESTONE N="249b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="17580">Callyd Cutt&euml;purs by name,
<PB REF="00000579.tif" N="471"></L>
<L>'Wych hath a knyff ful <SUP>1</SUP>sharp of egge,<SUP>1</SUP><NOTE PLACE="marg">[1_1 Stowe]</NOTE></L>
<L>And yet he dar no glovys begge;<NOTE PLACE="marg">[Stowe]</NOTE></L>
<L>ffor, to vse hys robbery</L>
<L N="17584">Off the glovere openly,</L>
<L>He kepeth hym cloos, al out off syht,</L>
<L>And vseth for to walke a<NOTE PLACE="marg">[on St.]</NOTE> nyht</L>
<L>In narwe lanys, vp and doun.</L>
<L N="17588">Whan that the mon&euml; ys go doun,</L>
<L>Than he maketh hys ordynaunce</L>
<L>(By gret mescheff and gret meschaunce)</L>
<L>ffor to vse ther brybery,</L>
<L N="17592">And for to havnte ther robbery:</L>
<L>On no thyng ellys they sette her thouht,</L>
<L>ffor off hyr owne they ha ryht nouht.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>'Thys hand, by force, ageyn al ryht,</L>
<L N="17596">Breketh vp howsys toward nyht,</L>
<L>Bothe in bowrys and in hallys,</L>
<L>And maketh hoolys thorgh the wallys.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>'Thys hand kan dygge and mak&euml; mynys;</L>
<L N="17600">Thys hand kan Royne also florynes;</L>
<L>Thys hand ful selde hath any reste;</L>
<L>Thys hand kan brake Cofer <I>and</I> cheste;</L>
<L>Thys hand, (in cold <I>and</I> ek in hete,)</L>
<L N="17604">Kan falsly selys counterfete,</L>
<L>And the prent ther-off y-graue;</L>
<L>And thys hand wyl also haue</L>
<L>(By som Engyn, or sleyht&euml; weye)</L>
<L N="17608">Vn-to euery look<NOTE PLACE="marg">[locke St.]</NOTE> a keye.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>'Thys hand kan forge (I vndertake)</L>
<L>ffals monye, and the prent make.</L>
<L>Thys hand in frenshe<NOTE PLACE="marg">[frenche St.]</NOTE> (I dar expresse)</L>
<L N="17612">Ys callyd 'Poitevyneresse,'</L>
<L>ffor yt forgeth (thys the ffyn)</L>
<L>A monye callyd Poytevyn,<MILESTONE N="250a" UNIT="folio"><NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Poitevine</I>, monnaie de Poitou. 'Une <I>poitevine</I>, c'est le quart d'un parisi (1273 Carl de Ponthieu, Richel., l. 10112, 1<SUP>o</SUP>, 159 r<SUP>o</SUP>.).' &mdash;Godefroi. <I>Sol Parisien</I> . . as much as the Tornois &amp; a quarter. <I>Sol Tournois</I>, The tenth part of one shilling.&mdash;Cotgrave, 1611.</NOTE></L>
<L>Wych ys in valu (by a-countyng)</L>
<L N="17616">fful skarsly worth halff a fferthyng.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>'Thys hand ek falsly beyth and sylleth;
<PB REF="00000580.tif" N="472"></L>
<L>'And in reknynge, thys hand mystelleth.</L>
<L>Thys hand also (yt ys no drede)</L>
<L N="17620">Kan spoyll&euml; folk whan they be dede.</L>
<L>Thys hand kan al the nyht wachche,</L>
<L>And ful streythly glene and kachche,<MILESTONE UNIT="Stowe folio" N="308a"></L>
<L>And rendyn vp (yt ys no nay,)</L>
<L N="17624">Al that euere lyth in hys way.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>'Thys hand, thogh men hadd&euml; sworn,</L>
<L>Kan robbe and bern away the corn</L>
<L N="17627">Out off bernys and garnerys;</L>
<L>Thys hand kan ferette in konnyngherys<NOTE PLACE="marg">[conyngers St.]</NOTE></L>
<L>Be nyht&euml; tym&euml;, whan men slepe;</L>
<L>Thys hand, by holys kan in crepe,</L>
<L>And bern a-way what he may fynde,</L>
<L N="17632">And lyst to leue nothyng behynde;</L>
<L>Thys hand maketh ydel offycerys</L>
<L>And many fals&euml; labourerys.</L>
<L>Thys hand (ageyns al resoun)</L>
<L N="17636">Doth many gret extors&iuml;oun</L>
<L>In euery lond <I>and</I><NOTE PLACE="marg">[in <I>struck out</I>, a <I>over</I> C, and St.]</NOTE> ech contre,</L>
<L>Worthy enhangyd for to be,</L>
<L>Yiff the falsnesse wer yknowe</L>
<L N="17640">That he doth, bothe hyh <I>and</I> lowe;</L>
<L>ffor thys hand wyl neuere spare</L>
<L>Por&euml; folk, to make hem bare</L>
<L>And nakyd (off entenc&iuml;on)</L>
<L N="17644">ffrom al ther pocess&iuml;oun.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>'My thrydd&euml; hand, mad by gret wyle<NOTE PLACE="marg">[<MILESTONE UNIT="prose cap" N="xix">; cap. xviii omit|ted.]</NOTE></L>
<L>With the wych I ber the ffyle,</L>
<L>I shal, as kometh to remembraunce,</L>
<L N="17648">Declar&euml; to the (in substaunce)</L>
<L>What thyng yt doth specefye.<MILESTONE N="250b" UNIT="folio"><NOTE PLACE="marg">[St. &amp; C.]</NOTE></L>
<L>And the trouthe doth sygnefye,<NOTE PLACE="marg">[St. &amp; C.]</NOTE></L>
<L>Thys hand ys wrouht ageyn nature,<NOTE PLACE="marg">[St. &amp; C.]</NOTE></L>
<L N="17652">Wych euere doth hys besy cure<NOTE PLACE="marg">[St. &amp; C.]</NOTE></L>
<L>Alway (off entent vntrewe)</L>
<L>To forg&euml; money newe <I>and</I> newe,</L>
<L>Other folkys gold dystresse,</L>
<L N="17656">And hys own&euml; to encresse,</L>
<L>By som fals collus&iuml;oun.
<PB REF="00000581.tif" N="473"></L>
<L>'And euere in hys entenc&iuml;oun</L>
<L>He ffynt out wey&euml;s sotylly</L>
<L N="17660">ffor tencresse hym-sylff ther-by;</L>
<L>By maner off enchauntement</L>
<L>He ffyndeth out (in hys entent)</L>
<L N="17663">To tourn&euml;, by hys sotylte,</L>
<L>A Tourneys to A parysee<NOTE PLACE="marg">[worth a fourth more: see note, p. 471.]</NOTE>;</L>
<L>By hys engyn, wyl vndertake,</L>
<L>Off fyv&euml;, syx&euml; for to make.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>'Thys hand kan also (in certeyn)</L>
<L N="17668">In gernerys shette vp hys greyn,</L>
<L>Abydynge (with an hevy chere)</L>
<L>Tyl ther kome A der&euml; yere,</L>
<L>At avauntage yt to selle,</L>
<L N="17672">And the pans<NOTE PLACE="marg">[pens St.]</NOTE> ful streyhtly telle,</L>
<L>Vsynge ther-in ful many a whyle.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>'And thys hand that halt the ffyle,<MILESTONE UNIT="Stowe folio" N="308b"></L>
<L>Wasteth both&euml; gret and smal,</L>
<L N="17676">Consumeth and devoureth al,</L>
<L>Off por&euml; folkys, the substaunce:</L>
<L>I pray god yive hym evele chaunce;</L>
<L>ffor nothyng may thys fyle endure.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="17680">'Thys hand ycallyd ys 'Vsure,'</L>
<L>Vsyd in ful many place,</L>
<L>Wych ys to god a gret trespace,</L>
<L>Bothe at marketys and at ffayres.</L>
<L N="17684">And also provostys <I>and</I> ek mayres</L>
<L>In toun&euml;s,<NOTE PLACE="marg">[touns C., St.]</NOTE> borwys and cytes&mdash;<MILESTONE N="251a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>ffolk off hyh and lowh degres&mdash;<NOTE PLACE="marg">[St. &amp; C.]</NOTE></L>
<L>Echon they may nat hem excuse<NOTE PLACE="marg">[excuse St., C. <I>burnt</I>.]</NOTE></L>
<L N="17688">But that somme off hem yt vse.'</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>Pilgrim:<NOTE PLACE="marg">[St., <I>om</I>. C.]</NOTE></HEAD>
<L>"Declar&euml; to me (in substaunce,)<MILESTONE UNIT="prose cap" N="xx"></L>
<L>Wher-off serueth thy balaunche.</L>
<L>I trowe thow wylt ther-in ryht sone</L>
<L N="17692">Peys&euml; ther-in bothe sonne and mone,</L>
<L>The sterrys ek, or thow ha do,</L>
<L>And the zodyak / also."</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>Avarice:<NOTE PLACE="marg">[St., <I>om</I>. C.]</NOTE></HEAD>
<L>'Lerne, and vnderstond me wel,
<PB REF="00000582.tif" N="474"></L>
<L N="17696">'And I shal telle the euerydel:</L>
<L>Grac&euml; dieu, ful yore agon,</L>
<L>Among the planetys euerychon,</L>
<L>(As clerkys wel rehers&euml; konne,)</L>
<L N="17700">In the zodyak sette a sonne,</L>
<L>ffor to shede hys bemys bryht,</L>
<L>And to mynystre hys cler lyht</L>
<L>Indyfferently (I the ensure)</L>
<L N="17704">Vn-to euery cr&euml;ature,</L>
<L>And to be comoun, ther-with-al,</L>
<L>To al the world in general;</L>
<L>To make the Erthe with frut habounde,</L>
<L N="17708">That ther wer no dyffaut&euml; founde.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>'Wh&eacute;r-off (yiff I shal nat lye)</L>
<L>I hadde in herte ful gret envye;</L>
<L>ffor, yt wente nat as I wolde;</L>
<L N="17712">ffor, my wyl were, that yt sholde</L>
<L>Vn-to my lust appropryd be,</L>
<L>By exaumple as thow shalt se.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>'ffyrst, ageyn[e]s al resoun,</L>
<L N="17716">I wolde, by vsurpac&iuml;oun,</L>
<L>ffro poynt to poynt in ech degre,</L>
<L>The zodyak sholde obey&euml; me,<MILESTONE N="251b" UNIT="folio"><NOTE PLACE="marg">[me St., C. <I>burnt</I>]</NOTE></L>
<L>Sonne and mone (ageyns alle skyll),<NOTE PLACE="marg">[St. &amp; C.]</NOTE></L>
<L N="17720">Wynd and wether were at my wyll;<NOTE PLACE="marg">[C. &amp; St.]</NOTE></L>
<L>Al put in my governaunce,<NOTE PLACE="marg">[C. &amp; St.]</NOTE></L>
<L>Yt to weye in my ballaunce.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>'Al thys thyng (as thow shalt se<NOTE PLACE="marg">[se St., C. <I>burnt</I>]</NOTE>)</L>
<L N="17724">I vsurpe yt vp-on me:</L>
<L>The yer, I weye yt in ballaunce,<MILESTONE UNIT="Stowe folio" N="309a"></L>
<L>And selle [yt] ek at my plesaunce;</L>
<L>I selle the wyke, I selle the day,</L>
<L N="17728">(To wych no man dar sey&euml;<NOTE PLACE="marg">[sey C., say St.]</NOTE> nay)</L>
<L>Somtyme by twelue and by thryttene,</L>
<L>By twenty ek, and by nyntene;</L>
<L>And in a yer (who kan yt telle)</L>
<L N="17732">The pound for xx<SUP>ty</SUP> pans<NOTE PLACE="marg">[pens St.]</NOTE> I selle;</L>
<L>The moneth also, by reknyng,</L>
<L>I selle for ix. or .x. shyllyng;<NOTE PLACE="marg">[C. &amp; St.]</NOTE></L>
<L>The wyke also for vj. or fyve,
<PB REF="00000583.tif" N="475"></L>
<L N="17736">'At a-counte that we nat stryve</L>
<L>Affter the somme, whan al ys do,</L>
<L>That my loon&euml; kometh to;</L>
<L>And lyk as euery man doth take,</L>
<L N="17740">Ther-on my reknyng I do make.'</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>Pilgrim:<NOTE PLACE="marg">[St., <I>om</I>. C.]</NOTE></HEAD>
<L>Than, quod I anon, "lat se<MILESTONE UNIT="prose cap" N="xxi"></L>
<L>Touchyng that I shal axen the;</L>
<L>I wolde ther-on have thy devys:</L>
<L N="17744">Her ys a woode off lytel prys,</L>
<L>Wych a woodeman selleth me;</L>
<L>And in the sal&euml;, thus seyth he,</L>
<L>'ffor .xxx.<SUP>ty</SUP> shyllyng I wyl yt selle,</L>
<L N="17748">So that a-noon (as I shal telle)</L>
<L>That thow to me, (lych myn entent,)</L>
<L>Mak&euml; to me thys pay&euml;ment</L>
<L>With-outen any mor delay.</L>
<L N="17752">But yiff I graunte a lenger day,</L>
<L>As thus, tabyde a yerys space,</L>
<L>Thanne I wyl (without&euml; grace<NOTE PLACE="marg">[without grace St., C. <I>burnt</I>]</NOTE>)<MILESTONE N="252a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Have fourty shyllyng (by iuste reknyng)<NOTE PLACE="marg">[C. &amp; St.]</NOTE></L>
<L N="17756">By-cause off myn &aacute;bydyng:'<NOTE PLACE="marg">[C. &amp; St.]</NOTE></L>
<L>Vp-on thys caas I wold&euml; se<NOTE PLACE="marg">[C. &amp; St.]</NOTE></L>
<L>Wh&eacute;r lyk (as yt semeth the)</L>
<L>The sellere off the wych I telle,</L>
<L N="17760">Outher peysseth or doth selle</L>
<L>The tyme, outher the zodyak,</L>
<L>Off the wyche to-forn we spak."</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>Avarice:<NOTE PLACE="marg">[St., <I>om</I>. C.]</NOTE></HEAD>
<L>'Touchyng thys thyng, now herkne me,</L>
<L N="17764">And I shal answerren vn-to the:</L>
<L>Thys cas (yiff thow lyst to lere,)</L>
<L>Ys vnderstonde in twey manere:</L>
<L>Par cas som man, (as thow shalt se,)</L>
<L N="17768">Off nede and off necessyte,</L>
<L>Hys woode, that were by good reknyng</L>
<L>Worth off valu syxty shyllyng,</L>
<L>ffor verray nede and indygence,</L>
<L N="17772">Off bothe to mak&euml; recompense,</L>
<L>ffor fourty shyllyng doth yt selle;
<PB REF="00000584.tif" N="476"></L>
<L>The caus&euml; pleynly for to telle,</L>
<L>He muste haue redy pay&euml;ment.<MILESTONE UNIT="Stowe folio" N="309b"></L>
<L N="17776">Thys marchaunt (to my Iug&euml;ment,</L>
<L>Who-so off resoun look&euml; wel)</L>
<L>The tym&euml; selleth neueradel;</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>'But that marchaunt (with-out&euml; wher,)</L>
<L N="17780">That abydeth al a yer,</L>
<L>Off hym the cas stant other wyse,</L>
<L>As I shal to the devyse:</L>
<L>By Old&euml;<NOTE PLACE="marg">[Old C., St.]</NOTE> tym&euml; (lyst my tale,)</L>
<L>Chapmen that made off wood&euml;<NOTE PLACE="marg">[of wood mad St.]</NOTE> sale,</L>
<L N="17785">They made her sale (who taketh hede)</L>
<L>By A mesour off lengthe and brede;</L>
<L>And to the byggere they wolde seyn:</L>
<L N="17788">'Yiff thow wylt my wodd&euml; beyn,</L>
<L>At O word, (so god me saue!)</L>
<L>At swych a prys thow shalt yt haue,<MILESTONE N="252b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>So that my payement be leyd doun</L>
<L N="17792">With-outen mor dylac&iuml;on.</L>
<L>And yiff thow byde a yerys day</L>
<L>Off my payment by dillay,<NOTE PLACE="marg">[delay St.]</NOTE></L>
<L>I shal the telle by short avys,</L>
<L N="17796">I wyl yt sette at hiher prys;</L>
<L>ffor yiff that I A yer abyde,</L>
<L>My wod&euml; shal on euery syde</L>
<L>Wexe and encresse (I the ensure),</L>
<L N="17800">And multeplyen off nature.'</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>'And yiff the marchaunt, in bargeynyng,</L>
<L>Telle hym thus in hys sellyng,</L>
<L>To-forn, or that the wode be bouht,</L>
<L N="17804">The tyme in soth he selleth nouht,</L>
<L>Nouther weyeth yt in ballaunce;</L>
<L>But yiff the wode (par cas or chaunce)</L>
<L>Wer yhewe, or feld a-doun</L>
<L N="17808">T&oacute;-for ther convenc&iuml;on,</L>
<L>Wych affterward (wo kan espye)</L>
<L>May nat encresse nor multeplye;</L>
<L>Yiff he sette the sale vp sore,</L>
<L N="17812">As thus to sellyn yt for more,</L>
<L>By cause off bydyng off A yer,&mdash;
<PB REF="00000585.tif" N="477"></L>
<L>'Than I suppose (with-out&euml; wer,)</L>
<L>He peyseth (as I rehers&euml; shal,)</L>
<L N="17816">Hys long abydyng tyme and al.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>'But whan the wode may multeplye,</L>
<L>Wexe and encressen at the Eye,</L>
<L>Than thencres and wexyng al</L>
<L N="17820">Ys mesuryd in esp&eacute;cyal,</L>
<L>And yweyed in ballaunce,</L>
<L>Who loketh euery cyrcumstaunce.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>'Now shal I make descrypc&iuml;on,</L>
<L N="17824">And a cler declarac&iuml;on</L>
<L>(Yiff thow kanst wel vnderstond):</L>
<L>Thys dyssh that I holde in myn hond,<MILESTONE UNIT="Stowe folio" N="310a"><MILESTONE UNIT="prose cap" N="xxii"></L>
<L>(In ffrenche callyd 'Coquynerye'<MILESTONE N="253a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="17828">And in ynglyssh 'Trwandrye,')</L>
<L>Thys hand I vse in bryberye,</L>
<L>In beggyng and in lasyngrye.</L>
<L>At euery dore I axe and craue,</L>
<L N="17832">My sustenaunc&euml; for to haue,</L>
<L>And offt&euml; sythe (yt ys no dred)</L>
<L>I put vp many a lompe off bred</L>
<L>In-to my sak, (so mot I the,)</L>
<L N="17836">And kepe yt tyl yt mowlyd be,</L>
<L>That yt may nothyng avaylle.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>'And euery man I kan asaylle</L>
<L>With myn Import&aacute;ble cry,</L>
<L N="17840">I spar&euml; noon that goth forby;</L>
<L>And thus I ax&euml; my purchace.</L>
<L>And I wyl payen in no place,</L>
<L>What vytaylle euere that I spende;</L>
<L N="17844">And to nothyng I do<NOTE PLACE="marg">[that I St.]</NOTE> entende,</L>
<L>But for to axen and to crye;</L>
<L>And al labour I do defye;</L>
<L>I wyl nat travaylle in no wyse;</L>
<L N="17848">I kan my sylff so wel desguyse</L>
<L>With my mantel al-to-rent,</L>
<L>That the peple ys verray blent</L>
<L>With my fals illus&iuml;oun</L>
<L N="17852">And feyned symulac&iuml;oun.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>'I crye and coniure al the day
<PB REF="00000586.tif" N="478"></L>
<L>'On pylgrymes that passe by the way,</L>
<L>As I wer fallyn in A rage;</L>
<L N="17856">And wer that folk ha most passage,</L>
<L>Ther I kan sytte in gret dystresse,</L>
<L>And crye on hem for ther almesse</L>
<L>With a pytous feyned face.</L>
<L N="17860">And, in hem to fynd&euml; grace,</L>
<L>I feyne ful many a mallady,</L>
<L>As I wer in A drop&euml;sy,</L>
<L>Or sodeynly podagre falle;</L>
<L N="17864">And alway, affter good I calle;<MILESTONE N="253b" UNIT="folio"><NOTE PLACE="marg">[C. &amp; St.]</NOTE></L>
<L>I feyne me blynd, I feyne me lame;<NOTE PLACE="marg">[St. &amp; C.]</NOTE></L>
<L>And for to lye, I ha no shame;<NOTE PLACE="marg">[St. &amp; C.]</NOTE></L>
<L>I crye with bak ycorbyd doun,<NOTE PLACE="marg">[St. &amp; C.]</NOTE></L>
<L N="17868">And mak&euml; many a pytous soun.<NOTE PLACE="marg">[St. &amp; C.]</NOTE></L>
<L>And thogh I fele no maner peyne,</L>
<L>I kan ful wel a caus&euml; feyne,</L>
<L>That I am falle in indygence,</L>
<L N="17872">ffor to beggyn my dyspence.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>'And yiff that folk ne yiff me nouht,</L>
<L>Than with a gruchchynge hevy<NOTE PLACE="marg">[hevy <I>om</I>. St.]</NOTE> thouht</L>
<L>I curse hem in-to hell&euml; pet.</L>
<L N="17876">Myn herte on malys ys so set,<NOTE PLACE="marg">[pit . . syt St.]</NOTE></L>
<L>On all I wolde avengyd be,</L>
<L>That wyl no pyte han off me.<MILESTONE UNIT="Stowe folio" N="310b"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>'Thys ys the hand off faussemblaunce;<MILESTONE UNIT="prose cap" N="xxiii"></L>
<L N="17880">And with thys hand, I kan avaunce</L>
<L>Alle thys trwauntys euerychon</L>
<L>Wych that on my daunc&euml; gon,</L>
<L>That, by her offyce and her name,</L>
<L N="17884">ffor to ax&euml;, haue no shame:</L>
<L>Brybours that gon vp <I>and</I> doun,</L>
<L>Devoyde off occupac&iuml;oun,</L>
<L>And lyst hem sylff nothyng avaunce,</L>
<L N="17888">To travaylle for ther sustenaunce,</L>
<L>As thow mayst sen ful many On</L>
<L>That aboute the world so gon.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>'Somme ax&euml; bred, somme ax&euml; chese;</L>
<L N="17892">And for that they wer loth to lese,</L>
<L>Somme axe clothys and cootys olde;
<PB REF="00000587.tif" N="479"></L>
<L>'And some off hem arn ek ful bolde,</L>
<L>Off dyvers housys to axe a rente,</L>
<L N="17896">Wych on the byldyng neuere spente,</L>
<L>As menstrallys <I>and</I> Tregetours,<NOTE PLACE="marg">[Trigetours St.]</NOTE></L>
<L>And other feyned sowdyours,</L>
<L>That with patentys about&euml; gon;</L>
<L N="17900">And among hem euerychon,</L>
<L>I holde thys fals&euml; pardownerys.<NOTE PLACE="marg">[Many leaves, Chapters 24-32 of the prose, are here out of C.]</NOTE></L>
<L><MILESTONE UNIT="Stowe folio" N="310b">I will nat spekyn of no ffrerys,</L>
<L>whiche, in every reg&iuml;on,</L>
<L N="17904">ar bound by theyr professyon</L>
<L>vnto wilfull poverte.</L>
<L>wherfore they haven lyberte</L>
<L>to beggen, as them selff affyrm,</L>
<L N="17908">and on this text they them confyrm:</L>
<L>Christ axyd, when he was her[e] man,</L>
<L>water of the Samaritan&mdash;</L>
<L>I mene, the woman at the well&mdash;</L>
<L N="17912">in erth&euml;, when he dyd her[e] dwell;</L>
<L>wherfore, befull [it] is to frerys,</L>
<L>sythe they be no processionerys,</L>
<L>to get theyr lyvelode wher they may.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="17916">'To ther beggyng I say nat nay,</L>
<L>so that they fayn[&euml;] not in dede</L>
<L>to ax&euml; nat, but for veray nede,</L>
<L>thayr trew&euml; sustentac&iuml;on,</L>
<L N="17920">without all symulat&iuml;on,</L>
<L>that wilfully men to them profrys;</L>
<L>nat to shit vp gold in coffers,</L>
<L>nor to setten ther labowr</L>
<L N="17924">to gathar and hepe gret tresure.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>'as to myn opynyon,</L>
<L>I hold it no perfect&iuml;on,</L>
<L>thowghe that my dyshe &amp; my sachell</L>
<L N="17928">can techen them the craft [ful] well;</L>
<L>for both&euml; two (in sothfastnes)</L>
<L>be gret[&euml;] tookens of falsnes;<MILESTONE UNIT="Stowe folio" N="311a"></L>
<L>and who that evar dothe them vse,</L>
<L N="17932">I ne can them nat excuse,</L>
<L>bothe of hyghe and low degre,
<PB REF="00000588.tif" N="480"></L>
<L>'but they be servants vnto me.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>'And also, yf thow lyst to loke,</L>
<L N="17936">touchynge myn hand eke with the crooke,</L>
<L>I will the tell, or I ha do,</L>
<L>in what wyse I cam therto:</L>
<L>thou shalt know[&euml;] certaynly,</L>
<L N="17940">that Symon Magus and Gyosy,</L>
<L>both&euml; twayn, in theyr entent,</L>
<L>made ther-of to me present.</L>
<L>but the crooke, by &oacute;blacion,</L>
<L N="17944">was gyven t&oacute; me of Symon.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>'and yf I shall the truthe atame,</L>
<L>the fyrst[&euml;] letter of his name</L>
<L>is an .s. (who takythe hede,)</L>
<L N="17948">of shape y-krokyd in the hed;</L>
<L>and of his name (be well certeyn)</L>
<L>it is chefe capytall &amp; cheftayn.</L>
<L>thow wost full well thy selfe, ywys,</L>
<L N="17952">that every .s. y-crokyd is,</L>
<L>lyche a crose highe in the top,</L>
<L>lyche the staffe of a byshope,</L>
<L>or of an abot, wher it be,</L>
<L N="17956">thow mayst example ther-of se.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>'and of an abbey, in sothnesse,</L>
<L>I am callyd an abbesse.</L>
<L>whiche abbey, by gret vyllenye,</L>
<L N="17960">ys [y]callyd symonye.</L>
<L>and as myn hand her with this hook,</L>
<L>of the .s. his nam[&euml;] tooke,</L>
<L>ryght so, in conclus&iuml;on,</L>
<L N="17964">symonye cam of symon.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>'and fyrst thow shalt well vnderstond,</L>
<L>that by falsnes of this hond,</L>
<L>most horryble and odyous,</L>
<L N="17968">was brought fyrst in-to christis hous</L>
<L>the fals&euml; vyce of symonye.</L>
<L>and by his feyned trecherye,</L>
<L>by his sleyhte, and by his gyn,</L>
<L N="17972">at the dore he cam not in;</L>
<L>but at some travas, lych a theffe,
<PB REF="00000589.tif" N="481"></L>
<L>'wher he dothe full gret myschefe;</L>
<L>for wher so evar he dothe aproche,</L>
<L N="17976">with this staffe he can a-croche</L>
<L>the herts of folks by covetyse,</L>
<L>and ordeynythe in full cursyd wyse</L>
<L>sheppards to kep&euml; christis shepe,</L>
<L N="17980">whiche of theyr offyse toke no kepe.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>'an herd man is [y]sayd, in dede,</L>
<L>only, for he shuld[&euml;] fede</L>
<L>his shepe with spyrituall doctryn;<MILESTONE UNIT="Stowe folio" N="311b"></L>
<L N="17984">but they draw by an othar lyn:</L>
<L>they may be callyd, for ther werkynge,</L>
<L>pastours only of fedynge.</L>
<L>they fede them selff with h&aacute;boundaunce,</L>
<L N="17988">and let ther shepe go to myschaunce;</L>
<L>I trow it is full well ysene,</L>
<L>them selfe be fatt, ther shepe be lene.</L>
<L>I trow, the most[&euml;] part of all,</L>
<L N="17992">men shuld them rather wolv[&euml;]s call</L>
<L>than trw&euml; herd[&euml;]s; yong and old,</L>
<L>they come to robb[&euml;] christis fold;</L>
<L>they shuld ther shepe from wolv[&euml;]s were;</L>
<L N="17996">the wool, the mylke, a-way they bere.</L>
<L>I can not se wher-of they serue,</L>
<L>that lat ther shepe at meschefe starue,</L>
<L>and put them selffe in gret defame.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="18000">'and they would ek&euml; mak&euml; lame</L>
<L>grac&euml; dieu of cursydnesse,</L>
<L>lyke as I shall a-non exprese,</L>
<L>ffrom the trone of hir mageste,</L>
<L N="18004">by gyfte of temporalite:</L>
<L>his fals office I can well tell;</L>
<L>he can now byen, he can now sell,</L>
<L>by bound[&euml;]s of collusyon;</L>
<L N="18008">and all comythe in by syr symon.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>'yet at the last it shall be found</L>
<L>that grac&euml; d&iuml;eu is nat bound,</L>
<L>nor, hathe not lost hir fraunchise</L>
<L N="18012">by none suche fals[&euml;] marchandyse,</L>
<L>as comythe in by symony,
<PB REF="00000590.tif" N="482"></L>
<L>'nor couetyse of Gy&euml;sy.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>'this hand also with his crochet,</L>
<L N="18016">in swyche a maner is yset</L>
<L>to sell and byen this gret vertwe</L>
<L>whiche is callyd grac&euml; dieu;</L>
<L>but, kyndly to specify,</L>
<L N="18020">the byggyng is callyd symony,</L>
<L>and the sellyng in certeyn,</L>
<L>(for to speke in word&euml;s pleyn,)</L>
<L>they that it sell, for gret or lyt,</L>
<L N="18024">bene y-callyd Gy&euml;site;</L>
<L>but symony, (who can entend,)</L>
<L>dothe bothe nam[&euml;]s comprehend;</L>
<L>and all that wold&euml; thus enchace</L>
<L N="18028">grac&euml; dieu out of hir place,</L>
<L>to sellen hir for gold &amp; good,</L>
<L>they be mad, or el[le]s wood;</L>
<L>and resemblen (in swiche cas,</L>
<L N="18032">I dare affirm,) vnto Iudas,</L>
<L>that ihesu christ for mony sold<MILESTONE UNIT="Stowe folio" N="312a"></L>
<L>full fallsly, and the panns he told.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>'and suche folke (as thynkythe me)</L>
<L N="18036">wers than iudas, yet thay be;</L>
<L>for the pennis that iudas toke,</L>
<L>aftarward he it forsoke,</L>
<L>and restoryd it agayn;</L>
<L N="18040">but this folke, be well certeyn,</L>
<L>will for no predicat&iuml;on</L>
<L>nevar make restituc&iuml;on,</L>
<L>and caws&euml; why, (who lokythe well,)</L>
<L N="18044">is only this, for the sachell</L>
<L>whiche hangythe fro my nek&euml; doune,</L>
<L>of nature and condic&iuml;oun:</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>'what-evar into my sake ther gothe,</L>
<L N="18048">(who that evar be lesse or lothe,)</L>
<L>it will nevar ysswe out ageyn;</L>
<L>the entre is bothe large and pleyne,</L>
<L>and the mouthe to gon in by</L>
<L N="18052">is evar open at the entry.</L>
<L>but to comyn out, that wyll nat be
<PB REF="00000591.tif" N="483"></L>
<L>'by no maner of sotelte;</L>
<L>the way is narow &amp; streyght certeyn,</L>
<L N="18056">for to comyn out ageyn,</L>
<L>lyke a wyle in a ryver,</L>
<L>to cache the fysche bothe fer and nere;</L>
<L>the entre large / the comynge out</L>
<L N="18060">is so strayt, it stant in dout.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>'A-nothar hand I have also,</L>
<L>with whiche I werk&euml; mych&euml; wo</L>
<L>by a maner of roberye:</L>
<L N="18064">and it is callyd 'trecherye,'</L>
<L>withe the whiche, (who can conceyve,)</L>
<L>full many folk[&euml;s] I deceve.</L>
<L>vndar colour of ryghtwysnes,</L>
<L N="18068">I do to folke full gret falsnes,</L>
<L>that be symple and inocent.</L>
<L>withe my frawd they be so blent</L>
<L>in marchandys&euml; that I vse,</L>
<L N="18072">I can my selffe nat well excuse.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>'in deceyt stant my labowr,</L>
<L>by fals weyght and fals mesure:</L>
<L>by larg&euml; mesure I can byen,</L>
<L N="18076">and streight mesure I sell ageyn;</L>
<L>in byggyng I wyll ha trwe wayt,</L>
<L>but in my salle I do gret slayt,</L>
<L>bothe in peys and in balance.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="18080">'with sobar cher and countenance</L>
<L>my chaff&eacute;r I can well sell,</L>
<L>and to symple folke I tell</L>
<L>that it is bettar than it is,</L>
<L N="18084">and wittyngly I do a-mys</L>
<L>touchynge the pris, how that it gothe,<MILESTONE UNIT="Stowe folio" N="312b"></L>
<L>and falsly swere many an othe,</L>
<L>sober all-way, and sad of chere.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="18088">'and whan that I am a drapere,</L>
<L>I hange out courteyns in the lyght,</L>
<L>for to blynd&euml; folk&euml;s syght,</L>
<L>that men may not sen at y<SUP>e</SUP> full</L>
<L N="18092">nothar the colowr nor the wull;</L>
<L>set it at hygh&euml; pris therto,
<PB REF="00000592.tif" N="484"></L>
<L>and swere I myght ha sold it so</L>
<L>the last[&euml;] day, to a chapman:</L>
<L N="18096">thus I begyll many a man</L>
<L>&para; withe this hand of whiche I tell,</L>
<L>both&euml; when I by and sell.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>'this hand myght nat well be worse:</L>
<L N="18100">some tyme ther-with I can sell horse,</L>
<L>and lyke a falce coursar, I can</L>
<L>with othis deceyue many a man.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>'som tyme by borows and by towns</L>
<L N="18104">I walke about[en] with pardons,</L>
<L>with reliks, and ded&euml; bones,</L>
<L>closyd vndar glase and stons:</L>
<L>I shew them vndar sell and bull,</L>
<L N="18108">and thus the pore people I pull,</L>
<L>of ther sylvar I make them quite,</L>
<L>in falsnes I ha so gret delyght.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>'to abbeys eke I can wel gon,</L>
<L N="18112">stell ymagis of tre and stone,</L>
<L>thowghe they ben old, &amp; paynt them newe,</L>
<L>and make them sem&euml; freshe of hewe,</L>
<L>with colours both&euml; whit and redd;</L>
<L N="18116">and at theyr brestis and at ther hedd</L>
<L>I set berryls and crystall;</L>
<L>vndar, I make an hole full smale;</L>
<L>I put in oyl&euml;, wyne, and blood,</L>
<L N="18120">and melke also, to get[ten] good;</L>
<L>make the lycour round about,</L>
<L>at small holes to rennyn out,</L>
<L>as it were done by myracle,</L>
<L N="18124">that ther nis balme nor triacle</L>
<L>in this world, so ryche of prys,</L>
<L>of foltyshe people that ben nat wys.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>'I set eke out swyche ymagis,</L>
<L N="18128">in stret[i]s and at hermytagis,</L>
<L>and in subbarbys at many a towne,</L>
<L>with bullis fret full of pardon;</L>
<L>byshops seles be nat behynd:</L>
<L N="18132">and thus I mak&euml; folk[&euml;]s blynd,</L>
<L>by my sleyght and by my guyle.
<PB REF="00000593.tif" N="485"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>'and yet I vse a-nothar whyle:</L>
<L>I go to faytours of entent,</L>
<L N="18136">and make them eke of myn assent,<MILESTONE UNIT="Stowe folio" N="313a"></L>
<L>and, by fals colusyon,</L>
<L>and cursyd dissymulat&iuml;on,</L>
<L>I men&euml; suche as ha no shame,</L>
<L N="18140">to fayne them selffe bothe blynd and lame,</L>
<L>crokyd, halt, and dome with all,</L>
<L>on euery leg a gret mormall,</L>
<L>full of plastars old and new,</L>
<L N="18144">to make the people on them rew.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>'and, for more decepc&iuml;on,</L>
<L>I make them to be leyd a-doun,</L>
<L>&para; to-forn the ymagys down to ly,</L>
<L N="18148">and for helth&euml; lowd[&euml;] cry,</L>
<L>ther to have amend&euml;ment.</L>
<L>and they and I of one assent,</L>
<L>I lyft them vp my selfe anon,</L>
<L N="18152">and make them on ther fet to gon</L>
<L>with-outen eny more obst&aacute;cle,</L>
<L>as all w&eacute;r wrowght by myr&aacute;cle.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>'the people, takynge none hede therto,</L>
<L N="18156">supposythe pleynly that it wer so;</L>
<L>with offerynge and with pilgrim&aacute;gis</L>
<L>come full oft to suche ym&aacute;gis,</L>
<L>for to done ther &oacute;bservaunce:</L>
<L N="18160">and thus I can my selffe avaunce</L>
<L>as oth&aacute;r los&eacute;ngars can,</L>
<L>with good that is full falsly won,</L>
<L>whiche that the people obeyethe full sore.</L>
<L N="18164">but of this thynge, as now no more</L>
<L>I wyll nat mak&euml; r&eacute;hersall.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>'&amp; for this hand may myche avayle</L>
<L>to profet me bothe day and nyght,</L>
<L N="18168">I take none hede of wronge or ryght,</L>
<L>thowghe it to folks do gret domage,</L>
<L>whill I ther-in fynd &aacute;dvauntage.</L>
<L>it hathe of falshed many a braunche,</L>
<L N="18172">and why? I<NOTE PLACE="marg">[MS. It]</NOTE> put it to my haunche,</L>
<L>and to my tonge reyse it agayne:
<PB REF="00000594.tif" N="486"></L>
<L>'the cawse I woll vnto th&egrave; sayne:</L>
<L>myn haunch&euml; is callyd lesynge,</L>
<L N="18176">and my tong&euml; forswerynge;</L>
<L>and, to this twayn, trechery</L>
<L>is famylyar, and of aly,</L>
<L>and to them bothe, of kyndly lawe,</L>
<L N="18180">of custome she will evar drawe.</L>
<L>wher they ben old or yong of age,</L>
<L>they be echon of o lynage,</L>
<L>and, by hyr&euml;, fyrst, certeyne,</L>
<L N="18184">myne haunch&euml; cawht&euml; this spaven.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>'she made my tong&euml; fyrst taplye</L>
<L>to fynd out lesynge, and to ly;</L>
<L>and of lyenge I made to-forne,</L>
<L>was forswerynge fyrst yborn;<MILESTONE UNIT="Stowe folio" N="313b"></L>
<L>for wher that evar forsweryng be,</L>
<L>lesynge is nyhe, as men may se;</L>
<L>and wher-so-evar that they go,</L>
<L N="18192">barret is nat fer them fro;</L>
<L>all thre bene of on accord,</L>
<L>with truthe evar-more at dyscord.'</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>pilgrim:</HEAD>
<L>"Tell on, I pray, let me se</L>
<L N="18196">in what wys&euml; may this be;</L>
<L>thow callyst thy tonge 'forswerynge,'</L>
<L>and thyn haunche also 'lyenge,'</L>
<L>whiche is so halt and corbyd doun;</L>
<L N="18200">tell me here-on some reson."</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>Avarice:</HEAD>
<L>quod avaric&euml;, 'lay to ere,</L>
<L>and anon thow shalt well here,</L>
<L>how that I this othar day</L>
<L N="18204">mett with truthe vp-on the way;</L>
<L>withe her was also equite,</L>
<L>and both&euml; tweyn, I dyd se.</L>
<L>of them, as I tok&euml; hede,</L>
<L N="18208">how they begged bothe ther bred;</L>
<L>they were so poor&euml; both&euml; two,</L>
<L>for theyr frynd[&euml;]s wer all go.</L>
<L>and yf I shall the truth&euml; showe,
<PB REF="00000595.tif" N="487"></L>
<L N="18212">'this day they ha but frynd[&euml;]s fewe,</L>
<L>ne non ne shal, yf that I may.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>'and when I met them on the way,</L>
<L>I gan to turne the bake full sone;</L>
<L N="18216">with them I had no thynge to done;</L>
<L>for me sempte, to my plesaunce,</L>
<L>they myght me no thynge avaunce,</L>
<L>nor no profit done to me.</L>
<L N="18220">therfore from them I gan to fle</L>
<L>over the feld[&euml;]s as they lay,</L>
<L>and I ne cept none hygh&euml; way,</L>
<L>but forthe, lyke myn opin&iuml;on.</L>
<L N="18224">as I rann, I fell doune;<NOTE PLACE="marg">[as, I, <I>each a foot</I>]</NOTE></L>
<L>and with that fall ther was no gayne,</L>
<L>but that I cawht a great spavayne</L>
<L>vpon my lege, whiche mad&euml; me</L>
<L N="18228">for to halt, as thow mayst se;</L>
<L>and sothly yet, (who lok&euml; well,)</L>
<L>to halt, I hate it nevar a dell.</L>
<L>for when with haltynge I am dull,</L>
<L N="18232">it makythe my sake to be more full;</L>
<L>haltynge dothe me more avaunce;</L>
<L>therby I mak&euml; chevysaunce,</L>
<L>for in haltynge is no synne;</L>
<L N="18236">who dothe vpryght, may nothynge wynn;</L>
<L>haltynge me wynnythe many a grote,</L>
<L>it maketh me hatter than my cote,<MILESTONE UNIT="Stowe folio" N="314a"></L>
<L>that I must my tunge in sothe</L>
<L N="18240">cast out as a dogg&euml; dothe.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>'and than full offe it falleth so,</L>
<L>that to the kyng[&euml;]s court I goo,</L>
<L>and am ther, of no man afferyd.</L>
<L N="18244">and whan I have the law&euml;s leryd,</L>
<L>and am come to hyghe estat,</L>
<L>than I become an advocat,</L>
<L>and mak&euml; folk[&euml;]s to me drawe,</L>
<L N="18248">swyche as hav to don with lawe.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>'but first I swere, with-out[en] doute,</L>
<L>my tunge I shall nat puten oute,</L>
<L>for ryght ne wronge, ne for no thynge,
<PB REF="00000596.tif" N="488"></L>
<L N="18252">'but wher I se ryght gret wynnynge.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>'on that party evar I hold,</L>
<L>lyche a balaunce of whiche y told,</L>
<L>whose tung&euml; draweth to that cost,</L>
<L N="18256">wher the weyht gothe doun&euml; most:</L>
<L>to that party he wyll nat fyne</L>
<L>the balaunc&euml; to enclyne.</L>
<L>and so fare I when I begyne,</L>
<L N="18260">to holden ther I may most wyne.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>'whan folke me pray with all ther myght</L>
<L>for to help them in theyr ryght,</L>
<L>wher the cawse be grene or rype,</L>
<L N="18264">a-non as I the money grype,</L>
<L>than I dare swaryn, by bone &amp; blood,</L>
<L>that theyr cawse is trwe and good,</L>
<L>thoughe I know the contrary.</L>
<L N="18268">and than anon I wyll not tary,</L>
<L>for gold and sylvar evar amonge,</L>
<L>to mak&euml; ryght, thowghe it be wronge;</L>
<L>for I can make, vnto hir syght,</L>
<L N="18272">ryght of wronge, and wrong of ryght;</L>
<L>tourne the matere vp se doune,</L>
<L>and preue it out by good reson,</L>
<L>that in the case there is no lake:</L>
<L N="18276">and all I do, to fyll my sake</L>
<L>withe gold and othar men[n&euml;]s good,</L>
<L>how evar aforne the cas&euml; stode.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>'thus haue I told the by resonne,</L>
<L N="18280">and mad a demonstrac&iuml;on,</L>
<L>why that my tonge (by dyscryvynge)</L>
<L>is [y]callyd 'forswerynge.'</L>
<L>and withe lesyngs, (who lyst know,)</L>
<L N="18284">vp and downe it is y-sowe;</L>
<L>to falshed I do most avauntage,</L>
<L>and to truth&euml; gretyst damage.</L>
<L>and in this plyht, as I the told,</L>
<L N="18288">ever my purpos I shall hold,</L>
<L>that yf the lawe ne chaung&euml; nought,</L>
<L>I will be fals of word and thought,</L>
<L>in every place, wher evar I be,<MILESTONE UNIT="Stowe folio" N="314b">
<PB REF="00000597.tif" N="489"></L>
<L N="18292">'that no man shall lev&euml; me:</L>
<L>now I ha told the of my sake.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>'touchinge the bonche vpon my bake,</L>
<L>I wyll to the now specifye</L>
<L N="18296">what thynge it dothe signefye.</L>
<L>this is the boch gret and hydous,</L>
<L>with whiche this folke relyg&iuml;ous</L>
<L>bene ybonchyd, full many on;|</L>
<L N="18300">som, I say, nat everychon,</L>
<L>suche as by transgressyon</L>
<L>kepe not theyr professyon,</L>
<L>as they be bound by theyr degre.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="18304">'and by example, (as thow mayst se,)</L>
<L>so as a boche or a fellon</L>
<L>ar cawsyd of corrupt&iuml;on</L>
<L>of wyckyd humours &amp; corrupt blood,</L>
<L N="18308">of colore adust, fervent and wood,</L>
<L>and othar suparfluyte;</L>
<L>ryght so, ryches and gret plente</L>
<L>ar caws&euml; that a rych&euml; man,</L>
<L N="18312">as the gospell rehers[&euml;] can,<NOTE PLACE="foot">The readable part of MS. Cotton Tiberius, A. vii, begins here.</NOTE></L>
<L>May in-to heven have none entre,<MILESTONE UNIT="Stowe folio" N="314b"><MILESTONE UNIT="Tib folio" N="39a"><NOTE PLACE="marg">[St. &amp; Tib.]</NOTE></L>
<L>But euen lyke as ye may se,<NOTE PLACE="marg">[St. &amp; Tib.]</NOTE></L>
<L>A camell may hym-silffe applye<NOTE PLACE="marg">[St. &amp; Tib.]</NOTE></L>
<L N="18316">To passen thorugh a nedelyes eye,<NOTE PLACE="marg">[St. &amp; Tib.]</NOTE><MILESTONE UNIT="Tib folio" N="39a"></L>
<L>Whiche is a thyng not credible,<NOTE PLACE="marg">[St. &amp; Tib.]</NOTE></L>
<L>But a maner impossible,<NOTE PLACE="marg">[St. &amp; Tib.]</NOTE></L>
<L>Thys beste is so encomerous,<NOTE PLACE="marg">[Stowe]</NOTE><MILESTONE UNIT="prose cap" N="xxxiii"></L>
<L N="18320">Off bak corbyd and tortuous,<NOTE PLACE="marg">[Stowe]</NOTE></L>
<L>And so to pass&euml;, no thyng able.<NOTE PLACE="marg">[Stowe]</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>'And euene lyk in caas sembl&aacute;ble,</L>
<L>ffolkis off relygyoun,</L>
<L N="18324">Bounde by ther professyoun</L>
<L>ffor to lyue in pouerte</L>
<L>Off ther own&euml; volunte,</L>
<L>And to pouert hem<NOTE PLACE="marg">[hym C., them St.]</NOTE> silffe proffesse,</L>
<L N="18328">&YOGH;eue they be bocchyd with<NOTE PLACE="marg">[by St.]</NOTE> richesse,</L>
<L>To gadre vp good<NOTE PLACE="marg">[good St., and Tib.]</NOTE> in ther bandoun,</L>
<L>Tresoure, and greet pocescyoun;<NOTE PLACE="marg">[St. &amp; Tib.]</NOTE>
<PB REF="00000598.tif" N="490"></L>
<L>'ffor hard it is ffor hem to trace,<NOTE PLACE="marg">[St. &amp; Tib.]</NOTE></L>
<L N="18332">Or by so smal an hoole to passe<NOTE PLACE="marg">[St. &amp; Tib.]</NOTE></L>
<L>Vp to that heuenly mansyoun,<NOTE PLACE="marg">[St. &amp; Tib.]</NOTE></L>
<L>To cleyme there habytacyoun.<NOTE PLACE="marg">[St. &amp; Tib.]</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>THis lytle hool&euml; (who kan se,)<NOTE PLACE="marg">[St. &amp; Tib.]</NOTE></L>
<L N="18336">Bytokeneth willefful pouerte,<NOTE PLACE="marg">[St. &amp; Tib.]</NOTE></L>
<L>Receyued with-outen eny stryffe;<NOTE PLACE="marg">[St. &amp; Tib.]</NOTE></L>
<L>ffor, pore we kam in-to this lyffe,<NOTE PLACE="marg">[St. &amp; Tib.]</NOTE></L>
<L>And nakyd, (who taketh heede ther-to,)<NOTE PLACE="marg">[St. &amp; Tib.]</NOTE></L>
<L N="18340">Out off this lyffe we schal eke go.<MILESTONE UNIT="Stowe folio" N="315a"><NOTE PLACE="marg">[St. &amp; Tib.]</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>'Wherffore late ffolkis good heede take,<NOTE PLACE="marg">[St. &amp; Tib.]</NOTE></L>
<L>(Swyche as han this world fforsake,)<NOTE PLACE="marg">[St. &amp; Tib.]</NOTE></L>
<L>Hem to preserue by holynesse<NOTE PLACE="marg">[St. &amp; Tib.]</NOTE></L>
<L N="18344">ffrom the bocche off ffalse richesse,<NOTE PLACE="marg">[St. &amp; Tib.]</NOTE></L>
<L>Whiche is a thyng (who kan discerne)<NOTE PLACE="marg">[St. &amp; Tib.]</NOTE></L>
<L>That wyl clos&euml; the posterne<NOTE PLACE="marg">[St. &amp; Tib.]</NOTE></L>
<L>Of Paradys<NOTE PLACE="marg">[St. (Tib. <I>blurd</I>)]</NOTE> and the entre,<NOTE PLACE="marg">[St. &amp; Tib.]</NOTE></L>
<L N="18348">And stope the hole<NOTE PLACE="marg">[St. (Tib. <I>blurd</I>)]</NOTE> off pouerte,<NOTE PLACE="marg">[St. &amp; Tib.]</NOTE></L>
<L>Whiche is, to parffyte ffolke, the gate<MILESTONE UNIT="Tib folio" N="39b"><NOTE PLACE="marg">[St. &amp; Tib.]</NOTE></L>
<L>To lete hem in, erly and late,</L>
<L>Alle that ben ffounden vertuous</L>
<L N="18352">In ffolkis eke relygyous.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>Properte.</HEAD>
<L>'THis bocche is callyd 'Properte,'<MILESTONE UNIT="prose cap" N="xxxiv"></L>
<L>Whiche is afferd off Pouerte;</L>
<L N="18355">ffor pouerte (as clerkys teche)</L>
<L>Is both&euml; medicyne<NOTE PLACE="marg">[medcyne Tib., medisyn St.]</NOTE> and leche</L>
<L>To launche the bocche off Properte,</L>
<L>And voyde alle superfluyte,</L>
<L>And the bollynge in ech&euml;<NOTE PLACE="marg">[on eche a St.]</NOTE> syde.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="18360">'But Properte dar not Abyde<NOTE PLACE="marg">[Tib. &amp; St.]</NOTE></L>
<L>To suffre Pouerte hym to kerue,<NOTE PLACE="marg">[Tib. &amp; St.]</NOTE></L>
<L>Leste off the wounde he schuly&euml; sterue<NOTE PLACE="marg">[Tib. &amp; St.]</NOTE></L>
<L>Leuere he hathe, in peyne tendure,<NOTE PLACE="marg">[Tib. &amp; St.]</NOTE></L>
<L N="18364">Than pouerte schulde his bocche recure;</L>
<L>ffor he is dredefful, and eke arwh,<NOTE PLACE="marg">[Tib. &amp; St.]</NOTE></L>
<L>To passe an hole that is so narwh<NOTE PLACE="marg">[Tib. &amp; St.]</NOTE></L>
<L>As hym<NOTE PLACE="marg">[it St.]</NOTE> semyth in his devys,<NOTE PLACE="marg">[Tib. &amp; St.]</NOTE></L>
<L N="18368">Outher to heven or paradys:<NOTE PLACE="marg">[Tib. &amp; St.]</NOTE></L>
<L>His herte is no thyng ther-on set.<NOTE PLACE="marg">[Tib. &amp; St.]</NOTE>
<PB REF="00000599.tif" N="491"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>'Now wole I speke off my mawmet.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>The Mawmet:</HEAD>
<L>'ANd off myn ydol that is so oold,<MILESTONE UNIT="prose cap" N="xxxv"></L>
<L N="18372">Made off siluer and off gold,</L>
<L>In the whiche (I the ensure)</L>
<L>Is the ymage and the ffygure</L>
<L>And the prynte (as thou mayste see)</L>
<L N="18376">Off the lord off the contre.</L>
<L>This is the god whiche, by depos,<NOTE PLACE="marg">[depose St.]</NOTE></L>
<L>Loueth to be schutte in hucches clos.</L>
<L>&para; Somwhyle, that men may hym not knowe,<MILESTONE UNIT="Tib folio" N="40a"></L>
<L N="18380">He wole hym hyde in erth&euml; lowe.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>'This god kan mak&euml; ffolkys blynde,</L>
<L>That to his &oacute;bseruaunce hem bynde;</L>
<L>And causith hem, ageyn resoun,</L>
<L N="18384">To caste her lok&euml;s low&euml; down</L>
<L>In-to the erthe, ageyne nature,</L>
<L>Hem-silffe so mykel they assure</L>
<L>In eerthely tresoure, whiche at<NOTE PLACE="marg">[in St.]</NOTE> o day</L>
<L N="18388">Schal vnwarely passe away;</L>
<L>ffor lawe<NOTE PLACE="marg">[low St.]</NOTE> in erthe, on euery syde,<MILESTONE UNIT="Stowe folio" N="315b"></L>
<L>Lyche a moll&euml; they abyde;</L>
<L>In erthe is hoolly ther labour;</L>
<L N="18392">In erthe ys also ther tresour;</L>
<L>Erthe is ther Ioye and ther plesaunce;</L>
<L>No thyng but erthe may hem avaunce;</L>
<L>Gold and seluer makyth hem nygh wood;</L>
<L N="18396">Gold is ther god, gold is ther good;</L>
<L>I worschipe gold and my tresour</L>
<L>As ffor my god and savyour;</L>
<L>Saue gold, noon other god I haue.<NOTE PLACE="inter">[Illumination.]</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="18400">'<B>I</B> Thenke not how I schal be grave</L>
<L>In eerth&euml; lowe, ther to be ffreete,</L>
<L>Corupcyoun and worm&euml;s mete,</L>
<L>Hydous, stynkynge, and horryble,<MILESTONE UNIT="Tib folio" N="40b"></L>
<L N="18404">And to loke vp-on, odyble:</L>
<L>What may my gold thanne me<NOTE PLACE="marg">[me than St.]</NOTE> avayle,</L>
<L>Whanne wormes han<NOTE PLACE="marg">[have St.]</NOTE> with me batayle?</L>
<L>But here, while I haue lyberte,
<PB REF="00000600.tif" N="492"></L>
<L N="18408">'This thyng to-fforne I kan no<NOTE PLACE="marg">[nat St.]</NOTE> se,</L>
<L>ffor in no thyng I<NOTE PLACE="marg">[I St., that I Tib.]</NOTE> kan affye,</L>
<L>But gold and good to multeplye.</L>
<L N="18411">Gold is my god and my Mawmet;</L>
<L>&para; And al on gold myne herte<NOTE PLACE="marg">[all [my] hert to gold St.]</NOTE> is sette;</L>
<L>ffor golde, I dyde fful greet offence,</L>
<L>In colys to rost&euml; seynt Laurence.</L>
<L>For he, off pite (thus it stood)<NOTE PLACE="marg">[St. &amp; Tib.]</NOTE></L>
<L N="18416">&YOGH;aue the tresoure and the good</L>
<L>Off holy church&euml; ffor almesse,</L>
<L>To pore ffolkis he<NOTE PLACE="marg">[to folke that he St.]</NOTE> ffonde in distresse.<NOTE PLACE="inter">[Illumination.]</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>'BUt I,<NOTE PLACE="marg">[I St., <I>om</I>. Tib.]</NOTE> in myne oppynyoun,</L>
<L>am<NOTE PLACE="marg">[am St., I am Tib.]</NOTE> not off that condicioun:</L>
<L N="18421">To get&euml; good is my laboure,</L>
<L>And to awment&euml; my tresoure,</L>
<L>And (as it is to ffolke fful kouthe,)</L>
<L N="18424">More in ag&euml; thanne in &yogh;outhe,</L>
<L>Som tyme with lesynges and with ffablys,</L>
<L>Som tyme at<NOTE PLACE="marg">[at St., at the Tib.]</NOTE> chesse, som tyme at tablys,</L>
<L>At merels and the botevaunt,<MILESTONE UNIT="Tib folio" N="41a"></L>
<L N="18428">At hasard and at<NOTE PLACE="marg">[at St., <I>om</I>. Tib.]</NOTE> [the] devaunt,</L>
<L>And at these pley&euml;s euerychon,</L>
<L>My mawmet I worschipe euere in oon.</L>
<L>&para; ffor, wher-so<NOTE PLACE="marg">[so St., <I>om</I>. Tib.]</NOTE> it be vyce or synne,</L>
<L N="18432">I do no thyng but ffor to wynne;</L>
<L>To good is al-way my repayre.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>'And, ffor my <B>Mawmet is so ffayre,</B></L>
<L>And ffulffylled off<NOTE PLACE="marg">[withe St.]</NOTE> alle plesaunce,</L>
<L N="18436">Do<NOTE PLACE="marg">[Do St., To do Tib.]</NOTE> ther-to som &oacute;bseruaunce,</L>
<L>And knele anoon vpon thy kne,<MILESTONE UNIT="Stowe folio" N="316a"></L>
<L>Lowely to<NOTE PLACE="marg">[vnto St.]</NOTE> his d&euml;yte.</L>
<L>ffor, but<NOTE PLACE="marg">[for but . . do St., But ffor . . a Tib.]</NOTE> thow do with-out[&euml;] more,</L>
<L N="18440">Thow schalt abyggen it fful sore;</L>
<L>And I schal ellys verrey<NOTE PLACE="marg">[warreye St.]</NOTE> the;</L>
<L>Thow geteste no lenger trewys off me.'</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>&para; The Pylgryme:</HEAD>
<L>ANd whil&euml; sche gan me<NOTE PLACE="marg">[me Tib., me to St.]</NOTE> assayle</L>
<L N="18444">fful cruelly, as by batayle,</L>
<L>Alle sodeynely I dyd&euml; sen,
<PB REF="00000601.tif" N="493"></L>
<L>How that &yogh;outh&euml; wente atwen,</L>
<L>Bytwyxen Avarise and me,</L>
<L N="18448">Cryed trewys, and bad let be.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>&para; Than &yogh;outhe spak:<NOTE PLACE="marg">[youthe St.]</NOTE></HEAD>
<L>'DO to hym no vyolence,</L>
<L>ffor I am komen in his diffence,</L>
<L>Ageynse<NOTE PLACE="marg">[agaynst St.]</NOTE> the to make hym stronge.</L>
<L N="18452">Thow schalt to hym do now no wronge,</L>
<L>(Thow<NOTE PLACE="marg">[thowghe St.]</NOTE> thow be cruel off entent,)</L>
<L>While that I am here present.'</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>&para; Auaryce:</HEAD>
<L>'&YOGH;Eue<NOTE PLACE="marg">[yf St.]</NOTE> thow ne were not ffast&euml; by,<MILESTONE UNIT="Tib folio" N="41b"></L>
<L N="18456">Thow myghtteste trust&euml; ffynaly,</L>
<L>That I ffor no thyng wold&euml; lette,</L>
<L>But that I schulde vp-on hym sette.<NOTE PLACE="inter">[Illustration.]</NOTE></L>
<L>&para; Thy komynge is not to my pay;</L>
<L N="18460">Thow haste me lettyd off my pray;</L>
<L>ffor the whiche, I am fful wo;</L>
<L>But now to hym I may nat do,</L>
<L>ffor to ffulffill&euml; my talent,</L>
<L N="18464">While thow art with hym present.</L>
<L>But go thi way, and late hym be,</L>
<L>And anoon thow schalt wel se,</L>
<L>I schal hem cacchen<NOTE PLACE="marg">[cachen St., cacche Tib.]</NOTE> in a trappe,</L>
<L N="18468">And aresten by the lappe,</L>
<L>That he schal not skape away</L>
<L>ffro my daungere, &yogh;eue<NOTE PLACE="marg">[yf St.]</NOTE> I may.'</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>&para; The Pylgryme:</HEAD>
<L>ANd whanne that I was at my large,</L>
<L N="18472">And thought I wold&euml; me<NOTE PLACE="marg">[me St., not Tib.]</NOTE> discharge,</L>
<L>ffrom all&euml; daunger to go ffre,</L>
<L>ffrom Auaryce at lyberte,<MILESTONE UNIT="Tib folio" N="42a"></L>
<L>Thorough helpe and ffavour (in this cas)</L>
<L N="18476">Off &yogh;outh&euml; that my guyd&euml; was,</L>
<L>I wolde, as tho, no lenger byde,</L>
<L>But in-tawod&euml;<NOTE PLACE="marg">[into a wood St.]</NOTE> there bysyde</L>
<L>I entryd, whiche stood ffast&euml;<NOTE PLACE="marg">[but fast St.]</NOTE> by.</L>
<L N="18480">And as I wente, alle sodeynely</L>
<L>I herde oon wonder lowd&euml; crye,
<PB REF="00000602.tif" N="494"></L>
<L>And afftir me gan ffaste hym hye,</L>
<L>As he h&aacute;dde ben in a rage.</L>
<L N="18484">And so straunge was his langage,</L>
<L>That I ne vnderstood hym nought;</L>
<L>ffor I conceyued in my thought,<MILESTONE UNIT="Stowe folio" N="316b"></L>
<L>How he that affter me gan gon:</L>
<L>ffrenche<NOTE PLACE="marg">[ffrenchs Tib., Frenche St.]</NOTE> nor Latyn he spak noon.</L>
<L N="18489">And in his hand (I was wel war,)</L>
<L>A nakyd swerde how that he bar,</L>
<L>fful scharp&euml; grownd&euml; ffor to byte,</L>
<L N="18492">And redy as he wold&euml; smyte,</L>
<L>And bade, I schulde me ffast&euml; dresse,</L>
<L>Kome to speke with his Maystresse.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Amydde<NOTE PLACE="marg">[and myd St.]</NOTE> the way, vpon a lond,</L>
<L N="18496">With-in a cercle I hym ffond,<NOTE PLACE="inter">[Illustration.]</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>WIth-in whiche (so god me save,)<MILESTONE UNIT="Tib folio" N="42b"></L>
<L>I sawgh fful many a ffygure grave,</L>
<L>fful meruelous, as in workynge;</L>
<L N="18500">And he bare armys off A kynge,</L>
<L>A Box&euml;, lyche a Messangere.</L>
<L>And trewely, as I neyghed nere,</L>
<L>By sygn&euml;s that I dyd&euml; se,</L>
<L N="18504">I wend&euml; so that he hadde be,</L>
<L>Hopynge the bette, at lyberte,</L>
<L>ffrom al daunger to skap&euml; ffre:</L>
<L N="18507">&para; To whom I spake fful bold&euml;ly,</L>
<L>And seyde, "I merveyl<NOTE PLACE="marg">[mervayll St., merveyled Tib.]</NOTE> ryght greetly</L>
<L>That thow byddeste me ffaste dresse</L>
<L>ffor to kome to thi maystresse;</L>
<L>And by no tokene that I kan se,</L>
<L N="18512">I wote not what sche schuld&euml; be;</L>
<L>ffor whiche, I preye the not to spare,</L>
<L>Off hir the maner to declare."</L>
<L>&para; And he to me in word&euml;s ffewe,</L>
<L N="18516">With his ffynger gan me schewe</L>
<L>fful ffast&euml; by, a mansyoun,</L>
<L>Ryght vp, lyche a p&aacute;vyloun;</L>
<L>And on the pomel (who lyste knowe)</L>
<L N="18520">Wonder hygh ther sate a krowe,
<PB REF="00000603.tif" N="495"></L>
<L>His whynges splayynge to and ffro;</L>
<L>And with the noyse he mad&euml; tho,</L>
<L>The messangere gan newe abreyde,</L>
<L N="18524">And vn-to me ryght thus he seyde:</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>&para; The Messangere:</HEAD>
<L>'Byhoolde &yogh;one habytacyoun</L>
<L>And the hygh&euml;<NOTE PLACE="marg">[hyghe St., hygh Tib.]</NOTE> p&aacute;vylloun:</L>
<L>In that place (I dar expresse)</L>
<L N="18528">There abydith my maystresse,</L>
<L>Whiche cessith, nowther nyght nor day,</L>
<L>To teche hir scolers what sche may,<MILESTONE UNIT="Tib folio" N="43a"></L>
<L>fful many wonderfful lessouns,</L>
<L N="18532">And many dyuerse c&oacute;nclusyouns.<NOTE PLACE="marg">[Illustration.]</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>'ANd, therffore, I callyd the,</L>
<L>That thow scholdeste the maner se<MILESTONE UNIT="Stowe folio" N="317a"></L>
<L>Off hir scole, and knowe it offte.</L>
<L N="18536">And ffor this skele, the crowe aloffte</L>
<L>Is sette, (&yogh;eue<NOTE PLACE="marg">[yf St.]</NOTE> thow kanste espye,)</L>
<L>Afftir hir scolerys ffor to crye;</L>
<L N="18539">That fforby passe, bothe este and west;</L>
<L>Thereffore sche hath made there<NOTE PLACE="marg">[ther made St.]</NOTE> hir nest.'</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>&para; The pylgryme:</HEAD>
<L>"CErtis me semyth it were ffolye</L>
<L>To kom&euml; there, or go fforby,</L>
<L>But &yogh;eue I knew&euml; (in sentence)</L>
<L N="18544">What doctryne or what science,</L>
<L>To hir scolers sche dothe teche.</L>
<L>Thereffore, opunly in thy speche,</L>
<L>Declar&euml; what it schuld&euml; be,</L>
<L N="18548">Or ellys I wole not go with the."</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>&para; The Messangere:</HEAD>
<L><SUP>4</SUP>'A yer&euml;,' quod he, 'and no mo,</L>
<L>ther I had to scol&euml; go;<SUP>4</SUP><NOTE PLACE="marg">[4_4 St., <I>om</I>. Tib.]</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>COuetys&euml;, off entente,<MILESTONE UNIT="Tib folio" N="43b"></L>
<L N="18552">To that scol&euml; sche me sente;</L>
<L>And sothely, as it semyth me,</L>
<L>So I trowe sche dyd&euml; the.'</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>&para; The Pylgryme:</HEAD>
<L>"CErteynely that is not so;</L>
<L N="18556">Though sche and I (both&euml; two)
<PB REF="00000604.tif" N="496"></L>
<L>"Hadde I-ffere longe dalyaunce,</L>
<L>Sche made no<NOTE PLACE="marg">[no St., me no Tib.]</NOTE> maner off r&eacute;membraunce</L>
<L>Off this scole, in no degre,</L>
<L N="18560">Off whiche thow spekist off<NOTE PLACE="marg">[off, <I>om</I>. St.]</NOTE> to me."</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>&para; The messangere:</HEAD>
<L>'THan I dar seyn (as thow schalt ffynde)</L>
<L>That it was, out off hyre mynde;</L>
<L>ffor at this scole ther comyth no wyght</L>
<L N="18564">ffor to leern&euml;, day nor nyght,</L>
<L>But &yogh;eue that he, ffirste, (off entent,)</L>
<L>Be ffro covetyse I-sent.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>'&YOGH;it off this scole, (&yogh;eue thow wylte dwelle,)</L>
<L N="18568">The maner, I schal the telle:</L>
<L>&para; ffirste, whanne I was heder sent,</L>
<L>I wolde, by som experiment,</L>
<L>Or by som schorte conclusyoun,</L>
<L N="18572">Haue preued<NOTE PLACE="marg">[provyd St.]</NOTE> out my lessoun;</L>
<L>ffor speculatyff and the practyk</L>
<L>Off this scol&euml; be not lyk;</L>
<L>ffor specul&aacute;tyff (in sentence)</L>
<L N="18576">With-outen good experience,</L>
<L>Avaylith lytle or ellis nought,</L>
<L>How longe euere that it be sought.</L>
<L>&para; Now take heede, and thow schalt se</L>
<L N="18580">I wolde hau&euml;<NOTE PLACE="marg">[haue a St.]</NOTE> dygnyte,</L>
<L>Or som other greet tresour,<MILESTONE UNIT="Tib folio" N="44a"></L>
<L>And ther-on sett&euml; my labour;</L>
<L>And wold&euml; knowe, to<NOTE PLACE="marg">[to to Tib., to St.]</NOTE> this estat<MILESTONE UNIT="Stowe folio" N="317b"></L>
<L N="18584">Wher I schal be ffortunat.</L>
<L>&para; ffirste, with my swerd, vp-on the ground</L>
<L>I make a cercle large and round,</L>
<L>With karectis and with<NOTE PLACE="marg">[with <I>om</I>. Tib., St.]</NOTE> ffygures,</L>
<L N="18588">And know&euml; not the &aacute;ventures,</L>
<L>Nor the dirkenesse hydde with-Inne,</L>
<L>Off the karectis, whanne I gynne</L>
<L>To emprynte: al<NOTE PLACE="marg">[tyll St.]</NOTE> they be sene,</L>
<L N="18592">I wot&euml; neuere what they mene;<NOTE PLACE="inter">[Illustration.]</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>SAue I conyecte yt may so be,</L>
<L>That spiritis scholde obeye to<NOTE PLACE="marg">[obey St.]</NOTE> me,
<PB REF="00000605.tif" N="497"></L>
<L>'By my<NOTE PLACE="marg">[myne St.]</NOTE> invocacyouns</L>
<L N="18596">To answere to my questyouns,</L>
<L>Swyche sperytis as I kalle;</L>
<L>And &yogh;it I knowe noon off hem alle,</L>
<L>Saue off entente, as thow mayste se,</L>
<L N="18600">That they schuld&euml; graunt&euml; me</L>
<L>Som maner gyffte, or som gerdoun,</L>
<L>Concernynge myn oppynyoun,</L>
<L>By vertu off the cercle round,</L>
<L N="18604">And Carectis graven in the ground,</L>
<L>By schewynge or by &aacute;pparence,<MILESTONE UNIT="Tib folio" N="44b"></L>
<L>Affter that I &yogh;eue credence.'</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>&para; The pylgryme:</HEAD>
<L>"Alle that thow doste specyffye,</L>
<L N="18608">Is but ffalsehed and ffantesye</L>
<L>And cursyd ymagynacyoun,</L>
<L>Brouth<NOTE PLACE="marg">[brought St.]</NOTE> in ffirste by Illus&iuml;oun.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>"This scole is nought, in sotheffastenesse,</L>
<L N="18612">Whos doctryne is but cursydnesse.</L>
<L>The scolers there-off, I holde hem wood;</L>
<L>Swyche spiritis may don to the no good;</L>
<L>And &yogh;eue thow koudeste the trouthe entende,</L>
<L N="18616">Harme they may, but not amende:</L>
<L>They wole wyrke in<NOTE PLACE="marg">[to St.]</NOTE> thi dam&aacute;ge,</L>
<L>But no thyng to thyne &aacute;vauntage,</L>
<L>Who that kan lok&euml; wel aboute.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="18620">"Also thi siluen<NOTE PLACE="marg">[my selffe St.]</NOTE> stante in doute</L>
<L>Where-off thi cercle schold&euml; serue;</L>
<L>And thyng&euml;s that thow doste obserue,</L>
<L>Alle is but ffoly and mysbyleve,<NOTE PLACE="marg">[fals beleve St.]</NOTE></L>
<L N="18624">Towchynge the spiritis, thow mayste wel leve;</L>
<L>ffor the they wyl no thynge do wel,</L>
<L>ffor they the louen neuere a del."</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>&para; The Messangere:</HEAD>
<L>'IDar afferme (with-out&euml;<NOTE PLACE="marg">[with-out C., St.]</NOTE> slouthe)</L>
<L N="18628">In party that thow haste seyde trouthe,</L>
<L>Excepte oonly (it is no nay)</L>
<L>In many thynges they help&euml; may,</L>
<L>A man<NOTE PLACE="marg">[man St., C. <I>blurd</I>]</NOTE> greetly to magnyffye,</L>
<L N="18632">Encresse also, and multeplye,<MILESTONE UNIT="Stowe folio" N="318a">
<PB REF="00000606.tif" N="498"></L>
<L>Whanne they be c&oacute;nstreyned to do so,</L>
<L>And haue no power to go ther-ffro,</L>
<L>Comaunded<NOTE PLACE="marg">[commaundyd St., comaunde Tib.]</NOTE> to swyche &oacute;bseruaunce</L>
<L N="18636">By hym<NOTE PLACE="marg">[them St.]</NOTE> that hathe the gouernaunce<MILESTONE UNIT="Tib folio" N="45a"></L>
<L>I mene the kyng, to whom, eche weye,</L>
<L>Mawgre ther myght, they muste obeye.'</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>&para; The Pylgryme:</HEAD>
<L>"IConceyue, and se wel here,</L>
<L N="18640">Thow art the kyng&euml;s messangere,</L>
<L>By the armes that thow dost were,</L>
<L>And by the sygnes I se the bere;</L>
<L>But mak&euml;<NOTE PLACE="marg">[make a St.]</NOTE> demonstracyoun</L>
<L N="18644">To me off thi comyssyoun,</L>
<L>By what power or by what peyne</L>
<L>Th&aacute;t thow mayste<NOTE PLACE="marg">[mayst St., muste Tib.]</NOTE> hem so constreyne."</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>&para; The Messangere:</HEAD>
<L>'COmmyssyoun I haue neuere on;</L>
<L N="18648">And trewely I dar ax&euml; non;</L>
<L>And though I dyde (as thow schalt se)</L>
<L>He wold&euml; graunt&euml; noon to me.'</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>&para; The Pylgryme:</HEAD>
<L>"THanne wote I wel, (&yogh;eue it be sought,)</L>
<L N="18652">ffor the, that they wole do ryght nought."</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>&para; The Messangere:</HEAD>
<L>'HEre vp-on, what so &yogh;e seye,</L>
<L>Wot&euml;<NOTE PLACE="marg">[I wott . . .that they will St.]</NOTE> wel they wole<NOTE PLACE="marg">[I wott . . .that they will St.]</NOTE> obeye</L>
<L>Pleynely vnto my byddynge;</L>
<L N="18656">ffor they wene that, off the kynge</L>
<L>I hadd&euml; fful auctorite,</L>
<L>Commyssyoun and fful pouste,</L>
<L>To maken them, lyche<NOTE PLACE="marg">[lyke St.]</NOTE> myn entent,<MILESTONE UNIT="Tib folio" N="45b"></L>
<L N="18660">To &oacute;beye<NOTE PLACE="marg">[<I>or</I> t'obey&euml;]</NOTE> my comaund&euml;ment</L>
<L>By vertu off myn orysoun,<NOTE PLACE="marg">[orisons . . .commyssions St.]</NOTE></L>
<L>Karectys and coniurysoun<NOTE PLACE="marg">[orisons . . .commyssions St.]</NOTE>;</L>
<L>ffor drede off whiche, (be wel certeyn,)</L>
<L N="18664">I knowe they dar me not with-seyn.'</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>&para; The Pilgryme:</HEAD>
<L>"WHer thow be wel or yuel apayd,</L>
<L>Take good heed what thow haste sayd:</L>
<L>Thow haste ben ffalse in thi workyng,
<PB REF="00000607.tif" N="499"></L>
<L N="18668">"And wrongely don vn-to thi kyng;</L>
<L>Wher-ffore thow shalt I-ponysshed<NOTE PLACE="marg">[punishid St.]</NOTE> be</L>
<L>ffor thi greet Inequyte,<NOTE PLACE="marg">[iniquite St.]</NOTE></L>
<L>To make spiritys the to obeye,<NOTE PLACE="marg">[tobbaye St.]</NOTE></L>
<L N="18672">And swych&euml; charges on hem leye</L>
<L>By disseyte and ffalse tresoun,</L>
<L>And, haste<NOTE PLACE="marg">[hast St.]</NOTE> no commyss&iuml;oun</L>
<L>ffor the to schewe on see nor lond,</L>
<L N="18676">And haste<NOTE PLACE="marg">[hast St.]</NOTE> I-made eke, with thyn hand,</L>
<L>Karectis and cercle round,</L>
<L>And compassid it vp-on the ground;</L>
<L>And art so blynd, thow kanste not seen,<MILESTONE UNIT="Stowe folio" N="318b"></L>
<L N="18680">On no party, what they mene.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>"And swyche karectis (I dar wel telle)</L>
<L>Be markis off the deuel off helle,</L>
<L>ffirste ordeyned (who kan conceyue)</L>
<L N="18684">Innocentis to disceyue.</L>
<L>And thow mayste also (trust&euml; me)</L>
<L>There-with thow schalt dysseyued be;</L>
<L>ffor this selis, thow schalt ffynde,</L>
<L N="18688">Constreyn&euml; the, and sor&euml; bynde</L>
<L>By a maner &aacute;llyaunce</L>
<L>To do the deuel swyche &oacute;bseruaunce</L>
<L>Made to thi conffus&iuml;oun,</L>
<L N="18692">As bonde or oblygacyoun;</L>
<L>By whiche he wole (off verrey myght)</L>
<L>Cleym&euml; the his man off ryght;</L>
<L>By swyche a tytle, make hym stronge.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="18696">"And to spiritis thow doste greet wronge,</L>
<L>Hem to constreyne in thi workynge</L>
<L>To brynge th&eacute; other menn&euml;s thynge,</L>
<L>(Be it by day, be it by nyght,)</L>
<L N="18700">Vn-to whiche thow haste no ryght;</L>
<L>Where-in thow art greetly<NOTE PLACE="marg">[gretly St., greet Tib.]</NOTE> to blame,</L>
<L>To bydde hem in the kyng&euml;s name</L>
<L>Or constreyne hem, ageyne resoun,</L>
<L N="18704">By karecte or by<NOTE PLACE="marg">[by, <I>om</I>. St.]</NOTE> comyssyoun,</L>
<L>To robbe or steele, to thi ffavour,</L>
<L>Off other ffolk&euml;s<NOTE PLACE="marg">[ffolkis St., ffolke Tib.]</NOTE> ther tresour,</L>
<L>By verrey fforce, ageyn&euml;<NOTE PLACE="marg">[agaynst St.]</NOTE> ryght.
<PB REF="00000608.tif" N="500"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>"And &yogh;eue thow loke about&euml;<NOTE PLACE="marg">[about Tib., St.]</NOTE> ryght,</L>
<L N="18709">To the kyng, vsynge this vice,</L>
<L>Thow doste fful greet preivdice<NOTE PLACE="marg">[preiudice St.]</NOTE></L>
<L>Ageyne his lawefful ordynaunce,</L>
<L N="18712">Where it is boden<NOTE PLACE="marg">[bodyn St.]</NOTE> (in substaunce)</L>
<L>And dyffendid, (who kan espye,)</L>
<L>Alle maner theffte and robrye,<NOTE PLACE="marg">[robery St.]</NOTE></L>
<L>In peyne off deth: take heede her-to,</L>
<L N="18716">And with-drawe thyne hand ther-ffro</L>
<L>With al thi myght and al thy peyne.</L>
<L>Thow standeste<NOTE PLACE="marg">[stanst St.]</NOTE> in daunger atwene tweyne;</L>
<L>Outher off God or off Sathan</L>
<L N="18720">Thow art off the leeg&euml; man;</L>
<L>And therffore, ffor to lyue in reste,</L>
<L>Leeue the worste, and cheese the beste;</L>
<L>ffor (schortly I schal devyse,)</L>
<L N="18724">Thow schalt be quytte lyke thi servyse,</L>
<L>In hell&euml; with dampnacyoun,</L>
<L>Or heuene, to thi savac&iuml;oun."<NOTE PLACE="marg">[C. &amp; St.]</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>&para; The Messangere:<MILESTONE UNIT="Tib folio" N="46b"></HEAD>
<L>'OF thy word&euml;s I<NOTE PLACE="marg">[words when I St.]</NOTE> take hede,</L>
<L N="18728">They putt&euml; me<NOTE PLACE="marg">[me St., me not Tib.]</NOTE> in fful greet drede:</L>
<L>But, o thyng comfforteth me,</L>
<L>Whanne that I considere and se</L>
<L>There is so greet a companye,<MILESTONE UNIT="Stowe folio" N="319a"></L>
<L N="18732">Me to susteyne in my ffolye,</L>
<L>Off ffolkis that to-fforne haue be</L>
<L>Off wonder greet autoryte,</L>
<L>As whylom was kyng Salamoun,</L>
<L N="18736">And <B>Virgyle,</B> off greet renoun,</L>
<L><B>Cypryan</B> and <B>Albalart,</B></L>
<L>And many an-other in this art,<NOTE PLACE="marg">[Tib. &amp; C.]</NOTE></L>
<L>Maystres by experyence,</L>
<L N="18740">And hadde also ther-to lycence</L>
<L>(With-outen<NOTE PLACE="marg">[outen St., out Tib.]</NOTE> eny noyse or stryffe,)</L>
<L>ffor to vse it al her lyffe.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>'And this ilk&euml; craffte also</L>
<L N="18744">(Who that takyth heed ther-to,)</L>
<L>Is not in rewarde so perillous,</L>
<L>Dredefful, nor superstyc&iuml;ous,
<PB REF="00000609.tif" N="501"></L>
<L>'As som crafftis that haue be do</L>
<L N="18748">With sacriffyce, and eke also</L>
<L>With &oacute;bseru&aacute;unces, vpon mownteynes,</L>
<L>In des&eacute;rte,<NOTE PLACE="marg">[decrert St.]</NOTE> and eke in pleynes,</L>
<L>And in placis fful<NOTE PLACE="marg">[full of St.]</NOTE> savage,</L>
<L N="18752">Solytarye, and fful off rage,</L>
<L>That, alle the maner ffor to noumbre,</L>
<L>It wolde a man greetly encombre,</L>
<L>As thow schalt se and knowe anon</L>
<L N="18756">&YOGH;eue thow lyste with me to gon;</L>
<L>And ffynally, thi pas to dresse<NOTE PLACE="marg">[Tib. &amp; St.]</NOTE></L>
<L>To hir that is the cheff maystresse<NOTE PLACE="marg">[Tib. &amp; St.]</NOTE></L>
<L>Off alle this thyng that I haue tolde,</L>
<L N="18760">That, &yogh;eue thow be hardy and bolde<NOTE PLACE="marg">[Tib. &amp; St.]</NOTE><MILESTONE UNIT="Tib folio" N="47a"></L>
<L>ffor to proche<NOTE PLACE="marg">[taproche St.]</NOTE> to hir presence,</L>
<L>Thow schalt haue fful experyence.'</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>&para; The Pylgryme:</HEAD>
<L>"THat euere I schuld&euml; this thyng se,<NOTE PLACE="marg">[shuld . . yse St.]</NOTE></L>
<L N="18764">God, off his grace, dyffend&euml; me;</L>
<L>And he be my proteccyoun</L>
<L>Fro<NOTE PLACE="marg">[fro St.,? Tib.]</NOTE> thylk&euml; habytacyoun!</L>
<L>ffor, by opene evidence,</L>
<L N="18768">And by recorde off thi sentence,</L>
<L>Thilk&euml; place, with-out&euml;<NOTE PLACE="marg">[with out Tib., St.]</NOTE> wene,</L>
<L>To good<NOTE PLACE="marg">[god St.]</NOTE> it doth no-thyng partene;</L>
<L>ffor, by the crowe that sytte aloffte,</L>
<L N="18772">Makyth noyse and cryeth offte,</L>
<L>It schewith wel how thylk&euml; place</L>
<L>Is devoyde, and ffer ffro grace,</L>
<L>And longeth (as I rehers&euml; kan)</L>
<L N="18776">To the Deuel and to Sathan;</L>
<L>ffor, save the Deuel, noon other wyght</L>
<L>Hathe power there, off verray ryght.</L>
<L>Therffore I wole me holden heere,</L>
<L N="18780">And to that plac&euml; kome noon nere;</L>
<L>And trew&euml;ly, (to my devys,)</L>
<L>Thi-silff also (&yogh;eue thow be wys,)</L>
<L>Thow schalt wysely with-draw&euml; the,<MILESTONE UNIT="Stowe folio" N="319b"></L>
<L N="18784">And abyd&euml;<NOTE PLACE="marg">[abyden St.]</NOTE> here with me</L>
<L>ffor thyne own&euml; &aacute;vauntage,
<PB REF="00000610.tif" N="502"></L>
<L>"Leste it turne to thi damage;</L>
<L>ffor, who gothe to that mancyoun,</L>
<L N="18788">Gothe streytte to his destruccyoun,</L>
<L>As ther haue do fful many oon,</L>
<L>Whiche here-to-fforne haue theder gon,</L>
<L N="18791">Resemblynge (as I kan devyse)</L>
<L>To hym that was the Duke of<NOTE PLACE="marg">[of St., <I>om</I>. Tib.]</NOTE> Fryse,</L>
<L>Whiche, whanne he shuld ha be baptisyd,<MILESTONE UNIT="Tib folio" N="47b"><NOTE PLACE="marg">[Tib. &amp; St.]</NOTE></L>
<L>(In storye as it ys devysed,</L>
<L>And as bok&euml;s kan wel telle,)</L>
<L N="18796">His o ffoot was putte in the welle,</L>
<L>To haue receyved cristis lawe,</L>
<L>But he in haste gan it with-drawe;<NOTE PLACE="inter">[Illustration.]</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>FOr hym thought he herde a cry,</L>
<L N="18800">That affermed certeynely,</L>
<L>ffor synne and ffor Inyquyte,</L>
<L>How mo ffolke schuld&euml; dampned be</L>
<L>At the day off Iug&euml;ment,</L>
<L N="18804">Gon to helle, there to be brent,</L>
<L>&YOGH;e mo (as in comparisoun)</L>
<L>Thanne ffolk ffor ther savacyoun</L>
<L>Scholde that day receyued be,</L>
<L N="18808">To dwelle in heuene, that ffayre cyte.</L>
<L>&para; But this duke, hym-silff to encombre,<NOTE PLACE="marg">[tencomber St.]</NOTE></L>
<L>Seyde<NOTE PLACE="marg">[Seyd St.]</NOTE> with the gretteste nowmbre,</L>
<L>And wold&euml; go,<NOTE PLACE="marg">[he would go St.]</NOTE> thorough his ffolye,</L>
<L N="18812">And with hem hold&euml;<NOTE PLACE="marg">[kepe St.]</NOTE> companye,</L>
<L>There-with affermynge, in his thought,</L>
<L>That, off baptysme, he sette<NOTE PLACE="marg">[sett St.]</NOTE> nought.</L>
<L>ffor whiche, me semeth it were ffolye,</L>
<L N="18816">The to halden companye</L>
<L>With swyche ffolke in thyn entent,<MILESTONE UNIT="Tib folio" N="48a"><NOTE PLACE="marg">[Tib. &amp; St.]</NOTE></L>
<L>Off whiche affter thow schalt repente.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>"ffor I suppose that <B>Salamoun</B></L>
<L N="18820">(Off whom thow madest mencyoun)</L>
<L>Wher in-ffectte, or hadde his parte,</L>
<L>In his day&euml;s, off swyche arte,</L>
<L>As som ffolk seyne, (who kan entende,)</L>
<L N="18824">That hym-silffe he dyde amende
<PB REF="00000611.tif" N="503"></L>
<L>"Off that and many another thyng,</L>
<L>To-ffore the hour off his deiyng,</L>
<L>And resceyued was to grace,</L>
<L N="18828">And hath in heuene a dwellynge place.</L>
<L>&para; And semblabely, the tother man,</L>
<L>The gret&euml; clerke callyd <B>Cypryan</B>,</L>
<L>To-fforne his deth, lyste to fforsake</L>
<L N="18832">This craffte, and ffor Crystis sake,</L>
<L>Suffred (as made is mencyoun)<MILESTONE UNIT="Stowe folio" N="320b"></L>
<L>Martirdam and passyoun,</L>
<L>And is in heuene stelleffyed,</L>
<L N="18836">And with seyntis gloreffyed.</L>
<L>&para; Take heede to hem, by reed off me,</L>
<L>And not to hem that dampned be.</L>
<L N="18839">Thenke on hem that ben in blysse;</L>
<L>And where as<NOTE PLACE="marg">[what that St.]</NOTE> thow haste don amysse,</L>
<L>With-drawe thy ffoot, and do penaunce,</L>
<L>And haue in hert&euml; r&eacute;pentaunce."</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>&para; The Messangere:</HEAD>
<L>'CErtys,' quod he ('&yogh;eue thow lyste se,)</L>
<L N="18844">That thow seyste, ne may not be.</L>
<L>Though thyne argumente be stronge,</L>
<L>At that scole I haue ben longe,</L>
<L>And fful wel lern&euml;d my lessoun;</L>
<L N="18848">And by sodeyne departysoun,</L>
<L>(Who takyth heede, it is no nay,)</L>
<L>So sone I may not part away,<MILESTONE UNIT="Tib folio" N="48b"><NOTE PLACE="marg">[Tib. &amp; St.]</NOTE></L>
<L>As<NOTE PLACE="marg">[And St.]</NOTE> I kan not (in myne entente)</L>
<L N="18852">ffynde in myne hert&euml; to repente,</L>
<L>Nor to departe vp-on no syde;</L>
<L>I am with-hoolde; I muste abyde,</L>
<L>With other scolers mo than oon,</L>
<L N="18856">Whiche that there to scol&euml; goon,</L>
<L>As ffolke may sen ther, gret ffoysoun.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>'And eke my skrippe and my bordoun</L>
<L>Ben I-leffte in that hostage,</L>
<L N="18860">And lyne in maner off morgage;<NOTE PLACE="marg">[Tib. &amp; St.]</NOTE></L>
<L>And I ne may not hem<NOTE PLACE="marg">[them nat St.]</NOTE> recure;</L>
<L>And also (as<NOTE PLACE="marg">[eke St.]</NOTE> I the ensure)</L>
<L>I gyue no forc&euml;,<NOTE PLACE="marg">[fors St.]</NOTE> in certeyn,
<PB REF="00000612.tif" N="504"></L>
<L N="18864">'Though I neuere hem haue ageyn.'</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>&para; The Pylgryme:</HEAD>
<L>ANd whanne that I these word&euml;s herde,</L>
<L>In maner<NOTE PLACE="marg">[St., Tib. <I>blurd</I>]</NOTE> trew&euml;ly I fferde</L>
<L>As though I hadde astonyed be;</L>
<L N="18868">And, as it semed vn-to me,</L>
<L>I stood in a per&eacute;lous<NOTE PLACE="marg">[perillous St.]</NOTE> cas.</L>
<L>And therffore I abasched was,</L>
<L>And sawe no bette reffute to me,</L>
<L N="18872">But ffro that plac&euml; ffor to ffle;</L>
<L>ffor he (schortely, in sentence)</L>
<L>To whome I neuere dyde offence,</L>
<L>Me to bryngen in-to<NOTE PLACE="marg">[in St.]</NOTE> distresse,</L>
<L N="18876">Gan to callen his maystresse</L>
<L>To kome vpon<NOTE PLACE="marg">[vpon St., on Tib.]</NOTE> me in greet rape,</L>
<L>That I schulde hir not escape.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>And sche, off ffalse entencyoun,</L>
<L N="18880">Kam out off hir p&aacute;villoun<NOTE PLACE="marg">[pavylyon St.]</NOTE></L>
<L>Affter me, that I wente abak,</L>
<L>Hydous off look, oolde and blak,</L>
<L N="18883">Off whom I greetly<NOTE PLACE="marg">[gretly I St.]</NOTE> was afferd.<MILESTONE UNIT="Tib folio" N="49a"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>In the<NOTE PLACE="marg">[In the, <I>om</I>. St.]</NOTE> mydde off a book, sche heelde a swerd;</L>
<L>Other scawberk hadde sche noon;</L>
<L>And, as I byhelde anoon,</L>
<L>Sche hadde (in sothe, as thought&euml;<NOTE PLACE="marg">[thought Tib., St.]</NOTE> me)<MILESTONE UNIT="Stowe folio" N="320b"></L>
<L N="18888">Larg&euml; whyng&euml;s ffor to ffle.</L>
<L>&para; And, by a maner ffelonye,</L>
<L>Sche gan loud&euml; ffor to crye;</L>
<L>And, me manasynge off pryde,</L>
<L N="18892">Bad me that I schulde abyde;</L>
<L>And ellis, mawgrey al my myght,</L>
<L>I schulde not skape out off hir<NOTE PLACE="marg">[his St.]</NOTE> syght</L>
<L>Til I hadd&euml; in partye</L>
<L N="18896">Somwhat seyne off hir maystrye.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>And towarde me hir look sche caste,</L>
<L>And gan to come vp-on fful ffaste;</L>
<L>But as sche kam, it sempt&euml; me,</L>
<L N="18900">That sche sate hygh vp-on a tre,</L>
<L>And pleynely gan to speceffye,</L>
<L>Hir nam&euml; was 'Nygr&oacute;mauncye,'
<PB REF="00000613.tif" N="505"><NOTE PLACE="inter">[Illustration.]</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>WHiche, by my craffte<NOTE PLACE="marg">[be craft St.]</NOTE> (in substaunce)</L>
<L N="18904">Kan ffolke encresse, and wel avaunce,</L>
<L>That ben in my subieccyoun</L>
<L>And lyste to leern&euml; my lessoun.</L>
<L><SUP>2</SUP>This ilk&euml; book that thou<NOTE PLACE="marg">[that thou <I>om</I>. Tib.]</NOTE> wolte se,<MILESTONE UNIT="Tib folio" N="49b"></L>
<L N="18908">Is I-callyd <B>Mors Anime,</B></L>
<L>Whiche is in englysche (ffor to seyn,)</L>
<L>'Dethe off the sowl&euml;,' in certeyn.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>And this nakyd swerd whiche I hoolde,</L>
<L N="18912">(As thow mayste thi silffe byholde,)</L>
<L>There-with (ffor schorte conclusyoun,)</L>
<L>Whanne thow haste herd&euml; my lessoun,<SUP>2</SUP><NOTE PLACE="foot">2_2 <I>om</I>. St. The good old tailor's eye caught the second 'lesson,' l. 18914, in his MS. instead of the first, l. 18906.</NOTE></L>
<L>There-with thow schalt yslayn&euml;<NOTE PLACE="marg">[yslayn St., slayne Tib.]</NOTE> be.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="18916">And thus sche gan manass&euml; me,</L>
<L>Where-off I stood in fful greet drede;</L>
<L>But off grace, (as I toke hede)</L>
<L>A whit&euml; dowu&euml; I dyde se</L>
<L N="18920">ffleen sodeynely toward&euml;s me;</L>
<L>But with me, where as I stood,</L>
<L>Sche ne made no lenger<NOTE PLACE="marg">[longe St.]</NOTE> abood.</L>
<L>And I ne made no greet delay,</L>
<L N="18924">But went&euml; fforthe vp-on my way;</L>
<L>And I mette (or I was war)</L>
<L>An oolde oon, whiche that<NOTE PLACE="marg">[a St.]</NOTE> ffagot bar</L>
<L>Vpon hir bak, and eke therto,</L>
<L N="18928">In hir hand sche heelde also</L>
<L>A peyr&euml; cysours scharpe I-grownde.</L>
<L>And, to me-ward as sche was bounde,</L>
<L>Sche bad (ffor schorte conclusyoun)</L>
<L N="18932">ffor to leye my skryppe adoun;</L>
<L>And gan vp-on me ffor to ffrowne,</L>
<L>Lowd&euml; cryed, hir lyste not rowne:</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>&para; Heresye:</HEAD>
<L>'FOr but thow ley&euml; here adoun,</L>
<L N="18936">I schal, to thi conffusyoun,</L>
<L>Schape thi skryppe off newe array,</L>
<L>ffor it is not to my pay;
<PB REF="00000614.tif" N="506"></L>
<L>'I schal it kutte in other wyse,</L>
<L N="18940">Lyche as my-syluen lyste devyse.'<NOTE PLACE="inter">[Illustration.]</NOTE><MILESTONE UNIT="Tib folio" N="50a"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>&para; The Pylgryme:</HEAD>
<L>"THow oold&euml; vekke, as semeth me,</L>
<L>That thow mayste not clerely se;</L>
<L>Wherffore me lyste, by thi byddynge,</L>
<L N="18944">ffor to do no maner thyng,</L>
<L>But &yogh;eue to-fforne I knowe and se<MILESTONE UNIT="Stowe folio" N="321a"></L>
<L>Thy powere and thyn autorite;</L>
<L>Thy worke also, and thyne office,</L>
<L N="18948">I wole ffirste knowe in myn avyce."<NOTE PLACE="inter">[Illustration.]</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>Heresie:<NOTE PLACE="marg">[St., <I>om</I>. Tib.]</NOTE></HEAD>
<L>'FOr pleyn&euml;ly, off lasse and more,</L>
<L>Evene afftir my ffadris lore,</L>
<L>I wole (off both&euml;<NOTE PLACE="marg">[bothe of St.]</NOTE> ffalse and trewe,)</L>
<L N="18952">The skripp&euml;s kutte and schap&euml; newe,</L>
<L>Off pylgrym&euml;s greet and smale,</L>
<L>Kutte hem alle on pecys smale;<MILESTONE UNIT="Tib folio" N="50b"></L>
<L>ffor it was I, my-silffe allon,</L>
<L N="18956">That schope the skrypp&euml;s &yogh;ore agon;</L>
<L>ffirste, off this Pellagyens,</L>
<L>And also off these Arryens,</L>
<L>And off other sectys newe,</L>
<L N="18960">ffound&euml; ffals&euml;, and<NOTE PLACE="marg">[and full St.]</NOTE> vntrewe,</L>
<L>As oold&euml; bok&euml;s speciffye;</L>
<L>ffor I am callyd 'Heresye,'</L>
<L>The whiche do alwey<NOTE PLACE="marg">[all ways St., awey Tib.]</NOTE> my labour</L>
<L N="18964">To bryng&euml; ffolke in greet errour,</L>
<L>That ffolwe<NOTE PLACE="marg">[folow St., ffolke Tib.]</NOTE> my condissiouns;</L>
<L>Only by ffalse oppynyouns,</L>
<L>Make her hertis to declyne</L>
<L N="18968">ffro the trouthe off Iuste doctryne,</L>
<L>And cause hem ffor to don ther cure,</L>
<L>And amys to<NOTE PLACE="marg">[Amys St.]</NOTE> expowne hooly scripture.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>'And, trew&euml;ly, nadd&euml; bene</L>
<L N="18972">The greet&euml;<NOTE PLACE="marg">[greet Tib., gret St.]</NOTE> counceyle at Nycene,</L>
<L>Ordeyned by greet Constantyn,</L>
<L>And nadde ben also Augustyn
<PB REF="00000615.tif" N="507"></L>
<L>'And many other greet doctours</L>
<L N="18976">ffor to anull&euml;<NOTE PLACE="marg">[tanull St.]</NOTE> myn errours,</L>
<L>The skryppes off holy churche echon,</L>
<L>I hadde ffor-don (fful &yogh;ore agoon,)</L>
<L>Off pylgrymes that passe by the way,</L>
<L N="18980">Sythen goon fful many a day.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>'And &yogh;it I schal, what so byffalle,</L>
<L>Assayl&euml; th&eacute; amonge hem alle,</L>
<L N="18983">And myn oold&euml; purpos holde,</L>
<L>In ffyre, though that<NOTE PLACE="marg">[that <I>om</I>. St.]</NOTE> I brenn&euml; schulde,</L>
<L>I wole my wytt&euml;s alle applye,</L>
<L>Hardyd with obst&yacute;nacye,</L>
<L>Contynue til the ffyre be hoot;</L>
<L N="18988">Therffore I ber&euml; this ffagot.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>'And ffirste, thow schalt me not escape,</L>
<L>But newe I wole thy skrypp&euml;s schape,<MILESTONE UNIT="Tib folio" N="51a"></L>
<L>Or ellis I dar vndirtake</L>
<L N="18992">Th&aacute;t thow schalt it here fforsake,</L>
<L>And leve it with me vtterly<NOTE PLACE="marg">[entterly St.]</NOTE>:</L>
<L>My ffader is here ffast&euml; by,<MILESTONE UNIT="Stowe folio" N="321b"></L>
<L>Whiche hathe power (as thow mayste se)</L>
<L N="18996">And<NOTE PLACE="marg">[ye St.]</NOTE> both&euml; vp-on londe and see,</L>
<L>Thow schalt not skape hym (in certeyne,)</L>
<L>But with daunger and greet peyne.'</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>&para; The Pylgryme:</HEAD>
<L>Myne eyen tho<NOTE PLACE="marg">[then St.]</NOTE> I gan vnffolde,</L>
<L N="19000">And anoon I gan byholde</L>
<L>In the wey&euml; me byfforne,</L>
<L>An hunt&euml; stood&euml;<NOTE PLACE="marg">[stood Tib., stode St.]</NOTE> with his horne,</L>
<L>Off chere and look&euml;<NOTE PLACE="marg">[look Tib., loke St.]</NOTE> ryght pervers.</L>
<L N="19004">And the passage, in travers,</L>
<L>With cordes he gan it ouere-leyne,</L>
<L>ffrette with nettys alle the pleyne.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>And he brought in his companye</L>
<L N="19008">The ffals&euml; vekk&euml; Heresye.</L>
<L>And, that men schulde hym wel knowe,</L>
<L>His horne he gan fful lowd&euml; blowe;</L>
<L>As it were to catche his pray,</L>
<L N="19012">Ryght so he blew&euml; on<NOTE PLACE="marg">[blew vp on St.]</NOTE> the way,<NOTE PLACE="inter">[Illustration.]</NOTE>
<PB REF="00000616.tif" N="508"></L>
<L>Bad<NOTE PLACE="marg">[bad St., And Tib.]</NOTE> his doughter Heresye,</L>
<L>The passage so to<NOTE PLACE="marg">[so to St., to Tib.]</NOTE> kepe and guye,</L>
<L>That I scholde not, in no syde,<MILESTONE UNIT="Tib folio" N="51b"></L>
<L N="19016">ffrom ther damage my sylffe provyde.</L>
<L>And trew&euml;ly (as I haue sayd)</L>
<L>The nettys were so narewe layd,</L>
<L>On<NOTE PLACE="marg">[on St., In Tib.]</NOTE> lond, on water, and in the hayr,</L>
<L N="19020">That I myght haue no repayr</L>
<L>To pass&euml; ffreely that pass&aacute;ge.</L>
<L>It was so fful off mortal rage,</L>
<L>Off daunger and adversite,</L>
<L>That, but yiff<NOTE PLACE="marg">[yiff that Tib., yf St.]</NOTE> I amydde the see</L>
<L N="19025">Durst&euml; swymme, ther was no way</L>
<L>ffor me to pass&euml;, nyght nor day.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>And there he dyde also malygne</L>
<L N="19028">To leyne out nettys, and assigne,</L>
<L>There to stoppen my pass&aacute;ge;</L>
<L>So that I ffonde noon &aacute;vauntage,</L>
<L>ffrom his dawngere to declyne;</L>
<L N="19032">ffor many an hook and many a lyne</L>
<L>Were caste in-to<NOTE PLACE="marg">[in St.]</NOTE> that peryllous se,</L>
<L>Off entente to letten me;<NOTE PLACE="inter">[Illustration.]</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>THat, mawgre alle my fforce and myght,</L>
<L N="19036">But &yogh;eue I kowd&euml; swymme aryght</L>
<L>Amonge the wawys ffeerse and ffelle,<MILESTONE UNIT="Tib folio" N="52a"></L>
<L>I muste vndir his dawnger dwelle.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>But ffirste, while he his trappys leyde,<NOTE PLACE="marg">[C. &amp; Tib.]</NOTE></L>
<L N="19040">Vnto<NOTE PLACE="marg">[St., Tib. <I>blurd</I>]</NOTE> the hunt&euml; thus I sayde:</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>The Pylgryme:</HEAD>
<L>"Hvnt&euml;," quod I, "telle me now,</L>
<L>What maner officere arthow,<NOTE PLACE="marg">[art tou St.]</NOTE></L>
<L>Whiche [thus] lyggeste on the way,</L>
<L>Vnlaweffully<NOTE PLACE="marg">[vnlawfully St., vnlawefull Tib.]</NOTE> to cacch&euml; pray,</L>
<L N="19045">Thus to mak&euml; thyne arestis,</L>
<L>Namely on the kyng&euml;s beestis?<MILESTONE UNIT="Stowe folio" N="322a"></L>
<L>I trowe thow haueste no lycence</L>
<L N="19048">ffor to don so greet offence;</L>
<L>I dar afferme (eerly and late),</L>
<L>Swyche hunters, the kyng doth hate;
<PB REF="00000617.tif" N="509"></L>
<L>"And it semyth, by thi manere,</L>
<L N="19052">Off his, thow art noon officere."</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>&para; The hunte<NOTE PLACE="marg">[huntar St.]</NOTE>:</HEAD>
<L>QVod he, 'what makystetow swyche stryff?</L>
<L>Thow art wonder Inquysytyff,</L>
<L>Besy also, by argument,</L>
<L N="19056">To hoolde with me a parlement,</L>
<L>By lang&aacute;ge, and longe pletyng;</L>
<L>ffor, though I longe not to the kyng,</L>
<L>(And thow conceyue aryght I-wys,)</L>
<L N="19060">Som tyme I was oon off his;</L>
<L>And though I hau&euml; no cong&eacute;<NOTE PLACE="marg">[liberte St.]</NOTE></L>
<L>Off hym, to hunte in this contr&eacute;,</L>
<L>He suffryth me here, in this place,</L>
<L N="19064">At his beestis ffor to chace,</L>
<L>And assaute on hem to make.</L>
<L>And whanne that I by fforce hem take,</L>
<L>Be it by day, be it by nyght,<MILESTONE UNIT="Tib folio" N="52b"></L>
<L N="19068">I cleyme hem to ben myn off ryght.'</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>&para; The Pylgryme:</HEAD>
<L>ANd while I herde alle his resouns</L>
<L>And ffrowarde oppynyouns,</L>
<L>Myne herte abaschyd, gan to colde,</L>
<L N="19072">Namely whanne I gan byholde</L>
<L>Pylgrymes, by greet aduersite,</L>
<L>fful many oon swymme<NOTE PLACE="marg">[swymmen St.]</NOTE> in the see;</L>
<L>And they were clothyd euerychon.</L>
<L N="19076">And som off hem, I sawe anoon,</L>
<L>Ther ffeet reversed vp so doun;</L>
<L>And som (in myn inspeccyoun)</L>
<L>Swomm&euml; fforth fful euene and<NOTE PLACE="marg">[a St.]</NOTE> ryght;</L>
<L N="19080">And som hadde whyng&euml;s ffor the fflyght,</L>
<L>That afforcyd<NOTE PLACE="marg">[offeryd St.]</NOTE> hem silff fful offte</L>
<L>For to fflowe<NOTE PLACE="marg">[for taflowe St.]</NOTE> fful hygh alloffte.</L>
<L>And though ther<NOTE PLACE="marg">[the St.]</NOTE> purpos was so sette,</L>
<L N="19084">The see hath hem fful offt&euml; lette;<NOTE PLACE="inter">[Illustration.]</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>SOmme, by the ffeet were bound&euml; stronge</L>
<L>With knottys, off<NOTE PLACE="marg">[of the St.]</NOTE> herbis longe;</L>
<L>And somme, with waw&euml;s wood and rage,
<PB REF="00000618.tif" N="510"></L>
<L N="19088">Were ysmytt<NOTE PLACE="marg">[St., Tib. <I>blurd</I>]</NOTE> in ther vysage,</L>
<L>That they losten look and syght,<MILESTONE UNIT="Tib folio" N="53a"></L>
<L>And ffeble were<NOTE PLACE="marg">[wex St.]</NOTE> off fforce and myght:</L>
<L>And, by dyuerse &aacute;pparaylle,</L>
<L N="19092">The rag&euml; so gan hem assayle,</L>
<L>In many another dyuerse wyse,</L>
<L>Mo than I may as now devyse.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>The Hunte:<NOTE PLACE="marg">[huntar St.]</NOTE></HEAD>
<L>'IDo fful wel,' quod he,<NOTE PLACE="marg">[quod he full well St.]</NOTE> 'espye</L>
<L N="19096">Where-on thow castyste so thyne eye.</L>
<L>ffor alle thy wyl&euml;s and thi Iape,</L>
<L>Thow schalt not so ffro me eskape;<MILESTONE UNIT="Stowe folio" N="322b"></L>
<L>I schal the cacch&euml; by som crook;</L>
<L N="19100">I haue leyde ffor the, las and hook,</L>
<L>As thow mayste thy-syluen se:</L>
<L>Thow schalt not skapen by this see.'</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>&para; The Pylgryme:</HEAD>
<L>"TElle me anoon, and ly&euml; nought,</L>
<L N="19104">As it lythe, ryght in thy thought,</L>
<L>These pylgrymes all&euml; that I se,</L>
<L>Who hathe thus putte hem in thys<NOTE PLACE="marg">[thy St.]</NOTE> see?"</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>&para; The hunte:</HEAD>
<L>'IS not this,' quod he anoon,</L>
<L>'An hygh&euml;<NOTE PLACE="marg">[hyghe St., hygh Tib.]</NOTE> way ffor ffolke to goon</L>
<L N="19109">Therby, alle day in ther vyage,</L>
<L>Swyche as goon on pilgrymage?</L>
<L>I hadde not ellis (as I haue seyde)</L>
<L N="19112">Myne hookys and my nettys leyde,</L>
<L>To cacchen all&euml; in this place</L>
<L>ffolke that fforby here do pace;</L>
<L>ffor this greet&euml;<NOTE PLACE="marg">[greet Tib., gret St.]</NOTE> larg&euml; see<MILESTONE UNIT="Tib folio" N="53b"></L>
<L N="19116">Which&euml; that thow here doste se,'</L>
<L>It is the world, ay fful off trowble,</L>
<L>fful off many wawys dowble,</L>
<L>And fful off woo and greet torment,</L>
<L N="19120">In whiche fful many a man is schent,</L>
<L>With bellewys blowe on euery syde,</L>
<L>Which that myne own&euml; douhter, Pryde,</L>
<L>Is wont&euml;, with hir ffor to bere,</L>
<L N="19124">Good pylgrym&euml;s ffor to dere.
<PB REF="00000619.tif" N="511"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>'And many a pylgryme thow mayste se</L>
<L>Swymme in this per&eacute;lous see:</L>
<L>S&oacute;mme off hem, (whiche is not ffeyre,)</L>
<L N="19128">Ther ffeet han vpwarde in the ayre<NOTE PLACE="marg">[hayr St.]</NOTE>;</L>
<L>And all&euml; swyche (&yogh;eue thow lyste se)</L>
<L>Ben thylk&euml; ffolke that charged be</L>
<L>With the sak off couetyse,</L>
<L N="19132">And ouere-lade in many wyse,</L>
<L>That they, to swymm&euml; be not able,</L>
<L>Ther burthen is so Import&aacute;ble;</L>
<L>Whiche, by ffalse affeccyoun,</L>
<L N="19136">Ploungith her heed&euml;s low a-down</L>
<L>Vnder the wawys off this world here,</L>
<L>That they may not (in no manere)</L>
<L>Swymm&euml;, ffor the hevynesse</L>
<L N="19140">That they bere, off greet rychesse.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>OTher ther ben that swymmen ryght,</L>
<L>And haue eke wyng&euml;s ffor the fflyght;</L>
<L>And tho ben ffolkis whiche, in this lyffe,</L>
<L N="19144">In hert&euml; ben contemplatyffe,</L>
<L>In wordely thyng haue no plesaunce,</L>
<L>Save in ther bar&euml; sustenaunce:</L>
<L>In this world, ther Ioye is nought;</L>
<L N="19148">ffor alle ther herte and alle ther thought,</L>
<L>And ffynal truste off ther workynge,</L>
<L>Is sette vp-on the heuenly kynge.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>'But ffor alle that, (I the assure,<NOTE PLACE="marg">[ensure St.]</NOTE>)<MILESTONE UNIT="Stowe folio" N="323a"><MILESTONE UNIT="Tib folio" N="54a"></L>
<L N="19152">In this see they muste endure</L>
<L>Bodily, by greet penaunce,</L>
<L>In hevene hem sylff&euml;<NOTE PLACE="marg">[them selven St.]</NOTE> to avaunce.</L>
<L>And, ffor the love<NOTE PLACE="marg">[love St., lawe Tib.]</NOTE> off crist ihesu,</L>
<L N="19156">They make hem whyng&euml;s off vertu,</L>
<L>To ffleen (by clene affeccyoun)</L>
<L>To the heuenly mansyoun;</L>
<L>Whiche greetly displesith me,</L>
<L N="19160">Theder whanne I se hem ffle.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Swych&euml; ffolke resemblen alle</L>
<L>Vn-to a bryd that clerkes calle</L>
<L><B>Ortigometra</B> in ther bokys;</L>
<L N="19164">And this bryd caste his lokys
<PB REF="00000620.tif" N="512"></L>
<L>'To-fforne hym prudently, to se</L>
<L>Whanne he schal swymm&euml; in the see:</L>
<L>This ffoul hath whyng&euml;s ffor the fflyght,</L>
<L N="19168">Be he<NOTE PLACE="marg">[to be St.]</NOTE> anoon off kyndely ryght.</L>
<L>Whanne he is wery off travayle,</L>
<L>And that his ffederes do<NOTE PLACE="marg">[done St.]</NOTE> hym ffayle,</L>
<L>Anoon (off his condiscyoun)</L>
<L N="19172">In-to the water he fallith doun,</L>
<L>And thanne<NOTE PLACE="marg">[that St.]</NOTE> to swymm&euml; wole not ffayle:</L>
<L>Off his o whynge, he makith a ssayle,</L>
<L>Amonge the sturdy wawys alle</L>
<L N="19176">To kepe hym silffe, that he not ffalle,</L>
<L>Til he resume ageyne his myght,</L>
<L>Off acustom,<NOTE PLACE="marg">[custom St.]</NOTE> to take his fflyght.</L>
<L>Thus stound&euml;mel &yogh;e may hym se,</L>
<L N="19180">Som tym&euml; swymme, som tym&euml; fflee,</L>
<L>In bokys as it is I-ffounde.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>'But they that hau&euml;<NOTE PLACE="marg">[haue ther St.]</NOTE> ffeet I-bounde</L>
<L>With herb&euml;s and with wed&euml;s greene,</L>
<L N="19184">That they may not aryght sustene,</L>
<L>Nowther to swymm&euml; nor to fflee,</L>
<L>They be so bounden in the see</L>
<L>Off wordely<NOTE PLACE="marg">[worldly St.]</NOTE> delectacyoun<MILESTONE UNIT="Tib folio" N="54b"></L>
<L N="19188">In ther inwarde affeccyoun;</L>
<L>ffor alle ther hool ffelicyte</L>
<L>Is sette in veyne<NOTE PLACE="marg">[veyne St., verrey Tib.]</NOTE> prosperite</L>
<L>Off the world, and in rychesse,</L>
<L N="19192">fful off chaunge and dowblenesse,</L>
<L>With whiche they be so<NOTE PLACE="marg">[so St., <I>om</I>. Tib.]</NOTE> sor&euml; bounde,</L>
<L>That her soulis yt wole conffounde;</L>
<L>ffor they haue power none,<NOTE PLACE="marg">[none St., Tib. <I>blurd</I>]</NOTE> nor myght,</L>
<L>Nowther to swymme nor ffleen<NOTE PLACE="marg">[flyen St.]</NOTE> aryght;</L>
<L N="19197">So sore the world doth hem constreyne,</L>
<L>That it were to hem greet peyne,</L>
<L>Her hertis ffro the world to vnbynde.<NOTE PLACE="marg">[tuunbynd St.]</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="19200">'And som also be makyd<NOTE PLACE="marg">[made St.]</NOTE> blynde,</L>
<L>Ther eyen cloos, they may not se,</L>
<L>ffor to considere the vanyte</L>
<L>Off this worldis ffalse veyneglorye,</L>
<L N="19204">Euere vnsure and transitorye,
<PB REF="00000621.tif" N="513"></L>
<L>'And fful off mvtabylyte,<NOTE PLACE="marg">[mutabylyte St., mvtabyte Tib.]</NOTE></L>
<L>Whiche schewith to hem fful greet bewete<MILESTONE UNIT="Stowe folio" N="323a"></L>
<L>By a<NOTE PLACE="marg">[a St., <I>om</I>. Tib.]</NOTE> maner off &aacute;pparence,</L>
<L N="19208">But it is ffalse in &eacute;xistence;</L>
<L>That is fful ffoule, dothe schew&euml; ffayre,</L>
<L>Lyche a ffloure that dothe vnapayre<NOTE PLACE="marg">[Tib. &amp; St. apayre St.]</NOTE></L>
<L>Whanne it is plukkyd and leyde lowe,</L>
<L N="19212">Or with som sodeyne wynde I-blowe.</L>
<L>Whiche bewete (as wryte <B>Salamoun)</B><NOTE PLACE="marg">&para; Prouerbiorum, 31<SUP>o</SUP>. Proverbs. 31. St.</NOTE></L>
<L>Is but a ffalse decepcyoun;</L>
<L>And ffolkis that beth there-with blente,</L>
<L N="19216">Or they be war, beth offt&euml; schente,</L>
<L>ffor lak ther eyen be not clere.</L>
<L>&para; 'Eke som ther swymmes<NOTE PLACE="marg">[swyme St.]</NOTE> (as &yogh;e may leere)</L>
<L>With hand and armys strecchyd out;</L>
<L N="19220">Swyche as parte her good aboute</L>
<L>To por&euml; ffolkis that haue neede;</L>
<L>And swyche vnbynde<NOTE PLACE="marg">[vnbynd St., vnkynde Tib.]</NOTE> her ffeet, in deede,</L>
<L>ffrom wordely<NOTE PLACE="marg">[worldly St.]</NOTE> delectacyoun,<MILESTONE UNIT="Tib folio" N="55a"></L>
<L N="19224">And off devoute entencyoun,</L>
<L>By councel off her c&oacute;nffessour,</L>
<L>Vnbynde her ffeet, by<NOTE PLACE="marg">[with St.]</NOTE> greet labour,</L>
<L>ffor to goon in there vy&aacute;ges,</L>
<L N="19228">Barffote, to sek&euml; pilgrym&aacute;ges;</L>
<L>Off ther synn&euml;s to haue pardoun,</L>
<L>ffor&yogh;euenesse and remyssyoun,</L>
<L>Whanne ther menynge trew&euml;ly</L>
<L N="19232">Is voyde ffrom al ypocrysy.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>ANd thus as now (without&euml;<NOTE PLACE="marg">[without Tib., St.]</NOTE> slouthe)</L>
<L>To the I hau&euml; tolde the trouthe.</L>
<L>'And trewely<NOTE PLACE="marg">[sothly St.]</NOTE> &yogh;it, ouere alle thyng,</L>
<L N="19236">I hat&euml; trowthe in my workyng;</L>
<L>And off malys, bothe day and nyght,</L>
<L>Werrey<NOTE PLACE="marg">[werray St., Verrey Tib.]</NOTE> trouthe with al my myght.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>'By nam&euml;, callyd I am <B>Sathan;</B></L>
<L N="19240">The whiche, as ffer as euere I kan,</L>
<L>I worke, in myne entencyoun,</L>
<L>ffor to cacche, in my bandoun,</L>
<L>Alle pylgrymes (as thow mayst se,)</L>
<L N="19244">That swymmen in the wawy see
<PB REF="00000622.tif" N="514"></L>
<L>'Off this world, fful off disseyte.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>'And euere I lye in greet awayte,</L>
<L>And no moment I ne ffyne</L>
<L N="19248">ffor to leyne out hook and lyne.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>'My lyne (by demonstracyoun)</L>
<L>I-callyd is Temptacyoun;</L>
<L>And whanne that ffolke (in ther entente)</L>
<L N="19252">Off herte and wylle ther-to concente,</L>
<L>Thanne on myn hook (by ffalse awayte,)</L>
<L>They ben I-cacchyd with the bayte;</L>
<L>And thann&euml;, by fful mortal lawe,</L>
<L N="19256">T&oacute; my bandoun, I hem drawe.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>'I leye out nett&euml;s nyght and day,</L>
<L>In water and lond, to cacche my pray.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>'With nettys, I haue eke my repayre<MILESTONE UNIT="Tib folio" N="55b"><MILESTONE UNIT="Stowe folio" N="224a"></L>
<L N="19260">ffor bryddes that ffleen eke in the hayre,</L>
<L>ffor to make hem ffalle adown</L>
<L>ffrom ther contemplacyown.</L>
<L>And, thus ffolkys to bygyle,</L>
<L N="19264">I am a ffoulere eke som whyle;</L>
<L>ffor alle that hygh or low&euml; goon,</L>
<L>I mak&euml; nettis ffor euerychoon,</L>
<L>(In myne entente, it is no drede),</L>
<L N="19268">To cacche hem, outher<NOTE PLACE="marg">[or St.]</NOTE> by ffoot or hede,</L>
<L>As an vreyne wewyth<NOTE PLACE="marg">[wevithe St.]</NOTE> a calle,</L>
<L>To mak&euml; fflyes there-in to<NOTE PLACE="marg">[to <I>om</I>. St.]</NOTE> ffalle.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>'But I ne may not do no wronge</L>
<L N="19272">To ffolke that ben in vertu stronge.</L>
<L>I venquysche (nouther nygh nor fferre)</L>
<L>No man that halte ageyne me werre;</L>
<L>And ffeble is my vyolence,</L>
<L N="19276">Whanne ther is manly r&eacute;systence.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>ANd &yogh;it I haue a thowsande treynes,</L>
<L>And as many laas and cheynes,</L>
<L>With<NOTE PLACE="marg">[<I>om</I>. St.]</NOTE> whiche I compasse, day by day,</L>
<L N="19280">To lett&euml; pylgrymes on ther way;</L>
<L>ffor I, by ffalse illusyoun</L>
<L>And by dyssumylacyoun,<NOTE PLACE="marg">[dyssimilasyon St.]</NOTE></L>
<L>Kan me<NOTE PLACE="marg">[me St., mys Tib.]</NOTE> transfform&euml; (anoon ryght,)</L>
<L N="19284">To lykenesse off an aungel bryght;
<PB REF="00000623.tif" N="515"></L>
<L>'Take off hym the r&eacute;semblaunce,</L>
<L>The vesage and the contenaunce,</L>
<L>So to disseyuen, in couert;</L>
<L N="19288">And to an heremyte in desert;</L>
<L>I<NOTE PLACE="marg">[And I Tib., I St.]</NOTE> dyde oon&euml;s so appere,</L>
<L>fful off ffetheres bryght and clere,</L>
<L>And toke<NOTE PLACE="marg">[toke St., do Tib.]</NOTE> on me the message</L>
<L N="19292">Off an aungel, by my vysage,</L>
<L>And bad vn-to that hooly man</L>
<L>To kepe hym warly ffrom <B>Sathan</B>,</L>
<L>ffor he was schapen, by batayle,<MILESTONE UNIT="Tib folio" N="56a"></L>
<L N="19296">The nexte morewe, hym to assayle;</L>
<L>And tolde hym also, (ffynally,</L>
<L>ffor to disceyve hym sotylly,)</L>
<L>He wold&euml; tak&euml;, (in sothenesse,)</L>
<L N="19300">Off hys ffader the lyknesse,</L>
<L>Bothe vesage and contenaunce,</L>
<L>The maner and the r&eacute;semblaunce.<NOTE PLACE="inter">[Illustration.]</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>'ANd bad the heremyte anoon ryght</L>
<L N="19304">To fforce hym, at the ffirst&euml; syght,</L>
<L>To smyte hym ffirste, with knyffe or swerde,</L>
<L>And no thyng to ben afferde</L>
<L>With al his myghtty vyolence,</L>
<L N="19308">Whanne he cam ffirste to his presence.</L>
<L>&para; And so, vpon the next&euml; morewe,</L>
<L>ffor to encresse his dool and sorewe,</L>
<L N="19311">I made his ffader hym vesyte;</L>
<L>And anoon, this seyde heremyte,<MILESTONE UNIT="Stowe folio" N="324b"></L>
<L>This Innocent, thys cely man,</L>
<L>Wenynge hit hadd&euml; be <B>Sathan</B>,</L>
<L>Vp sterte anoon, and toke a knyff,</L>
<L N="19316">And raffte his ffader off his lyff,</L>
<L>That he to ground&euml; ffel downe deed.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>'And thus I kan (who takyth heed)</L>
<L>A thousande wey&euml;s, ffolke<NOTE PLACE="marg">[ffolke to St.]</NOTE> dysceyue,<MILESTONE UNIT="Tib folio" N="56b"></L>
<L N="19320">Or they my treyn&euml;s<NOTE PLACE="marg">[trappis St.]</NOTE> kan conceyue.</L>
<L>And therffore,<NOTE PLACE="marg">[therfore St., herffore Tib.]</NOTE> be wel war off me,</L>
<L>ffor I caste eke<NOTE PLACE="marg">[eke to St.]</NOTE> dysseyu&euml; the;</L>
<L>&YOGH;eue I at larg&euml; may the ffynde,
<PB REF="00000624.tif" N="516"></L>
<L>'In my laas<NOTE PLACE="marg">[lace St.]</NOTE> I schal the bynde;</L>
<L>&para; ffor, as seynt Petre lyste endyte,<NOTE PLACE="marg">[tendit St.]</NOTE><NOTE PLACE="marg">&para; Prima Petri. 7<SUP>o</SUP>. Tanquam leo rugiens . . </NOTE></L>
<L>And in his pystelys ffor to wryte,</L>
<L>I go and serch&euml;, day and nyght,</L>
<L N="19328">With alle my fforce, with al my myght,</L>
<L>Lyche a ravenous lyoun,</L>
<L>ffor to devoure, vp and doun,</L>
<L>All&euml; ffolkys, &yogh;onge and oolde,</L>
<L N="19332">That lambre<NOTE PLACE="marg">[lambes St.]</NOTE> be off cristis ffoolde.</L>
<L>I haue off hem, fful &yogh;ore agoon,</L>
<L>Off hem devoured many oon;</L>
<L>Strangelyd mo than I kan telle;</L>
<L N="19336">And that<NOTE PLACE="marg">[it St.]</NOTE> were to longe to dwelle,</L>
<L>ffor to rekene hem alle in nowmbre,</L>
<L>Thousandis mo than I kan nowmbre;</L>
<L>And trewely, in two hundred &yogh;er,</L>
<L N="19340">I koude not tell&euml; the maner</L>
<L>Off alle my treyn&euml;s by and by.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>'And I warne the outerly,</L>
<L>Thow schalt not lyghttely (&yogh;eue I may,)</L>
<L N="19344">ffro my daunger skape away.'</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>&para; The Pylgryme:</HEAD>
<L>"WHer thow be wel or yuel apayd</L>
<L>In the wordes that thow haste sayd,</L>
<L>I haue ffounden a greet dyffence,</L>
<L N="19348">To make ageyne th&eacute;, r&eacute;sistence,</L>
<L>And conceyued<NOTE PLACE="marg">[conseyvyd St., conceyue Tib.]</NOTE> it in my thought.</L>
<L>Blowe thyne horne, and spar&euml; nought,</L>
<L>ffor thow schalt ffayle (&yogh;eue that I may)</L>
<L N="19352">To make off me<NOTE PLACE="marg">[the St.]</NOTE> schortely thi pray."<MILESTONE UNIT="Tib folio" N="57a"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>And to be more stronge in vertu,</L>
<L>With the crosse off crist ihesu,</L>
<L>And off his grac&euml; moste benygne,</L>
<L N="19356">I gan me crossen, and eke sygne,</L>
<L>ffor to assur&euml;<NOTE PLACE="marg">[tassure St.]</NOTE> my passage</L>
<L>Ageyne his laas so fful off rage.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>And by my crossynge, I anoon</L>
<L N="19360">Gan to passe hem euerichoon;</L>
<L>They hadde no power ffor to laste;</L>
<L>ffor, by the vertu, they to-braste;
<PB REF="00000625.tif" N="517"></L>
<L>And I anoon gan ffast&euml; fflee,<MILESTONE UNIT="Stowe folio" N="325a"></L>
<L N="19364">And wolde haue taken anoon the see;</L>
<L>But, longe or I entter myght,</L>
<L>Whan<NOTE PLACE="marg">[St., Tib. <I>blurd</I>]</NOTE> <B>Sathan</B> off me hadde a syght,</L>
<L>He gan to crye (so stood the cas)</L>
<L N="19368">'Out and harow! allas, allas!'</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>&para; Sathan the hunte weymentith<NOTE PLACE="marg">[huntar St.]</NOTE> And tormentyth with hym silffe.<NOTE PLACE="marg">[sathan ye huntar St.]</NOTE><NOTE PLACE="inter">[Illustration.]</NOTE></HEAD>
<L>'Vnhappy,<NOTE PLACE="marg">[St., I vnhappy Tib.]</NOTE> and fful off meschaunce</L>
<L>I was, whanne I dyde me avaunce</L>
<L>In any wys&euml; ffor to teche</L>
<L N="19372">Vertu, or<NOTE PLACE="marg">[of St.]</NOTE> trowth&euml; ffor to preche;</L>
<L>ffor, it longeth not to me</L>
<L>To tech&euml; trouthe in no degre;</L>
<L>But, off ffortune it happ&euml; so,<MILESTONE UNIT="Tib folio" N="57b"></L>
<L N="19376">That I be c&oacute;nstreyn&euml;d ther-to,</L>
<L>By vertu off som orysoun</L>
<L>Or by som conyurisoun,<NOTE PLACE="marg">[coniurasion St.]</NOTE></L>
<L>That greet&euml;<NOTE PLACE="marg">[greet Tib., grete St.]</NOTE> clerk&euml;s me compelle,</L>
<L N="19380">The verrey trowth&euml; ffor to telle,</L>
<L>Mawgrey my wylle, off many a thyng,</L>
<L>By vertu off the greet&euml;<NOTE PLACE="marg">[gret St., greet Tib.]</NOTE> kyng.</L>
<L>ffor ellys (who that kan espye)</L>
<L N="19384">My purpos is, euere ffor to lye,</L>
<L>And<NOTE PLACE="marg">[I St.]</NOTE> haue disseyued fful many a man,</L>
<L>Ryght as dyd&euml; <B>Iulyan</B>.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>'Though I were by hym constreyned,</L>
<L N="19388">And by his charm&euml;s greetly peyned,</L>
<L>&YOGH;it at the laste, whanne I abrayde,</L>
<L>I ly&euml;d, alle that euere I sayde.</L>
<L>And now I oughte a-cursyd be,</L>
<L N="19392">Whanne that I gan medle me</L>
<L>To seyne a trouthe agayn&euml;s<NOTE PLACE="marg">[agayns Tib., St.]</NOTE> kynde,</L>
<L>Sethen men, in me may<NOTE PLACE="marg">[ne may in me St.]</NOTE> noon ffynde;</L>
<L>There-off I r&eacute;pente me fful sore,</L>
<L N="19396">With trowth&euml;, medle I wole no more.'</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>&para; The Pylgryme answerth to Satan:<NOTE PLACE="marg">[pilgrim St.]</NOTE></HEAD>
<L>"<B>OSathan</B>, thi displesaunce</L>
<L>Was to me fful greet plesaunce,
<PB REF="00000626.tif" N="518"></L>
<L>"Releuynge me off my distresse."</L>
<L N="19400">I took there-off greet hardynesse,</L>
<L>Made as tho<NOTE PLACE="marg">[thow St.]</NOTE> no lenger lette,</L>
<L>I spared nowther hook nor nette,</L>
<L>But, trustynge (in conclusyoun)</L>
<L N="19404">Vp-on my skrippe and my burdoun,</L>
<L>And there-vp-on I bylened<NOTE PLACE="marg">[lened St.]</NOTE> me</L>
<L>Whanne I entryd in-to the see;</L>
<L>And, in swymmynge to be more stable,<MILESTONE UNIT="Tib folio" N="58a"></L>
<L N="19408">Me thought my skrypp&euml; proffitable</L>
<L>To kepe me sure in herte and thought,</L>
<L>In my way, that I err&euml;d nought.<NOTE PLACE="inter">[Illustration.]</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="19411">TRewely,<NOTE PLACE="marg">[yet truly St.]</NOTE> in this dredefful see,</L>
<L>Is<NOTE PLACE="marg">[<I>om.</I> St.]</NOTE> greet myscheeff and aduersyte:</L>
<L>Many a perel (I &yogh;ou ensure,)</L>
<L>And many a straung&euml; &aacute;venture</L>
<L N="19415">I ffelt&euml; tho in my passage,</L>
<L>Off wawys and off<NOTE PLACE="marg">[of St., <I>om.</I> Tib.]</NOTE> rokkis rage,<MILESTONE UNIT="Stowe folio" N="325b"></L>
<L>And many a tempeste (in certeyn)</L>
<L>Off thondrynge, lyghtnynge, and off reyn,</L>
<L>And other perels that be-ffelle,</L>
<L N="19420">That, &yogh;eue I schulde hem all&euml; telle,</L>
<L>Or the mysch&eacute;v&euml;s alle endyte,</L>
<L>They were to long&euml; for<NOTE PLACE="marg">[for St., <I>om.</I> Tib.]</NOTE> to wryte.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>But while that I, in my pass&aacute;ge,</L>
<L N="19424">Byheelde the see, sterne and sav&aacute;ge,</L>
<L>Me thought I sawe bysyd&euml; me,</L>
<L>That there stood a green&euml; tre;</L>
<L>And I was glad alle<NOTE PLACE="marg">[of St.]</NOTE> thilk&euml; while,</L>
<L N="19428">Wenynge there hadde ben an yle,</L>
<L>In hop&euml; that I schuld&euml; londe,</L>
<L>Hastely, vp at som stronde,</L>
<L>Whiche was to me fful greet plesaunce.<MILESTONE UNIT="Tib folio" N="58b"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="19432">And as I gan my silffe avaunce,</L>
<L>And thederward gan ffast&euml; hye,</L>
<L>Anoon my sylffe I dyde aspye</L>
<L>(Whanne that I gan lok&euml; wel)</L>
<L N="19436">That I was caste vp-on a whel,</L>
<L>Off whiche to-fforne I sawgh no thynge;
<PB REF="00000627.tif" N="519"></L>
<L>ffor the ffloodes, in ther fflowynge,</L>
<L>Hadde with his waw&euml;s euerydel</L>
<L N="19440">Ouere-fflowyd so that whel,</L>
<L>That I toke no heede there-at,</L>
<L>Tyl sodeynely there-on I sat.</L>
<L>And wyld&euml;ly the wawys smette</L>
<L N="19444">Vp-on this whel, ay as they mette;</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>ANd euere round, (as thought&euml; me,)</L>
<L>This whel wente aboute the tre,</L>
<L>Where-off, I astonyed was,</L>
<L N="19448">Whanne I sawe this sodeyne caas.</L>
<L>Vp on which&euml; tre anoon,</L>
<L>I sawgh nestys fful many oon;</L>
<L>And brydd&euml;s (that I koud&euml; knowe,)</L>
<L N="19452">Somm&euml; hyh, and somm&euml;<NOTE PLACE="marg">[som Tib., some St.]</NOTE> lowe,</L>
<L>Ther nestis made (I toke good hede)</L>
<L>Grete and smale (it is no drede).</L>
<L>&para; And I dem&euml;d,<NOTE PLACE="marg">[it semyd St.]</NOTE> in certeyne,<MILESTONE UNIT="Tib folio" N="59a"></L>
<L N="19456">That this tre hadd&euml; hoolys tweyne;</L>
<L>And on the hygher hoole aloffte,<NOTE PLACE="marg">[St. &amp; Tib.]</NOTE></L>
<L>I sawe an hand putte out fful offte.<NOTE PLACE="marg">[St. &amp; Tib.]</NOTE></L>
<L>And this hand (as to my look)<NOTE PLACE="marg">[St. &amp; Tib.]</NOTE></L>
<L N="19460">To the nestis put up an hook,<NOTE PLACE="marg">[St. &amp; Tib.]</NOTE></L>
<L>And (as to myne inspeccyoun)</L>
<L>Was besy to pulle the nestis doun.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>And as I stode a lytel throwe<NOTE PLACE="marg">[St. &amp; Tib.]</NOTE></L>
<L N="19464">At the hoole that stood moste lowe,</L>
<L>I sawgh heed&euml;s lokynge oute</L>
<L>Towarde the braunches rounde aboute,</L>
<L>In purpos (&yogh;eue it myght haue be)</L>
<L>To clymbe vp hygh&euml; on that<NOTE PLACE="marg">[hygh . . that Tib., highe . . thilke St.]</NOTE> tre:<MILESTONE UNIT="Stowe folio" N="236a"></L>
<L N="19469">They wolde haue take it ffayne in honde.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>And there I sawe a lady stonde</L>
<L>Amonge the wyld&euml; wawys trowble,</L>
<L N="19472">Vp-on a whel dyuerse and dowble.</L>
<L>Departyd was her garnemente,</L>
<L>Halffe hool, and haluendel was rente;</L>
<L>The to party, as snow was white</L>
<L N="19476">To loke vp-on, off greet delyte;</L>
<L>The tother party (&aacute;s thought me)
<PB REF="00000628.tif" N="520"></L>
<L>Was ffoule and owgely on to se.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>And hir vysage eke also</L>
<L N="19480">Was departyd euene a two;</L>
<L>The to party was amyable,</L>
<L>And to byhold&euml; d&eacute;lytable,</L>
<L>Bothe off porte and off manere,</L>
<L N="19484">Glad and lawynge off hir chere;</L>
<L>&para; The tother syde, hydous and old,</L>
<L>Whiche was ryuelyd many ffold;</L>
<L>And on hir schuldres rownd and square,</L>
<L N="19488">A crokyd staffe in sothe sche bare.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>And whanne I gan al this aduerte,</L>
<L>Dyscomff&oacute;rtyd in myn herte<NOTE PLACE="inter">[Illustration.]</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>THanne was I, greetly agaste<NOTE PLACE="marg">[I was, and gretly gan gaste St.]</NOTE>;<MILESTONE UNIT="Tib folio" N="59b"></L>
<L N="19492">And my burdoun I heelde ryghte ffaste,</L>
<L>And dyde also greetly my peyne</L>
<L>To grype it with myne hand&euml;s tweyne;</L>
<L>And seyde, (off sodeyne moscyoun,)</L>
<L N="19496">"Bordoun," quod I, "bordoun, bordoun!</L>
<L>But thow me help&euml;<NOTE PLACE="marg">[helpe now St.]</NOTE> in this caas,</L>
<L>I may<NOTE PLACE="marg">[may well St.]</NOTE> wepe and seyne 'allas,'</L>
<L>My peyn&euml;s ben so scharpe and kene.</L>
<L N="19500">And but thow help&euml; to sustene</L>
<L>Myne nownpowere and inpotence,<NOTE PLACE="marg">[impotence St.]</NOTE></L>
<L>That I may stonden at dyffence</L>
<L>Vp-on my ffeet, and that anoon,</L>
<L N="19504">ffare-wel! my Ioye is alle agoon!"</L>
<L>&para; But tho, thorough helpe off my bordoun,</L>
<L>I roos vp as a champyoun.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>But whanne this lady dyde espye</L>
<L N="19508">That I was vp, sche gan to hye</L>
<L>ffor to haue putte<NOTE PLACE="marg">[taput St.]</NOTE> me doun ageyn;</L>
<L>And I trowe ryght wel certeyn,</L>
<L>That, but I hadd&euml; spoken ffayre,</L>
<L N="19512">And off my porte be debonayre,</L>
<L>I hadde ben to<NOTE PLACE="marg">[to St., fful Tib.]</NOTE> ffeble off myght,</L>
<L>Vp-on my ffeet to stonde<NOTE PLACE="marg">[tastand St.]</NOTE> vp ryght.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>BVt I abrayde, and bade in deede<MILESTONE UNIT="Tib folio" N="60a"></L>
<L N="19516">that sche schold&euml; taken heede
<PB REF="00000629.tif" N="521"></L>
<L>To thilk&euml; party that was ffayre</L>
<L>Off hir, and putte me ffro dispayre,</L>
<L>And schew&euml;, lyke hir contenaunce,</L>
<L N="19520">Som counfforte or som plesaunce;</L>
<L>And that sche wolde expown&euml; me</L>
<L>What lady that sche schuld&euml; be,</L>
<L>Hir name, hir power, euerydel,<MILESTONE UNIT="Stowe folio" N="326b"></L>
<L N="19524">Bothe off hir and off hir whel,</L>
<L>And off the tre, and off the croppe,</L>
<L>And off the nestis in the coppe,<NOTE PLACE="marg">[cop St.]</NOTE></L>
<L>And do to<NOTE PLACE="marg">[done to St., do Tib.]</NOTE> me som &aacute;vauntage,</L>
<L N="19528">To ffurthre me in my vyage.<NOTE PLACE="foot">Stowe leaves a blank of 10 lines in his copy, and puts a side|note "fortune should be porturatyd."</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>&para; ffortune:</HEAD>
<L>'IN me (schortely to expresse)</L>
<L>There is no maner stablenesse;</L>
<L>ffor, (be hereoff ryght wel certeyn,)</L>
<L N="19532">Alle that I worke, is vncerteyn;</L>
<L>Lyke my dowble contenaunce,</L>
<L>I am so fful off variaunce.</L>
<L>Therffore, to axe how I me guye,</L>
<L N="19536">It is no wysdam, but ffolye;</L>
<L>I worke no thyng in certeynte,</L>
<L>But fful off greet duplycyte.</L>
<L>I am what-euere I do provyde;</L>
<L>ffor I lawe<NOTE PLACE="marg">[lawghe St.]</NOTE> on the ryght&euml;<NOTE PLACE="marg">[ryght Tib., St.]</NOTE> syde,</L>
<L N="19541">And schewe a cher off greet delyte</L>
<L>On the party that I am white.<NOTE PLACE="marg">[delyt . . . whit St.]</NOTE></L>
<L>Thanne men me call&euml; 'glad <B>ffortune</B>';</L>
<L N="19544">But, no while I do contune;</L>
<L>ffor, longe or ffolke may aparceyue,</L>
<L>I kan hem sodeynely disseyue,</L>
<L><NOTE PLACE="foot">The text is now again taken up from MS. Cott. Vit. c. xiii. leaf 253.</NOTE>And make her Ioy&euml; go to wrak<MILESTONE UNIT="Stowe folio" N="327a"><NOTE PLACE="marg">[Cott. Vitell. C. 13.]</NOTE></L>
<L>Wyth ffroward mowh&euml;s at the bak.<MILESTONE UNIT="Tib folio" N="60b"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="19549">'Than y, lykned<NOTE PLACE="marg">[lykenyd St.]</NOTE> to the moone,</L>
<L>ffolk wyl chaunge my nam&euml; sone;</L>
<L>And fro my whel whan they are falle,
<PB REF="00000630.tif" N="522"></L>
<L N="19552">"Infortun&euml;' they me calle.</L>
<L>To ffolk vnworthy, and nat dygne,</L>
<L>I am somwhyl&euml; most benygne,</L>
<L N="19555">Lyggynge awayt in euery cost,</L>
<L>Off ffolk whom that<NOTE PLACE="marg">[that Tib., <I>om</I>. C., St.]</NOTE> I cherysshe most.</L>
<L>And who that on me set hys lust,</L>
<L>I kan deceyve hym off hys trust.</L>
<L>Tak hed pleynly, and thow shalt se</L>
<L N="19560">A pleyn exaumple off thys tre,</L>
<L>How thys tre (at O word)</L>
<L>May be resemblyd to the world.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="19563">&para; 'ffyrst, in thys world be grete estatys,</L>
<L>Off kyng&euml;s, prynces, and off<NOTE PLACE="marg">[off <I>om</I>. Tib., of St.]</NOTE> prel&aacute;tys,</L>
<L>Wych in thys erth&euml;<NOTE PLACE="marg">[world St.]</NOTE> chaungen offte.</L>
<L>And the nestys hyh aloffte</L>
<L>Ben degr&euml;es<NOTE PLACE="marg">[degrees Tib., degres C., St.]</NOTE> off lordshepe,</L>
<L N="19568">That so offte on heiht&euml; lepe,</L>
<L>Bothe off hyh and lowh degre.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>'And they that al by-neth&euml; be,</L>
<L>Loke vp-ward, and al day gaze,</L>
<L N="19572">As yt wer vp-on A maze:</L>
<L>Tho be they, that so offte</L>
<L>Desyre for to clymbe aloffte</L>
<L>To hih estat and hih degre,</L>
<L N="19576">ffrom ther estaat off pouerte.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>'Somme<NOTE PLACE="marg">[(? None), Some Tib., St.]</NOTE> off hem may longe abyde,</L>
<L>ffor I sette hem offte asyde;</L>
<L>Wych thyng to hym ys no thyng soote,</L>
<L N="19580">Whan they be longe p&uacute;t vnder ffoote</L>
<L>Thorgh my double varyaunce.</L>
<L>And somm&euml; kan han<NOTE PLACE="marg">[haue St., som kan haue Tib.]</NOTE> suffysaunce,</L>
<L>And ben ryht glad in ther entent<MILESTONE N="254b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="19584">Off the lytel that god hath sent;<MILESTONE UNIT="Tib folio" N="61a"></L>
<L>They ha<NOTE PLACE="marg">[haueth Tib.]</NOTE> no care for<NOTE PLACE="marg">[of St., for Tib.]</NOTE> ther dyspence.</L>
<L>And somme haue euere Indygence,</L>
<L>And kan with no thyng be content,</L>
<L N="19588">With coveytyse they be so blent,</L>
<L>Wych, for ther oun&euml; wrechchydnesse,<MILESTONE UNIT="Stowe folio" N="327b"></L>
<L>Lyve euere in pouert and dystresse.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>'Touchyng my whel (yt ys no doute,)
<PB REF="00000631.tif" N="523"></L>
<L N="19592">'Wych tourneth euere round aboute,</L>
<L>Ther may no man aloffte Abyde</L>
<L>But yiff so be I be hys guyde.</L>
<L>Yt turneth euere to and ffro;</L>
<L N="19596">The pley ther-off ys meynt with wo;</L>
<L>The wych&euml; whel (who that<NOTE PLACE="marg">[C., St., whiche whel who Tib.]</NOTE> kan se,)</L>
<L>Ys a pereyl off the se,</L>
<L>On, the grettest off echon,<NOTE PLACE="marg">[one . . . one St.]</NOTE></L>
<L N="19600">ffor to rekne hem on by on;</L>
<L>And, thys phylisoffres alle,</L>
<L>'Karybdis' lyst yt for to calle,</L>
<L>Yt devoureth so many A man,</L>
<L N="19604">Ye, mo than I rehers&euml; kan.'</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>&para; The Pylgrym<NOTE PLACE="marg">[Tib., pilgryme St., <I>om</I>. C.]</NOTE>:</HEAD>
<L>"Touchyng thy staff, tel on, lat se</L>
<L>What maner tookne yt may be,</L>
<L>That yt corbyd lych and<NOTE PLACE="marg">[an Tib.]</NOTE> Crook,</L>
<L N="10608">And mad in maner off<NOTE PLACE="marg">[lyke St.]</NOTE> an hook."</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>&para; Dame Fortune<NOTE PLACE="marg">[Tib., <I>om</I>. C.]</NOTE>:</HEAD>
<L>'With thys Crook, by gret vengaunce,</L>
<L>ffolk, that to soon<NOTE PLACE="marg">[to fforne Tib., St.]</NOTE> I dyde avaunce,</L>
<L>Thorgh my transmutac&iuml;oun,</L>
<L N="19612">Al sodeynly I rende hem doun,</L>
<L>That sat in chayerys hih aloffte;</L>
<L>To whom ther fal ys<NOTE PLACE="marg">[falls St.]</NOTE> no thyng soffte.<MILESTONE UNIT="Tib folio" N="61b"></L>
<L>Reyse vp ageyn al sodeynly</L>
<L N="19616">Other that be nothyng worthy,</L>
<L>And cause ek somm&euml; (Est and west)</L>
<L>ffor to bylde fful hih ther nest<MILESTONE N="255a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>And ther habytc&iuml;oun;</L>
<L N="19620">Somtyme, off wyl, nat off resoun,</L>
<L>I take noon hed off no degre,</L>
<L>But only off my volunte.'</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>&para; The Pylgryme<NOTE PLACE="marg">[Tib., <I>om</I>. C.]</NOTE>:</HEAD>
<L>"fful ffayn I wolde ek vnderstonde</L>
<L N="19624">The menyng also off the hond,</L>
<L>At the hool&euml; hyh aloffte,</L>
<L>That reyseth vp his crook so offte,</L>
<L>The nestys for to rende a-doun:</L>
<L N="19628">Tel me thexposic&iuml;oun."
<PB REF="00000632.tif" N="524"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>&para; Dame Fortune<NOTE PLACE="marg">[Tib., <I>om</I>. C.]</NOTE>:</HEAD>
<L>'The nestys hih vp-on the tre,</L>
<L>That ben hyest off degre,</L>
<L>Ben they off ryht and good resoun</L>
<L N="19632">That entre by success&iuml;oun,<MILESTONE UNIT="Stowe folio" N="328a"></L>
<L>As kynges, by iust enherytaunce,</L>
<L>Whom that trouth&euml; lyst avaunce<NOTE PLACE="marg">[trouthe habundaunce Tib.]</NOTE></L>
<L>Only by lyneal dyscent,</L>
<L N="19636">Hys lyges echon<NOTE PLACE="marg">[leegis echone Tib.]</NOTE> off assent;</L>
<L>Or,<NOTE PLACE="marg">[Or Tib., Off C., of St.]</NOTE> for lak off success&iuml;oun,</L>
<L>Swyche as by ellecc&iuml;oun</L>
<L>Ben reysed vp to hih degre,</L>
<L N="19640">As many princes and lordys be.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>'Thogh I to hem have envye,</L>
<L>To reve hem off ther Regalye,</L>
<L>Yet, thogh I ther-to haue no myght</L>
<L N="19644">ffor to robbe hem off ther ryht,<MILESTONE UNIT="Tib folio" N="62a"></L>
<L>Yet (who lyst looke with Eyen cler)</L>
<L>They be ful offte in my daunger;</L>
<L>ffor they may nat assuryd be</L>
<L N="19648">Ageyn my mutabylyte,</L>
<L>Nor ageyn my mortal stryff;</L>
<L>ffor offt&euml; sythe they lese her lyff</L>
<L>By compassyng off ffals Tresoun,</L>
<L N="19652">By mordre also, and poysoun.</L>
<L>And trewly, al thys frowardnesse<MILESTONE N="255b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Ys tookned<NOTE PLACE="marg">[tokenyd St.]</NOTE> by the crookydnesse</L>
<L>Off my staff and off my crok,</L>
<L N="19656">Wrong<NOTE PLACE="marg">[wronge St.]</NOTE> at the ende, as ys an hook.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>'And whan I loke with Eyen cler,</L>
<L>Lawhe on ffolk,<NOTE PLACE="marg">[folk, <I>om</I>. Tib., folke St.]</NOTE> and make hem cher,</L>
<L>Thanne lygge I rathest in a-wayt,</L>
<L N="19660">ffor to don hem som deceyt.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>'Lo, her ys al; go forth<NOTE PLACE="marg">[fforthe Tib., forthe St., foth C.]</NOTE> thy way;</L>
<L>And trust&euml; wel, yiff that I may,</L>
<L>What weye euere that thow go,</L>
<L N="19664">Or thy pylgrymage be do,&mdash;</L>
<L>Tourne yt to sour, outher to swete,&mdash;</L>
<L>Onys I shal yet<NOTE PLACE="marg">[ther St.]</NOTE> with the mete.'</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>&para; Fortune is walkyd.<NOTE PLACE="marg">[Tib., <I>om</I>. C., St.]</NOTE>
</HEAD>
<PB REF="00000633.tif" N="525">
<L>And ffortune wente her way A-noon.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="19668">And also sone as she was gon,</L>
<L>I stood in dred and in gret doute</L>
<L>Vp-on hyr whel turnynge aboute,</L>
<L>Tyl that,<NOTE PLACE="marg">[That I, Tib.]</NOTE> by reuoluc&iuml;oun,</L>
<L N="19672">I<NOTE PLACE="marg">[I <I>om</I>. Tib.]</NOTE> was cast fful lowe A-doun,</L>
<L>By power off that<NOTE PLACE="marg">[the Tib.]</NOTE> double quene;</L>
<L>ffor, I myghte me nat sustene,</L>
<L>In iupartye and in gret dred,</L>
<L N="19676">Wysshynge that I hadde be ded.<MILESTONE UNIT="Stowe folio" N="238b"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>And in trouble and gret peyne,<MILESTONE UNIT="Tib folio" N="62b"></L>
<L>Thanne I gan my sylff<NOTE PLACE="marg">[lyffe St.]</NOTE> compleyne,</L>
<L>Dysconsolaat off al vertu,</L>
<L N="19680">Only for lak off Grac&euml; Dieu,</L>
<L>That was whylom to me ffrendly,</L>
<L>Whom I ha lost thorgh my foly,<NOTE PLACE="marg">[Stowe]</NOTE></L>
<L>Wher-off I felte ful<NOTE PLACE="marg">[ful, <I>om</I>. Tib.]</NOTE> gret offence,</L>
<L N="19684">That I forsook so penytence,</L>
<L>Only (allas!) for lak off grace,</L>
<L>By hyr sharp&euml; heggh<NOTE PLACE="marg">[sharp highe St.]</NOTE> to passe,</L>
<L>Wher I myhte have had socours,</L>
<L N="19688">And medycyne to myn Errours,</L>
<L>By hyr spyrytual doctryne</L>
<L>ffro the wyche I dyde enclyne.</L>
<L>Allas, my woful aventure,<MILESTONE N="256a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="19692">That I lefft&euml; myn Armure</L>
<L>Behynd&euml; me, allas, in veyn!</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>But yiff I myhte hem gete ageyn,<NOTE PLACE="marg">[ageyn Tib., <I>hole in MS.</I> C., get them agayne St.]</NOTE></L>
<L N="19695">I shold&euml;<NOTE PLACE="marg">[would St.]</NOTE> lyue bettre in pes,</L>
<L>And n&oacute; mor ben so rek&euml;les;<NOTE PLACE="marg">[rekeles Tib., rekles C., recles St.]</NOTE></L>
<L>But, allas my woful ffaate!</L>
<L>I make my c&oacute;mpleynt al to late;</L>
<L>ffor I stonde in Iupartye</L>
<L N="19700">Only off deth, thorgh my ffolye.</L>
<L>Allas! what may I now best werche?</L>
<L>O sacramentys off the cherche,</L>
<L>I hope by grac&euml; wel certeyn,</L>
<L N="19704">I receyvede yow nat in veyn;</L>
<L>But now, allas, that I am falle,</L>
<L>I ha lost yow,<NOTE PLACE="marg">[yow yow C., &yogh;ou Tib., yow St.]</NOTE> on and<NOTE PLACE="marg">[and <I>om</I>. Tib.]</NOTE> alle,
<PB REF="00000634.tif" N="526"></L>
<L>And ha no sustentac&iuml;oun</L>
<L N="19708">In my skryppe nor my bordoun,</L>
<L>Wher-on that I may len&euml; me,</L>
<L>Toward Ierusalem the cyte.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>And thogh al day I studye <I>and</I> muse,</L>
<L N="19712">How shal I my sylff excuse,</L>
<L>Or what answere<NOTE PLACE="foot">Some leaves are out of Tib. A. vii, after these catchwords, 'Or what answere.'</NOTE> shal I make,</L>
<L>Off al that I ha vndertake,</L>
<L>And behihte in my corage,</L>
<L N="19716">To fulfyll&euml; my vyage,</L>
<L>What<NOTE PLACE="marg">[(? Whan,) what St.]</NOTE> fyrst I hadde inspecc&iuml;oun</L>
<L>Off that noble Royal toun,</L>
<L>Wyth-Inne A merour, shene and bryht,</L>
<L N="19720">Wych gaff to me so cler a lyht,</L>
<L>That ther-wyth-al I was a-noon<MILESTONE UNIT="Stowe folio" N="329a"></L>
<L>Ravyssh&euml;d, thyder for to gon;</L>
<L>But I may syng&euml; 'weyllaway';</L>
<L N="19724">I am arestyd on the way,</L>
<L>And dystourblyd her, wepynge.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>And whyl I lay thus c&oacute;mpleynynge,</L>
<L>And knewh non help&euml; nor respyt,</L>
<L N="19728">A-noon ther kam A dow&euml; whyht</L>
<L>Towardys me, by goddys wylle,<MILESTONE N="256b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>And brouht&euml; me a lytel bylle,</L>
<L N="19731">And vndyde yt in my syht;</L>
<L>And affter that she took hyr flyht,<NOTE PLACE="marg">[St. &amp; C.]</NOTE></L>
<L>And, fro me gan passe away.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>And I, with-out&euml; mor delay,</L>
<L>Gan the byll&euml; to vnfolde;</L>
<L N="19736">And ther-in I gan beholde,</L>
<L>How Grac&euml; dieu, to myn avayl,</L>
<L>In that bylle gaff me counsayl,</L>
<L>'That I sholde, ful humbl&euml;ly</L>
<L N="19740">Knelynge on my knes,<NOTE PLACE="marg">[on knes St.]</NOTE> deuoutly</L>
<L>Salu&euml;, with fful good avys,</L>
<L>The blyssede quen off paradys,</L>
<L N="19743">Wych bar, for Our savac&iuml;on,<NOTE PLACE="marg">[savation St.]</NOTE>
<PB REF="00000635.tif" N="527"></L>
<L>The ffrut off Our redempc&iuml;on<NOTE PLACE="marg">[redemtion St.]</NOTE></L>
<L>And the ffourme off thys prayere</L>
<L>Ys ywrete, as ye shal here,</L>
<L>In Ordre pleynly (who kan se)</L>
<L N="19748">By maner off An .A. b. c.;</L>
<L>And ye may knowe yt sone, and rede,</L>
<L>And seyn yt whan that ye ha nede.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>the translator<NOTE PLACE="marg">[St., <I>om</I>. C.]</NOTE>:</HEAD>
<L>And touchynge the translacioun</L>
<L N="19752">Off thys noble Orysoun,</L>
<L>Whylom (yiff I shal nat feyne)</L>
<L>The noble poete off Breteyne,</L>
<L>My mayster Chaucer, in hys tyme,</L>
<L N="19756">Affter the Frenche he dyde yt ryme,</L>
<L>Word by word, as in substaunce,</L>
<L>Ryght as yt ys ymad in Fraunce,</L>
<L>fful devoutly, in sentence,</L>
<L N="19760">In worshepe, and in reuerence</L>
<L>Off that noble hevenly quene,</L>
<L>Bothe moder and a mayd&euml; clene.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>And sythe, he dyde yt vndertake,</L>
<L N="19764">ffor to translate yt ffor hyr sake,</L>
<L>I pray thys [Quene] that ys the beste,<MILESTONE N="257a" UNIT="folio"><NOTE PLACE="marg">[C. &amp; St.]</NOTE></L>
<L>ffor to brynge hys soule at reste,<NOTE PLACE="marg">[C. &amp; St.]</NOTE></L>
<L>That he may, thorgh hir prayere,<MILESTONE UNIT="Stowe folio" N="329b"><NOTE PLACE="marg">[C. &amp; St.]</NOTE></L>
<L N="19768">Aboue the sterrys bryht and clere,<NOTE PLACE="marg">[C. &amp; St.]</NOTE></L>
<L>Off hyr mercy and hyr grace</L>
<L>Apere afforn hyr sonys fface,<NOTE PLACE="marg">[C. &amp; St.]</NOTE></L>
<L>Wyth seyntys euere, for A mem&oacute;rye,</L>
<L N="19772">Eternally to regne<NOTE PLACE="marg">[regrne C., rengne St.]</NOTE> in glorye.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>And ffor memoyre off that poete,</L>
<L>Wyth al hys rethoryk&euml;s swete,</L>
<L>That was the ffyrste in any age</L>
<L N="19776">That amendede our langage;</L>
<L>Therfore, as I am bounde off dette,</L>
<L>In thys book I wyl hym sette,</L>
<L>And ympen thys Oryson</L>
<L N="19780">Affter hys translac&iuml;on,</L>
<L>My purp&oacute;s to d&eacute;termyne,</L>
<L>That yt shal &eacute;nlwmyne
<PB REF="00000636.tif" N="528"></L>
<L>Thys lytyl book, Rud off makyng,</L>
<L N="19784">Wyth som clause off hys wrytyng.<NOTE PLACE="foot">Compare Scogan's quoting Chaucer's <I>Balade of Gentilnesse</I>, though without its Envoy, in his Poem to his pupils, Henry IV.'s sons. Thynne's <I>Chaucer</I>, 1532, leaf 380, back, col. 1; Urry's, p. 547, col. 1.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>And as he made thys Orysoun</L>
<L>Off ful devout entenc&iuml;oun,</L>
<L>And by maner off a prayere,</L>
<L N="19788">Ryht so I wyl yt settyn here,</L>
<L>That men may knowe and pleynly se</L>
<L>Off Our lady the .A. b. c.<NOTE PLACE="foot">The remainder of this leaf, 257 of the MS., is left blank, the scribe never having copied-in Chaucer's poem. It is printed above from the first of the Society's Parallel-Texts. John Stowe also left blank three leaves of his copy, putting A, B, C, etc., where the successive stanzas should start.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 TYPE="prayer">
<HEAD>Incipit carmen secundum ordinem Litterarum alphabeti. [MS. Ff. v. 30, Camb. Univ. Libr.,] </HEAD>
<LG N="1. A." TYPE="stanza">
<L><MILESTONE N="112b" UNIT="folio"> Al mihty and al merciable queene,<NOTE PLACE="marg">&para; Cap<SUP>m</SUP> lvii<SUP>m</SUP></NOTE></L>
<L>To whom &thorn;at al &thorn;is world fleeth for socour,</L>
<L>To haue relees of sinne, of sorwe and teene,</L>
<L N="19794">Gloriowse virgine, of all&euml; flour&euml;s flour,</L>
<L>To &thorn;ee j flee, confounded in errour;</L>
<L>Help and releeue, &thorn;ou mihti debonayre!</L>
<L>Haue mercy on my perilous langour!</L>
<L N="19798">Venquisshed me hath my cruelle aduersaire</L>
</LG>
<LG N="2. B." TYPE="stanza">
<L>Bountee so fix hath in &thorn;in herte his tente,</L>
<L>&THORN;at wel j wot thou wolt my socour bee.</L>
<L>&THORN;ou canst not warne him, &thorn;at with good entente</L>
<L N="19802">Axeth &thorn;in helpe; &thorn;in herte is ay so free;</L>
<L>&THORN;ou art largesse of pleyn felicitee,</L>
<L>Hauene of refute, of quiete and of reste.</L>
<L>Loo how &thorn;at theev&euml;s sevene chasen mee!</L>
<L N="19806">Help, lady briht, er &thorn;at my ship to-breste!
<PB REF="00000637.tif" N="529"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="3. C." TYPE="stanza">
<L>Comfort is noon, but in yow ladi deere;</L>
<L>ffor, loo, my sinne and my confus&iuml;oun</L>
<L>(Which ouhten not in &thorn;i presence appeere,)</L>
<L N="19810">Han take on me a greevous acc&imacr;oun.</L>
<L>Of verrey riht and desperac&iuml;oun;</L>
<L>And as bi riht, &thorn;ei mihten wel susteene</L>
<L>&THORN;at j were wur&thorn;i my dampnac&iuml;oun,</L>
<L N="19814">Nere merci of you, blisful heuene queene!</L>
</LG>
<LG N="4. D." TYPE="stanza">
<L>DOwte is &thorn;er noon, &thorn;ou queen of misericorde,</L>
<L>&thorn;at &thorn;ou nart cause of grace and merci heere;</L>
<L>God vouched saf, thoruh &thorn;ee, with us to accorde;</L>
<L N="19818">ffor, certes, crystes blisful mooder deere,</L>
<L>Were now &thorn;e bow&euml; bent in swich maneere<MILESTONE N="113a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>As it was first, of justice and of jre,</L>
<L>&THORN;e rihtful god, nolde of no mercy heere;</L>
<L N="19822">But thoruh &thorn;ee han we grace, as we desire.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="5. E." TYPE="stanza">
<L>Euere hath myn hope of refuit been in &thorn;ee;</L>
<L>ffor heer biforn, ful ofte, in many a wyse</L>
<L>Hast &thorn;ou to misericorde resceyued me;</L>
<L N="19826">But merci, ladi, at &thorn;e grete assyse,</L>
<L>Whan we shule come bifore &thorn;e hye iustyse!</L>
<L>So litel fruit shal &thorn;anne in me be founde,</L>
<L>&THORN;at, but &thorn;ou er &thorn;at day <SUP>1</SUP>me wel<NOTE PLACE="marg">[wel Sion MS.]</NOTE> chastyse<SUP>1</SUP>,<NOTE PLACE="marg">[1_1 <I>over an erasure</I>.]</NOTE></L>
<L N="19830">Of verrey riht my werk me wole confounde.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="6. F." TYPE="stanza">
<L>Fleeinge, j flee for socour to &thorn;i tente,</L>
<L>Me for to hide from tempeste ful of dreede,</L>
<L>Biseeching yow, &thorn;at ye you not absente</L>
<L N="19834">&thorn;ouh j be wikke, O, help yit at &thorn;is neede!</L>
<L>Al haue j ben a beste in wil and deede,</L>
<L>Yit, ladi, &thorn;ou me clo&thorn;&euml; with &thorn;i grace!</L>
<L>&THORN;in enemy and myn, (ladi, tak heede!)</L>
<L N="19838">Vn-to my deth, in poynt is me to chace.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="7. G." TYPE="stanza">
<L>Gloriows mayde and mooder, which &thorn;at neuere</L>
<L>Were bitter, nei&thorn;<I>er</I> in eer&thorn;&euml; nor in see,
<PB REF="00000638.tif" N="530"></L>
<L>But ful of swetnesse, &amp; of merci euere,</L>
<L N="19842">Help, &thorn;at my fader be not wroth with me!</L>
<L>Spek &thorn;ou! for j ne dar not him ysee.</L>
<L>So haue j doon in eer&thorn;e, (allas &thorn;er-while!)</L>
<L>&THORN;at certes, but if &thorn;ou my socour bee,</L>
<L N="19846">To stink eterne, he wole my gost exile.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="8. H." TYPE="stanza">
<L>He vouched saaf, tel him, as was his wille,<MILESTONE N="113b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Bicomen a man, to haue oure &aacute;lliaunce;</L>
<L>And with his precious blood he wrot &thorn;e bille</L>
<L N="19850">Vp-on &thorn;e crois, as general &aacute;cquitaunce</L>
<L>To euery Penitent in ful criaunce;</L>
<L>And &thorn;erfore, ladi briht, &thorn;ou for us praye!</L>
<L>&THORN;anne shalt &thorn;ou bo&thorn;&euml; stinte al his greuaunce,</L>
<L N="19854">And make oure foo to failen of his praye.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="9. I." TYPE="stanza">
<L>I wot it wel, &thorn;ou wolt ben oure socour,</L>
<L>&thorn;ou art so ful of bowntee in certeyn;</L>
<L>ffor, whan a soul&euml; falleth in errour,</L>
<L N="19858">&thorn;i pitee goth &amp; haleth him ayein;</L>
<L>&thorn;anne makest &thorn;ou his pees with his souereyn,</L>
<L>And bringest him out of &thorn;e crooked strete.</L>
<L>Who so &thorn;ee loueth, he shal not loue in veyn;</L>
<L N="19862">&THORN;at shal he fynde, as he &thorn;e lyf shal lete.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="10. K." TYPE="stanza">
<L>Kalendeer&euml;s enlumyn&euml;d ben &thorn;ei</L>
<L>&thorn;at in &thorn;is world ben lighted with &thorn;i name;</L>
<L>And who-so goth to yow &thorn;e riht&euml; wey,</L>
<L N="19866">Him thar not drede in soul&euml; to be lame.</L>
<L>Now, queen of comfort, sithe &thorn;ou art &thorn;at same</L>
<L>To whom j seech&euml; for my medicyne.</L>
<L>Lat not my foo no more my wounde entame<NOTE PLACE="marg">[MS. vntame]</NOTE>;</L>
<L N="19870">Myn hele, in-to &thorn;in hand, al j resyne.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="11. L." TYPE="stanza">
<L>Ladi, &thorn;i sorwe kan j not portreye</L>
<L>Vnder &thorn;e cros, ne his greevous penaunce;</L>
<L>But, for youre bo&thorn;&euml;s peyn&euml;s, j yow preye,</L>
<L N="19874">Lat not oure alder foo make his bobaunce,</L>
<L>&THORN;at he hath, in hise lyst&euml;s of mischaunce,<MILESTONE N="114a" UNIT="folio">
<PB REF="00000639.tif" N="531"></L>
<L>Conuict &thorn;at ye bo&thorn;e hau&euml; bouht so deere.</L>
<L>As j seide erst, &thorn;ou ground of oure substaunce,</L>
<L N="19878">Continue on us &thorn;i pitous eyen cleere!</L>
</LG>
<LG N="12. M." TYPE="stanza">
<L>Moises, &thorn;at sauh &thorn;e bush with flawm&euml;s rede</L>
<L>Brenninge, of which &thorn;er neuer a stikk&euml; brende,</L>
<L>was signe of &thorn;in vnwemmed maidenhede.</L>
<L N="19882">&THORN;ou art &thorn;e bush on which &thorn;er gan descende</L>
<L>&THORN;e Holigost, &thorn;e which &thorn;at Moyses wende</L>
<L>Had ben a-fyir: and &thorn;is was in figure.</L>
<L>Now, ladi, from &thorn;e fyir &thorn;ou us deufende,</L>
<L N="19886">which &thorn;at in helle eternalli shal dure!</L>
</LG>
<LG N="13. N." TYPE="stanza">
<L>Noble princesse, &thorn;at neuere haddest peere!</L>
<L>Certes, if any comfort in us bee,</L>
<L>&THORN;at cometh of &thorn;ee, &thorn;ou crist&euml;s mooder deere.</L>
<L N="19890">We han noon oo&thorn;<I>er</I> melodye or glee,</L>
<L>Vs to reioyse in oure aduersitee;</L>
<L>Ne aduocat noon, &thorn;at wole, &amp; dar so preye</L>
<L>ffor us, and &thorn;at for litel hire as yee,</L>
<L N="19894">&THORN;at helpen for an Aue-Marie or tweye.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="14. O." TYPE="stanza">
<L>O verrey light of eyen &thorn;at ben blynde!</L>
<L>O verrey lust of labour and distresse!</L>
<L>O tresoreere of bountee to mankynde!</L>
<L N="19898">&THORN;ee whom god ches to mooder for humblesse!</L>
<L>ffrom his ancille he mad&euml; &thorn;e maistresse</L>
<L>Of heuene &amp; eer&thorn;e, oure bille up for to beede.</L>
<L>&THORN;is world awaiteth euere on &thorn;i goodnesse,</L>
<L N="19902">ffor &thorn;ou ne failest neuere wight at neede.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="15. P." TYPE="stanza">
<L>Purpos I haue, sum time for to enquere,<MILESTONE N="114b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Wherfore and whi &thorn;e Holi Gost &thorn;ee souhte:</L>
<L>Whan Gabriell&euml;s vois cam to<NOTE PLACE="marg">[MS. vn to]</NOTE> &thorn;in ere,</L>
<L N="19906">He, not to werre us, swich a wunder wrouhte,</L>
<L>But for to saue us &thorn;at he sithen bouhte.</L>
<L>&THORN;anne needeth us no wepene us for to saue,</L>
<L>But oonly &thorn;er we diden not, as us ouhte,</L>
<L N="19910">Doo penitence, and merci axe and haue.
<PB REF="00000640.tif" N="532"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="16. Q." TYPE="stanza">
<L>Queen of comfort, yit whan j me bithinke</L>
<L>&thorn;at j agilt haue bo&thorn;&euml; him and &thorn;ee,</L>
<L>And &thorn;at my soule is wurthi for to sinke,</L>
<L N="19914">Allas, j, caityf, whider may I flee?</L>
<L>Who shal vn-to &thorn;i sone my men&euml; bee?</L>
<L>Who but &thorn;i-self, &thorn;at art of pitee welle.</L>
<L>&THORN;ou hast more reuthe on oure aduersitee,</L>
<L N="19918">&THORN;an in &thorn;is world miht any tung&euml; telle.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="17. R." TYPE="stanza">
<L>Redress&euml; me, mooder, and me chastise!</L>
<L>ffor certeynly, my faderes ch&aacute;stisinge,</L>
<L N="19921">&THORN;at dar j nouht abiden in no wise;</L>
<L>So hidous is hys<NOTE PLACE="marg">[MS. it is: <I>later</I> hys <I>in margin</I>]</NOTE> rihful rekenynge</L>
<L>Mooder, of whom oure merci gan to springe</L>
<L>Beth ye my juge, &amp; eek my soul&euml;s leche;</L>
<L>ffor euere in you is pitee h&aacute;boundinge</L>
<L N="19926">To eche, &thorn;at wole of pitee you biseeche.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="18. S." TYPE="stanza">
<L>Soth is, &thorn;at God ne granteth no pitee</L>
<L>With-out&euml; &thorn;ee; for God, of his goodnesse,</L>
<L>fforyiveth noon, but it like vn-to &thorn;ee.</L>
<L N="19930">He hath &thorn;ee maked, vicair &amp; maistresse</L>
<L>Of al &thorn;e world, and eek gou&eacute;rnowresse<MILESTONE N="115a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Of heuene; and he represseth his iustise</L>
<L>After &thorn;i wil; and &thorn;erfore, in witnesse,</L>
<L N="19934">He hath &thorn;ee corowned in so rial wise.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="19. T." TYPE="stanza">
<L>Temple deuout, &thorn;<I>er</I> god hath his woninge,</L>
<L>ffro which &thorn;ese misbileeued depriued<NOTE PLACE="marg">[pryued, John's and Laud MSS.]</NOTE> been!</L>
<L>To you, my soul&euml; penitent j bringe.</L>
<L N="19938">Resceyu&euml; me! I can no fer&thorn;ere fleen.</L>
<L>With thorn&euml;s venymous, O heuene queen,</L>
<L>ffor which &thorn;e eer&thorn;e acursed was ful yore,</L>
<L>I am so<NOTE PLACE="marg">[<I>om</I>. MS.]</NOTE> wounded, as ye may wel seen,</L>
<L N="19942">&thorn;at j am lost almost; it smert so sore.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="20. V." TYPE="stanza">
<L>Virgine, &thorn;at art so noble of apparaile,</L>
<L>And ledest us in-to &thorn;e hy&euml; tour
<PB REF="00000641.tif" N="533"></L>
<L>Of Paradys! &thorn;ou m&eacute; wisse, and counsaile</L>
<L N="19946">How j may haue &thorn;i grace &amp; &thorn;i socour,</L>
<L>All haue j ben in filthe and in errour.</L>
<L>Ladi, vn-to &thorn;at court &thorn;ou me aiourne,</L>
<L>&THORN;at cleped is &thorn;i bench, O fresh&euml;<NOTE PLACE="marg">[MS. fresh]</NOTE> flour,</L>
<L N="19950">&THORN;er-as &thorn;at merci euere shal soiourne.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="21. X = Ch." TYPE="stanza">
<L>Xpc<NOTE PLACE="marg">[=Christus]</NOTE> &thorn;i sone, &thorn;at in &thorn;is world alighte,</L>
<L>Vp-on &thorn;e cros to suffre his passioun,</L>
<L>And eek<NOTE PLACE="marg">[MS. eek suffred]</NOTE> &thorn;at Longius his hert&euml; pighte,</L>
<L N="19954">And made his hert&euml; blood to renne adoun:</L>
<L>And al was &thorn;is for my saluac&iuml;oun;</L>
<L>And j to him am fals, and eek vnkynde;</L>
<L>And yit he wole not my dampnac&iuml;oun:</L>
<L N="19958">&THORN;is thanke j yow, socour of al mankynde.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="22. Y." TYPE="stanza">
<L>Ysaac was figure of his deth, certeyn,<MILESTONE N="115b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>&THORN;at so fer-forth his fader wolde obeye,</L>
<L>&thorn;at him ne rouht&euml; no-thing to be slayn;</L>
<L N="19962">Riht soo &thorn;i sone lust, as a lamb, to deye.</L>
<L>Now, ladi ful of merci, j yow preye,</L>
<L>Sithe he his merci mesur&euml;d so large,</L>
<L>Be ye not skant! for alle we singe &amp; seye</L>
<L N="19966">&THORN;at ye ben from vengeaunc&euml; ay oure targe.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="23. Z." TYPE="stanza">
<L>Zach&aacute;r&iuml;e yow clepeth &thorn;e opene welle</L>
<L>To wassh&euml; sinful soule out of his gilt;</L>
<L>&THORN;erfore &thorn;is lessoun ouht j wel to telle,</L>
<L N="19970">&THORN;at, nere &thorn;i tender herte, we weren spilt.</L>
<L>Now, ladi bry&yogh;t&euml;,<NOTE PLACE="marg">[MS. <I>om</I>., bry&yogh;t Gy.]</NOTE> sithe &thorn;ou canst and wilt,</L>
<L>Ben to &thorn;e seed of Adam merci&aacute;ble,</L>
<L>And<NOTE PLACE="marg">[And John's MS. <I>om</I>.]</NOTE> bring us to &thorn;at pala&iuml;s &thorn;at is bilt</L>
<L N="19974">To penitentes &thorn;at ben to merci able! Amen!</L>
</LG>
<TRAILER>&para; Explicit carmen.</TRAILER>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 TYPE="pilgrim">
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Whan I, wyth good deuoc&iuml;oun,<MILESTONE UNIT="Stowe folio" N="330a"><MILESTONE N="258a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Hadd&euml;<NOTE PLACE="marg">[whan with g. d. I had St.]</NOTE> sayd thys Orysoun,</L>
<L>Off the ffloodys the gret&euml; Rage</L>
<L N="19978">Ganne somwhat to a-swage,
<PB REF="00000642.tif" N="534"></L>
<L>And the wyndes, for myn ese,</L>
<L>Gan in party to apese.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>The whel I lefft&euml;, off ffortune,</L>
<L N="19982">Wych selde in On&euml;<NOTE PLACE="marg">[one St., On C.]</NOTE> doth contune;</L>
<L>I swam forth, in ful gret ffer;</L>
<L>I knew no way&euml;, her ne ther;</L>
<L>Tyl at the laste, off grace, I fond</L>
<L N="19986">A verray lytel hyl off sond,</L>
<L>And thyderward I gan me dresse,</L>
<L>To rest&euml; me for werynesse.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>And there, in soth, A-noon I ffond</L>
<L N="19990">A lady wrytynge in the sond,</L>
<L>Lokynge toward the ffyrmament</L>
<L>Thorgh a lytel instrument.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>A-nother lady I sawh ek ther,</L>
<L N="19994">That lenede hyre on A red sper:</L>
<L>I myht&euml; nat beholde her wel,</L>
<L>ffor I sawh but the halvendel</L>
<L>Off hyr body, nor hyr fasown;</L>
<L N="19998">And (as to myn inspecc&iuml;oun,)<MILESTONE UNIT="Stowe folio" N="330b"></L>
<L>In hyr hand she held a spere,</L>
<L>Lokynge vp on the sterrys clere.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>And doun I sat, and gan beholde</L>
<L N="20002">Thys .ij. ladyes off wych I tolde;</L>
<L>ffor I was wery off travaylle.</L>
<L>And yiff yt myht&euml; me avaylle,</L>
<L>I dyde also my besy peyne</L>
<L N="20006">To sen the maner off hem tweyne.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>And to hyr&euml; (A-noon ryht,)</L>
<L>That was but halff On<NOTE PLACE="marg">[one St.]</NOTE> in my syht,</L>
<L>I sayde a-non as ye shal here,</L>
<L N="20010">Somwhat abaysshed off my chere:</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>[The Pilgrim:]</HEAD>
<L>"Tel on," quod I, "lat me se;</L>
<L>Be ther swych monstres in thys<NOTE PLACE="marg">[ye St.]</NOTE> Se<MILESTONE N="258b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Abydynge, lyk as ye do seme?</L>
<L N="20014">ffor I kan noon other deme,</L>
<L>But, monstres that ye shold&euml; be,</L>
<L>By sygn&euml;s outward that I se.</L>
<L>Yiff thow mayst spek&euml;, nat ne spare,
<PB REF="00000643.tif" N="535"></L>
<L N="20018">"The trouthe to me for to declare."</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>Astrology:<NOTE PLACE="marg">[St., <I>om</I>. C.]</NOTE></HEAD>
<L>Quod she, 'I may spek&euml; wel,</L>
<L>And I ha lost ek neueradel</L>
<L>Off my spech&euml; nor language.</L>
<L N="20022">And thogh I shewe to thy vysage,</L>
<L>My-sylff, but halff on, in thy syht,</L>
<L>Wych halff (who so loke a-ryht)</L>
<L>Ys ryht noble and honurable,</L>
<L N="20026">And also ryht Auct&oacute;rysable.'</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>Pilgrime:<NOTE PLACE="marg">[St., <I>om</I>. C.]</NOTE></HEAD>
<L>"Touchyng thys halff, tel on clerly,</L>
<L>What maner thyng ye mene ther-by.</L>
<L>The tother part, what sholde yt be,</L>
<L N="20030">Wych as now I may nat se?"</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>Astrology:<NOTE PLACE="marg">[St.,? striogye (<I>in margin</I>) C.]</NOTE></HEAD>
<L>'Certys, (thogh thow yt nat espye,)</L>
<L>She ys callyd Astronomye,</L>
<L>Wych ys wont to wake a-nyht,</L>
<L N="20034">To loke vp on the sterrys bryht.</L>
<L>Off whom, whylom thus stood the cas:</L>
<L>In Egypt ffyrst she norysshed was,</L>
<L>Of thylk&euml; noble prudent kyng</L>
<L N="20038">Wych excellede in konnyng,</L>
<L>And was callyd (as thow mayst se)</L>
<L>The noble wys&euml; Tholomee,</L>
<L>(So thys clerkys Olde hym calle,)</L>
<L N="20042">That ffond the cours off sterrys alle,<MILESTONE UNIT="Stowe folio" N="331a"></L>
<L>Mevynge in ther bryht&euml; sperys,</L>
<L>Bothe be day&euml;s and by yerys;</L>
<L>How that they mev&euml;, long or sone,</L>
<L N="20046">And the cours off sonne and mone;<MILESTONE N="259a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>ffond out the eclypses (by resoun)<NOTE PLACE="marg">[C. &amp; St.]</NOTE></L>
<L>In the tayl off the dragoun,<NOTE PLACE="marg">[C. &amp; St.]</NOTE></L>
<L>Or in the hed (with-out&euml; lake);<NOTE PLACE="marg">[C. &amp; St.]</NOTE></L>
<L N="20050">The cours ek off the zodyake.<NOTE PLACE="marg">[C. &amp; St.]</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>'And many mo conclus&iuml;ouns<NOTE PLACE="marg">[C. &amp; St.]</NOTE></L>
<L>Off hevenly transmutac&iuml;ouns</L>
<L>He ffond al out, by gret labour;</L>
<L N="20054">Wher-ffore, worshep and gret honour,
<PB REF="00000644.tif" N="536"></L>
<L>'Thys worthy kyng gat in hys tyme,</L>
<L>Wych wer to long for me to ryme.</L>
<L>The causes and theffectys alle,</L>
<L N="20058">Wych off her mevyng shold&euml; falle</L>
<L>By ther mevyng, (with-out&euml;<NOTE PLACE="marg">[with out C., St.]</NOTE> lak:)</L>
<L>Thys ys the halff that I off spak;</L>
<L>And, al thys ys my partye,</L>
<L N="20062">Wych I calle Astronomye.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>'I sey also (yiff thow take hed,)</L>
<L>That ther be (yt ys no dred)</L>
<L>Many constellac&iuml;ouns</L>
<L N="20066">And many varyac&iuml;ouns;</L>
<L>And lyk affter ther dyfferences,</L>
<L>They yive in erth&euml; influ&eacute;nces,</L>
<L>Many dysposic&iuml;ouns</L>
<L N="20070">And dyvers operac&iuml;ouns.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>'And yiff I durst&euml; speke in pleyn,</L>
<L>And the trouthe apertly seyn,</L>
<L>I wolde affermen vn-to the,</L>
<L N="20074">To calle al thys 'Necessyte,'</L>
<L>Or name yt 'Dysposic&iuml;oun,'</L>
<L>Or 'Naturel Domynyoun.'</L>
<L>And therfor, toucyhng al thys Art,</L>
<L N="20078">Namyd for the tother part,</L>
<L>I am callyd 'Astrologye;'</L>
<L>The tother part, 'Astronomye.'</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>'And be-cause I tell&euml; more</L>
<L N="20082">Than Astron&oacute;mye dyde off yore,</L>
<L>Off ffolk to me-ward envyous,</L>
<L>Calle me 'superstycyous,'<MILESTONE N="259b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Be-cause off the dyfference,</L>
<L N="20086">That I glos&euml; the scyence,<NOTE PLACE="marg">[C. &amp; St.]</NOTE></L>
<L>And expoune it (fer &amp; nere)<NOTE PLACE="marg">[C. &amp; St.]</NOTE></L>
<L>Ryht as me lyst, on my manere;<NOTE PLACE="marg">[C. &amp; St.]</NOTE></L>
<L>And after myne opinioun,<NOTE PLACE="marg">[C. &amp; St.]</NOTE></L>
<L N="20090">Expoun&euml; the conclusyons,<MILESTONE UNIT="Stowe folio" N="331b"></L>
<L>And preve them out, fro day to day,<NOTE PLACE="marg">[C. &amp; St.]</NOTE></L>
<L>Who that euere ther-to seyth nay.<NOTE PLACE="marg">[C. &amp; St.]</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>'ffor, I pray the, lat now se,<NOTE PLACE="marg">[C. &amp; St.]</NOTE></L>
<L N="20094">How myhte yt falle, or elles be,<NOTE PLACE="marg">[C. &amp; St.]</NOTE>
<PB REF="00000645.tif" N="537"></L>
<L>'ffor to deme yt off resoun</L>
<L>By cler<NOTE PLACE="marg">[clere St.]</NOTE> demonstrac&iuml;oun,</L>
<L>Her in thys world, (by good avys,)</L>
<L N="20098">On ys a fool, A-nother wys;</L>
<L>Thys man glad, that man Irous;</L>
<L>He lovynge, he envyous;</L>
<L>On, ffrownyng, lokyng nat ffayre;</L>
<L N="20102">A-nother, off cher ys debonayre;</L>
<L>A-nother, off port ys gracyous;</L>
<L>A-nother, contrayre and d&eacute;spytous;<NOTE PLACE="marg">[contrary &amp; dispitious St.]</NOTE></L>
<L>On, stedefast, A-nother vnstable;</L>
<L N="20106">A-nother, in lou&euml; varyable.</L>
<L>On wyl do ryht, A-nother wrong;</L>
<L>Thys man ys ffeble, that man ys strong,</L>
<L>Thys man pensyff, that man ys sad,</L>
<L N="20110">He thys ys wroth, he that ys glad;</L>
<L>Thys man hasty in werkynge,</L>
<L>Another ys soffte and Abydynge;</L>
<L>Thys man ys hevy, that man ys lyht;</L>
<L N="20114">Thys goth be day, that man be nyht;</L>
<L>On vseth trouthe, he trecherye,</L>
<L>And to stele by Roberye.</L>
<L>O man ys trewe, A-nother ffals,</L>
<L N="20118">And somme Arn hangyd by the hals;</L>
<L>And (who lyst loken her-wyth-al,)</L>
<L>O man ys gret, A-nother smal;</L>
<L>Som man loueth wysdam and scyence;<MILESTONE N="260a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="20122">Som man, ryot and dyspence;</L>
<L>Som man ys large, som man ys hard;</L>
<L>Som man ys ek a gret nygard;<NOTE PLACE="marg">[C. &amp; St.]</NOTE></L>
<L>He<NOTE PLACE="marg">[his St.]</NOTE> thys A coward, he that ys bold;</L>
<L N="20126">And som man halt a good houshold;</L>
<L>And somme, off hertly indygence,</L>
<L>Ar fful streyhte off ther dyspence;</L>
<L>And som man, durynge al hys lyff,</L>
<L N="20130">Kan nat lyv&euml; but in stryff.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>'Wher-off komen al thys dyfferencys,</L>
<L>But off hevenly influencys,</L>
<L>By gouernaunce (who loketh al)</L>
<L N="20134">Off the bodyes celestyal?
<PB REF="00000646.tif" N="538"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>'And I dar also specefye,<MILESTONE UNIT="Stowe folio" N="332a"></L>
<L>As the planetys dyversefye</L>
<L>Abou&euml;, (who so koud&euml; knowe,)</L>
<L N="20138">So the bodyes her doun lowe</L>
<L>(Affter myn oppynyoun)</L>
<L>ffolwe ther constellac&iuml;oun.</L>
<L>ffor, thys philisoffres alle,</L>
<L N="20142">The 'secounde causys' dyde hem calle:</L>
<L>Affter ther name (in wordys ffewe)</L>
<L>Ther effectys they must shewe,</L>
<L>Or elles I wolde boldly seyn,</L>
<L N="20146">They tooke ther nam&euml; but in veyn.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>'The creatour, at begynnyng,</L>
<L>Whan he hem made in hys werkyng,</L>
<L>He gaff hem power, (clerk&euml;s ffynde)</L>
<L N="20150">Euerych to werkyn in hys kynde,</L>
<L>And for to mev&euml; to som ffyn.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>'And as the doctour seynt Awstyn</L>
<L>Recordeth shortly in sentence,</L>
<L N="20154">The lord, off hys magnyfycence,</L>
<L>Suffreth hem, (who-euere muse)</L>
<L>Affter ther kynde her cours to vse.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>'And dam&euml; Fortune ek also,</L>
<L N="20158">And hyr Karybdis<NOTE PLACE="marg">[carbdes St.]</NOTE> both&euml; two,<MILESTONE N="260b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>With al hyr domynac&iuml;oun,<NOTE PLACE="marg">[C. &amp; St.]</NOTE></L>
<L>Stant vnder subiecc&iuml;oun<NOTE PLACE="marg">[C. &amp; St.]</NOTE></L>
<L>Off the hevene, off verray ryht,<NOTE PLACE="marg">[C. &amp; St.]</NOTE></L>
<L N="20162">Al<SUP>2</SUP> hyr power and hyr myght</L>
<L>Ys<SUP>2</SUP><NOTE PLACE="marg">[2_2 <I>om</I>. St.]</NOTE> youe to hyre at certeyn tymes,</L>
<L>Bothe at Eve and ek at prymes,</L>
<L>To executen hyr<NOTE PLACE="marg">[ther St.]</NOTE> power</L>
<L N="20166">Vnder the sterrys bryht and cler:</L>
<L>Bothe hyr dedys infortunat,</L>
<L>And ek hyr werkys ffortunat,</L>
<L>Bothe to lawhen and to wepe.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="20170">'And, men muste her<NOTE PLACE="marg">[ther St.]</NOTE> houres kepe,</L>
<L>To rekne al the day&euml;s sevene</L>
<L>Affter the mevyng off the hevene;</L>
<L>Wych be goode, And wych contrayre,</L>
<L N="20174">Wych amende, and wych a-payre,
<PB REF="00000647.tif" N="539"></L>
<L>'Affter the sterrys hem assure</L>
<L>In good, or in Evele Aventure;</L>
<L>Wych hourys ben happy And Ewrous,</L>
<L N="20178">And wych also malic&iuml;ous.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>'And shortly, (who consydreth al)</L>
<L>Affter the bodyes celestyal,</L>
<L>Lych as they her cours done holde,</L>
<L N="20182">And the Stocyen&euml;s<NOTE PLACE="marg">[Stocyens C., St.]</NOTE> wolde<MILESTONE UNIT="Stowe folio" N="332b"></L>
<L>Holden with me, (yiff they wer here,)</L>
<L>In ther bookys as they lere.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>'And Mathesis wolde conferme</L>
<L N="20186">Al that euere I afferme,</L>
<L>Make a confyrmac&iuml;oun</L>
<L>Vp-on myn oppynyoun,</L>
<L>By ther Argument&euml;s cler.</L>
<L N="20190">And the poete ek, Homer,</L>
<L>Whylom merour off elloquence,</L>
<L>Contentyth ek to thys sentence:</L>
<L>He seyth in hys wrytyng thus:</L>
<L N="20194">At rysyng vp off Phebus,</L>
<L>That whan hys bemys y-reysed be,</L>
<L>He yiveth ech man volunte<MILESTONE N="261a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>And wyl (ther kan no man sey nay,)</L>
<L N="20198">How he shal gouerne hym that day.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>'And affter Phebus ordynaunce,</L>
<L>Somme ha sorwe, <I>and</I> som plesaunce;</L>
<L>Thys poete (in conclus&iuml;oun)</L>
<L N="20202">Leueth<NOTE PLACE="marg">[levethe St.]</NOTE> on thys oppynyoun:</L>
<L>And what-so other folkys do,</L>
<L>I leue ther-on my sylff also;</L>
<L>And my levyng that thow sest here,</L>
<L N="20206">Yfoundyd ys on a red sper;</L>
<L>And yiff thow kanst yt wel espye,</L>
<L>My leuyng doth so sygnefye.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>'Now tel on, and thyn hert&euml; bolde,</L>
<L>Wych&euml;<NOTE PLACE="marg">[whiche St., wych C.]</NOTE> party thow wylt holde,</L>
<L N="20211">And make a demonstrac&iuml;oun</L>
<L>Affter thyn oppynyoun;</L>
<L>And as thow hast her-in creaunce,</L>
<L N="20214">Outher ffeyth or affyaunce.'
<PB REF="00000648.tif" N="540"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>The Pilgrim:<NOTE PLACE="marg">[St., <I>om</I>. C.]</NOTE></HEAD>
<L>Whan I herde hyr wordys alle,</L>
<L>Off look and cher I gan to palle,</L>
<L>And wex abaysshed mor and more,</L>
<L N="20218">And be-gan to syh&euml; sore;</L>
<L>Thoghte in myn herte, off gret&euml;<NOTE PLACE="marg">[gret C., St.]</NOTE> ffer,</L>
<L>I was nat passyd al daunger<NOTE PLACE="inter">[Line wanting in both MSS., tho' neither has a gap.]</NOTE></L>
<L N="20222">As yet, in thys streyth passage;<NOTE PLACE="inter">[Blank in MS. for an Illumination.]</NOTE></L>
<L>Thouhte also, (so god me rede!)</L>
<L>That I hadd&euml; ful gret nede,</L>
<L>Touchynge thys oppynyoun,</L>
<L N="21226">To ax&euml; counsayl off Resoun.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>I answerde to that party:</L>
<L>"Thow spekyst," quod I, "ful largely.</L>
<L>God graunt&euml; me (to myn entent)<MILESTONE UNIT="Stowe folio" N="333a"></L>
<L N="20230">In thys mater A-vys&euml;ment,</L>
<L>My wordys so, for texpresse,</L>
<L>That ffynally I may represse</L>
<L>Thyn errours and thyn ffolye,<MILESTONE N="261b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="20234">Groundyd on Astrologye,</L>
<L>Wych ne be nat vertuous,</L>
<L>ffor they be superstyc&iuml;ous.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>"Yt semeth as thow haddest ben</L>
<L N="20238">Hih in the hevene, for to sen</L>
<L>Al about&euml;, nyh and fferre,</L>
<L>And axyd ther, off euery sterre,</L>
<L>Ther coursys and ther moc&iuml;ouns</L>
<L N="20242">And ther reuoluc&iuml;ouns,</L>
<L>And dyscuryd ther secres</L>
<L>To the, and al ther pryvytes,</L>
<L>Wych ar good, wych ar malygne,</L>
<L N="20246">Whan they shal entren any sygne,</L>
<L>Or entren any manc&iuml;oun,</L>
<L>Ther to haue domynyoun.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>"I trowe, thow wylt th&eacute; makyn bold,</L>
<L N="20250">How that Venus hath the told</L>
<L>The tyme assygn&euml;d, whan that she</L>
<L>Shal, next, conyoyned be
<PB REF="00000649.tif" N="541"></L>
<L>"And declaryd to the / the day</L>
<L N="20254">Whan that she shal parte away</L>
<L>ffro mars, that ys hyr own&euml; knyht:</L>
<L>In hevene thow haddyst her-off a syht.</L>
<L>Wher wer thow euere so pryve,</L>
<L N="20258">Or with the sterrys so secre,</L>
<L>To knowe the power and the myght</L>
<L>That god hath yove to hem off ryht?</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>"I dar affermen her a-noon,</L>
<L N="20262">Sterrys and planetys, euerychon,</L>
<L>Be soget to hys power royal</L>
<L>And to hys ryht Imperyal.</L>
<L>What-so-euere thow kanst allegge,</L>
<L N="20266">They ha noon other pryvylegge,</L>
<L>ffraunchys&euml; nor commyss&iuml;oun,</L>
<L>But vnder hys domynac&iuml;oun;</L>
<L>And vn-to that (I dar wel seye)</L>
<L N="20270">Alle the planetys muste obeye,</L>
<L>And fro that ordre neuere varye,<MILESTONE N="262a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Who-euere afferm&euml; the contr&aacute;rye."</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>[Astrology.]</HEAD>
<L>Quod she a-noon ageyn to me,</L>
<L N="20274">'Neuer in my lyff ne dyde I se</L>
<L>No pryvylege (touchyng thys thyng)<MILESTONE UNIT="Stowe folio" N="333b"></L>
<L>Yove<NOTE PLACE="marg">[gyven St.]</NOTE> to the sterrys in ther mevyng;</L>
<L>Nor, in the heuene so hih and fferre,</L>
<L N="20278">I spak<NOTE PLACE="marg">[spake St.]</NOTE> neuere with no sterre;</L>
<L>Nor I nat know&euml; ther secres,<NOTE PLACE="marg">[secretes St.]</NOTE></L>
<L>Ther mevyng, nor ther pryvytes,</L>
<L>Nor how ther cours aboff<NOTE PLACE="marg">[<I>or</I> aloff C., aloft St.]</NOTE> ys lad,</L>
<L N="20282">But as I haue in bookys rad,</L>
<L>And ther conceyved by wrytyng,</L>
<L>Bothe off her cours <I>and</I> ther mevyng.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>'And also long experyence</L>
<L N="20286">Hath yove to me ther-off scyence;</L>
<L>Ek old&euml; clerk&euml;s her-to-fforn&mdash;</L>
<L>That wer ful longe or thow wer born&mdash;</L>
<L>Yt dyde ynowh to hem suffyse,</L>
<L N="20290">To knowe the maner and the guyse</L>
<L>Off grete effectys off the hevene,
<PB REF="00000650.tif" N="542"></L>
<L>'And off the<NOTE PLACE="marg">[the St., <I>om</I>. C.]</NOTE> planetys all&euml; sevene.</L>
<L>Ther-in, ful myche they sette her lust,</L>
<L N="20294">And ther-in was fynally<NOTE PLACE="marg">[fynally was St.]</NOTE> her trust,</L>
<L>As they by wrytyng specefye.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>'And I ful<NOTE PLACE="marg">[will St.]</NOTE> gretly ek affye</L>
<L>In the hevenly moc&iuml;ouns</L>
<L N="20298">And in ther reuoluc&iuml;ouns,</L>
<L>Conceyvynge that, by ther mevyng,</L>
<L>That, alone<NOTE PLACE="marg">[tha alone St.]</NOTE> the myhty kyng,</L>
<L>Ys no party (fer nor ner)</L>
<L N="20302">The mor excludyd fro hys power,</L>
<L>Nor exempt in no degre</L>
<L>ffrom hys imperyal powste;</L>
<L>But semblably (and thys ys soth)</L>
<L N="20306">As a kyng off custom doth,</L>
<L>Off hys myght and hih renoun<MILESTONE N="262b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Graunteth a commyss&iuml;oun</L>
<L>ffor a space, or al ther lyves,</L>
<L N="20310">To hys prov&oacute;stys<NOTE PLACE="marg">[provosts St.]</NOTE> or bayllyves;</L>
<L>Yet for al that, in no manere</L>
<L>He restreyneth nat hys powere.'</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>[The Pilgrim:]</HEAD>
<L>"Thyn answere, I conceyve yt wel,</L>
<L N="20314">Wych may suffys&euml; neueradel,</L>
<L>No mor than may a red&euml;<NOTE PLACE="marg">[reade St., red C.]</NOTE> sper</L>
<L>Suffyse off myght, nor off power</L>
<L>(Who-so the trouthe espy&euml; konne)</L>
<L>To endure to bern<NOTE PLACE="marg">[bere St.]</NOTE> A tonne.<MILESTONE UNIT="Stowe folio" N="334a"></L>
<L N="20319">ffor yiff the kyng (shortly to devyse)</L>
<L>Hadde yove<NOTE PLACE="marg">[have gyve St.]</NOTE> hys power in swych wyse</L>
<L>To hys prov&oacute;stys,<NOTE PLACE="marg">[provost C.]</NOTE> and ek also</L>
<L>To hys baylyv&euml;s,<NOTE PLACE="marg">[baylys C., baylyvs St.]</NOTE> both&euml; two,</L>
<L N="20323">And hadde hem mad ther-off certeyn,</L>
<L>And myghte yt nat repelle ageyn,</L>
<L>Thanne he were (to our purpos)</L>
<L N="20326">Dysbarryd, and from hys power clos.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>"And evene lyk (to our entent)</L>
<L>Off planetys and the fyrmament,</L>
<L>And off sterrys the moc&iuml;oun,</L>
<L N="20330">Yiff they hadde commyss&iuml;oun
<PB REF="00000651.tif" N="543"></L>
<L>"Vp-on al thyng,<NOTE PLACE="marg">[thynge St.]</NOTE> hih and lowe,</L>
<L>Her in erth&euml; that men knowe,</L>
<L>Bothe to shette and ek vnclose,</L>
<L N="20334">And as hym lyst, ffor to dyspose</L>
<L>At ther own&euml; volunte,</L>
<L>That yt myhte noon other be,</L>
<L>But as the hevene (in substaunce)</L>
<L N="20338">Lyst to tourne the ordynaunce;</L>
<L>Than muste ther power (who kan se)</L>
<L>Be fallen off necessyte,</L>
<L>As the sterrys wolde ordeyne:</L>
<L N="20342">The kyng ne myght yt nat restreyne;</L>
<L>ffor he, off verray volunte,</L>
<L>Hath wyth-drawen hys powste.<MILESTONE N="263a" UNIT="folio"><NOTE PLACE="marg">[C. &amp; St.]</NOTE></L>
<L>Thus thow woldest hym exclude,<NOTE PLACE="marg">[C. &amp; St.]</NOTE></L>
<L N="20346">And by thy wordys ek conclude,<NOTE PLACE="marg">[C. &amp; St.]</NOTE></L>
<L>That all&euml; thyng&euml;s that her be,</L>
<L>Sholde fall&euml; off necessyte,</L>
<L>Wherby (who that kan dyscerne)</L>
<L N="20350">The lord that al hath to gouerne,</L>
<L>Sholde, by hys commyss&iuml;oun,</L>
<L>Restreyne hys domynac&iuml;oun,</L>
<L>Wych ys A maner impossible,</L>
<L N="20354">And as to me, no thyng credyble,</L>
<L>What-euere her-on thow lyst to seyn.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>"But I wyl answere the ageyn,</L>
<L>Touchyng the hevenly moc&iuml;ouns,</L>
<L N="20358">Ther power and ther commyss&iuml;ouns,</L>
<L>Ther influencys and ther mevyng:</L>
<L>Al thys, they haue yt off the<NOTE PLACE="marg">[theyr C.]</NOTE> kyng</L>
<L>And off the lord (who kan concerne)</L>
<L N="20362">That hevene and erth&euml; doth gouerne.</L>
<L>And trewly, in A-nother wyse</L>
<L>Than thy sylff dost her<NOTE PLACE="marg">[here St.]</NOTE> devyse.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>"Touchyng ther power, (tak good heede,</L>
<L N="20366">In Genesis thow mayst yt rede;)<MILESTONE UNIT="Stowe folio" N="334b"></L>
<L>He ordeynede sterrys for to shyne,</L>
<L>To yiv&euml; lyht, and enlwmyne,</L>
<L>And to the world, by ther bryhtnesse,</L>
<L N="20370">To yiv&euml; coumfort and clernesse;
<PB REF="00000652.tif" N="544"></L>
<L>"And to dyscerne, (who loke a-ryht)</L>
<L>To knowe the day&euml;s wel fro nyht,</L>
<L>He sette hem ther (by certeyn lynes)</L>
<L N="20374">As for markys and for sygnes:</L>
<L>Lat the byble wel be souht,</L>
<L>And other thyng thow fyndest nouht.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="20377">"Off the power that he hem sette,</L>
<L>Ther-off he wyle no thyng hem<NOTE PLACE="marg">[hem <I>om</I>. St.]</NOTE> lette;</L>
<L>But shortly, al ther gouernaunce</L>
<L>Abydeth vnder hys puissaunce;</L>
<L>He byndythe,<NOTE PLACE="marg">[St., vndoth C.]</NOTE> and vnbynt also;<MILESTONE N="263b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="20382">What euere hym lyst, that mot be do;</L>
<L>And O word that her ys sayd,</L>
<L>(And ful not&aacute;ble to be layd,</L>
<L>To be put in r&eacute;membraunce,</L>
<L N="20386">My conclusioun to Avaunce,)</L>
<L>That the sterrys ffer above,</L>
<L>W&eacute;r only ffor sygn&euml;s yove,</L>
<L>That thyng&euml;s (who so lyst to se)</L>
<L N="20390">Wyth hem shold&euml; markyd be.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>"And who that euere ageyn malygnes,</L>
<L>They be but markys, nor but sygnes</L>
<L>Off thylk&euml; lord celestyal,</L>
<L N="20394">That syt above, and rewleth al,</L>
<L>Sterrys and constellac&iuml;ouns.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>"And as in cytes and in townys,</L>
<L>Maystres off dyvers crafftys</L>
<L N="20398">Hang out, on polys<NOTE PLACE="marg">[bolys St.]</NOTE> and on rafftys,</L>
<L>Dyuers sygnys hih and lowe,</L>
<L>Wher-by that men ther crafft may knowe;&mdash;</L>
<L>As somme off hem hang out lyouns,</L>
<L N="20402">Somme Eglys and gryffouns,</L>
<L>Peynted on bordys and on stagys,</L>
<L>Dyuers Armys and ym&aacute;ges</L>
<L>(In cytes mo than .ix. or ten,)</L>
<L N="20406">Wherby men knowe thys<NOTE PLACE="marg">[thes St.]</NOTE> craffty men;</L>
<L>But wher-so-euere they hangyd be,</L>
<L>Hih aloffte, that men may se,</L>
<L>He wer A ffool, and nothyng sage,</L>
<L N="20410">That wold&euml; deme in hys corage,
<PB REF="00000653.tif" N="545"></L>
<L>"That thys markys, on pool or rafft,</L>
<L>Kan no thyng medlen off the crafft,</L>
<L>Nor helpe ther-to, (yt ys no ffayl,)</L>
<L N="20414">Nor to the craffty men avayl.<MILESTONE UNIT="Stowe folio" N="335a"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>"And at tavernys (with-out&euml; wene)</L>
<L><NOTE PLACE="foot">Tib. A vii. starts again with leaf 63.</NOTE>Thys tooknys nor thys bowys<NOTE PLACE="marg">[C. Tib. leves St.]</NOTE> grene,</L>
<L>Thogh they shew&euml; ffressh and ffayre,</L>
<L N="20418">The wyn they mende nat, nor apeyre,<MILESTONE N="264a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Nor medle no thyng (thys the ffyn)</L>
<L>Off the sale nor<NOTE PLACE="marg">[more Tib.]</NOTE> off the wyn,</L>
<L>N&oacute;r hath nothyng to gov&eacute;rne,</L>
<L N="20422">Off the celer nor taverne:</L>
<L>By hem ys no thyng do nor let;</L>
<L>They b&eacute; ther, but for markys set.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>"And semblably, to Our entent,</L>
<L N="20426">The sterrys and the ffyrmament,</L>
<L>Planetys and constellac&iuml;ouns,</L>
<L>Cerclys, sygnes, nor mans&iuml;ouns,</L>
<L>Ar (to speke in wordys ffewe)</L>
<L N="20430">No-thyng but markys, for to shewe</L>
<L>Off the workman, and off<NOTE PLACE="marg">[off <I>om</I>. Tib.]</NOTE> the lord</L>
<L>That made al thyng with A word.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>"In erthe, ther ys no taverner,</L>
<L N="20434">That couchyd hath in hys celer</L>
<L>So many wyn&euml;s red nor whyht,</L>
<L>Nor other drynk&euml;s off delyt,</L>
<L>As thys lord hath Bever&aacute;ges</L>
<L N="20438">Off Grace,<NOTE PLACE="marg">[gracys St.]</NOTE> y-mad ffor sondry ages.</L>
<L>And off al thys, (who lyst to se,)</L>
<L>The sterrys, no-thyng but toknys be,</L>
<L>That al our goodys, her doun lowe,</L>
<L N="20442">Kome fro that lord (who lyst to knowe);</L>
<L>And alle the gyfftys ek off grace</L>
<L>Descend&euml; from that hevenly place.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>"He partyth hys gyfftys dyversly,</L>
<L N="20446">And, off hys grace and hys mercy,</L>
<L>All folkys ha suffysaunce,</L>
<L>Plente ynowh, and h&aacute;bondaunce;</L>
<L>ffor, off hys grace (as yt ys skyl,)
<PB REF="00000654.tif" N="546"></L>
<L N="20450">"He parteth, as yt ys hys wyl.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>"Therfor lat grac&euml; be thy guyde,<MILESTONE UNIT="Tib folio" N="63b"></L>
<L>And al thy resouns set asyde;</L>
<L>And wen&euml; nat, in thyn entent,</L>
<L N="20454">The sterrys nor the ffyrmament<MILESTONE N="264b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Ha no vertu (with-out&euml; glose)</L>
<L>Good or evel, for<NOTE PLACE="marg">[for <I>om</I>. Tib.]</NOTE> to dyspose,</L>
<L>But as the lord celestyal</L>
<L N="20458">Ordeyneth, that gov&eacute;rneth al.</L>
<L>Wher-for, beholde and loke a-ryht,</L>
<L>And deme off resoun in thy syht,</L>
<L>And be with me nat evele apayd.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="20462">"Yiff yt wer soth that thow hast sayd,</L>
<L>Yt wer as<NOTE PLACE="marg">[all St.]</NOTE> good (thys, the cheff)</L>
<L>To ben a robbere and a theff,</L>
<L>(By the resouns that thow gan,<NOTE PLACE="marg">[began St.]</NOTE>)</L>
<L N="20466">As for to ben A trew&euml; man,</L>
<L>ffolwynge, off necessyte,</L>
<L>That yt myhte noon other be;<MILESTONE UNIT="Stowe folio" N="335b"></L>
<L>The sterrys, the hevene, both&euml; two,</L>
<L N="20470">Han ordeyned yt mot be so</L>
<L>By ther hevenly influence,</L>
<L>Wyth-outen any r&eacute;systence.</L>
<L>Why sholde A theff than punysshed be,</L>
<L N="20474">That fro robbry may nat ffle;</L>
<L>Or A trewe man, by resoun,</L>
<L>Vertuous off condyc&iuml;oun,</L>
<L>Mawgre hys wyl <I>and</I><NOTE PLACE="marg">[with St., and Tib.]</NOTE> al hys myht,</L>
<L N="20478">Escheweth wrong, and doth al ryht.</L>
<L>Touchyng hys meryte nor gerdoun,</L>
<L>He noon dysserveth, off resoun,</L>
<L>ffor the sterrys euerydel</L>
<L N="20482">Ben only cause that he doth wel.</L>
<L>Wher-vp-on (who-so taketh hede)</L>
<L>Both&euml; sholde haue ylych&euml; mede,</L>
<L>Good or harm, wher-so th&eacute; werche.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="20486">"And also off al hooly<NOTE PLACE="marg">[hooly <I>om</I>. Tib.]</NOTE> cherche,</L>
<L>Yiff thy resouns wer certeyn,</L>
<L>The sacramentys wer in veyn</L>
<L>In thys cas (yiff yt be souht);
<PB REF="00000655.tif" N="547"></L>
<L N="20490">"ffor they sholde a-vayll&euml; nouht,</L>
<L>Nor to mankynde do<NOTE PLACE="marg">[C., Tib., be St.]</NOTE> no good.<MILESTONE N="265a" UNIT="folio"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>"And Cryst Ihesu, that shadde hys blood,</L>
<L>Only mankynde for to save,</L>
<L N="20494">What effect&euml;<NOTE PLACE="marg">[Tib., effect C., St.]</NOTE> shold&euml; haue</L>
<L>Hys peyne or gret&euml; pass&iuml;oun,</L>
<L>To brynge vs to savac&iuml;oun,</L>
<L>Yiff no man myghte don evel<NOTE PLACE="marg">[C., Tib., do well St.]</NOTE> nor good,</L>
<L N="20498">But evene so as the hevene stood?</L>
<L>Ther wer noon help&euml; nor socour;</L>
<L>The wych<NOTE PLACE="marg">[whiche Tib.]</NOTE> wer a gret errour,</L>
<L>A man to leve in any<NOTE PLACE="marg">[C., Tib., such a St.]</NOTE> wyse</L>
<L N="20502">So as thow dost her devyse;</L>
<L>ffro<NOTE PLACE="marg">[Tib., ffor C., St.]</NOTE> wych, I pray god me preserue!</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>"Thow seyst also, men sholde obserue</L>
<L>Houres and constellac&iuml;ouns</L>
<L N="20506">ffor sondry operac&iuml;ouns;</L>
<L>The ascendent, consydre and se,</L>
<L>Off a manhys natyvyte,</L>
<L>To ffynde the dysposic&iuml;oun</L>
<L N="20510">Off A manhys condyc&iuml;oun,</L>
<L>To good or evel,<NOTE PLACE="marg">[badd St.]</NOTE> be kyndely lawe</L>
<L>Off nature, he shold&euml; drawe;</L>
<L>The wych&euml; (who<NOTE PLACE="marg">[C., Tib., who-so St.]</NOTE> the trouthe espyes)<MILESTONE UNIT="Stowe folio" N="336a"></L>
<L N="20514">Ar<NOTE PLACE="marg">[C., Tib., as St.]</NOTE> but fables, and ful off lyes;</L>
<L>ffor men ha seyn<NOTE PLACE="marg">[sene St., seyne Tib.]</NOTE> her-to-fforn,</L>
<L>Two chyldren in O moment born,</L>
<L>The ton ryht good and fortunat,</L>
<L N="20518">And the tother infortunat;</L>
<L>And men ha seyn<NOTE PLACE="marg">[C., Tib., such a St.]</NOTE> ek at O tyme,</L>
<L>(Bothe at Evyn and at pryme,)</L>
<L>Twey men that a crafft wel konne:</L>
<L N="20522">At On hour they ha be-gonne;<MILESTONE UNIT="Tib folio" N="64b"></L>
<L>The ton Off hem ful wel hath wrouht,</L>
<L><I>And</I> the tother hath<NOTE PLACE="marg">[The tother he hath Tib.]</NOTE> do ryht nouht.</L>
<L>And tweyne, on hour (who kan espye)</L>
<L N="20526">Han bothe had O malladye:</L>
<L>The ton was mad hol by nature,</L>
<L>The tother myght&euml; nat endure,<MILESTONE N="265b" UNIT="folio"><NOTE PLACE="marg">[C. &amp; St.]</NOTE></L>
<L>But hath deyed, in certeyn:<NOTE PLACE="marg">[C. &amp; St.]</NOTE>
<PB REF="00000656.tif" N="548"></L>
<L N="20530">"Wherfor thy resouns be but veyn.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>"Or telle me also a resoun</L>
<L>Touchynge thyn oppynyoun:</L>
<L>An hundryd thousand men assaylle</L>
<L N="20534">Euerych other in bataylle;</L>
<L>Wher-off kometh ther<NOTE PLACE="marg">[C., Tib., that St.]</NOTE> destyne,</L>
<L>That they ben alle at o Iourne,</L>
<L>And yet par cas (yt ys no nay)</L>
<L N="20538">They wer nat alle born on<NOTE PLACE="marg">[in St.]</NOTE> o day,</L>
<L>Nor they nat entre, nyh nor ferre,</L>
<L>All at tonys<NOTE PLACE="marg">[ones St.]</NOTE> in-to that werre;</L>
<L>And yet, by Martys<NOTE PLACE="marg">[martis St., marrys C.]</NOTE> mortal lawe,</L>
<L N="20542">Euerychon they ben yslawe:</L>
<L>Tel the cause what may thys be,</L>
<L>And spek no mor off destyne.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>"Yet som folk ben ordynat,</L>
<L N="20546">And also predestynat,</L>
<L>Prescryt<NOTE PLACE="marg">[prescryt St., Prescyt C., Prescys Tib.]</NOTE> to-forn to Ioye and blysse,</L>
<L>Off the wych som other mysse,</L>
<L>Swych as (in conclus&iuml;oun)</L>
<L N="20550">Gon vn-to<NOTE PLACE="marg">[C., St., in to Tib.]</NOTE> dampnac&iuml;oun.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>"And, trewly<NOTE PLACE="marg">[trewely Tib.]</NOTE> (yt ys no dred)</L>
<L>The cause ys nat (who taketh hed,)</L>
<L>The dyvyn&euml; prescyence;</L>
<L N="20554">But the gret&euml; dyfference</L>
<L>Ys causyd off good and off badde,</L>
<L>Affter the lyff that they her ladde.</L>
<L>And in this<NOTE PLACE="marg">[Tib., the St., thy C.]</NOTE> world (bothe ffer and ner,<NOTE PLACE="marg">[<I>leaves out of Tib. till</I> 555/20812 <I>below</I>.]</NOTE>)</L>
<L N="20558">As they rowede in the Ryuer,</L>
<L>Somme to Ioye, somme to peyne,</L>
<L>ffro synne as they hem-sylff restreyne;</L>
<L>The good&euml; to savac&iuml;oun,</L>
<L N="20562">The evele vn-to dampnac&iuml;oun,</L>
<L>Constreyned no-thyng by destyne,<MILESTONE UNIT="Stowe folio" N="336b"></L>
<L>But by ffre wyl and lyberte.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>"Thogh god knewe al thys thyng<NOTE PLACE="marg">[thyng <I>om</I>. St.]</NOTE> to-forn,</L>
<L N="20566">Many<NOTE PLACE="marg">[Many a St.]</NOTE> day or they wer born,<MILESTONE N="266a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Hys knowyng nor hys prescyence,</L>
<L>Vn-to man doth noon offence.</L>
<L>ffredam ys yove<NOTE PLACE="marg">[gyven St.]</NOTE> to hem to chese,
<PB REF="00000657.tif" N="549"></L>
<L N="20570">"Whether hym lyst to wynne or lese;</L>
<L>ffor, knowyng (who that look&euml; wel)</L>
<L>Off god, ne causeth neueradel</L>
<L>Wher them lyst, off both&euml; tweyne,</L>
<L N="20574">To gon to Ioye, outher to peyne.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>"And, ther-for, do by my lore,</L>
<L>And off destyne spek no more;</L>
<L>ffor the planetys euerychon,</L>
<L N="20578">And the sygn&euml;s, on by On,</L>
<L>And euery sterre, in hys degre,</L>
<L>Mevyn by the volunte</L>
<L>Off the lord that syt aloffte.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="20582">"And also (as yt falleth offte)</L>
<L>ffolkys that in thys world her be,</L>
<L>(At the Eye as thow mayst se,)</L>
<L>Somme be lame, and feble off myght;</L>
<L N="20586">And somm&euml; strong, and gon vp-ryht,</L>
<L>And many welde hem sylff ryht wel;</L>
<L>But, off the sterrys neueradel,</L>
<L>Nor off the hevenly influence,</L>
<L N="20590">Strength&euml;, myght, nor impotence,</L>
<L>Be nat causyd (on no syde)</L>
<L>But as the lord lyst to provyde.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>"No man blynd, nor no man lame</L>
<L N="20594">Born&mdash;the gospel seyth the same;&mdash;</L>
<L>ffor whan cryst, in swych A cas,</L>
<L>Off the Iewys axyd was,</L>
<L>(As in Iohan ye may fynde,)</L>
<L N="20598">Why the blynde man was bor<NOTE PLACE="marg">[borne St.]</NOTE> blynde,</L>
<L>He told hem pleynly at A word,</L>
<L>'To preve the workys off the<NOTE PLACE="marg">[oure St.]</NOTE> lord,</L>
<L>And hys dedys by myr&aacute;cle,</L>
<L N="20602">With-outen any mor obst&aacute;cle;'<MILESTONE N="266b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>And other caus&euml; was ther noon,</L>
<L>As seyth the gospel off seyn Iohn.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>"And nothyng thorgh the moc&iuml;oun</L>
<L N="20606">Off sterrys dysposic&iuml;oun,</L>
<L>Was thys blyndnesse to hym sent.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>"And davyd seyth 'the fyrmament</L>
<L>Was ordeyned, at O word,
<PB REF="00000658.tif" N="550"></L>
<L N="20610">To telle the werkys off the lord.<NOTE PLACE="marg">Celi enarrant.</NOTE></L>
<L>The sterrys, he<NOTE PLACE="marg">[be St.]</NOTE> makyd for to shyne,<MILESTONE UNIT="Stowe folio" N="337a"></L>
<L>Vp-on the Erth&euml; tenlwmyne;</L>
<L>Hih in hevene to abyde,</L>
<L N="20614">A-sonder only to devyde</L>
<L>The day and ek the dyrk&euml; nyht.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>"And in hys Centyloge a-ryht,</L>
<L>The gret&euml; clerk, kyng<NOTE PLACE="marg">[grete kynge St.]</NOTE> Tholome,</L>
<L N="20618">Affermeth ther (who lyst to se);</L>
<L>He seyth (As I rehers&euml; kan)</L>
<L>That in erthe A wys&euml;<NOTE PLACE="marg">[wyse St., wys C.]</NOTE> man<NOTE PLACE="marg">Sapiens dominabitur astris.</NOTE></L>
<L>Haueth domynac&iuml;oun</L>
<L N="20622">Above ech constellac&iuml;oun."</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>And affter he hadde herd me seyn,</L>
<L>Thus he answerde me ageyn:</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>Astrologye:<NOTE PLACE="marg">[St., <I>om</I>. C.]</NOTE></HEAD>
<L>'Affter thy wordys rehersyd here,</L>
<L N="20626">The heuene, with hys sterrys clere,</L>
<L>Shold&euml; hauen, in substaunce,</L>
<L>But lytel power or puissaunce,</L>
<L>And sholde also, by thy devys,</L>
<L N="20630">Ben also off lass&euml; prys</L>
<L>Than ys the erth&euml;, her doun lowe,</L>
<L>With greynys and with sedys sowe;</L>
<L>ffor the Erthe, wher-on we gon,</L>
<L N="20634">Bryngeth fforth ffruit&euml;s many On,&mdash;</L>
<L>Euerych grouynge in hys kynde,&mdash;</L>
<L>And flourys fayre, as thow mayst fynde;</L>
<L>And yet, for al hys gret ffayrnesse,</L>
<L N="20638">The hevene haueth mor noblesse<MILESTONE N="267a" UNIT="folio"><NOTE PLACE="marg">[St. &amp; C.]</NOTE></L>
<L>Than hathe therthe in hys degre,<NOTE PLACE="marg">[St. &amp; C.]</NOTE></L>
<L>By many effects, as man may se;<NOTE PLACE="marg">[St. &amp; C.]</NOTE></L>
<L>And it also more necessary.<NOTE PLACE="marg">[St. &amp; C.]</NOTE></L>
<L N="20642">And shortly, (for me lyst nat tarye,)<NOTE PLACE="marg">[St. &amp; C.]</NOTE></L>
<L>In hevenly myght and puissaunce,</L>
<L>The erthe hath al hys governaunce.'</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>[The Pilgrim]:</HEAD>
<L>"In som thyng thow seyst ful soth,</L>
<L N="20646">Touchyng that the hevene doth.</L>
<L>In erthe, ther shold&euml; non greyns sprynge,
<PB REF="00000659.tif" N="551"></L>
<L>"Nor ffruitys non yt sholde forth brynge,</L>
<L>Ne wer the hevene (wyth hys myght)</L>
<L N="20650">Gaff ther-to, coumfort and lyht;</L>
<L>ffor the hevene, thorgh hys bryhtnesse,</L>
<L>Thorgh hys hete, and hys clernesse,</L>
<L>Causeth in erth&euml; many a payre</L>
<L N="20654">fflourys and ffruit to spryng&euml; fayre,</L>
<L>And yiveth ther-to (as thow mayst se)</L>
<L>fful grete gyfftys off bewte,</L>
<L>Lych as the lord off most renoun</L>
<L N="20658">Hath yove hem by commyss&iuml;oun.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>"But hys power, nor hys powste,</L>
<L>Ne strechchet nat (who lyst to se,</L>
<L>Neuere sythe the world by-gan,)<MILESTONE UNIT="Stowe folio" N="337b"></L>
<L N="20662">Touchynge the gouernaunce off man.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>ffor man hath choys and volunte,</L>
<L>ffredam also, and lyberte.</L>
<L>Hevene ne sterrys, both&euml; two,</L>
<L N="20666">Ther-with haue no-thyng to do,</L>
<L>Nor neuer aforn, power hadde,</L>
<L>To cause hym<NOTE PLACE="marg">[them St.]</NOTE> to don good or badde.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>"But whan I mette ffyrst with the,</L>
<L N="20670">Off O thyng thow spak to me,</L>
<L>Touchyng thy tother halff partye</L>
<L>Wych callyd ys 'Astronomye.'</L>
<L>Tel me a-noon, and have y-do,<MILESTONE N="267b" UNIT="folio"><NOTE PLACE="marg">[St. &amp; C.]</NOTE></L>
<L N="20674">Ys she ffer now fro the go?<NOTE PLACE="marg">[St. &amp; C.]</NOTE></L>
<L>Wher ys hyr habytac&iuml;oun,<NOTE PLACE="marg">[St. &amp; C.]</NOTE></L>
<L>Hyr dwellyng, or hyr manc&iuml;oun?"<NOTE PLACE="marg">[St. &amp; C.]</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>Astrologie:<NOTE PLACE="marg">[St., <I>om</I>. C.]</NOTE></HEAD>
<L>'Wher that she be, her or yonder,<NOTE PLACE="marg">[St. &amp; C.]</NOTE></L>
<L N="20678">We ne be nat ffer asonder,</L>
<L>ffor vnder hyre protecc&iuml;ouns</L>
<L>I mak&euml; dyvynac&iuml;ouns;</L>
<L>And by hyr power grauntyd me,</L>
<L N="20682">I have scolerys two or thre,</L>
<L>Wych that on me euere abyde,</L>
<L>And departe nat fro my syde.'</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>Pilgrim:<NOTE PLACE="marg">[St., <I>om</I>. C.]</NOTE></HEAD>
<L>"Tel on a-noon, I pray the,
<PB REF="00000660.tif" N="552"></L>
<L N="20686">"Declare her namys here to me,</L>
<L>And thy-sylff no-thyng excuse,</L>
<L>Wher thow dost swych crafft&euml;s vse;</L>
<L>ffor syth thow seyst so nyh they be,</L>
<L N="20690">With al myn herte I wolde hem se."</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>Astrologie:<NOTE PLACE="marg">[St., <I>om</I>. C.]</NOTE></HEAD>
<L>'ffor to ffulfyll&euml; thy desyr:</L>
<L>The ffyrst&euml; place ys in the ffyre;</L>
<L>And my scoler, ffyrst off echon,</L>
<L N="20694">Wher-so-euere that we gon,</L>
<L>(I kan hyr in no wyse excuse,)</L>
<L>In that place she doth yt vse.</L>
<L>And she (as I shal specefye)</L>
<L N="20698">Callyd ys 'Pyromancye':</L>
<L>ffro thennys she may nat wel dysseuere;</L>
<L>And in the ffyr she dwelleth euere;</L>
<L>And therby (in conclus&iuml;oun)</L>
<L N="20702">She maketh hyr dyvynac&iuml;oun,</L>
<L>Be yt ffoul or be yt ffayr.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>'My secounde scoler in the hayr<NOTE PLACE="marg">[is the ayre St.]</NOTE></L>
<L>Pleynly, affter my doctryne,</L>
<L N="20706">At all&euml; tym&euml;s doth devyne;</L>
<L>And therfor (yiff thow konne espye,)</L>
<L>Hyr name ys callyd 'Aermancye.'<MILESTONE N="268a" UNIT="folio"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>'The thrydde ys off fful gret renoun,</L>
<L N="20710">And hath hyr habytac&iuml;oun<MILESTONE UNIT="Stowe folio" N="338a"></L>
<L>In the se (who kan dyscerne);</L>
<L>Whom Neptunus doth gouerne;</L>
<L>By whom (the story telleth thus)</L>
<L N="20714">The myghty man Neptanabus,</L>
<L>ffader to Alysaundre the kyng,</L>
<L>Wrouht fful many A dyuers thyng;</L>
<L>And in the water and in the se</L>
<L N="20718">Was al hys crafft, as thow mayst se.</L>
<L>Ther-fore (me lyst nat for to lye,)</L>
<L>Yt ys callyd Ydromancye,</L>
<L>By water (in conclus&iuml;oun),</L>
<L N="20722">Augurye or dyvynac&iuml;oun.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>'The ffourth&euml;, (yt nedeth nat telle,)</L>
<L>ffor, awhyle yiff thow wylt dwelle,
<PB REF="00000661.tif" N="553"></L>
<L>'Thow shalt A-noon, her in presence</L>
<L N="20726">Sen ther, off experyence,</L>
<L>ffor yt ys wrouht by manhys hond,</L>
<L>Somwhyle in erth&euml; and in sond:</L>
<L>Ther-fore (shortly to specefye)</L>
<L N="20730">Yt ys callyd Geomancye.'</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>[The Pilgrim]:</HEAD>
<L>Than quod I, "tel on to me,</L>
<L>What be the poyntys that I se:</L>
<L>Declare to me, and nat ne ffaylle,</L>
<L N="20734">What may they helpyn or A-vaylle."</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>Geomanc[y]e<NOTE PLACE="marg">[St., <I>om</I>. C.]</NOTE>:</HEAD>
<L>'Be-twyxen ernest and ek game,</L>
<L>'Geomancye,' her ys my name.</L>
<L>Astrologye ys my maystresse,</L>
<L N="20738">That dyde my name to th&eacute; expresse;</L>
<L>To whos doctryne and whos sentence</L>
<L>I yiv&euml; ffeyth and fful credence;</L>
<L>And by thys poyntys, I kan knowe</L>
<L N="20742">Whan ys tyme to Ere and sowe;</L>
<L>And wher, thys next&euml; yer certeyn,<MILESTONE N="268b" UNIT="folio"><NOTE PLACE="marg">[C. &amp; St.]</NOTE></L>
<L>Ther shal be plente off frut and greyn.<NOTE PLACE="marg">[C. &amp; St.]</NOTE></L>
<L>And I kan tell&euml;, nyh and fferre,<NOTE PLACE="marg">[C. &amp; St.]</NOTE></L>
<L N="20746">Bothe off pes and ek off werre;<NOTE PLACE="marg">[C. &amp; St.]</NOTE></L>
<L>And in effect, I wyl nat ffaylle<NOTE PLACE="marg">[C. &amp; St.]</NOTE></L>
<L>To telle the ffyn off a bataylle.</L>
<L>And, that I lese nat my labour,</L>
<L N="20750">I take the tyme and ek the hour</L>
<L>Whan that I my werk begynne,</L>
<L>Who shal lesyn, or who shal wynne,</L>
<L>Or who shal ffaylle<NOTE PLACE="marg">[who shallan St.]</NOTE> off hys plesaunce;</L>
<L N="20754">ffor thys poynt&yogh; ha r&eacute;semblaunce</L>
<L>To the sygn&euml;s in the hevene,</L>
<L>And to the planetys all&euml; .vij.<NOTE PLACE="marg">[seven St.]</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>'And, I taake also good heed</L>
<L N="20758">To the tayl and to the hed,</L>
<L>Hih a loffte, off the dragoun,</L>
<L>Whan I ffourme my questyoun,</L>
<L>Wher-on, by hevenly influence,<MILESTONE UNIT="Stowe folio" N="238b"></L>
<L N="20762">I yiv&euml; trewe and iust sentence
<PB REF="00000662.tif" N="554"></L>
<L>'On every thyng, <I>and</I> ech demaunde,</L>
<L>Lyk as my ffygures me comaunde.'</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>Pilgrym:<NOTE PLACE="marg">[St., <I>om</I>. C.]</NOTE></HEAD>
<L>"Tel fforth to me euerydel,</L>
<L N="20766">Wher-off serveth that tuel."</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>Geomancy:<NOTE PLACE="marg">[St., <I>om</I>. C.]</NOTE></HEAD>
<L>'I looke thorgh (off hool entent)</L>
<L>Vp-ward to the ffyrmament,</L>
<L>To han, vn-to my quest&iuml;oun,</L>
<L N="20770">A maner dysposic&iuml;oun,</L>
<L>Or that I my ffygur sue,</L>
<L>How the hevene doth influe.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>Pilgryme:<NOTE PLACE="marg">[St., <I>om</I>. C.]</NOTE></HEAD>
<L>"Now I telle the Outterly,</L>
<L N="20774">That thow art ryht vnhappy,</L>
<L>And dygne (to myn oppynyoun)</L>
<L>Off shame and off confus&iuml;oun,</L>
<L>That, so myche off thy ffolye</L>
<L N="20778">Trustest in astrologye,</L>
<L>Wenyng, at thy<NOTE PLACE="marg">[the St.]</NOTE> comaund&euml;ment,<MILESTONE N="269a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>ffor to make the ffyrmament</L>
<L>As thow lyst, ryht at thyn hond,</L>
<L N="20782">ffor to descende vp-on the sond,</L>
<L>By influence avale a-doun</L>
<L>By caus&euml; off thy quest&iuml;oun;</L>
<L>Wenynge ta fond<NOTE PLACE="marg">[to a found St.]</NOTE> Out a weye</L>
<L N="20786">That the hevene th&eacute; sholde obeye.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>"In thyn hed ys no resoun,</L>
<L>Clernesse nor dyscrec&iuml;oun;</L>
<L>Thy crafft and thow be<NOTE PLACE="marg">[be, <I>om</I>. St.]</NOTE> peryllous</L>
<L N="20790">To symple ffolkys vertuous,</L>
<L>To brynge hem in mysgouernaunce.</L>
<L>I praye god, saue me fro meschaunce,</L>
<L>And ffro thy gret Inyquyte!</L>
<L N="20794">Go hens, that I no mor th&eacute; se!</L>
<L>I drede me gretly in my thouht,</L>
<L>That I am in pereyl brouht;</L>
<L>Namly in thys dredful se,</L>
<L N="20798">I trow&euml; sothly that I be</L>
<L>ffalle on a pereyl dout&euml;les,
<PB REF="00000663.tif" N="555"></L>
<L>Wych that callyd ys 'Cyrces.' "</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L><NOTE PLACE="marg">[Astrolog[y]e and Geomanoy St., <I>om</I>. C.]</NOTE>Thys tweyn&euml; loud&euml; gan to crye,</L>
<L N="20802">And gan vn-to me specefye</L>
<L>That I was falle vp-on Cyrces,<NOTE PLACE="marg">[cyrces St., cyces C.]</NOTE></L>
<L>And that I shold&euml; (dout&euml;les,</L>
<L>By no treyne nor by no Iape)</L>
<L N="20806">ffrom ther<NOTE PLACE="marg">[theyr St.]</NOTE> daunger nat escape.</L>
<L>And I, for dred, gan hast&euml; me</L>
<L>Streyht ageyn vn-to the se,</L>
<L>And leffte hem bothe on An ylond,</L>
<L N="20810">Makynge ther poyntys in the sond.<MILESTONE UNIT="Stowe folio" N="339a"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>And thanne I gan to bydde and preye,</L>
<L>That god wolde helpe me<NOTE PLACE="marg">[me Tib., <I>om</I>. C., St.]</NOTE> on my weye,<NOTE PLACE="marg">[Tib. A 7 begins here again,<MILESTONE N="65a" UNIT="folio">]</NOTE></L>
<L>ffrom all&euml;<NOTE PLACE="marg">[alle Tib., al C., St.]</NOTE> stormys in my passage,</L>
<L N="20814">And also fro the gret outrage</L>
<L>Off wynd&euml;s wych that, hih and lowe,<MILESTONE N="269b" UNIT="folio"><NOTE PLACE="marg">[C. &amp; St.]</NOTE></L>
<L>Stern&euml;ly at me gan blowe.<NOTE PLACE="marg">[C. &amp; St.]</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>And in the sam&euml; sylu&euml; whyle,</L>
<L N="20818">I sawh apere a lytel yle,</L>
<L>Wher-off I hadd&euml; gret gladnesse;</L>
<L>And thyderward I gan me dresse;</L>
<L>Rauhte so ffer vp with myn hond,</L>
<L N="20822">That, off grace, I kam to lond.</L>
<L>And ther I sawh, off cher fful bold,</L>
<L>A vekk&euml;, hydous and ryht old,</L>
<L>And wonder Ougly off hyr chere;</L>
<L N="20826">Hyr handys she beet also yffere;</L>
<L>And hyr lawhyng to determyne,</L>
<L>Lych an hors she gan to wyne.<NOTE PLACE="marg">[whyne Tib.]</NOTE></L>
<L>And I, my look vp-on hyr leyde,</L>
<L N="20830">And evene thus to hyre I seyde:</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>The Pylgryme:<NOTE PLACE="marg">[Tib., Pilgrim St., <I>om</I>. C.]</NOTE></HEAD>
<L>"O thow most ffoul in b&eacute;holdyng,</L>
<L>Tel on the cause off thy lawhyng!"</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>Ydolatrie:<NOTE PLACE="marg">[C. in margin; Idolatrye Tib., St.]</NOTE></HEAD>
<L>'Kom On, and entre in with me,</L>
<L N="20834">And the caus&euml; thow shalt se.'</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>[The Pilgrim]:<NOTE PLACE="marg">[Blank for Illumination in C.]</NOTE></HEAD>
<L>And I entrede by hyr byddyng;</L>
<L>And ther I ffond On<NOTE PLACE="marg">[oon Tib., on St.]</NOTE> syttyng
<PB REF="00000664.tif" N="556"></L>
<L>In A chayer, an ymage,</L>
<L N="20838">Ryht ffoul off look and off vysage:</L>
<L>He sat crownyd lyk a kyng,</L>
<L>In hys hond a swerd holdyng;</L>
<L>Vp-on hys shuldrys brood and large</L>
<L N="20842">Me thouht&euml; that he had a targe,<MILESTONE N="270a" UNIT="folio"><MILESTONE UNIT="Tib folio" N="65b"><NOTE PLACE="marg">[Tib., C., &amp; St.]</NOTE></L>
<L>Wyth blak&euml; ffly&euml;s al depeynt:<NOTE PLACE="marg">[Tib., C., &amp; St.]</NOTE></L>
<L>Yreyn&euml;s<NOTE PLACE="marg">[And vreynes Tib.]</NOTE> wern A-mong hem meynt;<NOTE PLACE="marg">[Tib., C., &amp; St.]</NOTE><NOTE PLACE="inter">[An Illumination follows this line in Tib.]</NOTE></L>
<L N="20845">And (wych that ys ful foul to nevene)<NOTE PLACE="marg">[Tib., C., &amp; St.]</NOTE></L>
<L>Ther was a maner off smoky levene<NOTE PLACE="marg">[heuene Tib.]</NOTE><NOTE PLACE="marg">[Tib., C., &amp; St.]</NOTE></L>
<L>Wych the ydole dyde embrace.<NOTE PLACE="marg">[Tib., C., &amp; St.]</NOTE></L>
<L>And round abouten in the place,<NOTE PLACE="marg">[Tib., C., &amp; St.]</NOTE></L>
<L>Yt was fful (I yow ensure)</L>
<L N="20850">Off brydd&euml;s dunge <I>and</I> foul ordure.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>To-for thys mawmet (in certeyn)</L>
<L>I sawh knelyn a vyleyn,</L>
<L>With powdrys and<NOTE PLACE="marg">[and <I>om</I>. Tib.]</NOTE> with fumys blake,</L>
<L N="20854">Sacryfys&euml; for to make</L>
<L>To thys ydole, with hys sheld.</L>
<L>And he that<NOTE PLACE="marg">[that <I>om</I>. Tib.]</NOTE> knelede (as I be-held)</L>
<L>Was<NOTE PLACE="marg">[And was Tib.]</NOTE> (to myn Oppynyoun)</L>
<L N="20858">A Carpenter or a masoun.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>Idolatrye:<NOTE PLACE="marg">[Tib., St., <I>in margin</I> C.]</NOTE></HEAD>
<L>Thanne thys dame Ydolatrye,<MILESTONE UNIT="Stowe folio" N="339b"></L>
<L>ffoul and horryble off look and Eye,</L>
<L>'Behold,' quod she, 'and look&euml; wel,<MILESTONE UNIT="Tib folio" N="66a"></L>
<L N="20862">And se the maner euerydel</L>
<L>How I ha<NOTE PLACE="marg">[haue Tib.]</NOTE> Ioye and gret gladnesse</L>
<L>To sen thys cherl, by gret humblesse,</L>
<L>Toward thys mawmet hym-sylff tavaunce,<NOTE PLACE="marg">[to vaunce Tib.]</NOTE></L>
<L N="20866">Don worshepe, and &oacute;bseruaunce;</L>
<L>And I abyd&euml;, for to se</L>
<L>That thow shalt knele vp-on thy kne,</L>
<L>To-fforn hym, by devoc&iuml;oun.</L>
<L N="20870">fforsake thy skryppe and thy bordoun;</L>
<L>And, to hys myghty excellence,</L>
<L>Don worshepe and reuerence.'</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>The Pylgryme:<NOTE PLACE="marg">[Tib., Pilgrim St., <I>om</I>. C.]</NOTE></HEAD>
<L>Lyst for thys thyng I ffyl<NOTE PLACE="marg">[Leste . . ffelle Tib.]</NOTE> in blame,
<PB REF="00000665.tif" N="557"></L>
<L N="20874">"Tel on ffyrst, what ys thy name."</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>Dame Idolatrye:<MILESTONE N="270b" UNIT="folio"><NOTE PLACE="marg">[Tib., Ydolatre St., Ydolatrye <I>in margin</I> C.]</NOTE></HEAD>
<L>'Ydolatrye<NOTE PLACE="marg">[And Idolatrye Tib.]</NOTE> I am,' quod she,</L>
<L>'And off ffolkes that be ffre,<NOTE PLACE="marg">[free Tib., St., ff C. <I>burnt</I>]</NOTE></L>
<L>Thys my custom and vs&aacute;ge<NOTE PLACE="marg">[C., Tib., St.]</NOTE></L>
<L N="20878">ffor to brynge hem in seruage.<NOTE PLACE="marg">[C., Tib., St.]</NOTE></L>
<L>And I kan, by collus&iuml;oun,</L>
<L>Tourne al estatys vp-so-doun,</L>
<L>And sett&euml; (thogh ffolk hadde yt sworn,)</L>
<L N="20882">That ys bakward, to go beforn.</L>
<L>To dyfface, ys my labour,</L>
<L>The kyng&euml;s worshepe and honour,<NOTE PLACE="marg">&para; Deuteronomi. 6<SUP>o</SUP> (13) Dominum deum tuum timebis, &amp; illi soli se[r|vies]. Tib., <I>om</I>. C., St.</NOTE></L>
<L>And al that to my sylff applye.</L>
<L N="20886">ffor I am callyd 'Ydolatrye,'</L>
<L>The wych&euml; (who wel lok&euml; kan)</L>
<L>ffrend and douhter to Sathan;</L>
<L>ffor Sathan (shortly for to telle)</L>
<L N="20890">In mawmetys I make hym dwelle.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>'By thys cherl vp-on hys kne,<MILESTONE UNIT="Tib folio" N="66b"></L>
<L>Her thow mayst exaumple se,</L>
<L>How he, wyth al hys dyllygence,</L>
<L N="20894">Doth hym honour and reuerence,</L>
<L>Wenynge, by hys &aacute;pparaylle,</L>
<L>The mawmet myhte to hym avaylle.</L>
<L>ffor Sathan,&mdash;that ys cloos with-Inne,</L>
<L N="20898">To Infecte hys soule wyth synne,</L>
<L>And hys wyttys to entrouble,&mdash;</L>
<L>Yiveth an answere wych ys double,</L>
<L>Wych hath (to marren hys entent,)</L>
<L N="20902">A maner off double entend&euml;ment,</L>
<L>And leueth hym euere in none-certeyn,<NOTE PLACE="marg">[none certeyne St., non certeyne Tib.]</NOTE></L>
<L>Or kepeth hym Mu&euml;t<NOTE PLACE="marg">[muyt St., Muet Tib.]</NOTE> off dysdeyn;</L>
<L>And hys<NOTE PLACE="marg">[his Tib., hyr C., her St.]</NOTE> r&eacute;queste doth refuse,</L>
<L>To make the fool more for<NOTE PLACE="marg">[for C., St., <I>om</I>. Tib.]</NOTE> to muse,</L>
<L N="20907">Lose hys tyme, off wylfulnesse.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>'And yet, in al hys wrechchydnesse,<MILESTONE UNIT="Stowe folio" N="340a"></L>
<L>Efft<NOTE PLACE="marg">[Offte Tib., eft St.]</NOTE> he doth hys dyllygence,</L>
<L>With<NOTE PLACE="marg">[With <I>om</I>. Tib.]</NOTE> smoke and ffyr hym to encense,</L>
<L N="20911">Prayeth hys Mawmet nat to faylle,</L>
<L>To yive Answere, and hym<NOTE PLACE="marg">[C., Tib., hem St.]</NOTE> consaylle,
<PB REF="00000666.tif" N="558"></L>
<L>'And helpe hym, that he myght&euml; spede,<MILESTONE N="271a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="20914">To forthre hym in hys gret nede,</L>
<L>Syth he in hym doth so affye.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>'Se how thys fool, off hys ffolye,</L>
<L>Seth how hys Mawmet, ffoul off chere,</L>
<L N="20918">Herys<NOTE PLACE="marg">[eres Tib., St.]</NOTE> hath,<NOTE PLACE="marg">[he hath Tib.]</NOTE> and may nat here;</L>
<L>And syttynge also in hys se,</L>
<L>Eyen hath, and may nat se;</L>
<L>But ys as dowmb as stok or ston;</L>
<L N="20922">And hath ffet, and may nat gon,</L>
<L>Nor from hys chayer, a foot remewe,</L>
<L>Thogh al the world hym wold&euml; sue.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>'Hys swerd, hys targ&euml;, in bataylle</L>
<L N="20926">May to hym ryht nouht avaylle;</L>
<L>ffor he ys ded, as ston or<NOTE PLACE="marg">[C., Tib., in St.]</NOTE> tre.<MILESTONE UNIT="Tib folio" N="67a"></L>
<L>And<NOTE PLACE="marg">[And oonly Tib.]</NOTE> trewly (so as thynketh me,)</L>
<L>Who doth to swych on,<NOTE PLACE="marg">[oon Tib., one St.]</NOTE> reverence,</L>
<L>Requerynge<NOTE PLACE="marg">[Requyrynge Tib., requeryth St.]</NOTE> hys benyvolence,</L>
<L N="20931">He ys (for short conclus&iuml;oun)</L>
<L>A fool, in myn oppynyoun.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>'And for to touchyn hym mor ner,</L>
<L>The sam&euml; sylu&euml;<NOTE PLACE="marg">[selffe same St., same silffe Tib.]</NOTE> carpenter</L>
<L N="20935">Dyde a-forn hys bysy peyne</L>
<L>To forge hym, wyth hys handys tweyne,</L>
<L>And make hym ffyrst off swych entaylle,</L>
<L N="20938">And wot he may nothyng avaylle</L>
<L>To helpe hym, whan that<NOTE PLACE="marg">[that <I>om</I>. St., whanne Tib.]</NOTE> al ys do.</L>
<L>They ben A-coursyd, both&euml; two:<NOTE PLACE="marg">&para; Sapientie <B>14</B><SUP>o</SUP>. <B>(8)</B></NOTE></L>
<L>And thys the cause (wyth-out&euml; more)<NOTE PLACE="marg">&para; Idolum maledictum [est] et qui fecit illud. Tib.]</NOTE></L>
<L N="20942">ffyrst why that I lowh so sore.'</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>The Pylgryme:<NOTE PLACE="marg">[Tib., Pilgrim St., <I>om</I>. C.]</NOTE></HEAD>
<L>Yet nat-wyth-stondyng, off entente,</L>
<L>To the cherl<NOTE PLACE="marg">[Churle Tib.]</NOTE> A-noon I wente,</L>
<L>Bad hym a-ryse, and that a-noon,</L>
<L N="20946">And that he shold&euml; thenys gon,</L>
<L>And leue hys fals oppynyoun,</L>
<L>Go take<NOTE PLACE="marg">[Tib., St., (C. <I>burnt</I>)]</NOTE> hys skryppe <I>and</I> hys bordoun,<MILESTONE N="271b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>And, off hert&euml; ful mekly,<NOTE PLACE="marg">[Tib., St., (C. <I>burnt</I>)]</NOTE></L>
<L N="20950">Gon and crye the kyng, mercy</L>
<L>Off the gylt and the tresp&aacute;ce
<PB REF="00000667.tif" N="559"></L>
<L>That he hadde don in that place,</L>
<L>And that hys hert&euml; was so set</L>
<L N="20954">To worshep&euml; A Marmoset,</L>
<L>Wych to help&euml;, (fer nor ner,)</L>
<L>Hath no puissaunce nor power.<MILESTONE UNIT="Stowe folio" N="340b"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Wher-off (with-out&euml; mor respyt,)</L>
<L N="20958">The Cherl in herte hadde gret despyt,</L>
<L>And felly gan a-geyn abrayde,</L>
<L>And vn-to me ryht thus he sayde:<MILESTONE UNIT="Tib folio" N="67b"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>The Vyleyne:<NOTE PLACE="marg">[St., veleyne Tib., . . yleyn C., <I>in margin</I>.]</NOTE></HEAD>
<L>'How darstow<NOTE PLACE="marg">[darste thow Tib.]</NOTE> me her repreue,</L>
<L N="20962">Or thyn hert&euml; so to greue,</L>
<L>To sen me don swych &oacute;bseruaunce</L>
<L>With al myn hool&euml; affyaunce,</L>
<L>To thys yd&oacute;l&euml;s set on stages,</L>
<L N="20966">Syth pylgrymes, in ther<NOTE PLACE="marg">[ther <I>om</I>. Tib.]</NOTE> pass&aacute;ges</L>
<L>Honowre and worshepe, euerychon,</L>
<L>Ymages off tymber and off ston;</L>
<L>And crystene peple, ful nyh alle,</L>
<L N="20970">On ther knes to-forn hem falle;</L>
<L>And, whan al to-gydre ys souht,</L>
<L>They may help&euml; yow ryht nowht,</L>
<L>Nor done to yow noon &aacute;vauntage,</L>
<L N="20974">No mor than her, may myn ymage.'</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>&para; The Pylgryme:<NOTE PLACE="marg">[Tib., Pilgrim St., <I>om</I>. C.]</NOTE></HEAD>
<L>"That thow woldest her conclude,</L>
<L>Thy resouns ar<NOTE PLACE="marg">[C., St. they are, Tib., St. <I>The</I> 6-<I>syllable line is good</I>.]</NOTE> but rude.</L>
<L>ffor, sothly, we nothyng laboure</L>
<L N="20978">The ym&aacute;ges to honoure,</L>
<L>Stook nor ston, nor that men peyntes;</L>
<L>But we honoure the holy seyntes</L>
<L>Off whom they beryn the lyknesse,</L>
<L N="20982">In our mynd&euml;, to enpresse,</L>
<L>By cler&euml;<NOTE PLACE="marg">[clere St., cler C., cleer Tib.]</NOTE> demonstrac&iuml;ouns,<MILESTONE N="272a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Ther martyrdam, ther pass&iuml;ouns,</L>
<L>Ther holy lyff, ther<NOTE PLACE="marg">[and ther Tib.]</NOTE> myracles</L>
<L>Wych ben to vs but<NOTE PLACE="marg">[but St., but as C.]</NOTE> spectacles,</L>
<L>And as merours, that represente</L>
<L>Ther trewe menyng and ther<NOTE PLACE="marg">[ther <I>om</I>. St.]</NOTE> entente,</L>
<L>Ther gret&euml; labour and vyct&oacute;rye;
<PB REF="00000668.tif" N="560"></L>
<L N="20990">"That we shold&euml; ha mem&oacute;rye,<MILESTONE UNIT="Tib folio" N="68a"></L>
<L>By hem, a kalender to make,</L>
<L>What they suffrede for crystes sake,</L>
<L>Patryarch&euml;s and proph&eacute;tys,</L>
<L N="20994">Wych in hevene haue now her setys;</L>
<L>The<NOTE PLACE="marg">[And the Tib.]</NOTE> pass&iuml;oun off cryst hym-sylue,<NOTE PLACE="inter">[An Illumination follows in Tib.]</NOTE></L>
<L>And off hys apostelys twelue,</L>
<L>And off martyrs that wer vyctours;</L>
<L N="20998">The pacy&euml;nce off c&oacute;nfessours,</L>
<L>And off maydenes, in ther degre,</L>
<L>That deyd&euml;<NOTE PLACE="marg">[C., deyed Tib., dyed St.]</NOTE> in vyrgynyte,</L>
<L>As clerkys in ther lyv&euml;s<NOTE PLACE="marg">[boks St.]</NOTE> ffynde.<MILESTONE UNIT="Stowe folio" N="341a"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="21002">"Ym&aacute;ges pr&eacute;sente to Our mynde,</L>
<L>And to vs, clerly expresse,</L>
<L>Off her lyvyng the holynesse;</L>
<L>And for thys skyle, (with-out&euml; let)</L>
<L N="21006">Ymages in cherches ben vp set;</L>
<L>And vn-to folkys many On,</L>
<L>fful gret profyt also they done,</L>
<L>Namly, to swych (I yow ensure)</L>
<L N="21010">That ne kan, no lettrure;</L>
<L>ffor, on ym&aacute;ges whan they lookys,</L>
<L>Ther they rede, as in ther bookys,<NOTE PLACE="marg">[loke . . boke St., lokys . . bokys Tib.]</NOTE></L>
<L>What they ouhte off ryht to sue,<MILESTONE UNIT="Tib folio" N="68b"></L>
<L>And also what they shal<NOTE PLACE="marg">[schulde Tib., shuld St.]</NOTE> eschewe,</L>
<L N="21015">Ther they may yt clerly lere.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>"But off thy mawmet, I wolde here,</L>
<L>Wych may th&eacute; no thyng socoure,</L>
<L N="21018">Why thow sholdest hym honoure.<MILESTONE N="272b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>ffor (who that any resoun kan,)</L>
<L>With-Inne, enclosyd ys Sathan,</L>
<L>And ther hym-sylff hath mad a se,</L>
<L N="21022">The prynce off al inyquyte,</L>
<L>The wych&euml;<NOTE PLACE="marg">[whiche Tib., St., wych C.]</NOTE> (shortly for tendyte,)</L>
<L>fful mortally he shal the quyte,</L>
<L>Whan he seth tyme, and best leyser.</L>
<L N="21026">And therfor, now, whyl thow art her,</L>
<L>Off thy Mawmet for to telle,</L>
<L>Sey on; for I ne may nat dwelle."
<PB REF="00000669.tif" N="561"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>The Vyleyn:<NOTE PLACE="marg">[St., veleyne Tib., <I>om</I>. C.]</NOTE></HEAD>
<L>'Thow gest<NOTE PLACE="marg">[geste Tib., getst St.]</NOTE> no mor, as now, for me;</L>
<L N="21030">But off O thyng I warn&euml; the;</L>
<L>Yiff thow in thys place abyde,</L>
<L>Myn ax shal thorgh thy nekk&euml; glyde,</L>
<L>But yiff<NOTE PLACE="marg">[&yogh;eue Tib.]</NOTE> thow do to myn Im&aacute;ge,</L>
<L N="21034">Lowly worshepe and hom&aacute;ge.</L>
<L>Ches yiff<NOTE PLACE="marg">[&yogh;eue Tib.]</NOTE> the lyst, and lat me se,</L>
<L>ffor thow gest<NOTE PLACE="marg">[getest St., geste Tib.]</NOTE> no mor off me.'</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>The Pylgryme:<NOTE PLACE="marg">[Tib., Pilgrim St., <I>om</I>. C.]</NOTE></HEAD>
<L>Than I stood in fful gret doute.</L>
<L N="21038">And as I tournede me aboute,</L>
<L>Myd off thys Ile that I off tolde,</L>
<L>And euery party gan beholde,</L>
<L>Myd off thys se, lookyng ech way</L>
<L N="21042">How I myhte eskape a-way;</L>
<L>And to-for myn Eye<NOTE PLACE="marg">[eyne St.]</NOTE> I fond<MILESTONE UNIT="Tib folio" N="69a"></L>
<L>A Maryssh, or elles a merssh<NOTE PLACE="marg">[mershe St.]</NOTE> lond,</L>
<L>That peryllous was, and ful profounde,</L>
<L N="21046">And off ffylth&euml;s ryht habounde.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>And thyder-ward as<NOTE PLACE="marg">[was C.]</NOTE> I gan hye</L>
<L>A vekk&euml; Old me dyde espye,</L>
<L>Komyng with an owgly cher;<MILESTONE UNIT="Stowe folio" N="341b"></L>
<L N="21050">Vp-on hyr hed, a gret paner;</L>
<L>In hyr ryht hand (as I was war,)</L>
<L>An hand kut off, me sempte she bar.</L>
<L>And, or any hede I took,<NOTE PLACE="marg">[I took Tib. (C. <I>burnt</I>), she toke St.]</NOTE><MILESTONE N="273a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>She kauhte me <SUP>10</SUP>with a crokyd hooke.<SUP>10</SUP><NOTE PLACE="marg">[10_10 Tib. (C. <I>burnt</I>), hoke St.]</NOTE><NOTE PLACE="inter">[Blank in MS. for an Illumination, given in Tib. The old Witch has, in her left hand, a long stick, hookt under the Pilgrim's left armpit; and her right hand grasps a big cut-off hand by its wrist.]</NOTE></L>
<L>And as she gan me fast&euml; holde,</L>
<L N="21056">I axede hyre what that she wolde,</L>
<L>And make<NOTE PLACE="marg">[make C., Tib., St.]</NOTE> a declarac&iuml;oun</L>
<L>Off name and off condyc&iuml;oun.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>&para; Sorcerye:<NOTE PLACE="marg">[Tib., St., <I>om</I>. C.]</NOTE></HEAD>
<L N="21059">Quod she: 'vnderstond me thus;</L>
<L>My nam&euml; ys 'Byth&aacute;lassus,'<NOTE PLACE="marg">[bythalassus Tib., Bythassus C., St.]</NOTE></L>
<L>Wych ys to seyn&euml;, (who lyst<NOTE PLACE="marg">[lyste Tib., lyst C., St.]</NOTE> se)
<PB REF="00000670.tif" N="562"></L>
<L>'A ffamous pereyl off the se,</L>
<L>In wych (wyth-outen any grace)<MILESTONE UNIT="Tib folio" N="69b"></L>
<L N="21064">All&euml;<NOTE PLACE="marg">[Alle Tib., Al C., All St.]</NOTE> ffolk that forby pace,</L>
<L>And all&euml; tho that thorgh me gon,</L>
<L>I make hem perysshen,<NOTE PLACE="marg">[peryshe St.]</NOTE> euerychon.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>'And also ek touchyng my name,</L>
<L N="21068">I am callyd (by gret dyffame,</L>
<L>As som<NOTE PLACE="marg">[som C., Tib., some St.]</NOTE> ffolkys specefye,)</L>
<L>'Sortylege<NOTE PLACE="marg">[Cortylage Tib.]</NOTE> or Sorcerye.'</L>
<L>Many folkys thus me calle;</L>
<L>And yet they hat&euml; me nat<NOTE PLACE="marg">[not at St., nat C., not Tib.]</NOTE> alle;</L>
<L N="21073">I am be-lovyd, bothe ffer and ner.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>'And I ber ek in thys paner</L>
<L>(Who that with-Inn&euml; lyst to seke)</L>
<L N="21076">Many knyves and hoodys ek,</L>
<L>Dyvers wryt&euml;s and ym&aacute;ges,</L>
<L>Oynementys and herb&aacute;ges,</L>
<L>Gadryd in constellac&iuml;ouns;</L>
<L N="21080">ffor I obseru&euml; my sesouns,</L>
<L>and make off hem elleccyoun<MILESTONE N="273b" UNIT="folio"><NOTE PLACE="marg">[Tib.]</NOTE></L>
<L>afftir myne oppynyoun.<NOTE PLACE="marg">[Tib.]</NOTE></L>
<L>And 'Maleffyc&euml;', folkes<NOTE PLACE="marg">[Malyfite folks St.]</NOTE> alle,<NOTE PLACE="marg">[Tib.]</NOTE></L>
<L N="21084">Off ryght, they shuld&euml; me so calle.<NOTE PLACE="marg">[Tib.]</NOTE></L>
<L>I have ful many evel vs&aacute;ges<NOTE PLACE="marg">[Tib. &amp; C.]</NOTE></L>
<L>Off drynk&euml;s and off bever&aacute;ges,<NOTE PLACE="marg">[Tib. &amp; C.]</NOTE></L>
<L>Wherby I mak&euml; (her and yonder,)</L>
<L N="21088">ffrendys for to parte assonder;</L>
<L>ffor, with fals coniurysouns<NOTE PLACE="marg">[C. &amp; Tib., coniurations St.]</NOTE></L>
<L>And with myn incantac&iuml;ouns,</L>
<L>And many dyuers enchaunt&euml;ment,</L>
<L N="21092">Sondry folk ben offt&euml; shent.</L>
<L>And, with dyuers crafftys ek,</L>
<L>I kan mak&euml; men ful sek;</L>
<L>And somme also ful cursydly</L>
<L N="21096">ffor to dey&euml; sodeynly.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>'And, in lordys ek pres&eacute;ncys,<MILESTONE UNIT="Stowe folio" N="242a"></L>
<L>I kan make ek<NOTE PLACE="marg">[eke make Tib.]</NOTE> appar&eacute;ncys</L>
<L>Whan that me lyst, ful many On,<MILESTONE UNIT="Tib folio" N="70a"></L>
<L N="21100">Yiff I sholde telle hem euerychon.'</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>&para; The Pylgryme:<NOTE PLACE="marg">[Pilgrim Tib., St., <I>om</I>. C.]</NOTE>
</HEAD>
<PB REF="00000671.tif" N="563">
<L>"Tel on, (with-out&euml; mor taryng,)</L>
<L>Wher lernystow al thy konnyng.<NOTE PLACE="marg">[konynge St., kunnynge Tib.]</NOTE>"</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>&para; Sorcerye:<NOTE PLACE="marg">[Tib., St., erye, <I>in margin</I> C.]</NOTE></HEAD>
<L>'Sothly, (as I rehers&euml; kan,)</L>
<L N="21104">I lernede my konnyng off Sathan,<NOTE PLACE="inter">[An Illumination follows in Tib., of the Devil and four women, one with a long-headed rod, and an|other with a child in her arms.]</NOTE></L>
<L>Wych halt hys scole nat hennys ffer,</L>
<L>And hath ydon ful<NOTE PLACE="marg">[ydone St.]</NOTE> many A yer.</L>
<L N="21107">And to that scol&euml; kome and gon,</L>
<L>Off scolerys ful many<NOTE PLACE="marg">[scolars . . many a St., scolers . . many Tib., scolerys . . manyng C.]</NOTE> on;</L>
<L>And he, aboue al maner thyng,</L>
<L>Ys ful glad off ther komyng.</L>
<L>And off that Art, in many wyse,</L>
<L N="21112">Ther, I ha<NOTE PLACE="marg">[haue Tib.]</NOTE> lernyd the guyse.</L>
<L>And offt&euml;<NOTE PLACE="marg">[offte C., Tib., eft St.]</NOTE> sythe (yiff thow lyst se,)</L>
<L>Ther, wyth othor scolerys be.'</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>&para; The Pylgryme:<NOTE PLACE="marg">[Tib., Pilgrim St., <I>om</I>. C.]</NOTE></HEAD>
<L>"Tel on (and make no mor lettynge<NOTE PLACE="marg">[lettynge Tib. St. (C. <I>burnt</I>.)]</NOTE>)<MILESTONE N="274a" UNIT="folio"><MILESTONE UNIT="Tib folio" N="70b"></L>
<L>What gaff thow hym for thy kunnynge<NOTE PLACE="marg">[kunnynge Tib., conynge St.]</NOTE>?"</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>&para; Sorcerye:<NOTE PLACE="marg">[Tib., St., <I>om</I>. C.]</NOTE></HEAD>
<L N="21117">'The trouth&euml;, yiff I tell&euml; shal,</L>
<L>My soule I gaff hym, hool and al,</L>
<L>And forsook (by chaffaryng)</L>
<L N="21120">The werkys off the myghty kyng.</L>
<L>And who that euere wyl do so,</L>
<L>And to that scole approche vn-to,</L>
<L>He may (yiff that I shal nat lye,)</L>
<L>ffynd&euml; ther swych<NOTE PLACE="marg">[fynd . . suche St., ffynde . . swyche Tib.]</NOTE> mercerye.'</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>&para; The Pylgryme:<NOTE PLACE="marg">[Tib., Pilgrim St., <I>om</I>. C.]</NOTE></HEAD>
<L N="21125">"Thow hast (as I shal devyse,)</L>
<L>Mad a shrewd&euml;<NOTE PLACE="marg">[schrewyd Tib.]</NOTE> marchaundyse,</L>
<L>To yeue<NOTE PLACE="marg">[yue C., &yogh;eue Tib.]</NOTE> A thyng off gret noblesse,</L>
<L N="21128">Excellyng ek in worthynesse,</L>
<L>And also off so<NOTE PLACE="marg">[so C., St., <I>om</I>. Tib.]</NOTE> gret vertu,</L>
<L>ffor a thyng off no valu,</L>
<L>And (off trouthe and off resoun)</L>
<L N="21132">Most wyl<NOTE PLACE="marg">[vyle Tib., vyll St.]</NOTE> off reputac&iuml;oun;</L>
<L>ffor the wych, (I dar wel telle,)
<PB REF="00000672.tif" N="564"></L>
<L>"In gret&euml;<NOTE PLACE="marg">[gret C., St., gvet Tib.]</NOTE> pereyl thow dost dwelle,</L>
<L>(Off verray soth, And off no Iape,)</L>
<L N="21136">Neuere lykly to eskape."</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>&para; Sorcerye:<NOTE PLACE="marg">[Tib., St., <I>in margin</I> C.]</NOTE></HEAD>
<L>'Al thy seyyng, euerydel,</L>
<L>I wot my-sylff that, wonder wel;</L>
<L>ffor I stonde in swych meschaunce</L>
<L N="21140">That I ha<NOTE PLACE="marg">[haue St.]</NOTE> no r&eacute;pentaunce;</L>
<L>I am so ffer ybrouht with-Inne,<MILESTONE UNIT="Tib folio" N="71a"></L>
<L>And engluyd so with synne,<MILESTONE UNIT="Stowe folio" N="342b"></L>
<L>So clevynge vp-on myn errour,</L>
<L N="21144">That I truste on no socour;</L>
<L>ffor thogh I shold&euml; go to helle,</L>
<L>I wyl nat go ffro that I telle.'</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>&para; The Pylgryme:<NOTE PLACE="marg">[Tib., <I>om</I>. C., St.]</NOTE><MILESTONE N="274b" UNIT="folio"></HEAD>
<L>"Declare to me, and haue Ido,<NOTE PLACE="marg">[Tib.]</NOTE></L>
<L N="21148">Where-off seruith that hand also<NOTE PLACE="marg">[Tib.]</NOTE></L>
<L>whiche thow<NOTE PLACE="marg">[thow St., that Tib.]</NOTE> holdyst now so ffaste:<NOTE PLACE="marg">[Tib.]</NOTE></L>
<L>Thys thyng, expowne to me in hast."</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>&para; Sorcerye:<NOTE PLACE="marg">[Tib., St., erye <I>in margin</I> C.]</NOTE></HEAD>
<L>Quod she to me ageyn<NOTE PLACE="marg">[ageyn, <I>om</I>. Tib.]</NOTE> a-noon;</L>
<L N="21152">'M&aacute;thesis, fful yore agon,<NOTE PLACE="marg">[C. &amp; Tib.]</NOTE></L>
<L>Gaff yt to me (by gret outr&aacute;ge,)</L>
<L>And also ek<NOTE PLACE="marg">[C., Tib., eke also St.]</NOTE> an hool vys&aacute;ge,</L>
<L>Wych that I haue in my depoos,</L>
<L N="21156">Her, with-Inne my paner cloos.</L>
<L>Yt ys ycallyd 'Physonomye,'<NOTE PLACE="marg">[Tib. transposes these lines.]</NOTE></L>
<L>And thys hand 'Cyromancye,'<NOTE PLACE="marg">[Tib. transposes these lines.]</NOTE></L>
<L>To telle the dysposic&iuml;ouns</L>
<L N="21160">Off ffolk, and ther condyc&iuml;ouns.'</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>&para; The Pylgryme:<NOTE PLACE="marg">[Tib., Pilgrim St., <I>om</I>. C.]</NOTE></HEAD>
<L>"Tel on! expowne that thyng to me,</L>
<L>In what wys&euml; that myhte be,</L>
<L>Or that thow and I dysseuere;</L>
<L N="21164">ffor, at that scole I was neuere."</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>&para; Sorcerye:<NOTE PLACE="marg">[Tib., St., <I>om</I>. C.]</NOTE></HEAD>
<L>'Herdystow neuere (off &aacute;venture)<MILESTONE UNIT="Tib folio" N="71b"></L>
<L>That a man, in scrypture,</L>
<L>Off thys<NOTE PLACE="marg">[That off these Tib.]</NOTE> phylosofres alle,</L>
<L>How 'Mycrocosme'<NOTE PLACE="marg">[Tib., St., mycocrosme C.]</NOTE> they hym calle,
<PB REF="00000673.tif" N="565"></L>
<L>'(Shortly to tellen, at O word)</L>
<L N="21170">Nat ellys but 'the lass&euml; world'?'</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>&para; The Pylgryme:<NOTE PLACE="marg">[Tib., Pilgrim St., <I>om</I>. C.]</NOTE></HEAD>
<L>"I haue herd yt<NOTE PLACE="marg">[And I haue herd Tib.]</NOTE> in scolys offte,</L>
<L>Ther yrad,<NOTE PLACE="marg">[ther I rad St., where I radde Tib.]</NOTE> bothe loude and soffte."</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>&para; Sorcerye:<NOTE PLACE="marg">[St., . . erie <I>in margin</I> C.]</NOTE></HEAD>
<L N="21173">'Thyn Answere mvt be verrefyed;</L>
<L>Thys lass&euml; world ys stellefyed</L>
<L>Lych hevene, and as the ffyrmament,</L>
<L N="21176">Ther-off to make A Iug&euml;ment,&mdash;</L>
<L>Vnderstonde by both&euml; two,</L>
<L>The vysage and the hand also,&mdash;</L>
<L>Vp-on wych, by trew&euml; syht,</L>
<L N="21180">Men may yive a doom A-ryht,<MILESTONE N="275a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Tell&euml; the condyc&iuml;ouns</L>
<L>By dyvers lyneac&iuml;ouns</L>
<L>Wych ther be set (I the ensure,)</L>
<L N="21184">Ryht as sterrys off nature.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>&para; The Pylgryme:<NOTE PLACE="marg">[Tib., Pilgrim St., <I>om</I>. C.]</NOTE></HEAD>
<L>"To thy wordys I may accorde</L>
<L>In party, and nat dyscorde,</L>
<L>That a man whom we nevene<MILESTONE UNIT="Stowe folio" N="343a"></L>
<L N="21188">Ys ysterryd as the hevene;</L>
<L>But her-vp-on, in substaunce,</L>
<L>Thow puttest nat in r&eacute;membraunce,</L>
<L>Namynge thylk&euml; lyneaciouns,</L>
<L N="21192">By namys off constellaciouns;<MILESTONE UNIT="Tib folio" N="72a"></L>
<L>ffor trew&euml;ly<NOTE PLACE="marg">[trewely Tib., trewly C., truly St.]</NOTE> (who kan remembre)</L>
<L>The body off man, and euery membre,</L>
<L>Ben off erth&euml;, in certeyn,</L>
<L N="21196">And to erthe shal tourne ageyn.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>"And, affter philisofres talys,</L>
<L>Ther ben hyll&euml;s, ther ben wal&euml;s,<NOTE PLACE="marg">[talis . . valys Tib., tallis . . vallis St.]</NOTE></L>
<L>Medwes, ryvers, both&euml; two,</L>
<L N="21200">Wyld&euml; bestys ek also,</L>
<L>And gret&euml; ffeldys men may sen,</L>
<L>And pathes that hem departeth<NOTE PLACE="marg">[departe Tib.]</NOTE> a-twen,</L>
<L>And places also off desert,</L>
<L N="21204">Somm&euml; open, somme couert:</L>
<L>Thys be the lyneac&iuml;ouns
<PB REF="00000674.tif" N="566"></L>
<L>"Y-namyd constellac&iuml;ouns,</L>
<L>In the handys and the vysage,</L>
<L N="21208">Wherby, clerkys that be sage,</L>
<L>Affter thyn oppynyoun,</L>
<L>Mak&euml; dyvynac&iuml;oun,</L>
<L>And declare to the and me</L>
<L N="21212">(Who that kan beholde and se)</L>
<L>A manhys<NOTE PLACE="marg">[mannes Tib., mans St.]</NOTE> dysposic&iuml;oun.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>"But al thys, in conclus&iuml;oun;</L>
<L>To devyn&euml;, by swych<NOTE PLACE="marg">[swyche Tib., suche St.]</NOTE> thynges,</L>
<L N="21216">Ar but fables and lesynges.<MILESTONE N="275b" UNIT="folio"><NOTE PLACE="marg">[C. &amp; Tib.]</NOTE></L>
<L>ffor, (yiff thow wylt trewly nevene,)<NOTE PLACE="marg">[C. &amp; Tib.]</NOTE></L>
<L>In A man, ther ys noon hevene,</L>
<L>(ffor to name yt trew&euml;ly.<NOTE PLACE="marg">[trewly C., truly St.]</NOTE>)</L>
<L N="21220">But hys sowl&euml; al only.</L>
<L>What so euere ther-off thow telles,</L>
<L>That ys hys hevene, and nothyng ellys:</L>
<L>Thus clerkys seyn, that trouth&euml; konne.</L>
<L N="21224">And, off thys, the bryht&euml; sonne</L>
<L>Namyd ys (in sentement)</L>
<L>Intellect or entend&euml;ment.'<NOTE PLACE="marg">[C., Tib., Incelent or encendement St.]</NOTE></L>
<L>The mon&euml;<NOTE PLACE="marg">[mone Tib., name C.]</NOTE> (in conclus&iuml;oun)</L>
<L N="21228">Ys ycallyd hys resoun,<MILESTONE UNIT="Tib folio" N="72b"></L>
<L>Hys vertues, and good&euml; thewes.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>"And good exaumple that he shewes,</L>
<L>Tho ben the sterrys bryht and clere,</L>
<L N="21232">Wych that in thys heuene apere.</L>
<L>And hooly clerkys, in bookys kan,</L>
<L>'The lass&euml; world' thus calle A man.</L>
<L>And who that hath most holynesse</L>
<L N="21236">In vertu, haveth most bryhtnesse:</L>
<L>Wych sterrys make a man at al</L>
<L>To be callyd 'celestyal,'<MILESTONE UNIT="Stowe folio" N="343b"></L>
<L>And concluden (off Resoun,)</L>
<L N="21240">Hevenly dysposic&iuml;oun.</L>
<L>Thys the trowthe, with-out&euml; glose.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>"And lyk thy wordys, I suppose,</L>
<L>Affter the caas off thy seyyng.<NOTE PLACE="marg">[seiynge Tib., sayenge St.]</NOTE></L>
<L N="21244">That swyche toknys outward shewyng,</L>
<L>ffygures or<NOTE PLACE="marg">[and Tib.]</NOTE> lyneac&iuml;ouus,
<PB REF="00000675.tif" N="567"></L>
<L>"Shewede the condyc&iuml;ouns,</L>
<L>And outward made ther-on A skyl</L>
<L N="21248">Off governaunce towchyng hys wyl,</L>
<L>Off folkys inclinac&iuml;ouns,&mdash;</L>
<L>Yt ar<NOTE PLACE="marg">[That are Tib.]</NOTE> but fals fundac&iuml;ouns,</L>
<L>(Ther-vp-on, who lyst to se,)</L>
<L N="21252">To conclude necessyte,</L>
<L>That yt muste be so off ryht.<MILESTONE N="276a" UNIT="folio"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>"ffor tooknys, in A manhys<NOTE PLACE="marg">[mannes Tib., mans St.]</NOTE> syht,</L>
<L>And sygn&euml;s (bothe at eve and prime,)</L>
<L N="21256">Deceyve and faylle ful offt&euml; tyme,</L>
<L>To folk that looke with eyen cler.</L>
<L>Ryght as, off A tauerner,</L>
<L>The gren&euml; bussh that hangeth out,</L>
<L N="21260">Ys a sygne (yt ys no doute,)</L>
<L>Outward, folkys for to telle,</L>
<L>That with-Inne ys wyn to sell.</L>
<L>And for al that, (I the ensure)</L>
<L N="21264">Yt may falle<NOTE PLACE="marg">[fayle St.]</NOTE> off &aacute;venture,<MILESTONE UNIT="Tib folio" N="73a"></L>
<L>ffor alle the bowes, rekne echon,</L>
<L>That, with-Inne, wyn ys ther noon.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>"And Evene (to purpos off thys cas,)</L>
<L N="21268">Yt ffyl thus off Ypocras,</L>
<L>The phylysofre ful famous,</L>
<L>Ryht prudent and vertuous,</L>
<L>Off whom the ffygur and ym&aacute;ge</L>
<L N="21272">And tooknys alle off hys vys&aacute;ge,</L>
<L>Wer ybrouht to Phylemoun,</L>
<L>A phylisofre off gret renoun,</L>
<L>ffor to descryue hem by and by,</L>
<L N="21276">And to concluden naturelly</L>
<L>Al the inclynac&iuml;ouns</L>
<L>And also the condic&iuml;ouns</L>
<L>Off Ypocras, that was so wys.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="21280">"And Philemoun (by short avys)</L>
<L>Concludede (as in sentement)</L>
<L>That he was incontynent,</L>
<L>And off hys lyvyng vycyous,</L>
<L N="21284">And naturely ek lecherous.</L>
<L>ffor (whan he took good heed ther-to,)
<PB REF="00000676.tif" N="568"></L>
<L>"The tooknys outward told hym so,</L>
<L>By Open demonstrac&iuml;oun.<MILESTONE UNIT="Stowe folio" N="344a"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="21288">"But ypocras, (off good resoun)</L>
<L>By vertu only, dyde hys peyne,<MILESTONE N="276b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Alle the sygn&euml;s to restreyne,</L>
<L>ffor-dyde hys inclynac&iuml;oun</L>
<L N="21292">Wyth a brydel off resoun;</L>
<L>And wyth hys fflessh held swych a stryff,</L>
<L>That he was vertuous off lyff.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>"The tooknys (who so lyst to se)</L>
<L N="21296">Causede noon necessyte;</L>
<L>ffor, thogh they gaff an &aacute;pparence,</L>
<L>They wer fals<NOTE PLACE="marg">[were ffalse Tib.]</NOTE> in &eacute;xistence,</L>
<L>And maden a ful strong lesyng<MILESTONE UNIT="Tib folio" N="73b"></L>
<L N="21300">To Phylemoun in hys demyng.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>"Wher-for, lern&euml; thys off me;</L>
<L>Lat thy ffantasy&euml;s<NOTE PLACE="marg">[ffantesye Tib.]</NOTE> be,</L>
<L>ffor to bryng&euml;<NOTE PLACE="marg">[brynge Tib., bryng C., St.]</NOTE> folk in<NOTE PLACE="marg">[in a St.]</NOTE> rage,</L>
<L N="21304">Both off thyn hand and thy vys&aacute;ge,</L>
<L>And also ek off thy paner</L>
<L>Wych&euml;<NOTE PLACE="marg">[whiche Tib., St., wych C.]</NOTE> that thow shewest her.</L>
<L>ffor they be superstycious,</L>
<L N="21308">Cursyd, and ryht contagyous;</L>
<L>And therfor, by the rede off me,</L>
<L>A-noon let cast hem in the Se."</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>And in thys poynt, good hed I took,</L>
<L>And brak<NOTE PLACE="marg">[brake Tib., St.]</NOTE> loos oute off hys hook;</L>
<L N="21313">And, wyth-out&euml; mor delay,</L>
<L>Went&euml; forth vp-on my way,</L>
<L>Tyl at the laste I gan Aproche</L>
<L N="21316">ffast&euml; by vn-to A roche.</L>
<L>And I a-noon (off goode entente)</L>
<L>Ther-vp-on, a-noon I wente.</L>
<L>And to thys roch&euml; large<NOTE PLACE="marg">[longe Tib.]</NOTE> and squar,</L>
<L N="21320">The se kam doun, or I was war,</L>
<L>And besette me round aboute;</L>
<L>Wher-off I stood in ful gret doute,</L>
<L>And hadde in hert&euml; fful gret wo,</L>
<L N="21324">Whan I was besegyd so</L>
<L>Wyth the floodys sterne and huge,
<PB REF="00000677.tif" N="569"></L>
<L>And knew,<NOTE PLACE="marg">[knewe Tib., knew C., St.]</NOTE> as tho, no refuge,</L>
<L>Confort nor consolac&iuml;oun.<MILESTONE N="277a" UNIT="folio"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="21328">And sodeynly I sawh kome doun</L>
<L>A wonder Old enchaunteresse,</L>
<L>And to me-ward she gan hyr dresse.</L>
<L>And I sawh wel ek ther I stood,</L>
<L N="21332">On the waw&euml;s how she rood,</L>
<L>Off look and cher&euml;<NOTE PLACE="marg">[chere St., cher C.]</NOTE> fful pervers;</L>
<L>And howndys manye and dyvers<MILESTONE UNIT="Tib folio" N="74a"></L>
<L>She hadde, behynde and ek beforn;<MILESTONE UNIT="Stowe folio" N="344b"></L>
<L N="21336">And myghtyly she blewh an horn,</L>
<L>Made hyr houndys a gret route,</L>
<L>ffor tassaylle me round aboute.<NOTE PLACE="inter">[Blank in MS. for an Illumination, given in Tib., of the Hornblower on the waves, and the Pilgrim on his little bit of ground, and eight hounds round him.]</NOTE></L>
<L>And as I stood vp-on the wrak,</L>
<L N="21340">Evene thus to me she spak:</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>&para; Scilla, (or) Conspiraccioun:<NOTE PLACE="marg">[Tib. (<I>om</I>. St., <I>in margin</I> C.)]</NOTE></HEAD>
<L>Quod she, 'thow must descende a-doun,</L>
<L>ffor ther geyneth no raunsoun</L>
<L>But that thow shalt devour&euml;d be</L>
<L N="21344">Off thys houndys, that thow dost se.'</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>&para; The Pylgryme:<NOTE PLACE="marg">[Tib., Pilgrim St., <I>om</I>. C.]</NOTE></HEAD>
<L>"Certys," quod I, "yt is no nay,</L>
<L>I stonde in a perillous way;</L>
<L>But, I praye the, in thys rage,</L>
<L N="21348">Let me nat off my passage,</L>
<L>Nor bryng me nat in no dyffame</L>
<L>Tyl that thow ha told thy name,<MILESTONE UNIT="Tib folio" N="74b"></L>
<L>And shewyd, by relac&iuml;oun,</L>
<L N="21352">Thy maner, and thy condyc&iuml;oun."</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>Scilla, Conspiracyoun:<NOTE PLACE="marg">[Tib., St., <I>om</I>. C.]</NOTE></HEAD>
<L>'My name (for short conclus&iuml;oun)<MILESTONE N="277b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Ys callyd 'Conspirac&iuml;oun,'</L>
<L>Or ellys (what so euere falle,)</L>
<L N="21356">'Scilla' ek thow mayst me calle;</L>
<L>And am ek (yiff thow lyst<NOTE PLACE="marg">[lyste to Tib., lyst C., St.]</NOTE> se)</L>
<L>On off the pereilles off the se.
<PB REF="00000678.tif" N="570"></L>
<L>'I chace at hem that ther-in Rowe,</L>
<L N="21360">And make the fell&euml; floodys flowe,</L>
<L>ffolkys for to putte in doute,</L>
<L>Do myn houndys, ful gret route,</L>
<L>Berkyn, and gret noys&euml; make;</L>
<L N="21364">And gret&euml; bestys for to take</L>
<L>With-out&euml; noys&euml; or<NOTE PLACE="marg">[or greet Tib.]</NOTE> berkyng:</L>
<L>Wonder grevous ys ther bytyng.</L>
<L>I couple hem with myn owne hondys,</L>
<L N="21368">And gret&euml; hoth&euml;s<NOTE PLACE="marg">[othes Tib.]</NOTE> ben the bondys</L>
<L>Wyth wych I make ther &aacute;llyaunce,</L>
<L>Bothe by feyth and &aacute;ssuraunce.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>'Wyth the noys&euml; that they make,</L>
<L N="21372">Pylgrymes offte they don a-wake;</L>
<L>And thogh they berke nat On A man,</L>
<L>fful mortally they byten kan;</L>
<L>And thogh they byten by greet<NOTE PLACE="marg">[greet Tib., gre C., St.]</NOTE> sleyhte,</L>
<L N="21376">Ther berkyng ys no thyng on heyhte;</L>
<L>Ther fraude ys do so couertlye,</L>
<L>That no man may yt espye;</L>
<L N="21379">ffor, vnder colour, (in sothnesse,)</L>
<L>They wyl ha<NOTE PLACE="marg">[wole haue Tib.]</NOTE> thank for her falsnesse.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>'And, to purpos off thys thyng,<NOTE PLACE="marg">[<MILESTONE UNIT="Tib folio" N="75a"> with a big Illu|mination of two kings going to war.]</NOTE></L>
<L>Yt ffyl onys, that a kyng,</L>
<L>A-geyn a-nother kyng nat ferre,</L>
<L N="21384">Off purpos held A mortal werre;</L>
<L>And with the meyne that they with-held,</L>
<L>Bothe they kam in-to the ffeld.<MILESTONE UNIT="Stowe folio" N="345a"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>'The ffyrst&euml; kyng that I off telle,</L>
<L>With<NOTE PLACE="marg">[of St., with Tib., C.]</NOTE> knyhtys that aboute hym dwelle,</L>
<L N="21389">On whom he trustede as hys lyff,<MILESTONE N="278a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Gan fyrst asayllen in thys stryff;</L>
<L>But for al that, I, with my wyle,</L>
<L N="21392">Thus I dyde the kyng begyle:</L>
<L>I made hys knyhtys, the<NOTE PLACE="marg">[they C.]</NOTE> day to-forn,</L>
<L>Vn-to hym for to be sworn,</L>
<L>Ther-vp-on her lyff to spende,</L>
<L N="21396">That they sholde hym wel dyffende,</L>
<L>And knyhtly gouerne the bataylle.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>'But at the poynt, they dyde hym faylle;
<PB REF="00000679.tif" N="571"></L>
<L>'They entren in with manly chere;</L>
<L N="21400">And whan they gan assemble yfere,</L>
<L>Off purpos, thys<NOTE PLACE="marg">[these Tib., thes St.]</NOTE> knyhtys euerychon,</L>
<L>Wer y-yolden, On by On,</L>
<L>By sleyhte and by collus&iuml;oun,</L>
<L N="21404">To make hym pay&euml; ther raunsoun.</L>
<L>Wherfor, the sam&euml; kyng, allas,<MILESTONE UNIT="Tib folio" N="75b"></L>
<L>Was deceyved in thys caas;</L>
<L>With shame and gret confus&iuml;oun</L>
<L N="21408">Drowh bak vn-to hys pavyll&iuml;oun,</L>
<L>Supposynge, in hys drede,</L>
<L>That thys knyhtys off manhede</L>
<L>Hadde be take in that dystresse,</L>
<L N="21412">Off manhood and off hih prowesse.</L>
<L>And therfor, touchyng ther raunsoun,</L>
<L>The kyng made ther redempc&iuml;oun.</L>
<L>And whan that they kam to hys syht,</L>
<L N="21416">He thankede hem with al hys myght,</L>
<L>Demynge, off manhood, for hys sake,</L>
<L>That they hadde, echon be take,</L>
<L>And lovede hem mor&euml; than beforn,</L>
<L N="21420">Be-cause they han hem so wel born:</L>
<L>But al was fals decepc&iuml;oun,</L>
<L>Contrayre to hys oppynyoun.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>'<I>And</I> swych&euml;<NOTE PLACE="marg">[swyche Tib., swych C. suche St.]</NOTE> houndys dout&euml;les,</L>
<L N="21424">God wot, I ha mo than a les;</L>
<L>Off hem, plente and gret foysoun,<MILESTONE N="278b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>ffor to cachche me venysoun,</L>
<L>Off ffatt&euml; bestys, hih off gres,</L>
<L N="21428">With howndys that be nat Rekk&euml;les,</L>
<L>To chachche,<NOTE PLACE="marg">[cache St.]</NOTE> and bryng&euml; what they may,</L>
<L>Hoom to my larder, day be day.</L>
<L>Swych houndys, myn horn wel knowe,</L>
<L N="21432">And they wyl kom&euml; whan I blowe,</L>
<L>And fawne also whan they me seth.</L>
<L>And thow most fele ther sharp&euml; teth;</L>
<L>And<NOTE PLACE="marg">[And Tib., for St.]</NOTE> trust&euml; wele, they shal nat faylle,</L>
<L>In al hast, the tassaylle.'<NOTE PLACE="marg">[to assaylle Tib., to assayll St.]</NOTE><MILESTONE UNIT="Stowe folio" N="345b"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>And wyth the blowyng off hyr horn,</L>
<L>(Bothe behynd&euml; and beforn,)
<PB REF="00000680.tif" N="572"></L>
<L>As cruelly as the houndys kan,</L>
<L N="21440">Vp-on me echon they ran,<MILESTONE UNIT="Tib folio" N="76a"></L>
<L>And gan assaylle me mortally:</L>
<L>They berke, <SUP>1</SUP>they byt&euml;,<SUP>1</SUP><NOTE PLACE="marg">[1_1 <I>om</I>. St., they bete Tib.]</NOTE> ryht felly,</L>
<L>And to me dyd&euml; ful gret wrong,</L>
<L N="21444">The gret&euml; lemerys wer so strong.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>And hadd&euml; nat the floodys be,</L>
<L>That drowh ageyn in-to the See,</L>
<L>And ek Scilla (of whom I tolde,)</L>
<L N="21448">With hyr Eyen ffoul and Olde,</L>
<L>Caste hyr look on me A-non,</L>
<L>And sayd&euml; that she must&euml; gon</L>
<L>Bakward, and hyr-sylff with-drawe</L>
<L N="21452">Wyth the flood and wyth the wawe;</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>[Scylla or Conspiration.]</HEAD>
<L>'But ffyrst,' quod she, 'ha thys in mynde,</L>
<L>A-nother tyme, yiff I the ffynde,</L>
<L>Trust&euml; fully, I shal be</L>
<L N="21456">Bet avengyd vp-on the.'</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>[The Pilgrim.]</HEAD>
<L>And whan hyr houndys and she wer gon,</L>
<L>I leffte behynden al allon,<NOTE PLACE="inter">[Blank in MS. for an Illumination, given in Tib., of the Pilgrim lying on his little oval green Island in the sea, his bare knees, chest, and right arm showing thro' rents in his torn white robe.]</NOTE><MILESTONE N="279a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Al to-torn and rent with wondys</L>
<L N="21460">Thorgh bytyng off hyr cruel houndys,</L>
<L>Wyth gret sorwe and pass&iuml;oun,</L>
<L>In torment and afflicc&iuml;oun;</L>
<L>And me remembryng in certeyn,<MILESTONE UNIT="Tib folio" N="76b"></L>
<L N="21464">That yiff the floodys kome ageyn,</L>
<L>She sholde, tencress&euml; with my wo.</L>
<L>Kome ageyn hyr-sylff also;</L>
<L>Therfore, to fflen out off hyr syhte,</L>
<L N="21468">In the best&euml; wyse I myghte.</L>
<L>I dyde my labour and my cure,</L>
<L>In hope my syluen to assure,</L>
<L>Yiff I myhte, by hap or grace,</L>
<L N="21472">To draw&euml; to som other place.
<PB REF="00000681.tif" N="573"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>And whyl I lay thus in A trance,</L>
<L>In gret Anoy and p&eacute;rturbaunce,</L>
<L>I herde a voys mellodyus,</L>
<L N="21476">Wonder soote and gracyous,</L>
<L>Wych was to me ful gret plesaunce;</L>
<L>ffor I forgat al my grevaunce,</L>
<L>My dool and al my pass&iuml;oun,</L>
<L N="21480">Wyth mellodye off thylk&euml; soun.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>But as I stood thus in a wher,</L>
<L>And drowh&euml;<NOTE PLACE="marg">[I drowe Tib., And drowh C.]</NOTE> me toward the ryver,</L>
<L>A Tour I sawh, wylde and savage,</L>
<L N="21484">And squar abouten, off passage,<NOTE PLACE="inter">[An Illumination of the Tower follows in Tib., with flames coming out of six holes below the battlements. The Pilgrim is shown on his Island.]</NOTE></L>
<L>Wych hadd&euml; Round&euml;<NOTE PLACE="marg">[Round C., St., rownd Tib.]</NOTE> ffenestrallys,</L>
<L>Percyd thorgh, vp-on the wallys;</L>
<L>At wyche hoolys, (out off doute,)<MILESTONE UNIT="Tib folio" N="97a"></L>
<L N="21488">Smoke and flawm&euml; passede oute;<MILESTONE N="279b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>And yet thys tour (who lok&euml; wel,)</L>
<L>Tournede abouten as a whel<NOTE PLACE="inter">[Blank in MS. for an Illumination.]</NOTE></L>
<L>Vp-on the fflodys Envyroun,</L>
<L N="21492">Wyth the waw&euml;s vp and doun.</L>
<L>Somwhyle (as I koud&euml; knowe)</L>
<L>The hiest party was most lowe;</L>
<L>And also (ek I sawh ful offte)</L>
<L N="21496">The lowest party set aloffte;</L>
<L>And thus, by transmutac&iuml;oun,</L>
<L>Yt turnede alway vp so doun.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>And in thys whyle, euer Among,</L>
<L N="21500">I herd&euml; a melodyous song,</L>
<L>Off On (as I koude vnderstond,)</L>
<L>That ber a phetele<NOTE PLACE="marg">[phethele Tib., phetell St.]</NOTE> in hys hond;</L>
<L>And thys menstral (soth to seyne)</L>
<L N="21504">Was departyd evene a tweyne:</L>
<L>ffrom the myddel vp, A man,</L>
<L>Donward (as I rehers&euml; kan)</L>
<L>A bryd wynged merveyllously,</L>
<L N="21508">Wyth pawnys streynynge mortally.
<PB REF="00000682.tif" N="574"><NOTE PLACE="inter">[Blank in MS. for an Illumination, given in Tib., of a Bird-man flying to the Pilgrim, a curvd fiddle in his left hand, its curvd bow in his right.]</NOTE></L>
<L>And thys best&euml;<NOTE PLACE="marg">[beeste Tib., best C.]</NOTE> ful savage,<MILESTONE N="280a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Lyk a man off hys vysage,</L>
<L>Spak to me fful curteysly;<MILESTONE UNIT="Tib folio" N="77b"></L>
<L N="21512">And thus he sayd&euml; muryely;<NOTE PLACE="marg">[merely Tib.]</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>&para; Gladnesse off the World:<NOTE PLACE="marg">[Tib., <I>in margin</I> C.]</NOTE></HEAD>
<L>'Tel on to me (and sey nat nay,)</L>
<L>What maner solace, or what play</L>
<L>Lovest thow best: tel on, lat se,</L>
<L>And I shal pleyn to-for&euml;<NOTE PLACE="marg">[pleyen to fore Tib., pleyn to for C., p. to fore St.]</NOTE> the;</L>
<L N="21517">ffor I kan (lych to thyn entent)</L>
<L>Pleye on euery instrument;</L>
<L>And,<NOTE PLACE="marg">[And <I>om</I>. Tib.]</NOTE> for to mak&euml; lordys cher,</L>
<L N="21520">Bothe at ches and the cheker,</L>
<L>The drawhtes ther-off, ful wel I kan,</L>
<L>Ye / bet than any other man.</L>
<L>And whan that ylk&euml; play ys do,</L>
<L N="21524">ffor shepperdys I kan also,</L>
<L>At the merellys, best off alle,</L>
<L>Whan so that they lyst me calle,</L>
<L>Pype and taboure in the strete,</L>
<L N="21528">Wyth lusty folkys whan I<NOTE PLACE="marg">[they Tib.]</NOTE> mete.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>'At weddynges, to do plesaunce,</L>
<L>I kan karole wel, and<NOTE PLACE="marg">[and wel Tib.]</NOTE> daunce;</L>
<L>In euery play I do excelle.</L>
<L N="21532">And yt wer to long to telle</L>
<L>The dysportys and the playes</L>
<L>That I vse on somer dayes:</L>
<L N="21535">My Ioye ys al in merthe <I>and</I> game;</L>
<L>And 'Worrldly<NOTE PLACE="marg">[wordely Tib.]</NOTE> Play,' that ys my name.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>'Men may me calle (off equyte)</L>
<L>A Mermayden off the se,<MILESTONE UNIT="Stowe folio" N="346b"></L>
<L>That synge off custom, ay gladdest,</L>
<L N="21540">To-forn a storm and<NOTE PLACE="marg">[or St., and Tib.]</NOTE> a tempest,</L>
<L>To make ek folk<NOTE PLACE="marg">[folke eke Tib.]</NOTE> (thys my labour,)</L>
<L>To forget&euml; ther creatour;</L>
<L>And folk in my subiecc&iuml;oun,</L>
<L N="21544">I brynge hem to destrucc&iuml;oun.'<MILESTONE N="280b" UNIT="folio"><MILESTONE UNIT="Tib folio" N="78a">
<PB REF="00000683.tif" N="575"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>&para; The Pylgryme:<NOTE PLACE="marg">[Tib., Pilgrim St., <I>om</I>. C.]</NOTE></HEAD>
<L>"Thogh thow be-gynn&euml; in gladnesse,</L>
<L>Thow endest euere in wrechchydnesse;</L>
<L>Ellys I wolde, for my plesaunce,</L>
<L N="21548">Wyth the haven &aacute;queyntaunce.</L>
<L>I pray the, put me out off doute</L>
<L>Off thys tour turnynge aboute;</L>
<L>What maner thyng that yt may be,</L>
<L N="21552">ffyrst off alle, that wolde I se."</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>&para; Wordely Gladnesse:<NOTE PLACE="marg">[Tib., worldly gladnes St., <I>om</I>. C.]</NOTE></HEAD>
<L>'ffyrst,<NOTE PLACE="marg">[Fyrste Tib., Fyrst C., St.]</NOTE> (yiff thow lyst to se,)</L>
<L>The grete Am&yacute;ral off the see,</L>
<L>Wych that callyd ys Sathan,</L>
<L N="21556">Thys tour sothly he began;</L>
<L>ffor he fyrst (off entenc&iuml;oun)</L>
<L>Made ther hys habytac&iuml;oun.</L>
<L>And other shyp ne hath he noon,</L>
<L N="21560">Among the floodys for to gon,</L>
<L>In the wyche, by gret deceyt,</L>
<L>He lyth euere in a-wayt,</L>
<L>Wyth pylgrymes to hold&euml; stryff,</L>
<L N="21564">And to make hem lese her lyff.</L>
<L>He seth, bothe by hyl and vale,</L>
<L>Thorough<NOTE PLACE="marg">[Thorough Tib., Thorgh C., thrwghe St.]</NOTE> thylk&euml; hoolys smale,</L>
<L>By what wey&euml; that they gon;</L>
<L N="21568">(Amongys wych&euml;, thow art on,)</L>
<L>And, to deceyve hem in her weye,</L>
<L>Her he maketh me sytte, and pleye</L>
<L>With soot&euml; song and armonye,</L>
<L N="21572">Alle pylgrym&euml;s to espye.</L>
<L>Yt behoueth the taproche,</L>
<L>Or that thow go ner to that roche.'<MILESTONE UNIT="Tib folio" N="78b"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>The Pylgryme:<NOTE PLACE="marg">[Tib., Pilgrim St., <I>om</I>. C.]</NOTE></HEAD>
<L>"Expown&euml; fyrst-lyk<NOTE PLACE="marg">[ffirste Tib., fyrst lyke St.]</NOTE> my desyr;</L>
<L N="21576">Wherfor serueth the smoky ffyr</L>
<L>That ysseth<NOTE PLACE="marg">[yssyth Tib., yssuythe St.]</NOTE> at the hoolys oute,</L>
<L>In thylk&euml; tour<NOTE PLACE="marg">[towre Tib.]</NOTE> round aboute:</L>
<L>Wych thyng, fyrst to me declare;<MILESTONE N="281a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="21580">And thanne to pleye, I shal nat spare."</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>&para; Worldly Gladnesse:<NOTE PLACE="marg">[worldly C. <I>in margin</I>, Wordely Gladnesse Tib., worldly gladnes St.]</NOTE>
</HEAD>
<PB REF="00000684.tif" N="576">
<L>'Sathan, devoyded off al grace,</L>
<L>Haveth ther hys dwellyng place.</L>
<L N="21583">In thylk&euml; dyrk&euml; ffyr, (nat bryht,)<MILESTONE UNIT="Stowe folio" N="347a"></L>
<L>Ther he lyht,<NOTE PLACE="marg">[lythe Tib., lyethe St.]</NOTE> bothe daye and nyht;</L>
<L>And A-mong the smokys blake,</L>
<L>Ther he gan hys bed to make.</L>
<L>And wyth that ffyr despytous,</L>
<L N="21588">He maketh folkys amerous;<NOTE PLACE="inter">[A double Illumination in Tib.: on the left a man kissing and embracing a woman; on the right two men playing at dice.]</NOTE></L>
<L>And with the flawme he kan enbrace,</L>
<L>ffolkys hertys to han solace</L>
<L>In worldly Ioy&euml; (at A word)</L>
<L N="21592">Mor than in ther sovereyn lord.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>'The folkys wych, in ther desyr,</L>
<L>That nyht and day brenne in thys ffyr,</L>
<L>Ar thylk&euml; ffolkys (fynally)</L>
<L N="21596">Wych that brenne so fervently,</L>
<L>Worldly goodys, whan they be-gynne,</L>
<L>To encressyn and to wynne,</L>
<L>Gret tresour to multeplye;</L>
<L N="21600">In the wych they mor affye</L>
<L>Inwardly, in ther entent,</L>
<L>Than in the lord, that al hath sent.</L>
<L>fflowynge and ebbynge in thys se,</L>
<L N="21604">Som tyme with gret prosperyte,</L>
<L>Somwhyle, whan the tourn<NOTE PLACE="marg">[towr St., tourne Tib.]</NOTE> doth varye,</L>
<L>The world they fynde to hem contr&aacute;rye;</L>
<L>Al goth to wrak; they may nat chese;</L>
<L N="21608">And thogh so fall&euml; that they lese,</L>
<L>And fynde ffortune in nowncerteyn,<NOTE PLACE="marg">[no certayne St., nown certeyne Tib.]</NOTE></L>
<L>Yet they wylle hem awntre<NOTE PLACE="marg">[aventer St., aventure hem Tib.]</NOTE> ageyn</L>
<L>To sayllen in<NOTE PLACE="marg">[on Tib.]</NOTE> thys perillous see,</L>
<L N="21612">So ful off mutabylyte;</L>
<L>ffor the hoot&euml; smoky ffyr</L>
<L>Neuere quencheth, in her desyr.</L>
<L>And by his<NOTE PLACE="marg">[his Tib., St., C. <I>burnt</I>]</NOTE> sleyhtys, thus Sathan,<MILESTONE N="281b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="21616">He hath deceyvyd many A man.<NOTE PLACE="marg">[St. &amp; C.]</NOTE></L>
<L>Let now se, and make no Iape,<NOTE PLACE="marg">[St. &amp; C.]</NOTE>
<PB REF="00000685.tif" N="577"></L>
<L>'Wher thow hys treyn&euml;s kanst<NOTE PLACE="marg">[C., Tib., canst his trayns St.]</NOTE> eskape.'</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>&para; The Pylgryme:<NOTE PLACE="marg">[Tib., Pilgrim St., <I>om</I>. C.]</NOTE></HEAD>
<L>"Wyth-Out&euml; long processe to make,</L>
<L N="21620">Hys tour and hym, her I forsake;</L>
<L>And, (short&euml;ly<NOTE PLACE="marg">[schortely Tib., shortly C., St.]</NOTE> to specefye,)</L>
<L>Swych&euml; pley&euml;s I defye,</L>
<L>Wych bryng a man in sorwe and shame.</L>
<L N="21624">But yiff that any other game<MILESTONE UNIT="Tib folio" N="79b"></L>
<L>Thow kanst, I wyl abyde and se</L>
<L>The maner, how yt lyketh me."</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>And thys menstral than a-noon</L>
<L N="21628">Maade hys ffythele<NOTE PLACE="marg">[ffedle Tib.]</NOTE> for to gon,</L>
<L>And song wyth-al fful lustyly.</L>
<L>And wyth hys syngyng, sodeynly</L>
<L N="21631">To me he gan to<NOTE PLACE="marg">[to <I>om</I>. Tib.]</NOTE> tourne hys tayl;</L>
<L>And wyth hys pawnys,<NOTE PLACE="marg">[C., St., pawmes Tib.]</NOTE> sharp as A nayl,<MILESTONE UNIT="Stowe folio" N="347b"></L>
<L>By the Arm he gan me streyne:</L>
<L>Mawgre my myght and al my peyne,</L>
<L>Horrybely<NOTE PLACE="marg">[Horybely Tib., Horrybly C., horyble St.]</NOTE> he cast&euml; me</L>
<L N="21636">Amydd&euml;s off the gret&euml; se,<NOTE PLACE="inter">[An Illumination follows in Tib., of the Pilgrim thrown off his Island into the sea; the Bird|Merman playing his own fiddle, and Youth (with wings) embracing him.</NOTE></L>
<L>Among the waw&euml;s, ffer be southe.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>And nadd&euml; ben<NOTE PLACE="marg">[ne had be St.]</NOTE> that tym&euml;, Youthe,</L>
<L>(Off wych I thouht&euml; no thyng tho,</L>
<L N="21640">ffor she was ffled, off yore ago,)</L>
<L>I suppose that I hadde be</L>
<L>Perysshed Amyddys off the se.</L>
<L>But Youth&euml; than, in hyr Retour,</L>
<L N="21644">Was to myn help&euml; gret socour;</L>
<L>ffor Youth&euml;, in the sam&euml; place,</L>
<L>The Mer&euml;mayden gan enbrace,</L>
<L>That redy was, off cruelte,<MILESTONE UNIT="Tib folio" N="80a"></L>
<L N="21648">Thylke tym&euml; to ha stranglyd me,</L>
<L>And don to me gret vyolence.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>But, for Ioye off the presence</L>
<L>Off thys Youthe that I off spak,<MILESTONE N="282a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="21652">I eskapede from hyr wrak,
<PB REF="00000686.tif" N="578"></L>
<L>And hadde myn Arm ageyn at large;</L>
<L>And (with-out&euml;<NOTE PLACE="marg">[without Tib., St.]</NOTE> shyp or barge,)</L>
<L>I gan swymme, with-Inne a whyle,</L>
<L N="21656">Ageyn vn-to that sam&euml; yle</L>
<L>ffro the wych that I kam ffro.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Whan the mer&euml;mayde was go&mdash;</L>
<L>I mene, thys worldys fals solace,</L>
<L N="21660">That gan so sore at me to chace;&mdash;</L>
<L>But lyst<NOTE PLACE="marg">[leste Tib., lest St.]</NOTE> she sholde ha taken me,</L>
<L>I swam ful faste amyd the se;</L>
<L>ffor dred off hyre, I was in were.</L>
<L N="21664">But Youthe and she, to-gydre yfere,</L>
<L>fful gret Ioye they gan to make;</L>
<L>And thus hath Yowth&euml; me forsake;</L>
<L>ffor than I loste hyr in certeyn,</L>
<L N="21668">That she to me kam neuer ageyn.</L>
<L>And doun I sat, ffor werynesse,</L>
<L>And gan compleyne in gret dystresse:<NOTE PLACE="inter">[Blank in MS. for an Illumination, given in Tib., of the Pilgrim sitting on his Island.]</NOTE></L>
<L>"Allas," quod I, (myd off my wo,)<MILESTONE UNIT="Tib folio" N="80b"></L>
<L N="21672">"Allas, allas! what shal I do?</L>
<L>How shal I, wrechche, eskape a-way</L>
<L>Out off thys yl&euml;? weyllavay!</L>
<L>ffor, by .v.<NOTE PLACE="marg">[C., St., ffor ffyue Tib.]</NOTE> Enchaunteresses,</L>
<L N="21676">I am brouht in gret dystressys,</L>
<L>And in gret pereyl, dout&euml;les:</L>
<L>ffor Scilla ffyrst, and ek Cyrces,</L>
<L>Han causyd me to gon A-mys;</L>
<L N="21680">Syr&eacute;nes,<NOTE PLACE="marg">[Tib., C. <I>burnt</I>, Sirines St.]</NOTE> and Karibdis,<MILESTONE N="282b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>And Bythalassus,<NOTE PLACE="marg">[Tib., St., C. <I>burnt</I>]</NOTE> werst of alle,</L>
<L>Ben attonys on me falle;<MILESTONE UNIT="Stowe folio" N="348a"><NOTE PLACE="marg">[St. &amp; C.]</NOTE></L>
<L>And, mortally me to be-guyle,<NOTE PLACE="marg">[St. &amp; C.]</NOTE></L>
<L N="21684">They han me brouht in-to thys Ile,<NOTE PLACE="marg">[St. &amp; C.]</NOTE></L>
<L>Long in sorwe to soiourne,</L>
<L>And kan non other wey retourne,</L>
<L>To ffynd&euml; socour in thys cas.</L>
<L N="21688">I may wel sorwe and seyn allas!</L>
<L>Out off my wey, in nouncerteyn,<NOTE PLACE="marg">[nouncerteyn Tib.]</NOTE></L>
<L>And kan no mene to kome Ageyn.
<PB REF="00000687.tif" N="579"></L>
<L N="21691">"Was neuere pylgrym in swych poynt,</L>
<L>Trewly, nor in swych disioynt.<NOTE PLACE="marg">[C., Tib., suche ioynt St.]</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>"Now, good&euml; god, off thy grete grace,</L>
<L>Be my socour in thys place!</L>
<L>ffor thow, for my savac&iuml;oun,</L>
<L N="21696">Art the pomel off my bordoun.</L>
<L>To the, as for my<NOTE PLACE="marg">[the Tib., my St.]</NOTE> cheff coumfort,</L>
<L>In thys nede I ha resort,</L>
<L>To brynge me, throgh thy gret&euml; myght,</L>
<L N="21700">In-to the weye I may go ryht,</L>
<L>And ben supportyd (fer and ner)</L>
<L>Wyth that charbouncle bryht and cler,</L>
<L>Wych that, wyth hys bemys bryht,</L>
<L N="21704">Yiveth vn-to my bordoun lyht.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>"Now parte<NOTE PLACE="marg">[parten St.]</NOTE> with me, off thy clernesse,</L>
<L>And bryng me Out off my dystresse,</L>
<L>Out off thys dedly mortal rage!<MILESTONE UNIT="Tib folio" N="81a"></L>
<L N="21708">ffor, syth tyme off my tendre age,</L>
<L>My trust, &aacute;nd myn &aacute;ffyaunce,</L>
<L>My Ioye, and al my suffisaunce,</L>
<L>Al hooly hath ben in the,</L>
<L N="21712">Ageyns al aduersyte,</L>
<L>In euery peyne and ech labour,</L>
<L>To fynden confort and socour.</L>
<L>And now I<NOTE PLACE="marg">[I St., that C., Tib.]</NOTE> stonde in so gret drede,</L>
<L>Helpe me in thys gret&euml;<NOTE PLACE="marg">[gret C., St., greet Tib.]</NOTE> nede!"<MILESTONE N="283a" UNIT="folio"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="21717">And whyl I gan me thus compleyne,</L>
<L>Evene A-myd off al my peyne,</L>
<L>I sawh, A-myddys off the se,</L>
<L N="21720">A shyp&euml;<NOTE PLACE="marg">[shype St., shyp C.]</NOTE> saylle towardys me;</L>
<L>And evene above, vp on the mast</L>
<L>(Wherfor I was the lasse A-gast,)</L>
<L>I sawh a croos<NOTE PLACE="marg">[crosse Tib., crose St.]</NOTE> stonde, (and nat flytte,)</L>
<L N="21724">And ther-vp-on, A dow&euml; sytte,</L>
<L>Whyt as any mylk or snowh,</L>
<L>Wheroff I hadd&euml; Ioye ynowh.<NOTE PLACE="inter">[An Illumination follows in Tib., of a Ship with its fore and hind castles, and a Dove on a Cross at the top of the mast. The Pilgrim is on his isle.]</NOTE></L>
<L>And in thys shyp (a-geyn al shours,)
<PB REF="00000688.tif" N="580"></L>
<L N="21728">Ther wer castellys, and ek tours,</L>
<L>Wonder dyvers mans&iuml;ouns,<MILESTONE UNIT="Tib folio" N="81b"></L>
<L>And sondry habytac&iuml;ouns,</L>
<L>(By resemblaunce <I>and</I> semyng,)</L>
<L N="21732">Lych the loggyng off A Kyng:</L>
<L>And as I took good hed ther-at,<MILESTONE UNIT="Stowe folio" N="348b"></L>
<L>Al my sorwes I for-gaat;<NOTE PLACE="inter">[Blank in MS. for an Illumination.]</NOTE></L>
<L>Namly, syttyng on A roche,<NOTE PLACE="marg">Arystoteles (<I>later</I>)</NOTE></L>
<L N="21736">Whan I sawh the shyp aproche</L>
<L>Toward the Ile war<NOTE PLACE="marg">[where Tib., wher St.]</NOTE> I abood,</L>
<L>Wych dyd&euml; to me ful gret good;</L>
<L>Namly, whan yt kam so faste,</L>
<L N="21740">And began ther, Anker caste.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Out off wych ther ys descendyd,</L>
<L>On, that myhte nat ben amendyd,</L>
<L>I mene, the lady off most vertu,</L>
<L N="21744">Wych was callyd Grac&euml; Dieu.<MILESTONE N="283b" UNIT="folio"><NOTE PLACE="inter">[<I>Blank in MS. for an Illumination, given in Tib., of Grace Dieu, come out of the Ship (from which the Dove has gone) on to the Island, and the Pilgrim kneeling to her. A second Illumination of like kind is on the top of leaf</I> 82.]</NOTE></L>
<L>And ffyrst, whan that I dyde hyr se,</L>
<L>I ffyl a-doun vp-on my kne,</L>
<L>Prayede<NOTE PLACE="marg">[I prayed Tib.]</NOTE> hyr helpen in thys nede,</L>
<L N="21748">To me that stood in so gret drede,</L>
<L>Out off thys Ile, only by grace,</L>
<L>To helpyn that I myht&euml; pace.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>[Grace Dieu]:</HEAD>
<L>'What ys al thys?' A-noon quod she;<MILESTONE UNIT="Tib folio" N="82a"></L>
<L N="21752">'Whens komestow? wher hastow be?</L>
<L>fful longe (as thow shalt vnderstond)</L>
<L>I ha th&egrave; souht, On se and lond,</L>
<L>God woot, in ful good entent;</L>
<L N="21756">And yt wer mor convenyent</L>
<L>That thow sholdest, affter me</L>
<L>Ha souht, wher that I hadd&euml; be.</L>
<L>But tel me, or thow go asyde,</L>
<L N="21760">Castestow,<NOTE PLACE="marg">[C., Tib., cast towe St.]</NOTE> her for tabyde,
<PB REF="00000689.tif" N="581"></L>
<L>'Or to restyn any whyle</L>
<L>Wyth-Inne thys dredful peryllous yle?'</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>Pilgrim:<NOTE PLACE="marg">[St., <I>om</I>. C.]</NOTE><MILESTONE N="284a" UNIT="folio"></HEAD>
<L>"Certys, I stoonde in gret&euml;<NOTE PLACE="marg">[gret C., St., greet Tib.]</NOTE> where</L>
<L N="21764">Off that I am aryved here;</L>
<L>I whot<NOTE PLACE="marg">[woot Tib., wot St.]</NOTE> nat be what &aacute;venture.</L>
<L>And trew&euml;ly<NOTE PLACE="marg">[trewely Tib., trewly C., truly St.]</NOTE> I yow ensure,</L>
<L>Tabyden her ys no plesaunce,</L>
<L N="21768">But a-nooy, and gret grevaunce;</L>
<L>And fayn I wolde (wyth al my myght)</L>
<L>Kome to the wey&euml; that goth ryht;</L>
<L>And, Out off thys Il&euml; go,<MILESTONE UNIT="Tib folio" N="82b"></L>
<L N="21772">So fful off sorwen<NOTE PLACE="marg">[sorow St.]</NOTE> and off wo."</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>&para; Grace Dieu:<NOTE PLACE="marg">[Tib., St., <I>in margin</I> C.]</NOTE></HEAD>
<L>'Thanne I cast&euml;, for thy sake,</L>
<L>In-to my shyp, th&eacute; for to take,</L>
<L>Only off mercy and pyte.</L>
<L N="21776">Entre in, and I shal lede the</L>
<L>(Wyth-outen any mor delay,)</L>
<L>In-to A mor surer way:</L>
<L>That lyn&euml; ryht shal led&euml; the</L>
<L N="21780">To the place and the cyte</L>
<L>Wych thow hast (with herte and thouht,)</L>
<L>Long tyme, as a pylgrym, souht.<MILESTONE UNIT="Stowe folio" N="349a"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>'In myd weye thow must abyde,</L>
<L N="21784">And nat tourne on nouther syde.</L>
<L>And, redyly thy-sylff tavaunce,</L>
<L>Thow shalt fynd&euml; dame Penaunce,</L>
<L>Whom thow lefftest folyly;</L>
<L N="21788">And therfor wentystow<NOTE PLACE="marg">[wenteste thow Tib., wenst tow St.]</NOTE> wrongly:</L>
<L>Wyth hyre thow woldest nat soiourne;</L>
<L>But thow shalt ageyn retourne</L>
<L>Toward the heggh<NOTE PLACE="marg">[hegg Tib., heyghe St.]</NOTE> off hyr plauntyng,</L>
<L N="21792">And seyen<NOTE PLACE="marg">[seye Tib., seyn C.]</NOTE> to hyre thy felyng.'</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>&para; The Pylgrym:<NOTE PLACE="marg">[Pilgrim Tib., St., <I>om</I>. C.]</NOTE></HEAD>
<L>"Ma dame," quod I, "that ys my wyl;</L>
<L>ffor (off resoun and off skyl)</L>
<L>Ech pylgrym shold&euml; (what he may,)</L>
<L N="21796">Desyre to gon the shortest way;<MILESTONE N="284b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Yt wer goodly to do so.
<PB REF="00000690.tif" N="582"></L>
<L>"And, for the confort that ye ha do</L>
<L>To me, off mercy mor than ryht,</L>
<L N="21800">I thank&euml; yow wyth al my myght."</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>And than thys lady, off hyr grace,<MILESTONE UNIT="Tib folio" N="83a"></L>
<L>Brouht&euml; me vn-to a place</L>
<L>Wych, syth tyme that I was born,</L>
<L N="21804">I hadd&euml; neuere seyn to-forn;</L>
<L>And thyder<NOTE PLACE="marg">[theder Tib., thethar St.]</NOTE> she made me to gon</L>
<L>To a roche off hard&euml;<NOTE PLACE="marg">[hard C., St., Tib.]</NOTE> ston</L>
<L>And, At an ey&euml;, ther ran oute</L>
<L N="21808">Dropys off water al aboute:</L>
<L>The dropys wer (to my semyng)</L>
<L>Lych salt&euml; terys off wepyng;</L>
<L>And in-ta<NOTE PLACE="marg">[ta St., to a Tib.]</NOTE> cisterne ther besyde,</L>
<L N="21812">The dropys gonn&euml; for to glyde.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>&para; Grace Dieu:<NOTE PLACE="marg">[Tib., St., <I>om</I>. C.]</NOTE></HEAD>
<L>'ffyrst,' quod Grac&euml; Dieu to me,</L>
<L>'In thys vessel that thow dost se,</L>
<L>Wyth water off the hard&euml; ston</L>
<L N="21816">Thow must be bathyd, and that A-noon;</L>
<L>Wych shal helpe, and be refuge</L>
<L>To hele thy wondys large and huge;<NOTE PLACE="inter">[Blank in MS. for an Illumination, given in Tib., of tears dropping, from an Eye in a hill, into an oblong marble bath, Grace Dieu, with hands spread, speaking to the Pilgrim.]</NOTE></L>
<L>ffor in my shyp thow entryst nouht,</L>
<L N="21820">Tyl thy woundys be clen&euml; souht.'</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>&para; The Pylgrym:<NOTE PLACE="marg">[Tib., Pilgrim St., <I>om</I>. C.]</NOTE></HEAD>
<L>"I pray yow to<NOTE PLACE="marg">[Madame I preye you Tib.]</NOTE> declar&euml; me,<MILESTONE N="285a" UNIT="folio"><MILESTONE UNIT="Tib folio" N="83b"></L>
<L>Thys Eye, with dropys, that I se;</L>
<L>That &yogh;e wold&euml; specefye</L>
<L N="21824">What thyng that yt doth sygnefye."</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>&para; Grace Dieu answerith:<NOTE PLACE="marg">[Tib., Grace dieu St., C. <I>in margin</I>]</NOTE></HEAD>
<L>'Thys roche (yiff thow wylt wyt A-non)</L>
<L>Wych ys hard as any ston,</L>
<L>Ar the hertys, in ech estaat,</L>
<L N="21828">Off folkys wych ben Indurat</L>
<L>To knowe ther errour and ther synne,</L>
<L>In wych that they be fallyn Inne;
<PB REF="00000691.tif" N="583"></L>
<L>'Tyl I som whyl&euml; lyst to se<MILESTONE UNIT="Stowe folio" N="349b"></L>
<L N="21832">(Only off mercy and pyte,)</L>
<L>To tourne her herte, hard as a ston,</L>
<L>And make the<NOTE PLACE="marg">[there Tib., the St.]</NOTE> water out to gon,</L>
<L>At ther eye to renn&euml; doun<NOTE PLACE="marg">[adoun Tib.]</NOTE></L>
<L N="21836">By sorwe and by contric&iuml;oun.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>'The<NOTE PLACE="marg">[The om. Tib.]</NOTE> salt&euml; terys han ther her cours:</L>
<L>Ryht as a well&euml; hath hys sours</L>
<L>Vpward, with water quyk and cler,</L>
<L N="21840">And renneth in-ta<NOTE PLACE="marg">[in ta St., in to a Tib.]</NOTE> gret ryver,</L>
<L>Ryht so, by dystyllac&iuml;oun</L>
<L>The crystal terys descend&euml; doun,</L>
<L>Whan folk<NOTE PLACE="marg">[Whanne folke Tib.]</NOTE> for ther synn&euml;s wepe.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>'And swych&euml;<NOTE PLACE="marg">[swyche Tib., swych C.]</NOTE> dropys I do kepe,</L>
<L N="21845">And the water euerydel,</L>
<L>To make A bath, in a vessel,</L>
<L>ffor wondyd folk that fel&euml; peyne</L>
<L N="21848">In conscience, and sor&euml; pleyne,</L>
<L>Tyl they for elthe<NOTE PLACE="marg">[heelthe Tib.]</NOTE> and sur&euml;te,</L>
<L>Wyth thys bath ywasshen be;</L>
<L>ffor yt recureth euery wonde,<MILESTONE UNIT="Tib folio" N="84a"></L>
<L N="21852">Callyd 'bapteme the secounde,'</L>
<L>That doth a-way al<NOTE PLACE="marg">[alle Tib.]</NOTE> grevaunce.</L>
<L>Wyth wych water, dame Penaunce</L>
<L>Maketh a lye (I the ensure,)</L>
<L N="21856">To wasshen a-way al ordure;<MILESTONE N="285b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>In wych&euml; bath&euml;<NOTE PLACE="marg">[whiche bathe St., wych bath C., Tib.]</NOTE> (in certeyne)</L>
<L>The hooly womman Mawdeleyne</L>
<L>Ywasshen was, tak hed her-to.</L>
<L N="21860">Thapostel Peter ek also,</L>
<L>And many mo than I may telle,</L>
<L>Wer ywasshen in thys welle;</L>
<L>And so shaltow, by red off me,</L>
<L N="21864">Yiff thow lyst to purgyd be.'</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>&para; The Pylgryme:<NOTE PLACE="marg">[Tib., Pilgrim St., <I>om</I>. C.]</NOTE></HEAD>
<L>"Ma dame, (yiff that ye lyst to se,)</L>
<L>Thys vessel (as semeth vn-to me,)</L>
<L>Ys nat halff fful; and Trew&euml;ly<NOTE PLACE="marg">[trewely Tib., Trewly C., truly St.]</NOTE></L>
<L N="21868">Therfore I dred&euml; fynally</L>
<L>That I may nat bathyd be,
<PB REF="00000692.tif" N="584"></L>
<L>"But yiff ther wer&euml; mor plente."</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>&para; Grace Dieu Answerith:<NOTE PLACE="marg">[Tib., grace dieu St., <I>om</I>. C.]</NOTE></HEAD>
<L>Quod she to me (as in substaunce),</L>
<L N="21872">'Thow hast off water suffysaunce.'</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>She sayd&euml; soth, as I wel ffond,</L>
<L>And putt&euml; forth A-noon hyr hond</L>
<L N="21875">Toward hyr shyp off gret delyt.</L>
<L>And thanne a-noon, a<NOTE PLACE="marg">[a Tib., St., <I>om</I>. C.]</NOTE> dow&euml; whyt</L>
<L>Retournyd ys at hyr callyng,</L>
<L>And kam to hyre A-noon fleyng.<NOTE PLACE="marg">[anon to her flyenge St.]</NOTE></L>
<L>In hyr beek she brouht A wond,</L>
<L N="21880">Wych Grac&euml; Dieu took in hyr hond;</L>
<L>And thanne the dow&euml; (in certeyn)<MILESTONE UNIT="Tib folio" N="84b"></L>
<L>ffley vn-to the shyp a-geyn.<MILESTONE UNIT="Stowe folio" N="350a"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Thys yerd&euml; sempt&euml; (dout&euml;les)</L>
<L N="21884">Lyk<NOTE PLACE="marg">[C., St., <I>om</I>. Tib.]</NOTE> to the yerde off Moyses,</L>
<L>Wyth wych (the byble seyth apert,)</L>
<L>The ston he smett&euml;,<NOTE PLACE="marg">[smot Tib.]</NOTE> in desert;</L>
<L>And with the water that out ran,</L>
<L N="21888">Off Israel, bothe beste and man,</L>
<L>Drank ynowh in h&aacute;bondaunce,</L>
<L>Ther was so hug&euml; suffysaunce.<MILESTONE N="286a" UNIT="folio"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>And trewly, as to myn entent,</L>
<L N="21892">By sygn&euml;s that wer evydent,</L>
<L>Wyth the sam&euml; yerde a-noon,</L>
<L>Grac&euml; Dieu smette<NOTE PLACE="marg">[smot Tib.]</NOTE> on the ston.</L>
<L>And thanne the roch&euml;, Rowh and hard,</L>
<L N="21896">(I hadde ther-to ful good reward)</L>
<L>At an eye (yt ys no doute)</L>
<L>The water gan to ronnen oute</L>
<L>In-to the vessel that I off spak,</L>
<L N="21900">That off plente ther was no lak.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>[Grace Dieu]:</HEAD>
<L>Quod Grace Dieu A-noon to me,</L>
<L>'Now thow hast ynowh plente</L>
<L>Off water, (I dar vndertake,)</L>
<L N="21904">Suffysauntly a bath to make;<NOTE PLACE="inter">[<I>Blank in MS. for an Illumination, given in Tib., of the Pilgrim in a square white bath, filling with the drops from an Eye in a green rock, by which</I></NOTE>
<PB REF="00000693.tif" N="585"><NOTE PLACE="inter"><I>Grace Dieu stands, with a long wand in her right hand.</I>]</NOTE></L>
<L>'And mor holsom yt ys to the,<MILESTONE UNIT="Tib folio" N="85a"></L>
<L>Be-cause the water (as thow mayst se,)</L>
<L>Ys lewk: therfor yt ys mor hable,</L>
<L N="21908">And to bathys mor coumfortable.'</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>[The Pilgrim]:</HEAD>
<L>And Grac&euml; dieu me bad A-noon,</L>
<L>In-to the bath I shold&euml; gon.</L>
<L>And in I wente A-noon, by grace,</L>
<L N="21912">And ther a-bood but lytel space;</L>
<L>ffor (to rehersyn euerydel)</L>
<L>The bath lyk&eacute;de me nat ryht wel:</L>
<L>I gan feynte on euery syde,</L>
<L N="21916">Wher-fore I myht&euml; nat abyde<MILESTONE N="286b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>In that bath to stond&euml;<NOTE PLACE="marg">[C., Tib., bathe to stond St.]</NOTE> stable;</L>
<L>ffor, I was nat r&eacute;sembl&aacute;ble<NOTE PLACE="marg">&para; [Lavabo per singulas noctes] Lectum meum: lacrimis meis stratum [meum] rigabo [Psal. vi. 7] Tib., <I>om</I>. C., St.</NOTE></L>
<L>To kyng Davyd in my bathyng,</L>
<L N="21920">Wych, wyth the terys off hys wepyng,</L>
<L>Wyssh hys bed-strawh<NOTE PLACE="marg">[wysche . . bedstraw Tib.]</NOTE> euerydel,</L>
<L>Hys bed also, (who lok&euml; wel),</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>And<NOTE PLACE="marg">[out Tib., St.]</NOTE> off the bath whan I was go,</L>
<L N="21924">Grac&euml; Dieu A-non kam to:</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>&para; Now Grace Dieu spekyth:<NOTE PLACE="marg">[Tib., grace dieu St., <I>om</I>. C.]</NOTE></HEAD>
<L>Quod she, 'wenystow to be</L>
<L>Al hool off thyn infyrmyte,</L>
<L>And off thyn wondys euerychon,</L>
<L N="21928">That so son&euml; art out gon,</L>
<L>Out off thys ylk&euml; holsom welle,</L>
<L>And lyst nat ther<NOTE PLACE="marg">[not ther in Tib.]</NOTE> no lenger dwelle?</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>'What woldestow ha sayd to me,</L>
<L N="21932">Yiff I hadd&euml; wrappyd the,</L>
<L>Nakyd, cast the vp <I>and</I> doun<MILESTONE UNIT="Stowe folio" N="350b"></L>
<L>In thornys for thy savac&iuml;oun,</L>
<L>Ther ta suffryd<NOTE PLACE="marg">[to a suffred Tib., to sofer St.]</NOTE> sharp prykyng;</L>
<L N="21936">Or, A-mong netlys fful bytyng,</L>
<L>Bak and brest, and euery syde;</L>
<L>Whan thow myghtest nat abyde<MILESTONE UNIT="Tib folio" N="85b"></L>
<L>In sofft&euml; water, by suffraunce,</L>
<L N="21940">Thy-sylff in Elth&euml;<NOTE PLACE="marg">[helthe Tib.]</NOTE> to avaunce?
<PB REF="00000694.tif" N="586"></L>
<L>'Tel vn-to me the maner how,</L>
<L>What wys&euml; thow shalt entre now</L>
<L>In-to my shyp, wher dame Penaunce</L>
<L N="21944">Haueth al the gouernaunce,</L>
<L>Bothe to bynden and vnbynde?</L>
<L>I trowe thow wylt abyde behynde,</L>
<L>And make her-off a long delay,</L>
<L N="21948">And I shal seylle forth on my way.'</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>&para; The Pylgryme:<NOTE PLACE="marg">[Tib., Pilgrim St., <I>om</I>. C.]</NOTE></HEAD>
<L>"Madame," thanne a-noon quod I,</L>
<L>"Haueth<NOTE PLACE="marg">[Hath Tib., havythe St.]</NOTE> on<NOTE PLACE="foot">Many leaves are here missing in the MS. Cott. Vit., c. xiii.; but the missing portion is supplied from MS. Cott. Tib., A vii.</NOTE> me pyte and mercy!<MILESTONE UNIT="Tib folio" N="85b"></L>
<L>With-in &yogh;oure schippe, so doth<NOTE PLACE="marg">[do St.]</NOTE> provyde,</L>
<L N="21952">By-hynd&euml; that I not abyde.</L>
<L>To trowth&euml;, &yogh;eue<NOTE PLACE="marg">[yf St.]</NOTE> &yogh;e lyste entende,</L>
<L>With-in &yogh;oure schippe I schal amende,</L>
<L>And redresse also (I-wys,)</L>
<L N="21956">Alle that I haue don amys.</L>
<L>&para; Considerith also in &yogh;oure syght,</L>
<L>That in batayle, a manly knyght,</L>
<L>(By exaumple, as it is ffounde)</L>
<L N="21960">Whanne he hathe kaught eny<NOTE PLACE="marg">[hath ons cawht a St.]</NOTE> wounde,</L>
<L>Not-withstondynge his langour,</L>
<L>It encresith his vygoor,</L>
<L>Makith hym, off cher and off vysage,</L>
<L N="21964">The more hardy<NOTE PLACE="marg">[hardy St., hard Tib.]</NOTE> off corage,</L>
<L>Grete emprys&euml; vndertake,</L>
<L>ffor drede off deth, hem not fforsake."</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>&para; Grace dieu answerith:<NOTE PLACE="marg">[grace dieu St.]</NOTE></HEAD>
<L>Qvod <B>grace dieu</B> anoon ryght,</L>
<L N="21968">'Byholde and se a noble knyght,<MILESTONE UNIT="Tib folio" N="86a"></L>
<L>Makynge thyne owne chaumberer,<NOTE PLACE="marg">[chaumber Tib., chamberer St.]</NOTE></L>
<L>To bere thyne armure as<NOTE PLACE="marg">[lyke St.]</NOTE> a sqvyer,</L>
<L>Whiche mayste not thy silff assure</L>
<L N="21972">ffor to berne hem, nor endure.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>'I wold&euml; seen, to-ffore wytnesse,</L>
<L>Som knyghttely deede off hygh prowesse</L>
<L>Accomplyschid, thorough thi myght,</L>
<L N="21976">To bere recorde thow art a knyght,
<PB REF="00000695.tif" N="587"></L>
<L>'By arm&euml;s prev&euml;d in som coste.</L>
<L>Thow art no thyng but wynde and boste,</L>
<L>Byhotynge myche, whan al is wrought,</L>
<L N="21980">And in deed&euml; doste ryght nought.'</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>&para; The Pylgryme:</HEAD>
<L>"MAdame," quod I, "yt is no ffayle,</L>
<L>I schal amend&euml; with travayle;</L>
<L>And, I hope, vexacyoun<MILESTONE UNIT="Stowe folio" N="351a"></L>
<L N="21984">Schal &yogh;eue to me fful hygh renoun,</L>
<L>To conquere som excellence</L>
<L>By vse and longe experyence.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>"I haue pleynely, in the see,</L>
<L N="21988"><B>Nauffragus</B> fful long I-be,</L>
<L>And suffred (bothe este and weste,)</L>
<L>Many<NOTE PLACE="marg">[many a St.]</NOTE> perel and greet tempeste,</L>
<L>And &yogh;it I stonde in a deluge.</L>
<L N="21992">But &yogh;eue I haue off &yogh;ou reffuge,</L>
<L>With-in &yogh;oure schippe me ffor to marke,</L>
<L>As Noe was with-in his arke,</L>
<L>I may not (schort&euml;ly to telle,)</L>
<L N="21996">Escape out off this<NOTE PLACE="marg">[thes St.]</NOTE> fflood&euml;s ffelle."</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>&para; Grace dieu answerith:<NOTE PLACE="marg">[grace dieu St.]</NOTE></HEAD>
<L>'BE wel provyded in thi thought,</L>
<L>That thow behot&euml; me ryght nought,<MILESTONE UNIT="Tib folio" N="86b"></L>
<L>&YOGH;eue thow wolte<NOTE PLACE="marg">[wylt St.]</NOTE> my thanke disserue,</L>
<L N="22000">But that thow wolte<NOTE PLACE="marg">[wylt St.]</NOTE> trewely obserue;</L>
<L>ffor bette it is, not vndertake,</L>
<L>And avowys noon to make,</L>
<L>Than to make hem by assent,</L>
<L N="22004">And breke hem affter, off entent:</L>
<L>Swhiche avow&euml;s, loue I nought,</L>
<L>But they be made off herte and thought.</L>
<L>Wherffore, with-out eny slouthe,</L>
<L N="22008">Kepe thyne heeste to me, off trouthe.'</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>&para; The Pylgryme:</HEAD>
<L>"Wyth &yogh;oure supportacyoun,</L>
<L>It is myne entencyoun,</L>
<L>My promysse, both&euml;<NOTE PLACE="marg">[bothe <I>om</I>. St.]</NOTE> day and nyght,</L>
<L N="22012">To kepe yt, as I haue byhyght."</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>&para; Grace dieu answerith:<NOTE PLACE="marg">[grace dieu St.]</NOTE>
</HEAD>
<PB REF="00000696.tif" N="588">
<L>THanne <B>Grace dieu</B>, with good chere,</L>
<L>Ladde me doun to the revere;</L>
<L>And there we han a schippe I-ffonde.</L>
<L N="22016">With greet&euml; bondis it was bounde;</L>
<L>But the bond&euml;s sat not cloos;</L>
<L>The most&euml; parte off hem were loos;</L>
<L N="22019">The smal&euml; osyers, here and &yogh;onder,</L>
<L>To-brak&euml;<NOTE PLACE="marg">[brake St., brak Tib.]</NOTE> thanne, and<NOTE PLACE="marg">[and than St.]</NOTE> wente asonder,</L>
<L>The hop&euml;s &aacute;bout the vessel,</L>
<L>Bycause they were not bound&euml; wel;</L>
<L>&YOGH;it the hoopes (it is no nay)</L>
<L N="22024">Were stronge I-nowgh at good assay;</L>
<L>Deffaute in hem was ffound&euml; noon;</L>
<L>But, ffor the osyers nygh echon</L>
<L>Were brok&euml; ffyrste (as it is ffounde),</L>
<L N="22028">Wherffore the hoopys were vnbounde.<MILESTONE UNIT="Tib folio" N="87a"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>&para; The Pylgryme:</HEAD>
<L>"MAdame," quod I, "with-out&euml;<NOTE PLACE="marg">[with out Tib., St.]</NOTE> blame,</L>
<L>Off &yogh;oure schippe, telle me the name,</L>
<L>And who that scholde it wel gouerne;</L>
<L N="22032">ffor sothely, as I kan discerne,</L>
<L>The gou&eacute;rnour, is not wys,</L>
<L>(As me thynket<NOTE PLACE="marg">[thynkythe St.]</NOTE> in myn avys,)</L>
<L N="22035">That lyste suffren (off ffolye)</L>
<L>The boond&euml;s breke so reklesselye<MILESTONE UNIT="Stowe folio" N="351b"></L>
<L>In mydd&euml;s off the perelous see,</L>
<L>In whiche there is no sur&euml;te."</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>&para; Grace dieu answerith:</HEAD>
<L>'THis schippe (as by discripcyoun)</L>
<L N="22040">I-callyd ys Relygyoun;</L>
<L>Whiche is bounde with circumstauncis,</L>
<L>And ffret with dyuerse &oacute;bseruauncis.</L>
<L>And while that it is bound&euml; wel,</L>
<L N="22044">It may perysche neueradel;</L>
<L>But &yogh;ong&euml; ffolk&euml;s neclygent,</L>
<L>That entre this schippe off entent,</L>
<L>And, thorough ther mys-gouernauncis,</L>
<L N="22048">Kep&euml; not the &oacute;bseruauncis</L>
<L>That were made by ffolkis olde,</L>
<L>ffor to breke hem ben fful bolde:
<PB REF="00000697.tif" N="589"></L>
<L>'ffirst&euml;, thosy&eacute;rys smale,</L>
<L N="22052">Telle off hem but lytel tale,</L>
<L>Caste hem byhynden at her bak,</L>
<L>Where-thorwgh the schippe goth al to wrak:</L>
<L>Breke the smal&euml; circumstauncis,</L>
<L N="22056">And ffare-wel the greete &oacute;bseruauncis!</L>
<L>ffor, &yogh;eue the smale comaund&euml;mentis</L>
<L>Be not kepte in ther ententis,<MILESTONE UNIT="Tib folio" N="87b"></L>
<L>The greet&euml; (in conclusyoun)</L>
<L N="22060">Gon vn-to destruccyoun.</L>
<L>The smal&euml; (bothe in colde and heete,)</L>
<L>Be wardeyn&euml;s off the greete;</L>
<L>And &yogh;eue the smal&euml; sothely ffayle,</L>
<L N="22064">Aryght this schippe ne may not sayle.</L>
<L>Breke the smal&euml; here and &yogh;onder,</L>
<L>And the greete muste goon assonder.</L>
<L>Thus the schippe off religyoun</L>
<L N="22068">Gothe offte to distruccyoun.</L>
<L>So, wold&euml; god, ther lyvynge</L>
<L>Were lyk&euml; now ther gynnynge,</L>
<L>The schipp&euml; scholde the better preve,</L>
<L N="22072">Ageyne al tempeste hym<NOTE PLACE="marg">[them St.]</NOTE> -silffe releve:</L>
<L>It were almesse, by the roode.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>'&YOGH;it I hoop&euml; som are gode,</L>
<L>Swyche as to holynesse entende;</L>
<L N="22076">And who doth not, god hym amende!</L>
<L>God &yogh;eue hem grac&euml; so to dresse</L>
<L>The maste<NOTE PLACE="marg">[The mast St., He must Tib.]</NOTE> vpward, by holynesse,</L>
<L>And that they may, to her avayle,</L>
<L N="22080">By grac&euml;, so to cross&euml; sayle,</L>
<L>That in the wynde be no debat</L>
<L>To make ther passage ffortunat;</L>
<L>That redely they may, and blyue,</L>
<L N="22084">At the hauene vp taryve,</L>
<L>Where Ioye and blysse (who kan disserne)</L>
<L>Is endelesly, and lyffe enterne.</L>
<L>&para; Now cheese ffreely, affter my lawe,</L>
<L N="22088">To which&euml; castel thow wolt drawe;<MILESTONE UNIT="Stowe folio" N="352a"></L>
<L>And in my schippe, they ben echon</L>
<L>Bylte fful ffayre, off lyme and stoon.
<PB REF="00000698.tif" N="590"></L>
<L>'And sythen thow haueste lyberte</L>
<L N="22092">ffor to entren or go ffre,</L>
<L>Cheese amonge these towres alle,</L>
<L>At whiche gat&euml; thow wolte calle.<MILESTONE UNIT="Tib folio" N="88a"></L>
<L>&para; Ther<NOTE PLACE="marg">[her St.]</NOTE> ben the <B>Cystews</B> ffast&euml; by;</L>
<L N="22096">And not fful ffer is eke <B>Clwny</B>.</L>
<L>Byholde &yogh;onder a <B>Chartrehous</B>,</L>
<L><SUP>2</SUP>An ordur that is full vertuous.<SUP>2</SUP><NOTE PLACE="marg">[2_2 St., <I>om</I>. Tib.]</NOTE></L>
<L>Thow mayste eke sen&euml; ffrere <B>Prechours</B>,</L>
<L N="22100">And other that callyd ben <B>Menours</B>;</L>
<L>Ordres off many other<NOTE PLACE="marg">[a nothar St.]</NOTE> guyse,</L>
<L>Mo thanne as now I kan<NOTE PLACE="marg">[I can as now St.]</NOTE> devyse:</L>
<L>Cheese at thyne own&euml; volunte,</L>
<L N="22104">In whiche off all&euml; thow wolte<NOTE PLACE="marg">[wilt St.]</NOTE> be.<NOTE PLACE="marg">[Illustration.]</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>'Alle they stonde in<NOTE PLACE="marg">[on St.]</NOTE> stable grownd,</L>
<L>To kep&euml;, both&euml; saaff and sownd,</L>
<L>Body and soule, (it is no drede)</L>
<L N="22108">Who kepith his rule in verrey deede.</L>
<L>And these placis agr&euml;&aacute;ble,</L>
<L>All&euml; they ben dyffens&aacute;ble</L>
<L>Ageyne the ffende and alle his myght,</L>
<L N="22112">That man assayleth day and nyght</L>
<L>In this mortal trowbely see,</L>
<L>ffulffilled with greet aduersyte.</L>
<L>And, therffore, &yogh;eue thow do wel,</L>
<L N="22116">Entre anoon in som castel,</L>
<L>There thow mayste (at a word)</L>
<L>Kepe the within schipp&euml;s bord.<MILESTONE UNIT="Tib folio" N="88b"></L>
<L>This wordely see (it<NOTE PLACE="marg">[it St., <I>om</I>. Tib.]</NOTE> is no ffayle)</L>
<L N="22120">Eche day off newe the schal assayle;</L>
<L>Wherffore I councel the to ffle,</L>
<L>Whyle thow haste myght and lyberte.'</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>&para; The Pylgryme:</HEAD>
<L>"MAdame," quod I, "whan al ys sought,</L>
<L N="22124">I haue chose (off herte and thought,)</L>
<L>Off <B>Cystews</B>, (in ech&euml; syde)</L>
<L>In that castel to abyde,</L>
<L>In-to that ffortresse I wole gon."</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>Grace Dieu:<NOTE PLACE="marg">[St., <I>om</I>. Tib.]</NOTE></HEAD>
<L N="22128">'Entre my schyppe,' quod sche, 'anoon.'
<PB REF="00000699.tif" N="591"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>And affter that, sche lyste not dwelle,</L>
<L>But gan hir hanker vp to pulle,</L>
<L>And in the see, fforthe bygan to sayle</L>
<L N="22132">Towarde the castel, &yogh;eue it wolde avayle,</L>
<L>Me to spede on<NOTE PLACE="marg">[vp on St.]</NOTE> my Iorne.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>And at the laste, I ffonde a large entre;</L>
<L>But, off entente, stylle awhile I stood</L>
<L N="22136">Sool by my silffe, and at the gate abood.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>&para; The pylgryme:</HEAD>
<L>"POrter," quod I, in haste, "I preye the,</L>
<L>At this castel graunte me entre,</L>
<L>ffor <B>Grace dieu</B> hathe me hyder brought,<MILESTONE UNIT="Stowe folio" N="352b"></L>
<L N="22140">Off the entre that I ffayle not."</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>&para; The Porter answerith:</HEAD>
<L>QVod the porter anoon to me,</L>
<L>'&YOGH;eue I knew&euml;, and dyde se</L>
<L>That the kyng wolde it avowe,</L>
<L N="22144">Thyne entre I scholde alowe;</L>
<L>But the wyll&euml;<NOTE PLACE="marg">[will is St.]</NOTE> off the kyng<MILESTONE UNIT="Tib folio" N="89a"></L>
<L>There-off I knowe no maner thyng.'</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>&para; The Pylgryme:</HEAD>
<L>"TElle me thanne, lyke myne entent,</L>
<L>Is the kyng hym-silffe present?"</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>&para; The porter answerith:</HEAD>
<L N="22149">'TRust&euml; wel, as thow schalt leere,</L>
<L>I wolde not ellis sytten heere:</L>
<L>It is a sygne (eerly and late,)</L>
<L N="22152">Whanne thow seeste me at the gate,</L>
<L>To telle (by good avys&euml;ment,)</L>
<L>The kyng hym-silffe ys here present.'</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>&para; The Pylgryme:<NOTE PLACE="marg">[Illustration.]</NOTE></HEAD>
<L N="22155">"TElle me thy name, off gentillesse,</L>
<L>With-outen<NOTE PLACE="marg">[outen St., out Tib.]</NOTE> eny straung&euml;nesse."</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>&para; The Porter answerith:</HEAD>
<L>'ANd I schal<NOTE PLACE="marg">[I shall the St.]</NOTE> telle the with-out schame:<MILESTONE UNIT="Tib folio" N="89b"></L>
<L><B>Drede off god</B>, that is my name;</L>
<L>Whiche is ground (with-out offence)</L>
<L N="22160">Off wysdam and Sapyence.</L>
<L>I voyd&euml; synne, and vyces chace,</L>
<L>That noon<NOTE PLACE="marg">[noon St., men Tib.]</NOTE> may entren in this place;
<PB REF="00000700.tif" N="592"></L>
<L>'Nowther oolde nor &yogh;onge off age</L>
<L N="22164">Schal have heere<NOTE PLACE="marg">[ther St.]</NOTE> noon herbergage;</L>
<L>ffor this staffe (&yogh;eue thow take heede)</L>
<L>With the greet parlom<NOTE PLACE="marg">[plomer St.]</NOTE> of leed,</L>
<L>Is I-callyd (in substaunce)</L>
<L N="22168">'Off god almyghtty, the vengaunce;'</L>
<L>And there-with-al, in cruel wyse,</L>
<L>All&euml; synners I chastyse.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>'And with this ylk&euml; sturdy Maas,</L>
<L N="22172">I putte hem out a fful greet paas;</L>
<L>ffor noon swyche (&yogh;eue thow lyst&euml;<NOTE PLACE="marg">[none . . lyst St.]</NOTE> lere,)</L>
<L>Ben hardy to entre here.'</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>&para; The Pylgryme:</HEAD>
<L>"Syre,<NOTE PLACE="marg">[Syre, <I>om</I>. St.]</NOTE> I praye the, oonly off<NOTE PLACE="marg">[that of St.]</NOTE> grace,</L>
<L N="22176">I may entren in this place;</L>
<L>ffor myne entente and my menynge</L>
<L>Is to do servyse to the kyng."</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>&para; The Porter answerith:</HEAD>
<L>'&YOGH;Eue I knewe that it<NOTE PLACE="marg">[it St., <I>om</I>. Tib.]</NOTE> were so,</L>
<L N="22180">With-outen many word&euml;s mo</L>
<L>Thow scholdeste hau&euml; graunte off me,</L>
<L>To entren at good lyberte.'</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>&para; The Pylgryme:</HEAD>
<L>"IN other wys&euml; neuere a del</L>
<L>Wole I not entren in<NOTE PLACE="marg">[in <I>om</I>. St.]</NOTE> this castel,<MILESTONE UNIT="Tib folio" N="90a"></L>
<L N="22185">But ffor to do the kyng servyse."</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>And thann&euml;, in fful goodly wyse,</L>
<L>I was leten in off the porter:<MILESTONE UNIT="Stowe folio" N="353a"></L>
<L N="22188">Hym lyste to mak&euml; no daunger.</L>
<L>&para; Aboute I went&euml;, byholdynge</L>
<L>Vp-on many a rych&euml; thynge;</L>
<L>I sawe <B>A cloystre</B> and <B>A dortour</B>,</L>
<L><B>A chapytlehous</B><NOTE PLACE="marg">[chapytle hous St.]</NOTE> and <B>A ffreytour</B>;</L>
<L N="22193">And there-with-al, a ffayre <B>Hostrye</B>,</L>
<L>And a larg&euml; <B>ffermerye</B>;</L>
<L>And, off God, thanke to dysserve,</L>
<L N="22196">ffayr&euml; meyn&euml; I sawgh there serve.</L>
<L>And, I suppos&euml; ffor my beste,</L>
<L>There to herborewe and to reste,</L>
<L>On ther cam, and preyed me,
<PB REF="00000701.tif" N="593"></L>
<L N="22200">And hir name was <B>Charite</B>.<NOTE PLACE="inter">[Illustration.]</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>TO pylgrymes, in goodly wyse,</L>
<L>Sche dyde moste trewely the servyse.</L>
<L>With chere benygne, and glad vysage,</L>
<L N="22204">Sche brought hem to ther herbergage;</L>
<L>And euere sche was moste ententyff,</L>
<L>With-outen<NOTE PLACE="marg">[outen St., out Tib.]</NOTE> noyse or eny stryff:</L>
<L>To seru&euml; por&euml; ffolkys alle,<MILESTONE UNIT="Tib folio" N="90b"></L>
<L N="22208">That ffor help&euml; to hir calle,</L>
<L>Sche was besy euere more.</L>
<L>And in this book, not goon fful &yogh;ore,</L>
<L>I spak&euml; off hir, dowt&euml;les,</L>
<L N="22212">ffor sche heelde the wrytte off pees,</L>
<L>Whanne <B>Moyses</B>, the byschop cheeff,</L>
<L>Gan depart&euml; the releeff</L>
<L>To pilgrym&euml;s (in substaunce)</L>
<L N="22216">To &yogh;euen hem ther sustynaunce.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>ANd<NOTE PLACE="marg">[and <I>om</I>. St.]</NOTE> thorough the cloystre, thanne anoon,</L>
<L>By the waye as I gan goon,</L>
<L>Off &aacute;venture in my repayre,</L>
<L N="22220">I mette a lady Inly ffayre,</L>
<L>Bothe off schappe and off stature;</L>
<L>And sche bare (I &yogh;ou ensure)</L>
<L>In hir hand, a smal coffyn</L>
<L N="22224">Whiche was made off parchemyn.</L>
<L>A whit&euml; dowve (it is no dowte)</L>
<L>Alle-way sewyd hir abowte.<NOTE PLACE="marg">[Illumination.]</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>&para; The Pylgryme:</HEAD>
<L>ANd as I lokyd heere and ther,</L>
<L N="22228">I stood in a maner wher,</L>
<L>What tok&eacute;n&euml;s it<NOTE PLACE="marg">[tooknys that it St.]</NOTE> myght be,<MILESTONE UNIT="Tib folio" N="91a"></L>
<L>The thyng&euml;s that I dyd&euml; se;</L>
<L>Prayed hir in goodly wyse,</L>
<L N="22232">That sche wolde anoon devyse</L>
<L>There-off by exposicyoun,</L>
<L>A cleer sygnyffycacyoun.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>&para; Lessoun declarith:<NOTE PLACE="marg">[declarith, <I>om</I>. St.]</NOTE></HEAD>
<L>'TRewely,' quod sche, there as sche stood,</L>
<L N="22236">'I ne thenke no thyng but good,
<PB REF="00000702.tif" N="594"></L>
<L>'ffor I am <B>Sowcelerere</B><NOTE PLACE="marg">[sawcelerere St.]</NOTE></L>
<L>Off this place, and <B>Pytauncere</B>.</L>
<L>I menystre the lyfflode</L>
<L>To the sowle, and eke the ffoode:<MILESTONE UNIT="Stowe folio" N="353b"></L>
<L N="22241">The herte I ffeede (the pawnch&euml; nought,)</L>
<L>With fful many an hooly thought.</L>
<L>My ffoode is soote and cherischynge,</L>
<L N="22244">And ryght hoolsom in tastynge;</L>
<L>Whiche ffoode is delyuered me</L>
<L>By on whom that<NOTE PLACE="marg">[that <I>om</I>. St.]</NOTE> thow schalt se;</L>
<L>ffor sche is bothe <B>A Mercer</B><NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Mercier:</I> m. A good Pedler or meane Haberdasher of small wares; a tradesman that retailes all manner of small ware, and hath no better then a shed or booth for a shop. 1611. Cotgrave (1650).</NOTE></L>
<L N="22248">Off this place, and cheeff <B>Cloystrer</B>.'<NOTE PLACE="marg">[loyster C.]</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>&para; The Pylgryme:</HEAD>
<L>Lyke the desyre whiche that I hadde,</L>
<L>To that lady sche me ladde;</L>
<L>Whiche (schortely to speceffye)</L>
<L N="22252">Plente hadde off <B>Mercerye</B>,</L>
<L>And moste delytable off syght,</L>
<L>Sche hadd&euml; <B>Merours</B> ffeyre and bryght.</L>
<L>But this lady merveyllous</L>
<L N="22256">Was off schappe susp&eacute;cyous;</L>
<L>ffor I took good heede ther-to:</L>
<L>Sche departyd was on<NOTE PLACE="marg">[in St.]</NOTE> two;</L>
<L>That made hir body to devyde,<MILESTONE UNIT="Tib folio" N="91b"></L>
<L N="22260">Wonder cleer on the ryght syde;</L>
<L>But (as I aspyen koude,)</L>
<L>Hir lyffte was schadewed with a clowde.<NOTE PLACE="marg">[Illumination.]</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>ANd whanne that I byheelde the guyse</L>
<L N="22264">Off alle hir queynt&euml; marchaundyse,</L>
<L>"Madame," quod I, "in certeyn,</L>
<L>Wonder ffayne I wold&euml; beyn,</L>
<L>Somwhat off &yogh;oure thyng&euml;s heere,</L>
<L N="22268">&YOGH;eue so were &yogh;e wold&euml; lere</L>
<L>To me (by schorte conclus&iuml;oun,)</L>
<L>&YOGH;oure name and &yogh;oure condicyoun."</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>&para; Agyographe:
</HEAD>
<PB REF="00000703.tif" N="595">
<L>'<B>I</B> Am,' quod sche, 'cheeff noryce</L>
<L N="22272">To all&euml; ffolkes that ffle&euml;n vyce.</L>
<L>No cloyster is worthe (who looke aboute)</L>
<L>On no syde whan I am out.</L>
<L>I mak&euml; cloystris fferme and stable,</L>
<L>Worschipe-full<NOTE PLACE="marg">[full St., <I>om</I>. Tib.]</NOTE> and honowrable;</L>
<L N="22277">And my name (&yogh;eue thow lyste se,)</L>
<L>Is callyd <B>Agyographe</B>,<MILESTONE UNIT="Tib folio" N="92a"></L>
<L>Whiche is to seyne (I the ensure,)</L>
<L N="22280">Off holy wrytynge the scripture.<NOTE PLACE="marg"><B>&para; Sancta scrip[tura]</B></NOTE></L>
<L>And at ffeyr&euml;s and at ffeestis,</L>
<L>I reste in skynn&euml;s off dede bestis.'</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>&para; The Pylgryme:</HEAD>
<L>"DEclar&euml; me, and doth not ffeyne,</L>
<L N="22284">Why be &yogh;e partyd thus on tweyne:</L>
<L>The to parte, <SUP>2</SUP>wonder ffayre off cheere,</L>
<L>Lusty, amyable, and cleere;<SUP>2</SUP><NOTE PLACE="marg">[2_2 <I>here: leaf</I> 353-4]</NOTE></L>
<L>The tother party,<NOTE PLACE="marg">[St. repeats]</NOTE> wonder myrk,</L>
<L N="22288">Schrouded with a cloud&euml; dyrk."</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>&para; Agyographe:</HEAD>
<L>'<B>I</B> Was not,' quod sche, 'sothe to say,</L>
<L>Lyche th&eacute;, borne vp-on a day,</L>
<L>But by processe and leyser,</L>
<L N="22292">And by space off many a &yogh;er.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>'By oold&euml; tym&euml; (stylle and loude,)</L>
<L>I was schadewed with a cloude,</L>
<L>And fful derkely kepte in cloos,</L>
<L N="22296">Tyl tym&euml; that the sonne aroos&mdash;</L>
<L>I mene, the tyme that was to-fforn</L>
<L>That <B>Cryst ihesu</B> lyste to be born,&mdash;</L>
<L>Thilk&euml; tyme, my party ryght,</L>
<L N="22300">Off a cleer skye kaught his lyght;</L>
<L>The which&euml; skye, proffetys seyde,</L>
<L>Was that blessed holy mayde,</L>
<L>Off <B>Iesse</B> both&euml; braunche and fflour,</L>
<L N="22304">That bare <B>Ihesu</B>, oure sav&iuml;our.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>'That tym&euml;, with his streem&euml;s clere,</L>
<L>ffirste my bryghttenesse dyde appere;</L>
<L>And alle derkenesse to termyne,</L>
<L N="22308">Only by grace whiche is devyne.<MILESTONE UNIT="Tib folio" N="92b">
<PB REF="00000704.tif" N="596"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>'But the party off my vysage</L>
<L>Whiche is clowded with vmbrage,</L>
<L>Off cleernesse scholde haue no reporte,</L>
<L N="22312">But &yogh;eue he hadd&euml; his resorte</L>
<L>To that party, by vertu,</L>
<L>Off the cleernesse off <B>crist ihesu</B>;</L>
<L>Where-off,<NOTE PLACE="marg">[wherfore St.]</NOTE> lakkynge dyscrescyoun,</L>
<L N="22316">Thow madeste a lymytacyoun,</L>
<L>Affermynge (by a maner slouthe,)</L>
<L>My dyrk&euml;<NOTE PLACE="marg">[derke St., dyrk Tib.]</NOTE> parte wher voyde off trouthe:</L>
<L>I mene as thus, (in sentement,)</L>
<L N="22320">That the oold&euml; testament</L>
<L>Were derke and cloudy off his syght,</L>
<L>&YOGH;eue that it ne took his lyght</L>
<L>(Claryffyed by entend&euml;ment)</L>
<L N="22324">Off the new&euml; testament,</L>
<L>Whos schynynge (in conclusyoun)</L>
<L>Is cause off oure savacyoun.'</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>&para; The Pylgryme:</HEAD>
<L>"EXpown&euml; this with-out&euml;<NOTE PLACE="marg">[out Tib., St.]</NOTE> glose,</L>
<L N="22328">And &yogh;e schal haue the ffyrst&euml; rose</L>
<L>That I may ffynde (yt is no nay)</L>
<L>In the moneth of ffresch&euml; may."</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>&para; Agyographe:</HEAD>
<L>QVod sche, '&yogh;eue I schal the telle,</L>
<L N="22332">Mercerye I haue to selle,</L>
<L>In boyst&euml;s, soot&euml; oynementis,</L>
<L>There-with to don allegementis</L>
<L>To ffolkes whiche that<NOTE PLACE="marg">[that St., <I>om.</I> C.]</NOTE> be not glade,</L>
<L N="22336">But discorded<NOTE PLACE="marg">[discomfited St.]</NOTE> and mallade,</L>
<L>And hurte with perturbacyoun,<MILESTONE UNIT="Stowe folio" N="354b"><NOTE PLACE="marg">[perturbacions St., perturbacyoun Tib.]</NOTE></L>
<L>Off many trybulacyouns:<MILESTONE UNIT="Tib folio" N="93a"></L>
<L>I haue knyues, phyllettys, callys,</L>
<L N="22340">At ffeestes to hangen vp on wallys;</L>
<L>Komb&euml;s (mo than nyne or ten,)</L>
<L>Bothe ffor horse and eke ffor men;</L>
<L>Merours also, large and brode,</L>
<L N="22344">And, ffor the syght, wonder gode;</L>
<L>Off hem I haue fful greet plente</L>
<L>ffor ffolke that hauen volunte<NOTE PLACE="marg">[Illumination.]</NOTE>
<PB REF="00000705.tif" N="597"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>'to<NOTE PLACE="marg">[to St., <I>om</I>. Tib.]</NOTE> Byholde hem-silffe ther-ynne,</L>
<L>Wher they be clecne, or ffoule of synne.</L>
<L N="22349">'But, som ffolke hem-silffe byholde</L>
<L>ffor to hyde her ffylth&euml;s oolde,</L>
<L>Whiche ther bewete dothe apayre.</L>
<L N="22352">And somm&euml; merrours schewen ffayre,</L>
<L>By apparence off bewte,</L>
<L>Though that ther be no bewte:</L>
<L>Alle these thynges (who takith kep)</L>
<L N="22356">I haue hem towched on an hep.</L>
<L>&YOGH;eue here be aught that may &yogh;ou pleese,</L>
<L>Take it at thyne own&euml; eese.'</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>[The Pilgrim:]</HEAD>
<L>&para; In these thynges ffresche off delyte,</L>
<L N="22360">I sawgh there-in fful greet proffyte,</L>
<L>And also in her &aacute;cqueyntaunce,</L>
<L>Preyed hir to haue suffraunce,<MILESTONE UNIT="Tib folio" N="93b"></L>
<L N="22363">To graunte me leyser, and good ese,</L>
<L>To seen what thyng me myght&euml;<NOTE PLACE="marg">[myhte me St., me myght Tib.]</NOTE> pleese.</L>
<L>And, by good inspeccyoun,</L>
<L>Hadd&euml; turned al<NOTE PLACE="marg">[all tournyd St.]</NOTE> vp so doun,</L>
<L>&YOGH;eue eny thyng I koude espye</L>
<L N="22368">Amonge alle hir mercerye.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Vp and down I dyd&euml; se</L>
<L>What thyng lyked beste to me;</L>
<L>But, amonge hir thyng&euml;s alle,</L>
<L N="22372">Vp-on a merour I was ffalle,</L>
<L>Whiche schewyd me, in his glas,</L>
<L>More ffayre in sothenesse than I was,</L>
<L>By &aacute;pparenc&euml; sodeynely</L>
<L N="22376">The merour lyed verily:<NOTE PLACE="marg">[sodeynely Tib., verily St.]</NOTE></L>
<L>I knewe it wel in &eacute;xystence</L>
<L>And by oolde experyence.</L>
<L>Whan the trouth&euml; was conceyved,</L>
<L N="22380">I wyst&euml; wel I was deceyved;</L>
<L>To hir sayde, (in myne avys,)</L>
<L>That to hir it was no prys</L>
<L>To schewen out swyche mercerye,</L>
<L N="22384">Off merours to make men to prye.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; <B>Agyographe:</B>
<PB REF="00000706.tif" N="598"></L>
<L>'ISchewe no thyng, in sothe,' quod sche,</L>
<L>'But as it is in veryte.</L>
<L>I wole hoolden my byheste,</L>
<L N="22388">As ffolk&euml;s maken me requeste;</L>
<L>ffor, as ffer fforthe as I kan,</L>
<L>I wole deceyue no maner man;</L>
<L>The deceyt&euml;s, ffeytheffully<MILESTONE UNIT="Stowe folio" N="355a"></L>
<L N="22392">I wole schewe hem opunly.</L>
<L>Merours ther ben in many wyse,</L>
<L>As Craffty ffolk&euml;s kan devyse,</L>
<L>Whiche schewen dyuerse vysages<MILESTONE UNIT="Tib folio" N="94a"></L>
<L N="22396">And many wonderfful ymages,</L>
<L>Whiche to declare, I wole not dwelle:</L>
<L>Reede perspectyff, and that wole telle,</L>
<L>And schewen out the varyaunce</L>
<L N="22400">Off dyuerse ffacys, by d&eacute;monstraunce.'</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>&para; The Pylgryme:</HEAD>
<L>ANd off a merour that I ffonde,</L>
<L>Whiche that I heelde in myn hande,<NOTE PLACE="marg">[hond St.]</NOTE></L>
<L>I preyed hir, with-out&euml;<NOTE PLACE="marg">[out Tib., St.]</NOTE> schame,</L>
<L N="22404">To tell&euml; me there-off the name.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>&para; Agyographe:<NOTE PLACE="marg">[agiographye St.]</NOTE></HEAD>
<L>'HYt were good to hye and lowe,</L>
<L>That all&euml; ffolk&euml;s schold&euml; knowe,</L>
<L>And there-off hadde a trew&euml; syght,</L>
<L N="22408">Iustely what this merour hyght,</L>
<L>That ffolk&euml;s (ffor greet lak off lyght)</L>
<L>Were not deceyued in her syght.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>THis merour (by descripcyoun)</L>
<L N="22412">Is called <B>Adulacyoun:</B></L>
<L>This is (withouten eny blame)</L>
<L>Veryly his ryght&euml;<NOTE PLACE="marg">[ryght Tib., St.]</NOTE> name;</L>
<L>ffor, take good heede, that <B>fflateryng</B></L>
<L N="22416">Is engendred off <B>lesyng:</B></L>
<L>Somme callen hir <B>Placebo</B>,</L>
<L>ffor sche kan maken an <B>Eccho</B>,</L>
<L>Answere euere ageyn the same,</L>
<L N="22420">Because that he wole haue no blame.</L>
<L>Though it be ageyne resoun,</L>
<L>There is no contradiccyoun,
<PB REF="00000707.tif" N="599"></L>
<L>'ffor, bothe off newe, and &yogh;ore agon,</L>
<L N="22424">ffolk&euml;s sothely (mo than on)</L>
<L>Han in Adulacyoun<MILESTONE UNIT="Tib folio" N="94b"></L>
<L>ffounde fful greet decepcyoun:</L>
<L>Lordes (wherffore I seye 'allas!')</L>
<L N="22428">Han be dysseyued in this caas,</L>
<L>And, by advlacyoun</L>
<L>Brought to ther destruccyoun.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>&para; fflaterye:<NOTE PLACE="marg">[<I>om</I>. St. <I>Hagiography still speaks</I>.]</NOTE></HEAD>
<L>'FOr this custom hath fflaterye,</L>
<L N="22432">To seyne<NOTE PLACE="marg">[leyn St.]</NOTE> thus by los&eacute;ngerye&mdash;</L>
<L>Whanne hym lykyth to bygyle,</L>
<L>ffalsely by his sotyl while,&mdash;</L>
<L>To hem that be moste vycyous,</L>
<L N="22436">How that they are vertuous;</L>
<L>And though they ben to vyces thral,</L>
<L>They seyne eke they be lyberal,</L>
<L>Though they be streyte and ravynous,</L>
<L N="22440">And greet&euml; nygardes in her hous.</L>
<L>They call&euml; ffame and hygh renoun,</L>
<L>Raveyne and ffalse extorcyoun.</L>
<L>Though they be ffooles, and off no prys,</L>
<L N="22444">They afferme that they are wys.</L>
<L>&para; Who that trustith in swyche langage,</L>
<L>He is a ffool, and no thyng sage,<MILESTONE UNIT="Stowe folio" N="355b"></L>
<L>And ffolyly spente his labour,</L>
<L N="22448">That lokyth in any swyche merour;</L>
<L>And nam&euml;ly, whanne al is do,</L>
<L>That he knowith it is not so.</L>
<L>'Eche wyght knowe hym-syluen kan,</L>
<L N="22452">Bette thanne eny other man.</L>
<L>Leff, off<NOTE PLACE="marg">[Ieve of St.]</NOTE> fflaterye the sentence,</L>
<L>And &yogh;eue to trouth&euml; fful credence;</L>
<L>Thow knoweste bet thi-silffe, (off ryght,)</L>
<L N="22456">Thanne doth eny other wyght.</L>
<L>&para; 'Late<NOTE PLACE="marg">[let St.]</NOTE> lord&euml;s (whanne they kan espye,)</L>
<L>Sette asyde alle fflaterye!<MILESTONE UNIT="Tib folio" N="95a"></L>
<L>But now, allas, it stondyth so,</L>
<L N="22460">They be disseyu&euml;d by Eccho;</L>
<L>And ther sogetes,<NOTE PLACE="marg">[sogets St.]</NOTE> in many cost,
<PB REF="00000708.tif" N="600"></L>
<L>'Ben by fflatery&euml; lost,</L>
<L>And put in greet oppressyoun</L>
<L N="22464">And in greet tribulacyoun;</L>
<L>I mene, by swych&euml; as be stronge,</L>
<L>To por&euml; men ffor to do wronge,</L>
<L>And suppose, thorough ther greet myght,</L>
<L N="22468">That they may doon it off ryght;</L>
<L>fflaterers bere hem so on hande,</L>
<L>Whiche, day and nyght, aboute hem stonde,</L>
<L>And fful ffalsely hem counsayle</L>
<L N="22472">To dispoyl&euml; the porayle;</L>
<L>Seyn,<NOTE PLACE="marg">[seyne St.]</NOTE> the good is herys off ryght;</L>
<L>Whiche causith, in the peplys syght,</L>
<L>fful greet envye and greet haterede,</L>
<L N="22476">Whanne they be pressed with greet drede;</L>
<L>And causith, by swyche &oacute;ppressynges,</L>
<L>Greet&euml; rwmours and rysynges,</L>
<L>And, som while, rebellyoun</L>
<L N="22480">In many dyuerse regyoun;<NOTE PLACE="marg">[Illumination.]</NOTE></L>
<L>ffor lak oonly off polosye<NOTE PLACE="marg">[polecie St.]</NOTE><MILESTONE UNIT="Tib folio" N="95b"></L>
<L>Off ffolke aboue, that scholde hem guye;</L>
<L>Causith, som while, schedynge off blood.</L>
<L N="22484">Wherffore this meroure, &yogh;eue it be good,</L>
<L>Take it to thi pocessyoun,</L>
<L>To haue there-in Inspeccyoun.'</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>&para; The Pylgryme:</HEAD>
<L>"MAdame," quod I, "&yogh;ow not displeese,</L>
<L N="22488">This myroure schal do me noon eese:</L>
<L>For,<NOTE PLACE="marg">[for St., <I>om</I>. Tib.]</NOTE> wher-so that I leese or wynne,</L>
<L>I wole neuere looke there-Inne."</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>But ryght anoon, myne happe it was</L>
<L N="22492">To loken in another glasse,</L>
<L>In the whiche (withouten wene)</L>
<L>I sawe my-sylff, ffoule and vncleene,</L>
<L>And to byhold&euml;, ryght hydous,</L>
<L N="22496">Abhomynabel and vecyous.</L>
<L>Thilk&euml;<NOTE PLACE="marg">[Thilke St., That Tib.]</NOTE> merour and that glas</L>
<L>Schewyd to me what I was.<MILESTONE UNIT="Stowe folio" N="356a"><NOTE PLACE="marg">[Illumination.]</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>WHerffore, off rancour and dysdeyn,</L>
<L N="22500">The same merour I caste ageyn,
<PB REF="00000709.tif" N="601"></L>
<L>With-out abood,<NOTE PLACE="marg">[abod St.]</NOTE> in hir panere,<MILESTONE UNIT="Tib folio" N="96a"></L>
<L>ffrowarde off look, and eke off chere,</L>
<L>And gan my bak awey to turne;</L>
<L N="22504">And therffore soore I gan to morne.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>&para; Agyographe:</HEAD>
<L>'NOw I se wel, by thy<NOTE PLACE="marg">[thy St., <I>om</I>. Tib.]</NOTE> contenaunce,</L>
<L>And also by thy gouernaunce,</L>
<L>Thow haste no luste to loke and se</L>
<L N="22508">In this merour (yt semyth me)</L>
<L>Callyd 'the<NOTE PLACE="marg">[the <I>om</I>. St.]</NOTE> Merour off Concyence,'</L>
<L>Whiche schewith (by trewe experyence,</L>
<L>With-out Eccho or fflaterye,</L>
<L N="22512">Or eny other losengerye,)</L>
<L>Vn-to a man, what ymage</L>
<L>He bereth aboute, or what<NOTE PLACE="marg">[what <I>om</I>. St.]</NOTE> visage,</L>
<L>The portrature, ryght as it is,</L>
<L N="22516">And in what thyng he dothe amys,</L>
<L>And how he schal the bette entende,</L>
<L>Alle his ffylth&euml;s to amende.'</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>&para; Lessown [the Subcellarer]:</HEAD>
<L>THanne quod the southe-Celerer:<NOTE PLACE="marg">[sowcelerer St.]</NOTE></L>
<L N="22520">'Towchynge hir, the Mercer,</L>
<L>It is to hir, displesaunce,</L>
<L>That thow wolte not han &aacute;queyntaunce</L>
<L>With hir, whiche soth&euml;ly myght be</L>
<L N="22524">fful greet proffyte vn-to the,</L>
<L>In what thow scholdeste haue ado.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>'And &yogh;eue I wyste thow woldeste so,</L>
<L>I wolde maken the to ben able.</L>
<L N="22528">Eche day to sytten at hir table;</L>
<L>With hir to be c&oacute;mensal,</L>
<L>Off Cheerte<NOTE PLACE="marg">[cherite St.]</NOTE> in especyal.</L>
<L>And<NOTE PLACE="marg">[for St.]</NOTE> (&yogh;eue I schal the trouth&euml; telle)<MILESTONE UNIT="Tib folio" N="96b"><NOTE PLACE="marg">[St. &amp; Tib.]</NOTE></L>
<L N="22532">In howsholde with hir I dwelle,<NOTE PLACE="marg">[St. &amp; Tib.]</NOTE></L>
<L>And am to hir, off custom, ner.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>'And the name off this <B>Mercer</B></L>
<L>I-callyd is <B>'hooly scripture,'</B></L>
<L N="22536">Whiche ffor to leren, I do my cure,</L>
<L>In a vessyl off Parchemyn:&mdash;</L>
<L>Off ffee, I calle the offyce myn:&mdash;
<PB REF="00000710.tif" N="602"></L>
<L N="22539">'In swyche a vessel, euery coost,</L>
<L>I bere it that they<NOTE PLACE="marg">[it St.:? 2 <I>Testaments</I>, p.596.]</NOTE> be not lost.</L>
<L>Therto I do my dylygence,</L>
<L>To kepe it ffrom alle vyolence;</L>
<L>ffor it may not (as thow doste<NOTE PLACE="marg">[mayst St.]</NOTE> se,)</L>
<L N="22544">In noon other vessel be,</L>
<L>To kepe it in savacyoun;</L>
<L>And my name is eke 'Lessown,'</L>
<L>And 'Studye,' amonge these clerk&euml;s alle,</L>
<L N="22548">Whiche off bothe, thow lyste me calle.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>'And ffirst&euml;, &yogh;eue thow haue plesaunce,</L>
<L>With me to hauen &aacute;queyntaunce,</L>
<L>Thow schalt aqueyntyd ben anoon</L>
<L N="22552">With these ladyes euerychon,</L>
<L>Verreyly at thyne own&euml; lyst:</L>
<L>In my byheste haue ffully tryst,</L>
<L>ffor grac&euml; off the hooly goost</L>
<L N="22556">Schal ffolewe the in euery coost,</L>
<L>Ryght as this whyt&euml; dowu&euml; doth,<MILESTONE UNIT="Stowe folio" N="356b"></L>
<L>Ay sueth me, and that is soth,</L>
<L>Whiche schal the teche and tellen al</L>
<L N="22560">The secre&euml;s celestyal.</L>
<L>ffor, sche is off hevene (ffer and ner)</L>
<L>The verrey trew&euml; messager.</L>
<L>Erly at morewe, and at eve</L>
<L N="22564">Estudyantys<NOTE PLACE="marg">[estudiauncys St.]</NOTE> sche kan releve,</L>
<L>To &yogh;eue hem her reffeccyoun</L>
<L>By myne ad-mynystracyoun.'<NOTE PLACE="marg">[admyn . . St., and min . . Tib.]</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Other two ladyes I sawe also;<MILESTONE UNIT="Tib folio" N="97a"></L>
<L N="22568">To the chapitre that went&euml; tho;</L>
<L>The ton off hem, bar in hir hondis,</L>
<L>Cord&euml;s and eke strong&euml; bondis;<NOTE PLACE="marg">[Illumination.]</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>THe thother (in the sam&euml; while)</L>
<L N="22572">In hir mouthe sche bare a ffyle</L>
<L>Endentyd; the teth there-off were large;</L>
<L>And on hir breste, a fful brood targe.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>&para; The Pylgryme:</HEAD>
<L>ANd or they ffurther myght&euml;<NOTE PLACE="marg">[myght Tib., St.]</NOTE> goon,</L>
<L N="22576">I requyred hem anoon,</L>
<L>Te telle m&euml; (by good avys,)
<PB REF="00000711.tif" N="603"></L>
<L>Bothe ther names and ther offis.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>&para; Obedyence:</HEAD>
<L>THe lady that the boondys bar,</L>
<L N="22580">To me seyde (as I was war),</L>
<L>'I am,' quod sche, '(schortely to expresse),</L>
<L>Of this hous the<NOTE PLACE="marg">[the <I>om</I>. St.]</NOTE> cheeff pryoresse,</L>
<L>Nexte Grac&euml; Dieu (in substaunce,)<MILESTONE UNIT="Tib folio" N="97b"></L>
<L N="22584">I haue here<NOTE PLACE="marg">[here St., off hir Tib.]</NOTE> the gouernaunce,</L>
<L>(Bothe byfforne and eke byhynde.)</L>
<L>And with these boond&euml;s eke I bynde,</L>
<L>(Wher-so that they be soure or swete,)</L>
<L N="22588">Off ffolk&euml;s both&euml; hand and ffete,</L>
<L>That they, in no wys&euml;, doore<NOTE PLACE="marg">.i. audent St., <I>om</I>. Tib.</NOTE></L>
<L>Passen by noon opene doore:<NOTE PLACE="marg">.i. per hostium St., <I>om</I>. Tib.</NOTE></L>
<L>I holde hem in, lyke prisoners,</L>
<L N="22592">And off look and eke off cherys;</L>
<L>And my nam&euml; (in sentence)</L>
<L>Callyd is <B>Obedyence</B>.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>'My boondes and my lygamentys</L>
<L N="22596">Ben dyuerse comaund&euml;mentys,</L>
<L>To holden in subieccyoun</L>
<L>ffolk&euml;s off relygyoun.</L>
<L>&para; And off my ffyl&euml; to termyne,</L>
<L N="22600">It is I-called <B>Dyscyplyne</B>:</L>
<L>And that I (bothe northe and south)</L>
<L>Am wonte to bere it in my mouth,</L>
<L>Betokeneth reprehensyoun</L>
<L N="22604">Off ffolke, ffor her transgressyoun,</L>
<L>There-with I scoure in euery syde,</L>
<L>That ther may no ruste abyde,<NOTE PLACE="marg">[Illumination.]</NOTE></L>
<L>Nowther ffylthe, ffor noon offence.<MILESTONE UNIT="Tib folio" N="98a"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="22608">'My targ&euml; callyd ys 'Prudence:'</L>
<L>Euery thyng (I the ensure)</L>
<L>t&oacute; gou&eacute;rne it by mesure.'<NOTE PLACE="marg">[Tib. &amp; St.]</NOTE></L>
<L>&para; And, as I hadd&euml; good reward,<NOTE PLACE="marg">[Tib. &amp; St.]</NOTE></L>
<L N="22612">I sawgh oon in-to the ffreyterward</L>
<L>Goon a mesurable paas,<MILESTONE UNIT="Stowe folio" N="357a"></L>
<L>Wonder sobre off look and ffaas,</L>
<L>And no thyng dissolut off cher:</L>
<L N="22616">Armyd sche was with a gorger.
<PB REF="00000712.tif" N="604"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>The Pylgryme:</HEAD>
<L>Off whom I gan anoon enquere,</L>
<L>That sche wold&euml; goodly leere</L>
<L>To me (by schorte conclusyoun)</L>
<L N="22620">Hir name and hir condissyoun;</L>
<L>And off the tablys cured echon,</L>
<L>And there-ate syttynge many on;<NOTE PLACE="marg">[a one St.]</NOTE></L>
<L>And also, as I dyde obserue,</L>
<L N="22624">Noon other ffolke at met&euml; serve,</L>
<L>But ffolkes deed&euml; euere more,</L>
<L>Where-off I w&aacute;s abaschyd sore.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>&para; Abstynence:</HEAD>
<L>'<B>I</B> Am,' quod sche, 'the Freytourer</L>
<L N="22628">Off this hous, and Bot&euml;ler,</L>
<L>And mynystre the sustenaunce</L>
<L>To ffolk&euml;s, lyke to ther plesaunce.</L>
<L>I kepe hem hool, I kepe hem cleene,</L>
<L N="22632">By a mesurable meene,</L>
<L>That, surff&eacute;t be not to blame.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>'Abstynence,' that is my name;</L>
<L>And my gorger that thow doste se,</L>
<L N="22636">Is I-callyd 'Sobrete,'<NOTE PLACE="marg">[sobriete St.]</NOTE></L>
<L>To kepe the gorge in<NOTE PLACE="marg">[by St.]</NOTE> sobrenesse,<MILESTONE UNIT="Tib folio" N="98b"></L>
<L>ffrom sorff&eacute;t, and al excesse.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>'ANd these ffolk&euml;s that ben deede,</L>
<L>Whiche that serue, (&yogh;eue thow take heede,)</L>
<L N="22641">Be thilk&euml; ffolk&euml;s euerychon,</L>
<L>Which&euml; that, off &yogh;ore agoon,</L>
<L>To-fforne her deth, off holynesse</L>
<L N="22644">And off verrey parffytenesse,</L>
<L>Mad&euml; the ffoundacyoun</L>
<L>Off ffolkys off relygyoun;</L>
<L>Endowyd<NOTE PLACE="marg">[enduyd St.]</NOTE> hem with greet substaunce,</L>
<L N="22648">Ther-by to haue ther sustynaunce.</L>
<L>&para; And ffor that skele (as I devyse)</L>
<L>They don&euml;<NOTE PLACE="marg">[done St., don Tib.]</NOTE> eche day her servyse,</L>
<L>And ben to hem eke servysable</L>
<L N="22652">Whanne they sytten at the table.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>'And ageyneward, sothe to seye,</L>
<L>The tother ffor hem wake and praye,
<PB REF="00000713.tif" N="605"></L>
<L>'Bothe by day and eke by nyght,</L>
<L N="22656">As they are bounden, off dewe ryght,</L>
<L>To ther sowlis to don socowre,</L>
<L>And afftirward to the dortoure.'</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>[The Pilgrim]:</HEAD>
<L N="22659"><B>I</B> Wot&euml; not wel what it mente,</L>
<L>I sawgh how tweyn&euml;<NOTE PLACE="marg">[twyne St., two Tib.]</NOTE> ladyes wente:</L>
<L>The on<NOTE PLACE="marg">[tone St.]</NOTE> off hem, (as I was war,)</L>
<L>In hir hand, a staff sche bar;</L>
<L>The tother, save a gambesoun,</L>
<L N="22664">Was nakyd (in myne inspeccyoun).</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>And sche that bare the staff, anon</L>
<L>ffro bed to bed sche is agon</L>
<L>Thorowgh-out the dortour (by and by),</L>
<L N="22668">And made the bedd&euml;s fful clenly;</L>
<L>And with clothis cleene and white</L>
<L>Sche spradde hem ouer, by delyte,</L>
<L N="22671">That no thyng ne lay a<NOTE PLACE="marg">[a St., <I>om</I>. Tib.]</NOTE> wronge.<MILESTONE UNIT="Tib folio" N="99a"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Sche that was nakyd, gan a songe,<NOTE PLACE="marg">[Illumination.]</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>WHiche (to putte in r&eacute;membraunce)<MILESTONE UNIT="Stowe folio" N="357b"></L>
<L>Was pleynely this, as in substaunce:</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>&para; The ffyrste verse off the song:</HEAD>
<L>'<B>I</B> Schal synge, with al my myght,</L>
<L N="22676">And so I howe,<NOTE PLACE="marg">[<I>owe, ought:</I> have St.]</NOTE> off verrey ryght.</L>
<L>I am nakyd, as &yogh;e may se;</L>
<L>By no thyng men may holden me;</L>
<L>Thowgh they me p&uacute;rsue, day and nyght,</L>
<L N="22680">To hold[&euml;] me they have no myght.<NOTE PLACE="foot">The 2nd and 3rd verses have only 5 lines each; the first ought to have the same; but as Stowe's 6th line stops the line|numbering getting uneven, I put it in.</NOTE><NOTE PLACE="marg">[St., <I>om</I>. Tib.]</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>&para; The secunde verse:</HEAD>
<L>'<B>A</B> Smal&euml; posterne I may pace,</L>
<L>And, thorough thykke and thynn&euml; trace;</L>
<L>ffor, thow that ffolk&euml;s dyde her peyne,</L>
<L N="22684">They may off me no thyng restreyne,</L>
<L>Affter, euere thow<NOTE PLACE="marg">[thoghe St.]</NOTE> they chace.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>&para; The thryde verse:</HEAD>
<L>'<B>I</B> Am 'Wylleffull Pouerte;'</L>
<L>And, off myne own&euml; volunte,<MILESTONE UNIT="Tib folio" N="99b">
<PB REF="00000714.tif" N="606"></L>
<L N="22688">'I despys&euml; alle rychesse;</L>
<L>Slepe in Ioye and sekyrnesse,</L>
<L>Nor thev&euml;s may not robb&euml; me.'<NOTE PLACE="marg">[Illumination.]</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>The Pylgryme:</HEAD>
<L>TO hir, that so nakyd was,</L>
<L N="22692">I gan to hasten a greet paas;</L>
<L>Bysoughtte hir that sche nold&euml; spare,</L>
<L>Hir name, to me ffor to declare.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>&para; Pouerte:</HEAD>
<L>'My name, &yogh;eue I schal tell&euml; the,</L>
<L N="22696">I am 'wyllefful Poverte;'</L>
<L>ffor,<NOTE PLACE="marg">[<I>om</I>. St.]</NOTE> to swyche pouerte I haue me take,</L>
<L>And the world I haue fforsake,</L>
<L>Rychesse and alle pocessyoun,</L>
<L N="22700">Save oonly this Gambysoun,</L>
<L>Whiche is callyd 'Pacyence.'</L>
<L>And therffore, with-out offence,</L>
<L>fforsake I haue the Temperal</L>
<L N="22704">ffor goodes that ben celestyall:<MILESTONE UNIT="Tib folio" N="100a"><NOTE PLACE="marg">[Tib. &amp; St.]</NOTE></L>
<L>There is my rychesse and gerdoun,</L>
<L>My tresowre and my pocessyoun.'</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>&para; The Pylgryme:</HEAD>
<L>"<B>I</B> Prey&euml; the that thow not tarye:</L>
<L N="22708">Why is it callyd 'voluntarye'?"</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>&para; Pouerte:</HEAD>
<L>'TRyst&euml; this (it is no ffayle,)</L>
<L>Ther may no thyng a man avayle;</L>
<L>(What maner thyng that euere it be,)</L>
<L N="22712">But it be doon off volunte.</L>
<L>Kome fforthe, and se an exanplayre<NOTE PLACE="marg">[exemplayre St.]</NOTE></L>
<L>Off poverte not voluntarye.'</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>And, with-out&euml;<NOTE PLACE="marg">[out Tib., St.]</NOTE> more lettynge,</L>
<L N="22716">Sche Schewyd me oon, ffelle off lokynge:</L>
<L>Groynynge sche sat, ffrownynge and sad;</L>
<L>And off hir cheere sche was not glad.</L>
<L>'Here thow<NOTE PLACE="marg">[thow St., <I>om</I>. Tib.]</NOTE> mayste seen pouerte</L>
<L N="22720">Whiche is no thyng off volunte.<NOTE PLACE="marg">[Illumination.]</NOTE></L>
<L>Thow mayste off hir <SUP>5</SUP>anon enquere,<SUP>5</SUP><NOTE PLACE="marg">[5_5 St., Tib. <I>torn</I>.]</NOTE><MILESTONE UNIT="Tib folio" N="100b"></L>
<L>And the trouthe sche schal the leere.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>&para; The Pylgryme:
</HEAD>
<PB REF="00000715.tif" N="607">
<L>"THow oolde," quod I, "so ffoule off cheere,</L>
<L>What cause haste thow to abyden<NOTE PLACE="marg">[hastow tabiden St.]</NOTE> heere<MILESTONE UNIT="Stowe folio" N="358a"></L>
<L N="22725">Amonge this ffayr&euml; companye</L>
<L>Off ladyes? I trowe thow art a spye.</L>
<L>Thow owghttyest not, with so ffoule a fface,</L>
<L N="22728">To<NOTE PLACE="marg">[To <I>om</I>. St.]</NOTE> abyden in so ffeyre a place."</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>&para; Pouerte Impacyent:<NOTE PLACE="marg">[impacyent Tib., <I>om</I>. St.]</NOTE></HEAD>
<L>QVod sche, 'the trowth&euml; ffor to kythe,</L>
<L>Thow haste seyne fful offt&euml; sythe</L>
<L>With lord&euml;s, ladyes, (it is no doute,)<NOTE PLACE="marg">[St. &amp; Tib.]</NOTE></L>
<L N="22732">In her<NOTE PLACE="marg">[thayr St.]</NOTE> chawmbres rounde abowte<NOTE PLACE="marg">[St. &amp; Tib.]</NOTE></L>
<L>For to maken dyuerse Iapes,<NOTE PLACE="marg">[St. &amp; Tib.]</NOTE></L>
<L>Foxes rennen, and eke apes,<NOTE PLACE="marg">[St. &amp; Tib.]</NOTE></L>
<L>Dysporte and pleye on euery syde:</L>
<L N="22736">And semblably, here I<NOTE PLACE="marg">[I here St.]</NOTE> abyde;</L>
<L>Where-off thow scholdest me not<NOTE PLACE="marg">[not me St.]</NOTE> repreve;</L>
<L>ffor vn-to hem, no thyng I greve;</L>
<L>It dothe hem non dys&aacute;vauntage,</L>
<L N="22740">ffor to my silffe is the dam&aacute;ge.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>ANd<NOTE PLACE="marg">[and, <I>om</I>. St.]</NOTE> &yogh;eue men me callen 'Pouerte,'</L>
<L>And I<NOTE PLACE="marg">[I <I>om</I>. St.]</NOTE> take it not at gree</L>
<L N="22743">Thorough myne nowne<NOTE PLACE="marg">[owne St.]</NOTE> Impacyence,</L>
<L>My grucchynge doth no wight<NOTE PLACE="marg">[no wight St., myn owne Tib. (<I>from line above</I>).]</NOTE> offence,</L>
<L>(Who so takyth heede ther-to)</L>
<L>But to my silffe, and to no mo.</L>
<L>Off ffolk&euml;s off dyscressyoun,</L>
<L N="22748">I am had in derysyoun;</L>
<L>They holde off me but a Iape,</L>
<L>As a lord dothe off his ape.'<MILESTONE UNIT="Tib folio" N="101a"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>The Pylgryme:</HEAD>
<L>"Hyt semyth, as<NOTE PLACE="marg">[as <I>om</I>. St.]</NOTE> by thy r&eacute;semblaunce</L>
<L>And by thy owgely<NOTE PLACE="marg">[own St.]</NOTE> contenaunce,</L>
<L N="22753">By lyfftynge vp off thy mosel,</L>
<L>That thow pleyest the ap&euml; wel;</L>
<L>And that thow art the comune ape,</L>
<L N="22756">Affor&euml; ffolke to pleye and Iape."</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>&para; Pouerte Impacyent:<NOTE PLACE="foot">I need hardly say in an E. E. Text that the vulgar error of holding that 'like' is not a conjunction, is due to ignorance. Like, from 'like as,' is a conjunction; Like, from 'like to or unto,' is a preposition. See S. Walker, <I>Crit. on Shakesp</I>., ii. 115-123.</NOTE>
</HEAD>
<PB REF="00000716.tif" N="608">
<L>'THat is thorough myne Impacyence,</L>
<L>And ffor lak off pacyence,</L>
<L>That makyth me in hert&euml; swelle,</L>
<L N="22760">And, with greet&euml; wynd&euml;s belle,</L>
<L>That dothe my lypp&euml;s hygh&euml;<NOTE PLACE="marg">[hygh Tib., high St.]</NOTE> reyse,</L>
<L>Whiche, no man ne schuld&euml; preyse;</L>
<L>ffor it makyth a d&eacute;monstraunce</L>
<L N="22764">Off an apys contenaunce.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>'I love no maner besynesse,</L>
<L>But oonly slouthe and ydelnesse.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>'Ryghtffully, thorough my dyssert,<NOTE PLACE="marg">[decert St.]</NOTE></L>
<L N="22768">I may ben callyd wel 'Povert.'</L>
<L>Off good, I haue no maner thyng,</L>
<L>But as the<NOTE PLACE="marg">[a St.]</NOTE> bycch&euml;, ay groynyng,</L>
<L>Wel wors&euml; sothely than I seme;</L>
<L N="22772">Off euery thyng, the worst I deme.'</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>&para; The Pylgryme:</HEAD>
<L><B>A</B> Noon I laffte hir companye,</L>
<L>And gan me ffast&euml; ffor to hye</L>
<L>To hir that, with hir lok&euml;s glade,</L>
<L N="22776">In<NOTE PLACE="marg">[In St., But in Tib.]</NOTE> the dortoure bedd&euml;s made;</L>
<L>And curteysely I gan hir preye,<MILESTONE UNIT="Tib folio" N="101b"><NOTE PLACE="marg">[St. &amp; Tib.]</NOTE></L>
<L>To me sche wolde hir nam&euml; seye.<MILESTONE UNIT="Stowe folio" N="358b"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>&para; Dame<NOTE PLACE="marg">[Dame <I>om</I>. St.]</NOTE> chastyte:</HEAD>
<L>'<B>I</B> Am callyd by my name,</L>
<L>The ffeyre, with-out&euml;<NOTE PLACE="marg">[out Tib., St.]</NOTE> spotte or blame,</L>
<L N="22781">That may, in no place endure</L>
<L>Where that ffylthe is, or ordure.</L>
<L>And of<NOTE PLACE="marg">[of St., <I>om</I>. Tib.]</NOTE> ffolk&euml;s that me se,</L>
<L N="22784">I am<NOTE PLACE="marg">[They calle Tib.]</NOTE> callyd Chastyte;</L>
<L>Off thys castel, chasteleyne,</L>
<L>Whiche, day and nyght, I<NOTE PLACE="marg">[I <I>om</I>. St.]</NOTE> do my peyne</L>
<L>ffor to kepen this castel</L>
<L>ffrom schotte off Gonne and of<NOTE PLACE="marg">[of St., <I>om</I>. Tib.]</NOTE> quarel.</L>
<L N="22789">And therffore I am armed wel,</L>
<L>Bette thanne in yren and<NOTE PLACE="marg">[Bet than yren outher St.]</NOTE> steel;</L>
<L>Nyght and day is my laboure,<NOTE PLACE="marg">[St. &amp; Tib.]</NOTE></L>
<L>For to dyffend&euml;<NOTE PLACE="marg">[for to defenden St.]</NOTE> euery toure,</L>
<L N="22793">Bothe<NOTE PLACE="marg">[St., Tib. <I>blurd</I>]</NOTE> erly and also late,</L>
<L>And on myne handys, I haue off plate,<NOTE PLACE="marg">[Illumination.]</NOTE>
<PB REF="00000717.tif" N="609"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>'<B>A</B> Peyr&euml;<NOTE PLACE="marg">[peyre of St.]</NOTE> glou&euml;s, ffor dyffence,</L>
<L N="22796">I-callyd 'Dowble Contynence,'</L>
<L>Myghty venus to rechace,</L>
<L>And to putte hir ffro that place,<MILESTONE UNIT="Tib folio" N="102a"><NOTE PLACE="marg">[Tib. &amp; St.]</NOTE></L>
<L>That sche may hau&euml; noon entre</L>
<L N="22800">ffor to assayil&euml;<NOTE PLACE="marg">[fortassaille St.]</NOTE> chastyte,</L>
<L>Whiche schal, as a<NOTE PLACE="marg">[a St., <I>om</I>. Tib.]</NOTE> conquerour,)</L>
<L>Kepe and deffend&euml; the dortour,</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>'To alle my ffreendes, I wole socoure,</L>
<L N="22804">That with hert&euml; me honowre,</L>
<L>Hem to kepe ffrom vnclennesse,</L>
<L>While I to hem am cheeff maystresse.'</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>&para; The Pylgryme:</HEAD>
<L><B>A</B> fftir this, anoon I wente</L>
<L N="22808">In-to the mynstre (off good entente),</L>
<L>And, asyde castynge my syght,</L>
<L>I sawe a lady ffayre and bryght,</L>
<L>Sad off contenaunce and off<NOTE PLACE="marg">[off <I>om</I>. St.]</NOTE> cheere;</L>
<L N="22812">And sche bare, lyke a messangere,</L>
<L>A boyste; and anon ryght,<NOTE PLACE="marg">[6-<I>syllable line</I>]</NOTE></L>
<L>Toward the heuene sche took hir fflyght;</L>
<L>ffor (as I kowde byholde and se,)</L>
<L N="22816">Sche was whynged, ffor to ffle.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>ANd trewely (as I koude espye,)</L>
<L>Sche ffley&euml;<NOTE PLACE="marg">[flygh St.]</NOTE> ffer aboue the skye.</L>
<L>And, as me thought&euml;, longe and large,<MILESTONE UNIT="Tib folio" N="102b"><NOTE PLACE="marg">[St. &amp; Tib.]</NOTE></L>
<L N="22820">Affor hir brest, sche bare a targe;<NOTE PLACE="marg">[St. &amp; Tib.]</NOTE></L>
<L>And (schortely as I kan reherse)<NOTE PLACE="marg">[St. &amp; Tib.]</NOTE></L>
<L>The sylv&euml; heuene sche dyd&euml; perse.<NOTE PLACE="marg">[St. &amp; Tib.]</NOTE></L>
<L>And I thought (in sotheffastenesse)<NOTE PLACE="marg">[St. &amp; Tib.]</NOTE></L>
<L N="22824">Hir laboure and hir besynesse<NOTE PLACE="marg">[St. &amp; Tib.]</NOTE></L>
<L>Was ffor to maken (in certeyne)</L>
<L>Deed&euml; men to ryse<NOTE PLACE="marg">[lyve St.]</NOTE> ageyne.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>And I gan ffor to neygh&euml;<NOTE PLACE="marg">[neygh Tib., nyghe St.]</NOTE> nere,</L>
<L N="22828">Prey&euml;d hir (off herte entere)</L>
<L>To &yogh;eue me infformacyoun</L>
<L>Off name and of<NOTE PLACE="marg">[and of St., and Tib.]</NOTE> condyscyoun.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>&para; Prayere:</HEAD>
<L>'My nam&euml;, &yogh;eue thow lyste to here,<MILESTONE UNIT="Stowe folio" N="359a"></L>
<L N="22832">I am, off ffolke, callyd 'Prayere';
<PB REF="00000718.tif" N="610"></L>
<L>'And lerne off me that (off resoun,)<NOTE PLACE="marg">[St. &amp; Tib.]</NOTE></L>
<L>Eche man is worthi the guerdoun<NOTE PLACE="marg">[St. &amp; Tib.]</NOTE></L>
<L>(Yf<NOTE PLACE="marg">[Tib. would be '&yogh;eue.']</NOTE> that trouth&euml; be obserued,)<NOTE PLACE="marg">[St. &amp; Tib.]</NOTE></L>
<L N="22836">Lyke as he hath trewely deserued.<NOTE PLACE="marg">[St. &amp; Tib.]</NOTE></L>
<L>And ech&euml; wyght, ffor his good dede,</L>
<L>Is worthi to resseyue his mede,</L>
<L>Lyke his meryte, off equyte.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="22840">'These deed&euml; ffolk whiche thow doste se,<NOTE PLACE="inter">[Illumination. Pilgrim, Angel, and two dead Men.]</NOTE></L>
<L>Ben they whiche, euery day suynge,<MILESTONE UNIT="Tib folio" N="103a"><NOTE PLACE="marg">[Tib. &amp; St.]</NOTE></L>
<L>&YOGH;euen lyuelode and fost[e]rynge<NOTE PLACE="marg">[Tib. &amp; St.]</NOTE></L>
<L>To lyvynge ffolkes that here-in dwelle:</L>
<L N="22844">In what wyse, I schal the telle.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Whanne they alyue were heere present,</L>
<L>They gaff off herte, in<NOTE PLACE="marg">[and St.]</NOTE> good entent,</L>
<L>Thorough ther parffyte holynesse,</L>
<L N="22848">In-to this hous fful greet almesse;</L>
<L>And, to ther sustentacyoun,</L>
<L>They mad&euml; the ffoundacyoun</L>
<L>Off this ylk&euml; sam&euml;<NOTE PLACE="marg">[same ilke St.]</NOTE> hous;</L>
<L N="22852">And &yogh;aff vnto relygyous</L>
<L>Meete and drynke (off good entent)</L>
<L>And lyuelod&euml; competent;</L>
<L>Off purpos (soth&euml; ffor<NOTE PLACE="marg">[for <I>om</I>. St.]</NOTE> to seye)</L>
<L N="22856">Th&aacute;t they schold&euml; ffor hem preye.</L>
<L>And so they don, bothe day and nyght,</L>
<L>Off consu&eacute;tude and off ryght.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>'Wherffore, callyd I am 'Prayere,'</L>
<L N="22860">Whiche that am the messagere</L>
<L>That fflee<NOTE PLACE="marg">[fly St.]</NOTE> to heuene with whyng&euml;s lyght,</L>
<L>ffer aboue the sterres bryght,</L>
<L>To-ffore the lord, to presente</L>
<L N="22864">Prayere made in good entente,</L>
<L>Lyche as these ffolk&euml;s haue in charge.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>'And the name eke off my Targe,</L>
<L>Is Fervente Contynuacyoun</L>
<L N="22868">Off preyere by devocyoun.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>FOr there nys<NOTE PLACE="marg">[nys St., is Tib.]</NOTE> halpeny nor fferthyng,</L>
<L>But it requerith his guerdownyng</L>
<L>More trewely (&yogh;eue it be tolde)
<PB REF="00000719.tif" N="611"></L>
<L N="22872">'Thanne the somme a thowsande ffolde,</L>
<L>In the lyffe that is eterne,</L>
<L>Off hym that eche thyng kan concerne,</L>
<L>Eternally lyvyng in glory.<MILESTONE UNIT="Stowe folio" N="359a"><MILESTONE UNIT="Tib folio" N="103b"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="22876">'Prayer abreggeth purgat&oacute;ry,<NOTE PLACE="marg">[St. &amp; Tib.]</NOTE></L>
<L>And alleggeth (in certeyne,)<NOTE PLACE="marg">[St. &amp; Tib.]</NOTE></L>
<L>Of sowl&euml;s the greet&euml;<NOTE PLACE="marg">[greet Tib., gret St.]</NOTE> peyne,<NOTE PLACE="marg">[St. &amp; Tib.]</NOTE></L>
<L>And gyveth to hem remyssyoun.<NOTE PLACE="marg">[St. &amp; Tib.]</NOTE></L>
<L N="22880">Wher-ffore I am callyd 'Orysoun,'<NOTE PLACE="marg">[St. &amp; Tib.]</NOTE></L>
<L>That do off ffolk&euml;s the message</L>
<L>To<NOTE PLACE="marg">[to St., And to Tib.]</NOTE> god, by fful swyffte passage.</L>
<L N="22883">The request&euml;s I kan speede,</L>
<L>Off ffolke that preye in love and dreede,<MILESTONE UNIT="Stowe folio" N="359b"></L>
<L>And make the procuracyoun</L>
<L>Off Pr&aacute;yere and off Orysoun.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>ANd with the kyng (take heede also,</L>
<L N="22888">Who hath any thyng ado</L>
<L>To expleyten his laboure)</L>
<L>I am cheveste procuratoure;<NOTE PLACE="marg">[St. &amp; Tib.]</NOTE></L>
<L>And euere my supplycacyoun,<NOTE PLACE="marg">[St. &amp; Tib.]</NOTE></L>
<L N="22892">Whanne<NOTE PLACE="marg">[Whan St., Euere Tib.]</NOTE> it is grownded on resoun,<NOTE PLACE="marg">[St. &amp; Tib.]</NOTE></L>
<L>It is never, I dar devyse,<NOTE PLACE="marg">[St. &amp; Tib.]</NOTE></L>
<L>Not refusyd, in no wyse.<NOTE PLACE="marg">[St. &amp; Tib.]</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="22895">WHerffore, by the reed off me,</L>
<L>&YOGH;eue thow wolte<NOTE PLACE="marg">[wilt St.]</NOTE> gon to that Cyte,</L>
<L>I schal the schewe the ryght&euml;<NOTE PLACE="marg">[ryght Tib., St.]</NOTE> way,</L>
<L>And the passage (it is no nay)</L>
<L>Gladdely eke, &yogh;eue it may pleese.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="22900">'And also, ffor to doon th&egrave; eese,</L>
<L>I schal the lene a mansyoun,</L>
<L>To make thyne habytacyoun:</L>
<L>It sytte wel, bothe<NOTE PLACE="marg">[bothe <I>om.</I> St.]</NOTE> to hygh and lowe,</L>
<L N="22904">Thy comynge ther afforne be<NOTE PLACE="marg">[to St.]</NOTE> knowe;</L>
<L>ffor who that schal haue there entre,</L>
<L>Knowe, to-fforn&euml;, it muste be;</L>
<L>Nor n&oacute; man may haue there host&aacute;ge,</L>
<L N="22908">But I to-fforne do his message.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>'And off the theeff, in his hangynge,<NOTE PLACE="marg">[Tib. &amp; St.]</NOTE><MILESTONE UNIT="Tib folio" N="104a"></L>
<L>Whanne he henge by the myghty kynge<NOTE PLACE="marg">[Tib. &amp; St.]</NOTE></L>
<L>Crist ihesu, vp-on the roode,
<PB REF="00000720.tif" N="612"></L>
<L N="22912">'That deyed ffor oure alder goode;</L>
<L>Off whom the theeff fful humbely</L>
<L>Axed off that lord mercy;</L>
<L>The sam&euml; tyme, ffor his socoure,</L>
<L N="22916">I<NOTE PLACE="marg">[I St., And Tib.]</NOTE> wente afforne enbassatoure,</L>
<L>And trew&euml;ly dyde his message,</L>
<L>And mad&euml;<NOTE PLACE="marg">[To make St.]</NOTE> redy his passage,</L>
<L>That he myght resseyued be</L>
<L N="22920">In Paradys, that ffayre contre.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>ANd semblabely, as by my reed,</L>
<L>By this exaumple take good heed,</L>
<L>That thow b&eacute; not putte in blame,</L>
<L N="22924">Thy-silff&euml;, ffor to do th&eacute; schame.</L>
<L>Thow haste as greet neede, at a preeff,<NOTE PLACE="marg">[? meeff Tib.]</NOTE></L>
<L>I<NOTE PLACE="marg">[in St.]</NOTE> sothe, as hadd&euml; the seyde theeff.</L>
<L>And, to ffurther thy vyage,</L>
<L N="22928">I wole my silffe don thi message.'</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>&para; The Pylgryme:</HEAD>
<L>ANd thanne anoon, with humble cheere</L>
<L>I thankyd tho vnto Preyere,</L>
<L>And seyde, "my caus&euml; to amende,</L>
<L N="22932">That to-fforne I wolde hir sende,</L>
<L>ffor my reffute and my socoure,</L>
<L>ffor to ben my procuratoure."</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Anoon affter, in certeyne,</L>
<L N="22936">Whanne I hadde the plac&euml; seyne,<MILESTONE UNIT="Stowe folio" N="360a"></L>
<L>And, by cleer inspeccyoun,</L>
<L>Made my vysitacyoun,</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>ANd in my way as I gan go,</L>
<L N="22940">Within the plac&euml; to and ffro,<MILESTONE UNIT="Tib folio" N="104b"><NOTE PLACE="marg">[St. &amp; Tib.]</NOTE></L>
<L>Of aventur&euml; me by-fforn,<NOTE PLACE="marg">[St. &amp; Tib.]</NOTE></L>
<L>I sawgh one that blewe an horn,<NOTE PLACE="marg">[St. &amp; Tib.]</NOTE></L>
<L>And made a noys&euml; wonder lowde.<NOTE PLACE="marg">[St. &amp; Tib.]</NOTE></L>
<L N="22944">And (as I espyen koude)<NOTE PLACE="marg">[St. &amp; Tib.]</NOTE></L>
<L>In organys and in sawtrye<NOTE PLACE="marg">[St. &amp; Tib.]</NOTE></L>
<L>She made a wonder melodye.<NOTE PLACE="marg">[St. &amp; Tib.]</NOTE><NOTE PLACE="inter">[Illumination: the Pilgrim, with a Woman at an Organ, blowing a cow's horn; beyond, a table with a Harp on it. One large and five small windows in the room.]</NOTE>
<PB REF="00000721.tif" N="613"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>WHom I by-sought, off hardynesse,</L>
<L N="22948">To me, that sche wolde expresse,</L>
<L>(Off hir grace, in goodly wyse,)</L>
<L>Her office, and her servyse.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>&para; Latrya:<NOTE PLACE="marg">[<GAP DESC="Greek">, the state of a hired workman.]</NOTE></HEAD>
<L>'Off this plac&euml;, ffolkes alle,</L>
<L N="22952">'Latrya'<NOTE PLACE="marg">[Lat-er-&iuml;a]</NOTE> they me calle.</L>
<L>Myne offyce is moste in wakynge,</L>
<L>To kepe the gate aboute the kynge.</L>
<L>I wacch&euml; thereon, day and nyght,</L>
<L N="22956">Do my fforse,<NOTE PLACE="marg">[servys St.]</NOTE> and eke my myght,</L>
<L>ffor to lyne<NOTE PLACE="marg">[ly St.]</NOTE> aye in awayt,</L>
<L>That there be ffounden no dysceyt.</L>
<L>Nowther behynde nor beforn;<MILESTONE UNIT="Tib folio" N="105a"><NOTE PLACE="marg">[Tib. &amp; St.]</NOTE></L>
<L N="22960">ffor thanne anoon I blowe myn horn.<NOTE PLACE="marg">[Tib. &amp; St.]</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>'Who lythe to longe, I make hym ryse;</L>
<L>Slogardes all&euml;, I<NOTE PLACE="marg">[all I do St.]</NOTE> chastise,</L>
<L>And to slouthe I do greet sorewe;</L>
<L N="22964">ffor, bothe at eeue and eke at morew,</L>
<L>I kepe the howr&euml;s off rysynge,</L>
<L>To do worschipe vnto<NOTE PLACE="marg">[vnto St., to Tib.]</NOTE> the kynge.</L>
<L>All&euml; ffolk&euml;s vp I calle,</L>
<L N="22968">That no slomber on hem ffalle.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>'Myne horne is <B>Invocacyoun</B></L>
<L>Off <B>Deus in adiutorium:</B></L>
<L>I blowe myn horn toward mydnyght,</L>
<L N="22972">To reyse vp ffolk&euml;s anoon ryght;</L>
<L>I suffre hem not, off sleep to deye.</L>
<L>Myne orgones, I tempre ffor to pleye,</L>
<L>And vp-on hem I make a sown</L>
<L>With-outen Intermyssyown.<NOTE PLACE="marg">sine intermissione orare. St. <I>om.</I> Tib.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="22977">'And trewely, alle my melodye</L>
<L>Is in songe off Persalmodye.<NOTE PLACE="marg">[and psalmody St.]</NOTE></L>
<L>And, devoutely, in myne ententis,</L>
<L N="22980">I call&euml; so myne Instrumentis;</L>
<L>ffor thylk&euml; kyng that is most stronge,</L>
<L>Moste hym delytyth in swyche songe;</L>
<L>To hym it<NOTE PLACE="marg">[it <I>om.</I> St.]</NOTE> is moste pertynente,</L>
<L N="22984">Whanne it is songe off good entente,</L>
<L>In clennesse and in purete.'
<PB REF="00000722.tif" N="614"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>And while that Latrya spak to me,</L>
<L>I sawgh the lady, whiche in<NOTE PLACE="marg">[lady within St.]</NOTE> hir handys</L>
<L>Whiche I off spak, that bar the bondys,<NOTE PLACE="marg">[bands St.]</NOTE><MILESTONE UNIT="Stowe folio" N="360b"></L>
<L N="22989">Sad and demure off hir vysage.</L>
<L>To me sche takyth hir passage:</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>&para; Obedyence:</HEAD>
<L N="22991">'TElle me,' quod sche, 'on euery part</L>
<L>Verely what that thou art,<MILESTONE UNIT="Tib folio" N="105b"><NOTE PLACE="marg">[Stowe MS., Tib. <I>burnt</I>]</NOTE></L>
<L>And the truth&euml; specifye,<NOTE PLACE="marg">[Stowe MS., Tib. <I>burnt</I>]</NOTE></L>
<L>Yf thou come ought as espye<NOTE PLACE="marg">[St. &amp; Tib.]</NOTE></L>
<L>Into this plac&euml;, to or<NOTE PLACE="marg">[and St.]</NOTE> ffro,<NOTE PLACE="marg">[St. &amp; Tib.]</NOTE></L>
<L N="22996">Or thou eny ffurther go.'<NOTE PLACE="marg">[St. &amp; Tib.]</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>&para; The Pylgryme:</HEAD>
<L>"MAdame," quod I, "haue on me ruthe.</L>
<L>I am no spy&euml;, in good trouthe;</L>
<L>My purpos is, and that anoon,<NOTE PLACE="marg">[St. &amp; Tib.]</NOTE></L>
<L N="23000">To Ierusalem ffor to goon.<NOTE PLACE="marg">[St. &amp; Tib.]</NOTE></L>
<L>And, the wey&euml;s as I sought,<NOTE PLACE="marg">[St. &amp; Tib.]</NOTE></L>
<L>Hedre <B>grace dieu</B> me brought<NOTE PLACE="marg">[St. &amp; Tib.]</NOTE></L>
<L>Only my way&euml; ffor tabrygge,<NOTE PLACE="marg">[St. &amp; Tib.]</NOTE></L>
<L N="23004">And to eschewe eche other brygge."<NOTE PLACE="marg">[St. &amp; Tib.]</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>&para; Obedyence:<NOTE PLACE="marg">[latria St.]</NOTE></HEAD>
<L>'Tolde she the not (&yogh;eue thow haue mynde,)<NOTE PLACE="marg">[St. &amp; Tib.]</NOTE></L>
<L>Here-in that thow scholdest ffynde<NOTE PLACE="marg">[St. &amp; Tib.]</NOTE></L>
<L>Bedd&euml;s harde, and no thyng soffte,</L>
<L N="23008">As it is I-prev&euml;d offte</L>
<L>Off ffolke off euery maner age:</L>
<L>And heere is a fful hard passage.'</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>&para; The Pylgryme:</HEAD>
<L>"HOw harde euere that it be,</L>
<L N="23012">Trewely I schal it take at gre;</L>
<L>To grac&euml; dieu, what that I kan,</L>
<L>Serue hir as hir trew&euml; man."<NOTE PLACE="marg">[St. &amp; Tib.]</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>&para; Obedyence:<NOTE PLACE="marg">[latria St.]</NOTE></HEAD>
<L>'Take heder thy ffeet and thyne hondes;'<NOTE PLACE="foot">There is only one more after leaf in MS. Cott. Tib. A. vii, and the portion of the poem contained on that leaf,&mdash;which is nearly illegible,&mdash;is not missing in Vit. c. xiii.&mdash;W. WOOD (copier).</NOTE><NOTE PLACE="marg">[St. &amp; Tib.]</NOTE></L>
<L N="23016">I shall them both&euml; knett in bands.<MILESTONE UNIT="Stowe folio" N="360b"></L>
<L>thow shalt ha ges [lyke] a faucon,
<PB REF="00000723.tif" N="615"></L>
<L>'only of entenc&iuml;oun,</L>
<L>without eny contrariouste,</L>
<L N="23020">that [thou] shalt ylured be.'</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>Pilgrim:</HEAD>
<L>she band me foot and hand also,</L>
<L>that to mev&euml; to ne fro</L>
<L>I hadd no maner lyberte;</L>
<L N="23024">nor my tong&euml; was not fre</L>
<L>for to speke, but by lycence;</L>
<L>nor in the seller, nor in the spence,</L>
<L>ete nor drynk&euml; on no syde,</L>
<L N="23028">but lycens were my gyde.<NOTE PLACE="marg">[6-<I>syllable line</I>]</NOTE></L>
<L>And, for tacounte the terme entier,</L>
<L>the space of xxxix<NOTE PLACE="marg">[nine and thirty]</NOTE> yere</L>
<L>I was bound of volunte,</L>
<L N="23032">to obedience (as ye may se),</L>
<L>as the statuts, fayn and well,</L>
<L>bound the folk of that castell.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>and truly, in hert nor in thought,<MILESTONE UNIT="Stowe folio" N="361a"></L>
<L N="23036">my bond&euml;s<NOTE PLACE="marg">[bonds St.]</NOTE> greuyd me ryght nought;</L>
<L>but (as it comythe to r&eacute;membraunce)</L>
<L>ther befell a wondar chaunce:</L>
<L>the portar happede on a day</L>
<L N="23040">to ben fer out of the way;</L>
<L>the kynge was absent eke also;</L>
<L>and, in absence of both&euml; two,</L>
<L>(and the gat&euml; was vnshet,)</L>
<L N="23044">ther cam in, without&euml;<NOTE PLACE="marg">[without St.]</NOTE> let,</L>
<L>a thefe, that no man coude espye,</L>
<L>that was callyd Falls Envye:</L>
<L>hir two doughtars, the ton, 'Treson'</L>
<L N="23048">called / the tother, 'Detract&iuml;on':</L>
<L>with them (by gret cruelte)</L>
<L>Scilla, a monstre of the se,</L>
<L>and her hounds hir folowynge</L>
<L N="23052">with grete noyse and gret barkynge.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>and this meyne, in the castell</L>
<L>mad&euml; noyse and gret revell:</L>
<L>In a lenton (who lyst se)</L>
<L N="23056">they made the ladyes for to fle
<PB REF="00000724.tif" N="616"></L>
<L>out of thilk&euml; holy boundes.</L>
<L>and Scilla folowed with hir hounds,</L>
<L>gan at them sore enchace;</L>
<L N="23060">and Envy, thrughe all the place,</L>
<L>with hir doughters (out of doute,)</L>
<L>gan to seke me round about.</L>
<L>they were conspiryd all&euml;<NOTE PLACE="marg">[all St.]</NOTE> thre</L>
<L N="23064">playnly to devoure me,</L>
<L>only by conspirac&iuml;on</L>
<L>of envie and detracc&iuml;on.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>their felowship I forsoke;</L>
<L N="23068">and anon an horse I toke,</L>
<L>for to flyen, with all my myght,</L>
<L>to escape out of hir syght.</L>
<L>and truly, for no maner rape,</L>
<L N="23072">theyr treyn&euml;s<NOTE PLACE="marg">[treyns St.]</NOTE> I myght not eskape.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>quod Scilla then, (of gret despyt,)</L>
<L>'he wenythe for to have respit,</L>
<L>and by his horse to bene socowryd,</L>
<L N="23076">that he shall nat ben devowryd</L>
<L>of vs by persecut&iuml;on.'</L>
<L>'ye, for &aacute;ll that,' quod Treason,</L>
<L>'as it is [vn]to vs dwe,</L>
<L N="23080">aftar hym we shall pursue.</L>
<L>what maner of horsse myght he have,<MILESTONE UNIT="Stowe folio" N="361b"></L>
<L>that from owr daunger shuld hym save?'</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>Scilla:</HEAD>
<L>quod Scilla, 'I shall well telle,</L>
<L N="23084">yf ye lyst a whil&euml; dwelle:</L>
<L>this horse is cawlyd 'Good Renowne,'</L>
<L>whiche hathe (in conclusyon)</L>
<L>fowr fette hym to susteyne;</L>
<L N="23088">and ell&euml;s<NOTE PLACE="marg">[ells St.]</NOTE> (without eny wene)</L>
<L>he shuld (to his confus&iuml;on,)</L>
<L>at myscheffe halten even a-downe,</L>
<L>with thre, tweyn&euml;, or with one,</L>
<L N="23092">vpryght he shuld nevar gon,</L>
<L>but stomble aye, and gon a-myse.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>'the first&euml;<NOTE PLACE="marg">[first St.]</NOTE> fote of his horse is,</L>
<L>that he have no condic&iuml;on
<PB REF="00000725.tif" N="617"></L>
<L N="23096">'sownynge to dyffamac&iuml;on,</L>
<L>this is to seyne, touchynge shame,</L>
<L>that he be voyde of dyffame.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>'The second, (to his &aacute;dvant&aacute;ge,)</L>
<L N="23100">that he be borne out of serv&aacute;ge:</L>
<L>this to meane, that he, in all,</L>
<L>out of thraldome be lyberall.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>'The third, (withouten all outr&aacute;ge,)</L>
<L N="23104">to be borne in trwe mari&aacute;ge.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>'the fourthe is, a foot full good,</L>
<L>of nature that he be nat wood,</L>
<L>nor that he, by no frolage,</L>
<L N="23108">be nat fallen into rage.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>'thes&euml; fowre feet (in sothnesse),</L>
<L>of truth&euml; all-way bere witnesse;</L>
<L>but we (by conspirat&iuml;oun)</L>
<L N="23112">shall maken hym alryght a-doune;</L>
<L>and, shortly, (to owr avayle),</L>
<L>here-on we shall haue a consayle.'</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>and, lyke to theyr opynyon,</L>
<L N="23116">fyrst ther spake Detract&iuml;on:</L>
<L>quod she, 'I can a noble songe</L>
<L>that aye resownythe vnto wronge,</L>
<L>That <I>Dan</I> of <I>Inuidia</I><NOTE PLACE="marg">[Fiat Dan coluber in via, cerastes in semita, mordens ungulas equi, ut cadat ascensor ejus retro.&mdash;<I>Genesis</I> xliv. 17.]</NOTE></L>
<L>ffiat coluber in via.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="23121">'this songe I wot ryght welle,' quod she,</L>
<L>'was I-songen first for me.</L>
<L>to vse it, I am nat rekles,</L>
<L>I am the horned Cerastes,<NOTE PLACE="marg">[<GAP DESC="Greek">, <I>cerastes</I>, a horned serpent.]</NOTE></L>
<L N="23125">whiche evar (as ferforthe as I may,)</L>
<L>trace ever the wrong&euml; way.</L>
<L>and covertly, in my werkynge,</L>
<L N="23128">I vs&euml; for to byte and stynge;</L>
<L>with tethe &amp; tonge I do most wrake,</L>
<L>evar behynden at the bake.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>'the hors&euml; of hym, in diffame,</L>
<L N="23132">[. . . . . . <I>no blank in MS.</I>]</L>
<L>so priveily I shall disceyve,<MILESTONE UNIT="Stowe folio" N="362a"></L>
<L>that he shall nat apparceyve.</L>
<L>I shall be falshed so prevyd,
<PB REF="00000726.tif" N="618"></L>
<L N="23136">'to make hym halten in some syde;</L>
<L>whiche so sor&euml; shall hym greve,</L>
<L>that he shall not mowe releve.'</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>'Sothly,' quod tho Treason,</L>
<L N="23140">'that good was hir oppinion.'</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>and when she hadd hir tal&euml; do,</L>
<L>echon they accordyd well therto;</L>
<L>the hound&euml;s<NOTE PLACE="marg">[hounds St.]</NOTE> stoden at abaye</L>
<L N="23144">and gan barke, by gret affray.</L>
<L>and at[t&euml;] last, Detracc&iuml;on</L>
<L>made myn hors to falle a-doun,</L>
<L>and to halten in swyche wyse</L>
<L N="23148">that I myght&euml;<NOTE PLACE="marg">[myght St.]</NOTE> nat a-ryse:</L>
<L>withe a tonge of a serpent</L>
<L>myne horse and I were both&euml; shent;</L>
<L>And doun at erthe, in gret affray,</L>
<L N="23152">amonge the hound&euml;s ther I lay.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>and aftar (by great felonye)</L>
<L>I was assaylyd by Envye;</L>
<L>and with thre sper&euml;s sharp&euml; ground,</L>
<L N="23156">she gave to me many a wound.</L>
<L>and of Scilla, the cruell hounds,</L>
<L>gaue me many mortall wounds;</L>
<L>I was to-torne with ther chas.</L>
<L N="23160">and than cam Treason with hir mas,</L>
<L>hevy as a clobbe of leed,</L>
<L>and ther-of set me on y<SUP>e</SUP> hede;</L>
<L>lege and arme she brake in twayne,</L>
<L N="23164">that yet I fell the gret&euml;<NOTE PLACE="marg">[gret St.]</NOTE> payne</L>
<L>of that ylk&euml; mortall stryffe,</L>
<L>and shall felle it all my lyffe.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>and whill I lay thus in a traunce</L>
<L N="23168">of grete anoye and grete grevaunce,</L>
<L>those old&euml;<NOTE PLACE="marg">[old St.]</NOTE> vekk&euml;s dispitious,<NOTE PLACE="inter">[No gap in MS.]</NOTE></L>
<L>they me left in full gret drede,</L>
<L N="23172">wenynge that I had be dede.</L>
<L>and comfort, truly was ther none,</L>
<L>for all my frynd&euml;s<NOTE PLACE="marg">[frynds St.]</NOTE> wer&euml; gon:</L>
<L>in prison, lay Charite;
<PB REF="00000727.tif" N="619"></L>
<L N="23176">Mercy was hound, &amp; eke Pitie,</L>
<L>whiche lykyd me nothyng well.</L>
<L>and Scilla cawsyd everydell;</L>
<L>for my sorow and my grevaunce</L>
<L N="23180">was to her full gret pleasaunce;</L>
<L>and it grevyd hir full sore</L>
<L>that I hadd&euml;<NOTE PLACE="marg">[MS. had]</NOTE> harme no more;<MILESTONE UNIT="Stowe folio" N="362b"></L>
<L>and she (of indignat&iuml;on,)</L>
<L N="23184">made a quarell to Treason,</L>
<L>that she dyd no more vengaunce,</L>
<L>to encrese my wofull chaunce.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>wherfore I (in myn entent)</L>
<L N="23188">I axyd a ryghtfull iug&euml;ment,</L>
<L>cast my gage tofore the kynge,</L>
<L>to have amende of all this thynge;</L>
<L>and, for this great transgress&iuml;on,</L>
<L N="23192">I made a-pele vppon Treson;</L>
<L>and complaynynge thus my wo,</L>
<L>I lay, and turnyd to and fro,</L>
<L>maymyd in so mortall wyse</L>
<L N="23196">that I myght&euml;<NOTE PLACE="marg">[myght St.]</NOTE> nat aryse</L>
<L>on my fete, for gret destrese;</L>
<L>and vpreard my-selfe to drese.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>I mad&euml; me a leg of tre</L>
<L N="23200">to rysen (yf it wold ha be);</L>
<L>and that leg (in my discese)</L>
<L>dede me after full gret ese;</L>
<L>for, to my gret confus&iuml;on,</L>
<L N="23204">lost I hadd&euml;<NOTE PLACE="marg">[had St.]</NOTE> my bordon;</L>
<L>I mist not wher&euml;, in serteyn,</L>
<L>tyll Grac&euml; Dieu it brought ageyn,</L>
<L>whiche that found it on a day</L>
<L N="23208">at the turnynge of a waye.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>and in thes wofull &aacute;uentures,</L>
<L>as I anoynted my bresures,</L>
<L>complaynynge early on a morow,</L>
<L N="23212">as I lay, and mad&euml; sorowe,</L>
<L>when phebus, with his bem&euml;s bryght,</L>
<L>gilt the hyll&euml;s<NOTE PLACE="marg">[hylls St.]</NOTE> with his lyght,</L>
<L>to chase the myst&euml;s that were derke,
<PB REF="00000728.tif" N="620"></L>
<L N="23216">to me there come a full old clerke,</L>
<L>whom, syth&euml; tyme that I was bore,</L>
<L>I had nevar sene tofore;</L>
<L>and his booke on me he layd,</L>
<L N="23220">and euen thus to me he sayd:<MILESTONE UNIT="Stowe folio" N="363a"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>Ouidius:</HEAD>
<L>quod he, 'of true affect&iuml;on,</L>
<L>I ha gret compassyon</L>
<L>on thy sorowe and on thy doole,</L>
<L N="23224">that thow liggest here all soole</L>
<L>in grete myscheffe (as semethe me)</L>
<L>wher-of I haue full gret pyte.'</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>Pilgrim:</HEAD>
<L>"for to put me in certeyne,</L>
<L N="23228">I pray the that thou woldest seyn</L>
<L>thy name openly to me,</L>
<L>that I myght&euml;<NOTE PLACE="marg">[myght St.]</NOTE> thanken the."</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>Ouidius:</HEAD>
<L>'of my name it stondethe thus;</L>
<L N="23232">I am callyd Ovydius,</L>
<L>whiche loue thee, more than thou canst wene:&mdash;</L>
<L>here-aftar it shall be sene.</L>
<L>and yf thow haddyst, her-to-forne,</L>
<L N="23236">in my tyme, in sothe be borne,</L>
<L>to thy consolat&iuml;on</L>
<L>I shold haue towght thee a lessonne,</L>
<L>whiche shuld ha be to thy plesaunce,</L>
<L N="23240">and shuld ha made thee in substaunce</L>
<L>ffull sufficiaunt, in many a thynge,</L>
<L>bothe in doctryne and in connynge.</L>
<L>but I am com&euml; to denounce</L>
<L N="23244">a sertayn curse, &amp; to pronounce,</L>
<L>on all&euml;<NOTE PLACE="marg">[all St.]</NOTE> thilk&euml; the sentence,</L>
<L>whiche vnto the ha don offence.</L>
<L>whiche sentence (in word&euml;s<NOTE PLACE="marg">[words St.]</NOTE> fewe)</L>
<L N="23248">to the in latyn I shall shewe,</L>
<L><I>Terra sibi fruges</I> &amp; cetera /'</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>Pilgrim:</HEAD>
<L>whan his vers weren all ysayd,</L>
<L>vnto hym thus I abrayd:
<PB REF="00000729.tif" N="621"></L>
<L>"that ye (of true affect&iuml;on,)</L>
<L N="23252">have on me compassyon,</L>
<L>on my doolle and on my smert.</L>
<L>I thank&euml; yow with all myn hert;<MILESTONE UNIT="Stowe folio" N="363b"></L>
<L>but I ha no devosyon</L>
<L N="23256">In cursynge nor in malison;</L>
<L>I shall delay[e]n all cursynge,</L>
<L>tyll tym&euml; that the myghty kynge,</L>
<L>by iug&euml;ment, eche thyng shall deme,</L>
<L N="23260">as vnto hym it shall but seme,</L>
<L>of ryghtwiseness&euml;, to provide."</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>and in this wise, the clerke Ovide</L>
<L>went his way, and left&euml;<NOTE PLACE="marg">[left St.]</NOTE> me</L>
<L N="23264">lyggynge in great adversitie;</L>
<L>and to expresse (in complaynynge)</L>
<L>my gret&euml;<NOTE PLACE="marg">[great St.]</NOTE> sorow by writynge,</L>
<L>I will myn own&euml; nam&euml; shewe,</L>
<L N="23268">sette out by lettars on a rowe</L>
<L>at the gynnynge of this ditie</L>
<L>in eche ballad as ye may se,</L>
<L>of Frenche and Lattyn, bothe I-fere,</L>
<L N="23272">ryght anon as ye shall here.</L>
<L>hauythe me excusyd of my rudenesse,</L>
<L>thowghe I to you my name expresse:</L>
</LG>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 TYPE="acrostic">
<HEAD>[ACROSTIC OF GUILLAUME DE DEGUILVEVILLE'S NAME: GUILLERMUS DE DEGUILEVILLA.]</HEAD>
<LG N="1" TYPE="stanza">
<L>Grato messium tempore,</L>
<L>Quant nature sez beaux<NOTE PLACE="foot">beaux, Petit print, <I>om</I>. St.</NOTE> fruiz dore,<NOTE PLACE="foot">Stowe ends here. The rest is copied from Petit's French edition of <I>Le romant des trois Pelerinaiges. Le premier pelerinaige est de l'homme durant qu'est en vie</I>. . . ab. 1500. Foeillet .lxxxiiij. col. 2, sign. l.iiij.</NOTE></L>
<L>Et prompta sunt in liquore</L>
<L N="4">Ses vins qu'encore pas n'affore,</L>
<L>Quo folium in arbore</L>
<L>Se commence a deuenir sore,</L>
<L>Et boreas in equore</L>
<L N="8">Si n'est pas trop nuysant encore.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="2" TYPE="stanza">
<L>VIdi scriptum in margine</L>
<L>Ou cestuy escript s'enracine,</L>
<L>Mirandam pulcritudine,</L>
<L N="12">Grace dieu, du ciel royne digne,</L>
<L>Me vocantem ex nomine:</L>
<L>'Vien auant, et si t'achemine</L>
<L>Mecum, quia regimine</L>
<L N="16">Tu as mestier, et de doctrine.'</L>
</LG>
<LG N="3" TYPE="stanza">
<L>ILla me duxit prospere</L>
<L>En l'ung des chasteaulx de son pere,</L>
<L>Exhortando summopere,</L>
<L N="20">Que l'un de leans ie fusse frere,</L>
<L>Virginique puerpere,</L>
<L>Estoille de mer pure et clere,</L>
<L>Me servum vellem tradere,</L>
<L N="24">En la faisant ma bonne mere.
<PB REF="00000730.tif" N="622"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="4" TYPE="stanza">
<L>LEgis audite nouelle,</L>
<L>Plaisante me fut la nouuelle,</L>
<L>Nam, mel mundi mixtum felle,</L>
<L N="28">Si me nuysoit &agrave; la forcelle.</L>
<L>Tunc pellem dedi pro pelle,</L>
<L>Pour seruir &agrave; ceste pucelle,</L>
<L>Puro sperans frui melle,</L>
<L N="32">Pour quoy la vie se renouuelle.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="5" TYPE="stanza">
<L>LOngo cursu pacifice</L>
<L>Remains ou chastel sans malice,</L>
<L>Vtilitati publice</L>
<L N="36">Entendant, selon mon office.</L>
<L>Sparsim apparent rubrice</L>
<L><MILESTONE UNIT="Petit folio" N="lxxxiiijb">A tout chascun, s'il n'est trop nyce,</L>
<L>Nam factum est theatrice,</L>
<L N="40">Sans quelconque notable vice.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="6" TYPE="stanza">
<L>EA propter prodiente</L>
<L>D'une cauerne pestilente,</L>
<L>Inuidia furiente,</L>
<L N="44">Et du bien de l'autruy dolente,</L>
<L>Improuise ac repente,</L>
<L>Scilla la lisse pullulente,</L>
<L>Proditione presente,</L>
<L N="48">Sans nul delay me mist en vente.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="7" TYPE="stanza">
<L>RAbida sic orta peste,</L>
<L>De corner fist tres grant moleste</L>
<L>Cum canibus atque reste;</L>
<L N="52">Moy, comme vne sauuaige beste,</L>
<L>Alba circumtecta veste,</L>
<L>De chasser se monstra moult preste;</L>
<L>Alta echo bosci teste,</L>
<L N="56">Trop me fut ceste chace agreste.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="8" TYPE="stanza">
<L>ME persequens indefesse,</L>
<L>La tres cruelle veneresse,</L>
<L>Ac violenter me subesse</L>
<L N="60">Fist a ses chiens hors de lesse,</L>
<L>Sicque clamare necesse</L>
<L>Bien me fut, pour yssir de presse,</L>
<L>Sed, si potuit prodesse,</L>
<L N="64">N'est pas bien ceste chose expresse.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="9" TYPE="stanza">
<L>VAluisset facta pace,</L>
<L>Se trahison vne autre trace</L>
<L>Non intrasset sine face,</L>
<L N="68">Afin qu'on n'apperceust la face;</L>
<L>Nam, duce nicticorace,</L>
<L>Par le coup d'une grosse masse,</L>
<L>Ostenso vultu fallace,</L>
<L N="72">Si m'abatit en my la place.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="10" TYPE="stanza">
<L>SIc persequitur peruerse</L>
<L>Tous temps / et assault et reuerse</L>
<L>Viros, sinderesis terse,</L>
<L N="76">Faulse trahison la peruerse;</L>
<L>Et timendum, si sic per se,</L>
<L>Au dedans du chastel conuerse,</L>
<L>Me per hanc oues disperse</L>
<L N="80">Soient par maniere bien diuerse.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="11" TYPE="stanza">
<L>DEtraction cum murmure,</L>
<L>Pour luy ayder, tres grande cure</L>
<L>Subministrant, et gutture,</L>
<L N="84">Par le dur glaiue qui trop dure;</L>
<L>Asseruntque de iure,</L>
<L>Que faire doyuent grant iniure</L>
<L>Hominibus vite pure,</L>
<L N="88"><NOTE PLACE="foot"><MILESTONE UNIT="Petit folio" N="84b:2"></NOTE>Que le susdit chastel enmure.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="12" TYPE="stanza">
<L>EXpertus hoc minis dure,</L>
<L>Soustiens leur griefue forfaicture,</L>
<L>Maxime cum nullo rure;</L>
<L N="92">Bestes y ait de tel facture,</L>
<L>Turpissime sunt figure,</L>
<L>Et sans ouuraige de nature;</L>
<L>Vnde earum iacture</L>
<L N="96">Plus griefues me sont sans mesure.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="13" TYPE="stanza">
<L>DE quarum turpitudine,</L>
<L>Et du tout mauuaise conuine,</L>
<L>Exaratur in margine,</L>
<L N="100">De ceste voye ou ie chemine,</L>
<L>Non quod alie pagine</L>
<L>D'auctorite saincte et diuine,</L>
<L N="103">Maiores certitudine</L>
<L>N'en contiennent mieulx la doctrine.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="14" TYPE="stanza">
<L>EArum tormentum graue,</L>
<L>Plus assez que cy ne l'agraue</L>
<L>Sustinui / non pro caue</L>
<L N="108">Trahison qui les maulx encaue,</L>
<L>Sepe mihi dicens aue,</L>
<L>Combien qu'elle me fust moult haue,</L>
<L>Me prostrauit ictu claue,</L>
<L N="112">En faisant de moy son espaue.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="15" TYPE="stanza">
<L>GRauiter sic, et nocue,</L>
<L>El m'abatit de sa massue,</L>
<L>Constat ouibus pascue,</L>
<L N="116">Que bien i'ay ma peine perdue,</L>
<L>Et castrum superuacue,</L>
<L>Pour auoir la teste tondue,</L>
<L>Intraui nam precipue;</L>
<L N="120">Mon esperance y est rompue.
<PB REF="00000731.tif" N="623"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="16" TYPE="stanza">
<L>VT seruirem virge iesse,</L>
<L>Me mist grace de dieu en lesse;</L>
<L>Quod fruerer magna messe,</L>
<L N="124">M'acertena par grant promesse;</L>
<L>Sed video nunc expresse,</L>
<L>Dont grande doleur mon cueur presse,</L>
<L>Quod egredi est necesse,</L>
<L N="128">Et ailleurs celebrer ma messe.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="17" TYPE="stanza">
<L>ID, si seruato ordine,</L>
<L>Et bonne paix a marie digne,</L>
<L>De qua, cum moderamine,</L>
<L N="132">A elle plaindre ie me fine.</L>
<L>Potuissem pro nemine</L>
<L>Qui en cestuy monde chemine,</L>
<L>Stetissem tanto turbine,</L>
<L N="136">Demourant hors de discipline.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="18" TYPE="stanza">
<L>LEgatus celi curie</L>
<L><MILESTONE UNIT="Petit folio" N="lxxxv">Pleust a saincte vierge marie,</L>
<L>Quatinus nunc summarie,</L>
<L N="140">Et de plain sans point farderie,</L>
<L>Cognosceret ex serie,</L>
<L>Se ie dy voir ou menterie,</L>
<L>Et quis currentis furie</L>
<L N="144">A punicion demerie.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="19" TYPE="stanza">
<L>EX hoc iustificatiue,</L>
<L>A bon aduis tournant l'estriue,</L>
<L>Deus auctoritatiue</L>
<L N="148">Osteroit tout ce qui estriue;</L>
<L>Impediret causatiue</L>
<L>Sa nef, qu'&agrave; bon port elle n'arriue,</L>
<L>Simul, et miseratiue</L>
<L N="152">Me feroit il grace hastiue.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="20" TYPE="stanza">
<L>VTinam nutu gratie,</L>
<L>Gardienne qu'est de ma vie,</L>
<L>Impetum tante furie,</L>
<L N="156">En memoire ie n'eusse mie;</L>
<L>Sed defectus iusticie,</L>
<L>Qui ou poulce fut endormie</L>
<L>Im cellula memorie,</L>
<L N="160">Trestous les iours Harou i'en crie.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="21" TYPE="stanza">
<L>ILlud nesciens nescire,</L>
<L>A dur colier mon ame tire,</L>
<L>Presertim cum inuenire</L>
<L N="164">Je ne puisse, ou trouueray mire,</L>
<L>Qui iam velit subuenire</L>
<L>A ma playe las qui s'empire</L>
<L>Ex descensu magne ire,</L>
<L N="168">Dont souuent ie ne suis pas sire.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="22" TYPE="stanza">
<L>LVcis creator optime,</L>
<L>Estre vueillez fort anim&eacute;</L>
<L>Succurrendi promptissime</L>
<L N="172">A tel grief dont suis opprim&eacute;!</L>
<L>Et sum certus firmissime,</L>
<L>Se luy est mon fait intim&eacute;,</L>
<L>Michi succurret proxime,</L>
<L N="176">Et sera mon vieil roil lim&eacute;.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="23" TYPE="stanza">
<L>LEgi quodam volumine,</L>
<L>Quant fait est bien examin&eacute;</L>
<L>Justicie libramine,</L>
<L N="180">Qui a tort, est tantost min&eacute;;</L>
<L>Et iustus not redit sine</L>
<L>Honneur, quant le plait est fin&eacute;,</L>
<L>Et iudici sine fine</L>
<L N="184">Est vray salut predestin&eacute;.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="24" TYPE="stanza">
<L>ARbores solis et lune,</L>
<L>Se m'eussent dit quant ie fuz n&eacute;,</L>
<L>Cui casui vel fortune</L>
<L N="188"><MILESTONE UNIT="Petit folio" N="lxxxv:2">Je seroye ioinct et adun&eacute;,</L>
<L>Non dedissem causam prime</L>
<L>Pour ainsi estre destin&eacute;,</L>
<L>Nam semper me trahens fune,</L>
<L N="192">Grande trahison m'a esgrun&eacute;.<NOTE PLACE="foot">The French goes on:&mdash;<Q><LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>OR ai ie dit que vne aduenture</L>
<L>Au chastel ie trouuay moult dure,</L>
<L>Pour le portier qui ne fut pas</L>
<L>A la porte gardant le pas,</L>
<L>Que cestes vieilles n'y entrassent,</L>
<L>Et que leurs chiens n'y amenassent;</L>
<L>Mais pour ce ne doy ie pas taire</L>
<L>Ce que par apres i'en vy faire.</L>
</LG></Q>This French edition was 'corrected' by a Monk of DeGuilleville's monastery, and was printed in or about 1500 by "Maistre Barthole et Jehan petit" (title, last line), and "A paris, Au soleil d'or / en la maison Maistre bertholde" (Fo. j. back, col. 1), as the "Correcteur," P. Virgin, says.<LB>Prof. Paul Meyer refers me to three other Acrostics by DeGuileville on his own name: 1. in <I>Le P&egrave;lerinage de l'Ame</I>, Roxburghe Club, 1895, p. 57-64, in alternate French and Latin lines, beginning<Q><LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Grace Dieu, du ciel royne,</L>
<L>Semper regnans sine fine,</L>
<L>Cognoissant pous et orine,</L>
<L>Et magistra medicine . . .</L>
</LG></Q>and making the writer's name "Guillermus de Guillevilla" as above; 2. in the same volume, an Acrostic in French only, in three separate sections&mdash;the third in but a few MSS.&mdash;p. 348-53, 376-8 (see note, p. 356 there), having the <I>guile</I> with one <I>l</I> only: "Guillermus de Guilevila"; this begins, p. 348:&mdash;<Q><LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Gracieuse est l'assembl&eacute;e</L>
<L>Qui n'est onques dessembl&eacute;e,</L>
<L>Et en rien n'est descordable,</L>
<L>Qui en .iii. est distincter . . .</L>
</LG></Q>3. In the <I>P&egrave;lerinage Jhesucrist</I>, Roxburghe Club, 1897, p. 119-130, in French only. This begins:&mdash;<Q><LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Glorieus Dieu, dont te vint il</L>
<L>Qu'envoias ci aval ton fil,</L>
<L>Et que pelerin le f&euml;is</L>
<L>Bien savoies, qu'en tel courtil,</L>
<L>N'avoit pour li May ne Avril,</L>
<L>Et son soulas point n'i v&euml;is.</L>
</LG></Q>This Acrostic makes the name "Guillermus de Deguilevilla"; but the editor of the Roxburghe volume, the late Prof. St&uuml;rzinger, notes on p. 125 that ten MSS. leave out one couple of the <I>De</I> stanzas, thus reducing the name to "Guillermus de Guilevilla."<LB>I may add here that the prose treatise on the Virgin as the sinner's Refuge from Tribulation, and the Consolation of Afflicted Hearts, p. 437, etc., above, is substituted by Lydgate for about a page of DeGuileville's French verse, Foeillet. lvij., cols. 2-4, which I shall print in the Forewords to this Part II.</NOTE>
</L>
</LG>

</DIV3>
<DIV3 TYPE="pilgrim"><PB REF="00000732.tif" N="624">
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>now I ha told myn &aacute;dventure</L>
<L N="23276">of all that evar I dyd endure,</L>
<L>of Scilla and her hound&euml;s fell,</L>
<L>and eke (as ye ha hard me tell)</L>
<L>of Envy and of Treason,</L>
<L N="23280">and of falce Detract&iuml;on.</L>
<L>how they ha wrought to my hyndrynge</L>
<L>In the absens of the kynge</L>
<L>and of his portar, in sertayne.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="23284">But when they were come home agayne,</L>
<L>and enteryd in-to the castell,</L>
<L>it lyked me ryght wonder well.</L>
<L>a-non I went to his presens,</L>
<L N="23288">and tolde hym of the gret offens</L>
<L>whiche that Scilla with hir hounds</L>
<L>had don to me within his bounds,</L>
<L>by the conspirac&iuml;on</L>
<L N="23292">of Envy and [of] Treason:</L>
<L>my wrong I dyd specifye.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>the kynge a-non let make a crye,</L>
<L>that were-so-evar they myght be</L>
<L N="23296">found in towne or in citie,<MILESTONE UNIT="Stowe folio" N="364a">
<PB REF="00000733.tif" N="625"></L>
<L>that folk&euml; shuld them spar&euml; nought,</L>
<L>to his presens till they were brought.</L>
<L>for he cast hym, anone ryght,</L>
<L N="23300">on them to done iustice and ryght,</L>
<L>that they go no more at large;</L>
<L>and gave his porter eke in charge</L>
<L>forto shette the gat&euml;s sore,</L>
<L N="23304">that they entre there no more,</L>
<L>nor that they have ther no chere.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>and then I saughe a messagere</L>
<L>wher the kynge of custome dwells,</L>
<L N="23308">In the castell ryng&euml; bells,</L>
<L>for to maken &aacute;ssembl&eacute;,</L>
<L>where the kynge set in his se,</L>
<L>of the ladyes that ther dwell,</L>
<L N="23312">(of whome to-forne ye have herd tell,)</L>
<L>that suffred gret oppressyon</L>
<L>of Envy and Detracc&iuml;on,</L>
<L>of Scillas hound&euml;s,<NOTE PLACE="marg">[hounds St.]</NOTE> by berkynge,</L>
<L N="23316">in th[e] absens of the kynge,</L>
<L>of their drede and mortall rage,</L>
<L>wher-of they suffred gret damage.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>'Madams,' quod this messegere,</L>
<L N="23320">'the kynge, most myghty of power,</L>
<L>whiche hathe, in great charitie,</L>
<L>(in effecte, as ye shall se,)</L>
<L>and purposethe in his entent,</L>
<L N="23324">he hathe be longe from yow absent,</L>
<L>(as ye know yowr-selffe full well,)</L>
<L>but of new, to this castell,</L>
<L>he is come for his pleasaunce;</L>
<L N="23328">and he hathe made an ordynaunce</L>
<L>and statut&euml;s full coven&aacute;ble,</L>
<L>to yow echon ryght profytable,</L>
<L>commaundynge yow, echon, in dede,</L>
<L N="23332">that, hens-forthe, ye ha no drede</L>
<L>of your enemys, nor hevynesse,<MILESTONE UNIT="Stowe folio" N="364b"></L>
<L>but that yow do yowr besynesse</L>
<L>(as it is the kyng&euml;s<NOTE PLACE="marg">[kyngs St.]</NOTE> will)</L>
<L N="23336">yowr office truly to fulffyll,
<PB REF="00000734.tif" N="626"></L>
<L>'as ye dyd, when ye began,</L>
<L>and bettar, yf ye bettar can;</L>
<L>for the kynge (as ye shall se)</L>
<L N="23340">will on your foon avengid be:</L>
<L>to yow I ha no more to say.'</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>than the messengar went his way,</L>
<L>and thes ladys, by good advyse,</L>
<L N="23344">full truly dyd theyr offyse,</L>
<L>evereche, lyke to ther degre,</L>
<L>voyde of all contrariouste;</L>
<L>and (shortly for to devyse)</L>
<L N="23348">wher that truth&euml; and iustice</L>
<L>be truly kept in any place,</L>
<L>I dare sayne ther abydythe grace;</L>
<L>And where the gat&euml; is kept well,</L>
<L N="23352">of palays, maner, or castell,</L>
<L>that vycis may ha none entrie,</L>
<L>that place stant in su&euml;rte,</L>
<L>and eche thynge tournethe for the best;</L>
<L N="23356">for, ther is peace, and ther is rest,</L>
<L>and evar gladly, to theyr forthynge,</L>
<L>ther abyte the ryghtffull kynge;</L>
<L>and ther is suraunce &amp; eke trust.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="23360">and afftar this, I had a lust,</L>
<L>cawght in my-selfe a great corage,</L>
<L>for to holden my passage,</L>
<L>and greatly gan my selffe delyght,</L>
<L N="23364">dyvers castells to vysyte,</L>
<L>for to consythar the maner</L>
<L>of euery maner offycer,</L>
<L>How euerych dede in his degre.<NOTE PLACE="marg">[MS. Cott. Vitell. C. xiii,<MILESTONE N="287a" UNIT="folio">, <I>begins again</I>.]</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="23368">and it is good, a man to se</L>
<L>many thyng&euml;s, and to here,</L>
<L>for therby a man may lere<NOTE PLACE="marg">[C. &amp; St.]</NOTE><MILESTONE UNIT="Stowe folio" N="365a"></L>
<L>ful moche thynge outward by syght,<NOTE PLACE="marg">[C. &amp; St.]</NOTE></L>
<L N="23372">and take example to done right.<NOTE PLACE="marg">[C. &amp; St.]</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>And whan I hadde ther-to lycence<NOTE PLACE="marg">[lycens St.]</NOTE></L>
<L>I wente and dede my diligence<NOTE PLACE="marg">[dylygens St.]</NOTE></L>
<L>to visiten, and to se</L>
<L N="23376">ful<NOTE PLACE="marg">[ful <I>om</I>. St.]</NOTE> many wonderful countre.
<PB REF="00000735.tif" N="627"></L>
<L>and ther<NOTE PLACE="marg">[ther St., <I>om</I>. C.]</NOTE> I fond ful gret foysoun</L>
<L>Of many dyuers Religyoun;</L>
<L>and I saugh, of many oon,</L>
<L N="23380">The gret&euml; bond&euml;s euerychon</L>
<L>broke, that shuld hem wel conserve,</L>
<L>yef they wold hem wel observe,</L>
<L>Kepe hem from al aduersite,</L>
<L N="23384">as here-to-forn ye ded&euml; se,</L>
<L>Whan the smale wikres<NOTE PLACE="marg">[wyrks St. (<I>See p</I>. 588, <I>above</I>.)]</NOTE> brak,</L>
<L>The hop&euml;s wenten al to wrak,</L>
<L>And many shippes for lak, allas,</L>
<L N="23388">Was yperysshed<NOTE PLACE="marg">[peryshyd St.]</NOTE> in the same cas,</L>
<L>and brought vnto confus&iuml;oun,</L>
<L>(toforn as is maad<NOTE PLACE="marg">[made is St.]</NOTE> mens&iuml;oun)</L>
<L>for lak in their gouernaunces,</L>
<L N="23392">Nat kepyng their obseruaunces.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>And her-vpon I ferther wente</L>
<L>to sen&euml;<NOTE PLACE="marg">[sene St., sen C.]</NOTE> more (in myn entente).</L>
<L>And withyne a litel space</L>
<L N="23396">I cam into a noble place;</L>
<L>and at the gate I saugh somers;</L>
<L>and on hem sitt&euml;,<NOTE PLACE="marg">[sat St.]</NOTE> fressh of chers,</L>
<L>Aungels, of gret vertu;<NOTE PLACE="marg">[6-<I>syllable line</I>]</NOTE></L>
<L N="23400">and hafter hem, kam Grac&euml; Dieu,</L>
<L>fresshly Ridyng in a char.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>and the gate (I was wel war)</L>
<L>Of the castel stood vnshet.<MILESTONE N="287b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="23404">and tru&euml;ly, whan I had met</L>
<L>the Somers, I gan enquere<NOTE PLACE="marg">[C. &amp; St.]</NOTE></L>
<L>of oon, that he wold[&euml;] lere<NOTE PLACE="marg">[C. &amp; St.]</NOTE></L>
<L>goodly, and inform&euml; me,<NOTE PLACE="marg">[C. &amp; St.]</NOTE><MILESTONE UNIT="Stowe folio" N="365a"></L>
<L N="23408">whos the somers shold&euml;<NOTE PLACE="marg">[shold St.]</NOTE> be,<NOTE PLACE="marg">[C. &amp; St.]</NOTE></L>
<L>Which hadde, vpon hir weye,<NOTE PLACE="marg">[C. &amp; St.]</NOTE></L>
<L>Aungels hem to conveye,<NOTE PLACE="marg">[6-<I>syllable line</I>]</NOTE><NOTE PLACE="marg">[C. &amp; St.]</NOTE></L>
<L>Only for to make hem strong.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>The aungel:</HEAD>
<L N="23412">'To Grace Dieu,' quod he, 'they long.'</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>The pilgrym:</HEAD>
<L>Quod I to oon that rood behynde,</L>
<L>"telle me wher I shal hir fynde."
<PB REF="00000736.tif" N="628"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>The Aungel:<MILESTONE UNIT="Stowe folio" N="365b"></HEAD>
<L>Quod thaungel, 'as it is due,</L>
<L N="23416">her, in hast, she shal vs sue.'<NOTE PLACE="inter">[Blank in MS. for an Illumination.]</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>And in my way so I me bar,</L>
<L>that I fonde hir in hir char;</L>
<L>and a-mong hir folk&euml;s alle,</L>
<L N="23420">benign&euml;ly<NOTE PLACE="marg">[benyngly St., benigly C.]</NOTE> she gan me calle,</L>
<L>and bad I shold ek ha no fere</L>
<L>to tell&euml; what I ded&euml; there.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>The pilgrym:</HEAD>
<L>And I answeryd<NOTE PLACE="marg">[answeryd St., answerd C.]</NOTE> anon ryght,</L>
<L N="23424">how I wente to haue a syght</L>
<L>of sondry castelles (it is no doute,)</L>
<L>that in the countre stood aboute,</L>
<L>and of folk&euml;s gouernaunce,</L>
<L N="23428">that ther abood for her plesaunce.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>Grace dieu:<MILESTONE N="288a" UNIT="folio"></HEAD>
<L>Graciously, y-wys, quod she,</L>
<L>'Now thou hast yfounden me</L>
<L>toforn or that I was ago.</L>
<L N="23432">but (without&euml;<NOTE PLACE="marg">[without C., St.]</NOTE> word&euml;s mo),</L>
<L>come and folwe on after me,</L>
<L>and many thyng&euml;s thou shalt se.'</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>and she ladde me, vp and doun,</L>
<L N="23436">by many diuerse mans&iuml;oun,</L>
<L>In cloystres, as went&euml; tho</L>
<L>Round about, to and fro:<NOTE PLACE="marg">[6-<I>syllable line</I>]</NOTE></L>
<L>ther I saugh vertues and ek vices,</L>
<L N="23440">and many dyuerse edifices.</L>
<L>I saugh ther places ruynous,</L>
<L>and to dwelle in / perillous.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>she shewed me, on our walkyng,</L>
<L N="23444">an old&euml; lady ther haltyng,</L>
<L>and (as by her contenaunce,)</L>
<L>She hadd&euml; ther gret gouernaunce:</L>
<L>she bar a Rewle of a masoun,</L>
<L N="23448">and pleyed by derys&iuml;oun,</L>
<L>and (as I coud&euml; tho espie)</L>
<L>by a maner mokerye.
<PB REF="00000737.tif" N="629"></L>
<L>In hir hand (as I was war)</L>
<L N="23452">a gret&euml;<NOTE PLACE="marg">[gret C., grete St.]</NOTE> spoon also she bar;</L>
<L>and as she reysed it a-lofte,</L>
<L>to hir mouth she putte it ofte.<NOTE PLACE="inter">[Blank in MS. for an Illumination.]</NOTE></L>
<L>And also (as to my reward,)</L>
<L N="23456">hir hed was turned ek bakward,</L>
<L>that toforn (as I ha mynde,)</L>
<L>Was turned and ysette behynde.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>[Grace Dieu]:</HEAD>
<L>Quod Grace dieu a-noon to me,<MILESTONE N="288b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="23460">'at the ey&euml; thou mayst se;</L>
<L>this hous (yef thou canst espye,)</L>
<L>whilom was by masounrye</L>
<L>bilt, and founded spiritually<MILESTONE UNIT="Stowe folio" N="366a"></L>
<L N="23464">by sent Benet, feithfully</L>
<L>by lyne and level of masoun,</L>
<L>thorugh gostly foundac&iuml;oun,</L>
<L>for which, whilom parmanable,</L>
<L N="23468">it was tabid&euml; the mor stable.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>'conceyve also, (by my doctryne,)</L>
<L>thyng that is maad by rule and lyne,</L>
<L>In it self hath more beaute</L>
<L N="23472">tendure, and mor stabilite.</L>
<L>but whan the masoun was agoon,</L>
<L>the rul&euml; wente, and that a-noon,</L>
<L>and the lyn&euml; stood nat faire</L>
<L N="23476">Whan the rul&euml; gan apaire;</L>
<L>and thus the rule, and ek the lyne,</L>
<L>bothe atton&euml;s gan declyne.</L>
<L>and feithfully, in this castel,</L>
<L N="23480">the rul&euml; was nat kept ryght wel;</L>
<L>for, sith the halt held this place,<NOTE PLACE="marg">[<I>See</I> 1. 23,444]</NOTE></L>
<L>al good rul&euml; gan difface.</L>
<L>of vertu ek she is so bare,</L>
<L N="23484">the edifices to repare;</L>
<L>for the old fundac&iuml;oun,</L>
<L>She hath nat but deris&iuml;oun;</L>
<L>She reccheth nat what-euere falle;</L>
<L N="23488">thaugh the stoon&euml;s fallen alle,
<PB REF="00000738.tif" N="630"></L>
<L>'of vertu, bilden in the place;</L>
<L>for, save to play and to solace,</L>
<L>I dar sey she, in hir werkyng,</L>
<L N="23492">Intendeth to noon other thyng.'<NOTE PLACE="marg">[St. &amp; C.]</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>The Pylgrym:</HEAD>
<L>"Ma dame," quod I, "to my semyng,<MILESTONE N="289a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>this plac&euml; first, in his bildyng,</L>
<L>(Who consydereth euerydel)</L>
<L N="23496">the masounry was nat maad wel,</L>
<L>Was not duely maad, nor stable,</L>
<L>Sith it is not parmanable."</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>Grace Dieu:<NOTE PLACE="marg">[St., <I>om</I>. C.]</NOTE></HEAD>
<L>'Touchyng the bildyng, tak good heed:</L>
<L N="23500">the masounry, (it is no dreed,)</L>
<L>I dar ful wel thy-self assure,</L>
<L>it was maad for to endure,</L>
<L>and to haue last<NOTE PLACE="marg">[lust C., last St.]</NOTE> for many yer,</L>
<L N="23504">Save oonly the morter</L>
<L>Was not iustly (as I ha sayd)</L>
<L>stably among the stoon&euml;s layd,</L>
<L>ffounded vpon true entent</L>
<L N="23508">more stedfastly than is cyment.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>'It was first maad of orisouns,</L>
<L>of fastyng and afflicc&iuml;ouns,</L>
<L>to holde the cloystre round about</L>
<L N="23512">by stablenesse, and not gon out</L>
<L>into the world, vagabound,<MILESTONE UNIT="Stowe folio" N="366b"></L>
<L>the edifices to confound;</L>
<L>but in their cloystres stille abyde</L>
<L N="23516">in mek&euml;nesse, and not in pryde,</L>
<L>Haue their frequentac&iuml;ouns</L>
<L>in pray&euml;r and in orisouns;</L>
<L>erly on morwen to aryse,</L>
<L N="23520">in vertu to haue excercyse;</L>
<L>and at fest&euml;s more and lasse,</L>
<L>oft&euml; tym&euml;s syng&euml; masse.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>'this was whilom, (I you ensure,)</L>
<L N="23524">of their morter, the temprure,</L>
<L>founded vppon charyte,</L>
<L>on concord and fraternyte,
<PB REF="00000739.tif" N="631"></L>
<L>'In love and in perfecc&iuml;oun,</L>
<L N="23528">Voyde of al devis&iuml;oun,<MILESTONE N="289b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>In parfit pes and vnyte</L>
<L>of high and lowe in their degre,</L>
<L>for love only of crist ihesu.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="23532">'And yef the morter, in his vertu,</L>
<L>had abide in stabilnesse,</L>
<L>Withouten eny doublenesse,</L>
<L>Lich the first fundac&iuml;oun,</L>
<L N="23536">The werk&euml;<NOTE PLACE="marg">[werk C., worke St.]</NOTE> nad not falle a-doun,</L>
<L>but stable stonde in his degre.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>'and now, echon ha liberte,</L>
<L>at &thorn;eir lust, to slepe and wake;</L>
<L N="23540">and noon other hed<NOTE PLACE="marg">[heode St.]</NOTE> ne take</L>
<L>forto kepe their &oacute;bseruaunce:</L>
<L>and thus, for lak of gouernaunce,</L>
<L>Pes from hem, and vnyte,</L>
<L N="23544">Exil&euml;d is, and charyte.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>'th&aacute;t whilom gaff drynke and foode,</L>
<L>and vnto pore their lyv&euml;loode,</L>
<L>oonly of mercy and pyte,</L>
<L N="23548">and, held hospitalyte;</L>
<L>and, of euery manere age,</L>
<L>gaf to pore folk herbegage,</L>
<L>such as thei seyen, in distresse,</L>
<L N="23552">in myschif, and in Seknesse.'</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>Pilgrim:<NOTE PLACE="marg">[St., <I>om</I>. C.]</NOTE></HEAD>
<L>"Ma dame (and ye list take hede,)</L>
<L>Who hath nought, (it is no drede,)</L>
<L>may not parten his Almesse</L>
<L N="23556">to folk that Leven in distresse."</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>Grace Dieu:<NOTE PLACE="marg">[St., <I>om</I>. C.]</NOTE></HEAD>
<L>'Thow seyst soth, (as thynketh me,)</L>
<L>but wher thou leggest pouerte,</L>
<L>whilom thei had suffisaunce,</L>
<L N="23560">plente ynowh, and h&aacute;bundaunce,</L>
<L>whan thei worsheped in special<MILESTONE UNIT="Stowe folio" N="367a"></L>
<L>The myghty kyng that gaf hem al<MILESTONE N="290a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>suffisaunce in euery lond;<NOTE PLACE="marg">[land . . .hand St.]</NOTE></L>
<L N="23564">but now he hath withdrawe his hond<NOTE PLACE="marg">[land . . .hand St.]</NOTE>
<PB REF="00000740.tif" N="632"></L>
<L>'for their offences; this the fyn:</L>
<L>ther good&euml;s drawen to declyn;</L>
<L>for thei be Rekles of livyng</L>
<L N="23568">forto serue that noble kyng;</L>
<L>and, for slouth and necligence,</L>
<L>they doon in o thyng gret offence.</L>
<L>ffor wher the lord (in his degre)</L>
<L N="23572">Duely shuld honnour&euml;d<NOTE PLACE="marg">[honoryd shuld St.]</NOTE> be,</L>
<L>the place is not, with diligence,</L>
<L>Clenly kept with reuerence;</L>
<L>for beforn, and ek behynde,</L>
<L N="23576">Yraynes and webb&euml;s men may fynde;</L>
<L>and also ek, (yef thou take hede,)</L>
<L>Swalwes and othre brydd&euml;s brede;</L>
<L>and also ek (through al their boundes)</L>
<L N="23580">dong of dogg&euml;s and ek of houndes,</L>
<L>nettles and wed&euml;s round aboute,</L>
<L>in cymyterys ful gret route,</L>
<L>lich a disert or places<NOTE PLACE="marg">[place St.]</NOTE> wilde,</L>
<L N="23584">wher no man hath lust to bilde,</L>
<L>Replevissh&euml;d of al ordure,</L>
<L>as it were withouten cure;</L>
<L>and many oother dishonest&euml;s,</L>
<L N="23588">bestial in ther degres,</L>
<L>mor than I can here devyse.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>'&aacute;nd crist ihesus dede iustyse</L>
<L>on hem that in the temple solde:</L>
<L N="23592">becaus&euml; oonly thei were bolde</L>
<L>to done dishonnour to his hous,</L>
<L>he was in party Regerous,</L>
<L>As the gospel kan you telle;</L>
<L N="23596">he bett hem out with a flagelle,</L>
<L>That noon of hem durst abyde.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>'Wherfore this halte that here is guyde,<MILESTONE N="290b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>list nat, of hir frowardnesse,</L>
<L N="23600">such&euml;<NOTE PLACE="marg">[suche St., such C.]</NOTE> thyng&euml;s to redresse,</L>
<L>nor do seruyse in hir werkyng</L>
<L>for tentende vpon the kyng:</L>
<L>her look, hir cher, (as ye may se,)</L>
<L N="23604">is vpon worldly vanyte,
<PB REF="00000741.tif" N="633"></L>
<L>'and al hir hertes besynesse,</L>
<L>rather than on holynesse;</L>
<L>for which the kyng (iustly and wel,</L>
<L N="23608">that considereth euerydel)<MILESTONE UNIT="Stowe folio" N="367b"></L>
<L>hem to quyt&euml; wil not cesse,</L>
<L>maketh their good&euml;s to discresse;</L>
<L>and, for their pompe and their pryde,</L>
<L N="23612">Set her Richesse out a-syde,</L>
<L>&aacute;menusyng their substance,</L>
<L>their tresour and their h&aacute;bundance,</L>
<L>Which made hem first their<NOTE PLACE="marg">[theyr St., the C.]</NOTE> lord forsake.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="23616">'therfore he can it fro hem take</L>
<L>Whan-euere he list, who lok&euml; wel;</L>
<L>ffor the Prophete Ezechel<NOTE PLACE="marg">[ezechiell St.]</NOTE></L>
<L>Writeth, (who so taketh hede)</L>
<L N="23620">Idelnesse, plente of bred,</L>
<L>caused (in conclus&iuml;oun)</L>
<L>of Sodom the distrucc&iuml;oun.'</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>Pilgrim:<NOTE PLACE="marg">[St., <I>om</I>. C.]</NOTE></HEAD>
<L>"I pray yov, telle on a-noon ryght,</L>
<L N="23624">She that halteth in my syght,</L>
<L>What is hir name, and hir offys,</L>
<L>of whom ye sette<NOTE PLACE="marg">[is set St.]</NOTE> so litel prys?"</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>Grace Dieu:<NOTE PLACE="marg">[St., <I>om</I>. C.]</NOTE></HEAD>
<L>'To make a playn discripc&iuml;oun,</L>
<L N="23628">She is called 'Abus&iuml;oun,'</L>
<L>because, the good that god hath sent,</L>
<L>by hir thei ben wrongly dispent,<NOTE PLACE="marg">[spent St.]</NOTE></L>
<L>And ageyn his wul<NOTE PLACE="marg">[will St.]</NOTE> abused;</L>
<L N="23632">Wherof she may nat ben excused.<MILESTONE N="291a" UNIT="folio"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>'She halt a rule of a masoun,</L>
<L>only by fals collus&iuml;oun;</L>
<L>for, to the rule that she is bounde,</L>
<L>(Whan the trouth is sough[t]<NOTE PLACE="marg">[known St.]</NOTE> <I>and</I> founde,</L>
<L N="23637">Therto she haveth no reward,)</L>
<L>Hir hed ytourned is bakward;</L>
<L>Vnto the world she cast hir look,</L>
<L N="23640">Wich, vnder colour, she forsook.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>'hir spon also doth signefye</L>
<L>the foul&euml; vice of Glotonye,
<PB REF="00000742.tif" N="634"></L>
<L>'for, ageyn ryght and al Resoun,</L>
<L N="23644">by force and vsurpac&iuml;oun,</L>
<L>she hath forsake the vnyte</L>
<L>of fraternal antiquyte,</L>
<L>by perfecc&iuml;oun to contune</L>
<L N="23648">to haue hir good&euml;s in comune.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>'but this fals Abus&iuml;oun,</L>
<L>only by vsurpacioun</L>
<L>In Religioun (who list se),</L>
<L N="23652">fonde out the vice of propurte,</L>
<L>Which is thyng most vic&iuml;ous,</L>
<L>rennyng among relig&iuml;ous,<MILESTONE UNIT="Stowe folio" N="368a"></L>
<L>Which causeth ofte discord and stryf,</L>
<L N="23656">contrary to Thapostles lyf.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>'In propurte (ye may ther rede)</L>
<L>thei ne dide nothyng possede;</L>
<L>her good was comoun, in certeyn.</L>
<L N="23660">Wherfore the Spon that thou hast seyn</L>
<L>ys callede 'Syngularyte,'</L>
<L>thyng to possede in propurte;</L>
<L>to gedre the fatt&euml; (thus I mene,)</L>
<L N="23664">vnto hir self, and leve the lene:</L>
<L>As the Prophete Ezechiel,</L>
<L>to the sheperdes of Israel</L>
<L>Spak and wrot, ful yore a-go:</L>
<L N="23668">'Sorwe be to you, and wo,<MILESTONE N="291b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>that ne take to nothyng hede,</L>
<L>but your silven<NOTE PLACE="marg">[selvs St.]</NOTE> forto fede;</L>
<L>not lik sheperdes of cristus hous;</L>
<L N="23672">but verray wolv&euml;s Ravinous,</L>
<L>liggyng awayt, bothe nyght and day,</L>
<L>forto devoure what thei may:</L>
<L>they tak&euml; both&euml; mylk and wolle;</L>
<L N="23676">and the fatte, away thei pulle</L>
<L>with the spoon of cruelte</L>
<L>ycalled Syngularyte,</L>
<L>thei Robb&euml; pantener and purs,</L>
<L N="23680">and gete hem oft&euml; Cristes cours.<NOTE PLACE="marg">[curs St.]</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>'ffor which cause, I, Abus&iuml;oun,</L>
<L>&aacute;m come of entenc&iuml;oun
<PB REF="00000743.tif" N="635"></L>
<L>'Such abus&iuml;ouns to se,</L>
<L N="23684">and their superfluyte</L>
<L>to kutte away, which that thei vse,</L>
<L>and their goodes to &aacute;menuse.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>'The Aungels han hem take away,</L>
<L N="23688">Which thou mettest this same day,</L>
<L>With gret&euml; somers in sothnesse,</L>
<L>ledyng away the gret Richesse,</L>
<L>to parte it (of entenc&iuml;oun)</L>
<L N="23692">to folk that in deuoc&iuml;oun</L>
<L>lede her liv&euml;s in comune,</L>
<L>and in deuocioun do contune;</L>
<L>such as in god gretly delyte,</L>
<L N="23696">fro good to bet alway profyte.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>'figure herof, ye may se,</L>
<L>how that by olde Antiquyte,</L>
<L>the bible ful wel can you tel,</L>
<L N="23700">how the childre of Israel</L>
<L>took of Egypt the Tresour</L>
<L>In recompense of her labour.<MILESTONE UNIT="Stowe folio" N="368b"></L>
<L>As for guerdoun, by dw&euml;te</L>
<L N="23704">Whan they passed the red&euml; Se,<MILESTONE N="292a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>they tooke in thyng by Robberye,</L>
<L>as clerk&euml;s list to specifye;</L>
<L>they bar&euml;<NOTE PLACE="marg">[bare St., bar C.]</NOTE> with hem gret substaunce,</L>
<L N="23708">only by Godd&euml;s ordynaunce,</L>
<L>Egipciens (it is no drede)</L>
<L>Were not worthy it to possede.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>'and som folk deme off Resoun,</L>
<L N="23712">that folk that haue possess&iuml;oun,</L>
<L>and ben cursed of livyng,</L>
<L>It is leful (by their demyng)</L>
<L>forto spoylle hem du&euml;ly,</L>
<L N="23716">and yeve it hem that ben worthy.'</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>Pilgrim:<NOTE PLACE="marg">[St., <I>om</I>. C.]</NOTE></HEAD>
<L>Touchyng that oppynyoun,</L>
<L>thus I answerd of Resoun:</L>
<L>"god ne doth nat thus alway,</L>
<L N="23720">who that conceyveth, day by day;</L>
<L>for ther ys many an vsurer
<PB REF="00000744.tif" N="636"></L>
<L>"in dyuers lond&euml;s fer and ner,</L>
<L>that wynn&euml; gold ful cursedly,</L>
<L N="23724">and it possede ful<NOTE PLACE="marg">[ful, <I>om</I>. St.]</NOTE> vnworthily,</L>
<L>how falsly that they come therto;</L>
<L>and god suffreth that it be so;</L>
<L>and yet, to pore they yeve no thyng,</L>
<L N="23728">though they be ryghtful of livyng."</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>Grace Dieu:<NOTE PLACE="marg">[St., <I>om</I>. C.]</NOTE></HEAD>
<L>'As to thy conclus&iuml;oun,</L>
<L>ther is noon soluc&iuml;oun:</L>
<L>god gaf neuere (fer nor ner,)</L>
<L N="23732">licence to noon vsurer,</L>
<L>that he shuld (I the ensure)</L>
<L>ben admytted to fals vsure.</L>
<L>god suffreth hem to han tresour,</L>
<L N="23736">gold, Richesse, and gret honour:</L>
<L>of al the tresour that they weld,</L>
<L>To hym they shal acount&euml;s yeld.<MILESTONE N="292b" UNIT="folio"><NOTE PLACE="marg">[C. &amp; St.]</NOTE></L>
<L>first, they it wan<NOTE PLACE="marg">[yt wan St.]</NOTE> by violence,</L>
<L N="23740">of god hauyng no licence;</L>
<L>wherfor, to their Dampnac&iuml;oun,</L>
<L>he suffreth their pocess&iuml;oun,</L>
<L>as he hadd&euml;<NOTE PLACE="marg">[had C., St.]</NOTE> no reward;</L>
<L N="23744">but he wil punysshe hem afterward,</L>
<L>(though they for a while habound,)</L>
<L>the vice of Vsure to confound.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>'but good&euml;s of relig&iuml;ous,</L>
<L N="23748">that was yeve in-to<NOTE PLACE="marg">[wnto St.]</NOTE> her hous</L>
<L>In ther first foundac&iuml;oun,</L>
<L>their tresour and possess&iuml;oun,</L>
<L>it was yove hem of almesse</L>
<L N="23752">for their gret&euml; perfitnesse,</L>
<L>of entent that, day and nyght,<MILESTONE UNIT="Stowe folio" N="369a"></L>
<L>that they shold, with al their myght,</L>
<L>Worshepe god with grete honours,</L>
<L N="23756">and truely pray for their foundours.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>'and iustly, this condic&iuml;oun</L>
<L>is worth an obligac&iuml;oun.</L>
<L>that<NOTE PLACE="marg">[then St.]</NOTE> whan it falleth their fooly,</L>
<L N="23760">that thei not vs&euml; du&euml;ly
<PB REF="00000745.tif" N="637"></L>
<L>'their offices as thei sholde do,</L>
<L>to kepe ther obseruaunces also</L>
<L>(lich to their profess&iuml;oun)</L>
<L N="23764">in prayer and deuoc&iuml;oun,</L>
<L>god wil, of his ryghtful lawe,</L>
<L>to chastice hem, his hond with-drawe,</L>
<L>suffre her good&euml;s to vnthryve,</L>
<L N="23768">but if thei amende hem blive;</L>
<L>yive it to hem that wil hym serue,</L>
<L>and his comand&euml;mentes obserue.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>'herof ye may sen a figure</L>
<L N="23772">fful wel rehersed in scripture:</L>
<L>In Egipt whilom, how it fel,</L>
<L>Whan the childre of Israel<MILESTONE N="293a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Wher<NOTE PLACE="marg">[were St.]</NOTE> ther in subiecc&iuml;oun</L>
<L N="23776">al that ilk&euml; regioun;</L>
<L>thorugh their travaill and labour,</L>
<L>was maad ryche of gret tresour;</L>
<L>but afterward (as ye may se)</L>
<L N="23780">Vij yeres of Sterylite</L>
<L>folwed on, (as ye may red,)</L>
<L>wherof Ioseph took good hed</L>
<L>long a-forn, of high prudence;</L>
<L N="23784">and &thorn;augh his noble providence,</L>
<L>Ageyn the hunger, Ech&euml; syde,<NOTE PLACE="marg">[eche syde St., ech a syde C.]</NOTE></L>
<L>ful prudently gan to provide,</L>
<L>and shop ther-fore a remedye,</L>
<L N="23788">(as Genesis doth specifye;)</L>
<L>for, thorugh the myght of godd&euml;s hond,</L>
<L>he sustened al the lond</L>
<L>from hunger and aduersite,</L>
<L N="23792">The vij yer of Sterilite.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>'but of al this gret&euml; dede,</L>
<L>thei of Egipt took non hede,</L>
<L>to thanken (in especial)</L>
<L N="23796">the myghti lord that gaf hem al;</L>
<L>nor wolde suffre, in no wyse,</L>
<L>Israel do sacrifyse;</L>
<L>but held in subiecc&iuml;oun,</L>
<L N="23800">out of the lond of promyssioun.
<PB REF="00000746.tif" N="638"></L>
<L>'wherfore, merveille neuere a del,</L>
<L>thaugh god suffred Israel,</L>
<L>oonly of his ryghtwesnesse,</L>
<L N="23804">to robben hem of their Richesse,</L>
<L>and spoylen hem of their Tresour.<MILESTONE UNIT="Stowe folio" N="369b"></L>
<L>god gaf it hem for their labour,</L>
<L>And as for a mede in guerdoun,</L>
<L N="23808">Departyng from that Regioun.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>'They hadde disserued it of yore,</L>
<L>by gret labour that sat hem sore,<MILESTONE N="293b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>thorugh c&oacute;nstreynt of Kyng Pharao,</L>
<L N="23812">which wolde not suffren hem to go,</L>
<L>Nor to departe in rest and pes,</L>
<L>for no massage of Moyses;<NOTE PLACE="marg">[message off mosese St.]</NOTE></L>
<L>but put hem euere in delay,</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="23816">'and thus the lord can take a-way</L>
<L>Richesse of folk&euml;s vic&iuml;ous,<NOTE PLACE="marg">[C. &amp; St.]</NOTE></L>
<L>and yive it hem that be vertuous;<NOTE PLACE="marg">[C. &amp; St.]</NOTE></L>
<L>As he hath done here in this place:</L>
<L N="23820">thou mayst beholde it with thy face.'</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>Pilgrim:<NOTE PLACE="marg">[St., <I>om</I>. C.]</NOTE></HEAD>
<L>"Certes," quod I with hevy cher,</L>
<L>"In other places mo than her</L>
<L>(to tell&euml; shortly, and not tarye)</L>
<L N="23824">I ha beholde the contrary,</L>
<L>wher folk, by gret deuoc&iuml;oun,</L>
<L>han kept their relig&iuml;oun</L>
<L>ful streytly, in gret honeste,</L>
<L N="23828">that han falle in pouerte,</L>
<L>bothe of liflood and vesture,</L>
<L>that thei myght&euml;<NOTE PLACE="marg">[myght C., St.]</NOTE> nat endure,</L>
<L>Mischef hath hem brought so lowe.</L>
<L N="23832">and fayn I wold the caus&euml; knowe,</L>
<L>why god wil suffre their grevaunce,</L>
<L>forto lakke their suffisaunce."</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>Grace Dieu:<NOTE PLACE="marg">[St., <I>om</I>. C.]</NOTE></HEAD>
<L>Quod Grace Dieu a-noon to me,</L>
<L N="23836">'I wil herof answere the,</L>
<L>and make therof no gret delay;</L>
<L>but her cometh oon nov in our way,
<PB REF="00000747.tif" N="639"></L>
<L>'and I wil first, of good resoun,</L>
<L N="23840">knowen his entenc&iuml;oun;</L>
<L>or go thy self, by my biddyng,</L>
<L>And axe the cause of his comyng.'</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>And sodeynly, good hede I took;<MILESTONE N="294a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="23844">and cast on syde on hym my look,</L>
<L>which, lich a dwerf, (this the caas,)</L>
<L>of his fetures shapen was.</L>
<L>a pyk of Iren, sharp and longe,</L>
<L N="23848">he held, that was of makyng strong.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>Pilgrim:<NOTE PLACE="marg">[Blank in MS. for an Illumination.]</NOTE></HEAD>
<L>And to me-ward his look he layde.<NOTE PLACE="marg">[St., <I>om</I>. C.]</NOTE></L>
<L>but first, to hym ryght thus I sayde.</L>
<L>"Telle on, thou dwerf, (ha no shame,)</L>
<L N="23852">To vs, thyn office and thy name."</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>Sterelite:<NOTE PLACE="marg">[St., <I>om</I>. C.]</NOTE></HEAD>
<L>'I called am (yef thou list se)</L>
<L>Of folk&euml;s alle, 'Sterility,'<MILESTONE UNIT="Stowe folio" N="370a"></L>
<L>which ha this hous maad ful bareyn,</L>
<L N="23856">bothe of frut and ek of greyn.</L>
<L>Ther good, their lond, (yef it be sought,)</L>
<L>I ha distruyed and brought to nought:</L>
<L>This my craft and myn offys;</L>
<L N="23860">and therfor (by gret avys)</L>
<L>to cast&euml; folk in pouerte,</L>
<L>I am called 'Sterilite;'</L>
<L>foul and ougly of look and cher:</L>
<L N="23864">In Egypt I dwell&euml;d vij yer.</L>
<L>wher I abyde, (be wel certeyn,)</L>
<L>I make the land to be bareyn.'</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>Grace Dieu:<NOTE PLACE="marg">[St., <I>om</I>. C.]</NOTE></HEAD>
<L>Quod Grac&euml; Dieu, 'a litel space,</L>
<L N="23868">Go thy way out of this place;</L>
<L>and what-so-euere herafter falle,</L>
<L>whan me list, I shal the calle.'</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>And whan that tourned was his bak,<MILESTONE N="291b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="23872">Grac&euml; dieu thus to me spak:</L>
<L>'touchyng the good&euml;s, day be day,</L>
<L>which that I ha take away</L>
<L>fro this plac&euml; here present,
<PB REF="00000748.tif" N="640"></L>
<L N="23876">'I dide [it] oonly of entent</L>
<L>that other folk shold it possede,</L>
<L>which (bothe in wark and ek in dede,)</L>
<L>lede her lyf in perfitnesse,</L>
<L N="23880">In vertu, and more holynesse</L>
<L>than thei which that her now be.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>'and touchyng that thou askest me,</L>
<L>Thou shalt haue answere therof noon.</L>
<L N="23884">but first, I charg&euml; the to goon</L>
<L>to hir that is the Selerere</L>
<L>of this place that stondeth here;</L>
<L>aske hir (that thou mayst conceyve)</L>
<L N="23888">touchyng the good she doth receyve,</L>
<L>to telle the playnly al the guyse,</L>
<L>how it is spent, and in what wyse.</L>
<L>and, hir to knowe among hem alle,</L>
<L N="23892">'Purveyaunc&euml;' folk hir calle.</L>
<L>and whan she hath declared al,</L>
<L>thou shalt haue (in spec&iuml;al)</L>
<L>of the demaunde (by good resoun)</L>
<L N="23896">a tru&euml; Declarac&iuml;oun,</L>
<L>as it accordeth and is dwe.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>'and forth my Somers I wil swe;</L>
<L>for, in this place, on no syde,</L>
<L N="23900">I caste me no lenger to abyde;</L>
<L>nor neuere (to speke in word&euml;s playn)</L>
<L>hider<NOTE PLACE="marg">[hethar St.]</NOTE> to retourne agayn,</L>
<L>til the tyme that I may se</L>
<L N="23904">that vertu and honeste<MILESTONE UNIT="Stowe folio" N="370b"></L>
<L>Resort&euml; by deuoc&iuml;oun</L>
<L>Into thys Relig&iuml;oun.'</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>And with that word, (as I was war,)<MILESTONE N="295a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="23908">I saugh hir gon in-to hir char.</L>
<L>and in this while (of good entent,</L>
<L>lich to hir comand&euml;ment)</L>
<L>I went&euml; with a sobre chere,</L>
<L N="23912">forth vnto the celere[re].</L>
<L>and, my iourne to avaunce,</L>
<L>I knewe<NOTE PLACE="marg">[knew St., knowe C.]</NOTE> hir by hir contenaunce;</L>
<L>for (the trouth&euml;<NOTE PLACE="marg">[trouth C.]</NOTE> to expresse)
<PB REF="00000749.tif" N="641"></L>
<L N="23916">She was of gret sobrenesse,</L>
<L>of gret reuerence and honeste,</L>
<L>and of gret maturyte;</L>
<L>saad of look, and ek of cher,</L>
<L N="23920">Egle-ey&euml;d, bryght and cler.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>[The Pilgrim]:</HEAD>
<L>"Ma dame," quod I, "of good entent,</L>
<L>Grac&euml; Dieu hath to you sent,</L>
<L N="23923">that ye sholde (in word&euml;s fewe)</L>
<L>the playn&euml; trouth&euml;<NOTE PLACE="marg">[playn trouth C., playn truthe St.]</NOTE> to me shewe,</L>
<L>wher ye putt&euml; the rychesse</L>
<L>that ye receyve, in sothfastnesse."</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>Celerar:<NOTE PLACE="marg">[St., after l. 23928, <I>om</I>. C.]</NOTE></HEAD>
<L>And she that spak no word in vyyn,</L>
<L N="23928">to me answerd thus agayn;</L>
<L>'al that I haue in my depos,</L>
<L>from hir ther shal nothyng be clos.</L>
<L>Kome forth in hast, and folwe me,</L>
<L N="23932">and thou shalt the trouth&euml;<NOTE PLACE="marg">[trouth C., truthe St.]</NOTE> se.'</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>and I cam after (for the best),</L>
<L>and she gan vnlokke a chest,</L>
<L>the which&euml;,<NOTE PLACE="marg">[whiche St., which C.]</NOTE> whan I ded&euml; se,</L>
<L N="23936">I gan gretly abassh&euml; me,</L>
<L>for the huchche (it is no doute)</L>
<L>was ful of hol&euml;s round aboute;</L>
<L>and at ech hole (as thought&euml;<NOTE PLACE="marg">[thought C., thowght St.]</NOTE> me)</L>
<L N="23940">an hand put out, I did&euml; se,</L>
<L>(who<NOTE PLACE="marg">[wher C., who St.]</NOTE>-so euere slepe or wake)<MILESTONE N="295b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Redy to receyve and<NOTE PLACE="marg">[and St., and to C.]</NOTE> take.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>Pilgrim:<NOTE PLACE="marg">[St., <I>om</I>. C.]</NOTE><NOTE PLACE="marg">[Blank for Illumination.]</NOTE></HEAD>
<L>I pray&euml;d her, to specifye</L>
<L N="23944">what thyng it ded&euml; signefye.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>Celerar:<NOTE PLACE="marg">[St., <I>om</I>. C.]</NOTE></HEAD>
<L>'To telle, and voiden al deceyt,</L>
<L>this the place of the receyt</L>
<L>of good&euml;s, which that, day and nyght,</L>
<L N="23948">kome to this place of verray ryght,</L>
<L>(forto speke in general,)</L>
<L>but this handes consumen al,</L>
<L>Spende and waste on euery syde,<MILESTONE UNIT="Stowe folio" N="371a">
<PB REF="00000750.tif" N="642"></L>
<L N="23952">'that ther may no thyng abyde,</L>
<L>for to depart&euml; by almesse</L>
<L>to folk that liven in distresse.'</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>Pilgrim:<NOTE PLACE="marg">[St., <I>om</I>. C.]</NOTE></HEAD>
<L>"Ma dame," quod I, "as semeth me,</L>
<L N="23956">ye sholde, of ryght and equyte,</L>
<L>The hand&euml;s kerve, and kutte away,</L>
<L>and stoppe the hol&euml;s nyght and day."</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>Provide[n]s Celerar:<NOTE PLACE="marg">[St., <I>om</I>. C.]</NOTE></HEAD>
<L>Quod Providence anoon to me,</L>
<L N="23960">'Thes, ben the hand&euml;s thre,<NOTE PLACE="marg">[6-<I>syllable line</I>]</NOTE></L>
<L>which that thev&euml;s (by assent)</L>
<L>ar wont to vsen (of entent),</L>
<L>I men&euml;, pyratys of the Se,</L>
<L N="23964">which bryng&euml; folk in pouerte.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>'The first hand of all&euml; thre,</L>
<L>ys called (lern&euml; this of me,)</L>
<L>'the hand of Dym&euml;s,' by gadryng,</L>
<L N="23968">To gadre vp dym&euml;s for the kyng.<MILESTONE N="296a" UNIT="folio"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>'the tother hand, ful sor&euml; pulles</L>
<L>gold for trentals and for bulles,</L>
<L>and dyuers subuenc&iuml;ouns</L>
<L N="23972">and grevous contribuc&iuml;ouns,</L>
<L>graunted (in espec&iuml;al)</L>
<L>at Chipytres<NOTE PLACE="marg">[chapters St.]</NOTE> general.</L>
<L>the hand&euml;s do no thyng, nor werche,</L>
<L N="23976">but waste the good of holy cherche.'</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>Pilgrim:<NOTE PLACE="marg">[St., <I>om</I>. C.]</NOTE></HEAD>
<L>"What hand is that (telle on, let Se,)</L>
<L>Which hath an Eye (as thynketh me,)</L>
<L>Sett in the mydd&euml;s of the hand?</L>
<L N="23980">for I saugh neuere (on Se nor land)</L>
<L>Such another her-toforn,</L>
<L>Sith the tyme that I was born."</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>Providens:<NOTE PLACE="marg">[St., <I>om</I>. C.]</NOTE></HEAD>
<L>'Be nat astonyed, neuere a del!</L>
<L N="23984">this hand is (who so lok&euml; wel,)</L>
<L>of our noble Visitour,</L>
<L>Which doth his peyne and his labour</L>
<L>to looke for lucre and fals guerdoun,
<PB REF="00000751.tif" N="643"></L>
<L N="23988">'alway, for retribuc&iuml;oun,</L>
<L>they caste her ey&euml; for wynnyng,</L>
<L>and, ryght nought for &aacute;mendyng;</L>
<L>take (in their entenc&iuml;ouns,)</L>
<L N="23992">pans for<NOTE PLACE="marg">[and St.]</NOTE> procurac&iuml;ouns.</L>
<L>ther entent, in no wyse,<NOTE PLACE="marg">[6-<I>syllable line</I>]</NOTE></L>
<L>ys sett on ryght nor on iustice.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>'ek other hand&euml;s, mo than thre,</L>
<L N="23996">han cast vs in gret pouerte.'</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>[The Pilgrim:]</HEAD>
<L>With that word, makyng no delay,</L>
<L>I took my leve and wente away.<NOTE PLACE="marg">[my way St.]</NOTE><MILESTONE UNIT="Stowe folio" N="371b"></L>
<L>I hadde no leve, (shortly to telle,)</L>
<L N="24000">but shop me hom to my castel.</L>
<L>And on my way&euml;,<NOTE PLACE="marg">[way C., St.]</NOTE> me be-fel,<NOTE PLACE="inter">[No gap in either MS.]</NOTE></L>
<L>I mette an olde oon in that tyde,<MILESTONE N="296b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="24004">that to me kam on the left syde,</L>
<L>Of whos look I was affrayed:</L>
<L>hir hand&euml;s partid, and displayed</L>
<L>vpward to a castel wal,</L>
<L N="24008">resemblyng (as me thought in al)</L>
<L>That hir entent was to ascende</L>
<L>vpon the wal, or to descende.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>a blak Ravoun<NOTE PLACE="marg">[ravyn St.]</NOTE> (it is no doute,)</L>
<L N="24012">took his flyght ful round aboute,</L>
<L>Wher-so-euere that she went.</L>
<L>and I knewh nothyng what it ment;<NOTE PLACE="inter">[Blank in MS. for an Illumination.]</NOTE></L>
<L>But I caste, withynne a throwe,</L>
<L N="24016">playnly that I wold&euml;<NOTE PLACE="marg">[wold C., would St.]</NOTE> knowe,</L>
<L>of al thys thyng som evidence;</L>
<L>and wente a-noon to hir presence.</L>
<L>and first of al, I gan enquere,</L>
<L N="24020">to telle me what she did&euml; there;</L>
<L>of name and of condic&iuml;oun</L>
<L>Make a declarac&iuml;oun.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>Apostacye:<NOTE PLACE="marg">[St., <I>om</I>. C.]</NOTE></HEAD>
<L>Quod she, 'yef thou konne espye,</L>
<L N="24024">I am called 'Apostacye,'
<PB REF="00000752.tif" N="644"></L>
<L>'which whilom, of entenc&iuml;oun,</L>
<L>mad&euml; my profess&iuml;oun,</L>
<L>In al my best&euml;<NOTE PLACE="marg">[best C., St.]</NOTE> feythful wyse,</L>
<L N="24028">for to ha do<NOTE PLACE="marg">[done St.]</NOTE> truely seruyse</L>
<L>duryng my lif, vnto the kyng</L>
<L>that is most myghty of werkyng.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="24031">'I sette myn hand vnto the plough;<NOTE PLACE="marg">[plughe St.]</NOTE></L>
<L>But I haue hym falsed ynough,<NOTE PLACE="marg">[ynughe St., nough C.]</NOTE><MILESTONE N="297a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>tourned the bak (as thou mayst se)</L>
<L>vnto wordly<NOTE PLACE="marg">[worldly St.]</NOTE> vanyte,</L>
<L>left myn homage, trouth and al,</L>
<L N="24036">and am kome doun ouere the wal</L>
<L>for vayn glorie (out of doute);</L>
<L>In many countre roune<NOTE PLACE="marg">[round St.]</NOTE> aboute,</L>
<L>of entent, for to purchaas</L>
<L N="24040">prosperite and vayn solas.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>'and yet ful ofte (in many caas,)</L>
<L>myn entent and purpos was,</L>
<L>fro worldly glorie, fals and vayn,</L>
<L N="24044">to haue tourned hom<NOTE PLACE="marg">[? MS., hem C., them St.]</NOTE> agayn,</L>
<L>and amended my livyng</L>
<L>In the seruyse of the kyng;</L>
<L>but truely (it is no nay)<MILESTONE UNIT="Stowe folio" N="372a"></L>
<L N="24048">the Ravoun<NOTE PLACE="marg">[raven St.]</NOTE> was euere in my way.'</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>Pilgrim:<NOTE PLACE="marg">[St., <I>om</I>. C.]</NOTE></HEAD>
<L>"Truely, and thou dedest wel,</L>
<L>thou sholdest lette neuere a del</L>
<L>for to delay&euml; so thy paas.</L>
<L N="24052">thaugh that he crye on th&eacute;, 'cras, cras,'</L>
<L>thou sholdest<NOTE PLACE="marg">[shulst St.]</NOTE> remembre th&eacute; among,</L>
<L>and take noon hede vnto his song."</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>Apostasie:<NOTE PLACE="marg">[St., <I>om</I>. C.]</NOTE></HEAD>
<L>'The trouth&euml;<NOTE PLACE="marg">[trouth C., truthe St.]</NOTE> forto specifye,</L>
<L N="24056">I folwe, in<NOTE PLACE="marg">[in, <I>om</I>. St.]</NOTE> myn Apostasye,</L>
<L>In my passage vp and doun,</L>
<L>the Raven&euml;s condic&iuml;oun,</L>
<L>that whilom was of Noe sent</L>
<L N="24060">out of the ark&euml;, of entent</L>
<L>to beholden how it stood,</L>
<L>of the deluge and the flood
<PB REF="00000753.tif" N="645"></L>
<L>'boyllyng with many sturdy wawe;</L>
<L N="24064">Wher the water gan withdrawe.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>'but the Raven fond a kareyn;</L>
<L>therfore he cam not agayn.<MILESTONE N="297b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>and I stonde in the sam&euml; caas,</L>
<L N="24068">abyde, and synge alway 'cras, cras,'<NOTE PLACE="marg">[C. &amp; St.]</NOTE></L>
<L>makyng many fals delayes,<NOTE PLACE="marg">[C. &amp; St.]</NOTE></L>
<L>and prolong&euml; forth my dayes,<NOTE PLACE="marg">[C. &amp; St.]</NOTE></L>
<L>forto Resorten hom ageyn,</L>
<L N="24072">and spend&euml;<NOTE PLACE="marg">[spend C.]</NOTE> thus my tyme in veyn.'</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>Pilgrim:<NOTE PLACE="marg">[St., <I>om</I>. C.]</NOTE></HEAD>
<L>"Thy werk&euml;s (yef I shal not tarye)</L>
<L>ben vnhappy and contr&aacute;rye;</L>
<L>and thyn hand&euml;s, both&euml; two,</L>
<L N="24076">ben yperced &thorn;orugh also.</L>
<L>greyn nor frut, vpon no syde,</L>
<L>In no wys&euml; wyl abyde;</L>
<L>for shortly (who so list to sek)</L>
<L N="24080">al goth thorugh, and wasteth ek.<NOTE PLACE="marg">[seke . . eke St.]</NOTE></L>
<L>Who-so-euere the trouthe atame,</L>
<L>thy tonge is dampned, and ek lame,</L>
<L>that it may seyn noon orisoun,</L>
<L N="24084">nor make no supplicac&iuml;oun,</L>
<L>Which shold&euml; ben acceptable</L>
<L>vnto that kyng most honourable.</L>
<L>he is not plesed, (on noo syde,)</L>
<L N="24088">Whil in this staat thou dost abyde,</L>
<L>and hast no purpos to Retourne,<NOTE PLACE="marg">[for to tourn St.]</NOTE></L>
<L>but in the world dost ay soiourne."</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>Apostacie:<NOTE PLACE="marg">[St., <I>om</I>. C.]</NOTE></HEAD>
<L>'Tru&euml;ly, to thy sentence</L>
<L N="24092">I may yev&euml; ful credence;</L>
<L>for Seynt Poule hym-silf&euml;<NOTE PLACE="marg">[selfe St., silf C.]</NOTE> saith,</L>
<L>(to whom, men must yev&euml; fayth,</L>
<L>and ful belev&euml; to his word,)<MILESTONE UNIT="Stowe folio" N="372b"></L>
<L N="24096">'who is not withynne shippes<NOTE PLACE="marg">[syppes St.]</NOTE> bord,</L>
<L>stant in perail of Perysshyng,</L>
<L>and on the poynt of his drownyng,'</L>
<L>fel fer from his savac&iuml;oun,</L>
<L N="24100">ffor lakkyng of discrec&iuml;oun.<MILESTONE N="298a" UNIT="folio">
<PB REF="00000754.tif" N="646"></L>
<L>'and I wot wel, for my partye,</L>
<L>I issed<NOTE PLACE="marg">[yswyd St.]</NOTE> out thorugh my folye;</L>
<L>Wherfore I stonde in nonecerteyn,</L>
<L N="24104">yef I retourned hom ageyn,</L>
<L>wher I shold&euml; grac&euml; haue,</L>
<L>therby my soul&euml; for<NOTE PLACE="marg">[for St., <I>om</I>. C.]</NOTE> to save.'</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>Pilgrim:<NOTE PLACE="marg">[St., <I>om</I>. C.]</NOTE></HEAD>
<L>"ne doute the nat to tourne ageyn,</L>
<L N="24108">but be therof ryght wel certeyn,</L>
<L>That of grace thou shalt not faille,</L>
<L>So that thou mak&euml; a<NOTE PLACE="marg">[a <I>om</I>. St.]</NOTE> stoupaille</L>
<L>of the hool&euml;s that open<NOTE PLACE="marg">[St., apon C.]</NOTE> be</L>
<L N="24112">in thyn handes (as thou maist se),</L>
<L>this to mene, in sentement,</L>
<L>that playn and hool be thyn entent,</L>
<L>grounded on perfecc&iuml;oun;</L>
<L N="24116">and that, by gret deuoc&iuml;oun,</L>
<L>that thou make thyn hert&euml; stable,</L>
<L>and of entent not variable.</L>
<L>look her-to on euery syde,</L>
<L N="24120">for I may no lenger abyde,</L>
<L>for, I cast&euml; me a-noon,</L>
<L>hom to my castel forto goon,</L>
<L>and by the next&euml; way&euml;<NOTE PLACE="marg">[St., next way C.]</NOTE> wende,</L>
<L N="24124">and ther, vnto my liv&euml;s ende,</L>
<L>abiden in the sam&euml; place,</L>
<L>lik as god wil yeve me grace."</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>and whan I was kome hom ageyn,</L>
<L N="24128">of al that euere I had seyn,</L>
<L>I mad&euml; playn Relac&iuml;oun</L>
<L>to folk of that Relig&iuml;oun;</L>
<L>and afterward (I you ensure,)</L>
<L N="24132">ther fel a wonder &aacute;venture,</L>
<L>the which&euml;,<NOTE PLACE="marg">[which C., whiche St.]</NOTE> whan I dede aduerte,</L>
<L>yt liked nothyng to myn herte:</L>
<L>I saw tweyne old&euml; (by assent,)<MILESTONE N="298b" UNIT="folio"><NOTE PLACE="marg">[St. &amp; C.]</NOTE></L>
<L N="24136">Kome to me of oon entent,</L>
<L>Wonder dyuers of her cheres;</L>
<L>and both&euml; two wer massageres:<NOTE PLACE="marg">[messengers St., massager C.]</NOTE></L>
<L>the toon of hem (I was wel war)
<PB REF="00000755.tif" N="647"></L>
<L N="24140">Vpon hir bak, a bed she bar;</L>
<L>The tother (if I shal not feyne)</L>
<L>bar also, patent&euml;s tweyne;</L>
<L>the toon also, in hir commyng,<NOTE PLACE="marg">[comming St., counning C.]</NOTE><MILESTONE UNIT="Stowe folio" N="273a"></L>
<L N="24144">gird with a baudrek, for wrastelyng:</L>
<L>In their comyng I fonde gret lak,</L>
<L>and evene thus to me they spak:</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>Age &amp; Sicknes:<NOTE PLACE="marg">[St., <I>om</I>. C.]</NOTE></HEAD>
<L>'deth,' quod they, 'hath to th&eacute; sent</L>
<L N="24148">bothe vs tweyn&euml;, of entent,</L>
<L>pleynly to the to declare,</L>
<L>that hym self ne wil not spare</L>
<L>forto come to the anoon;</L>
<L N="24152">and bad, aforn we shold&euml;<NOTE PLACE="marg">[shold C., shuld St.]</NOTE> goon,</L>
<L>and done our full&euml; besynesse,</L>
<L>with al our myghte, the to opprese,<NOTE PLACE="marg">[to oppresse St., tappresse C.]</NOTE></L>
<L>and not departe fro the at al,</L>
<L N="24156">til thou be cast, and haue a fal,</L>
<L>that he may, at his commyng,</L>
<L>fynd&euml; the, by our workyng,</L>
<L>So awhap&euml;d and amat,</L>
<L N="24160">that he may seyn to th&eacute;, 'chek mat."</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>Pilgrim:<NOTE PLACE="marg">[St., <I>om</I>. C.]</NOTE><NOTE PLACE="inter">[Blank for Illumination.]</NOTE></HEAD>
<L>Quod I, "declareth vnto me,</L>
<L>ffirst of all&euml;, what ye be.</L>
<L>I know&euml; not your gouernaunce;<MILESTONE N="299a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="24164">With deth I ha non &aacute;queyntaunce;</L>
<L>and yef that he be your maystresse,</L>
<L>I pray you, first, that ye expresse</L>
<L>your office, and your seruyse,</L>
<L N="24168">and your nam&euml;s doth devyse."</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>Age &amp; Sicknes:<NOTE PLACE="marg">[St., <I>om</I>. C.]</NOTE></HEAD>
<L>Quod they, 'it wer not but in veyn,</L>
<L>With vs to stryve, or wynse ageyn;</L>
<L>for, ther is noon<NOTE PLACE="marg">[none St.]</NOTE> so hardy,</L>
<L N="24172">so wys, so Rich&euml;, so myghty,</L>
<L>that may, by forc&euml; nor<NOTE PLACE="marg">[or St.]</NOTE> allye,</L>
<L>holden with vs Champartye.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>'for deth hath had, ful yore agoon,</L>
<L N="24176">lordshipe of folk&euml;s euerychoon;
<PB REF="00000756.tif" N="648"></L>
<L>'for, who considereth all&euml; thynges,</L>
<L>Drad more of lord&euml;s and of kynges</L>
<L>than of folk&euml;s (who list se)</L>
<L N="24180">which that duellen in pouerte.</L>
<L>for por&euml; folk that lakk&euml;<NOTE PLACE="marg">[lak C., lake St.]</NOTE> bred,</L>
<L>desire ful oft&euml;<NOTE PLACE="marg">[desyr ofte for St.]</NOTE> to ben ded.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>'and, yef thou aryght behold,</L>
<L N="24184">vnto deth thou art yhold,</L>
<L>that he, toforn<NOTE PLACE="marg">[to toforn C.]</NOTE> hath to the sent;</L>
<L>for ofte, without avis&euml;ment</L>
<L>he cometh to folk&euml;s vnwarly,</L>
<L N="24188">and hem assailleth sodeynly,</L>
<L>though the contrary had sworn.</L>
<L>but, he hath vs sent to-forn,</L>
<L>as massagers<NOTE PLACE="marg">[messengers St.]</NOTE> to warn&euml; the;<MILESTONE UNIT="Stowe folio" N="273b"></L>
<L N="24192">from his power thou mayst<NOTE PLACE="marg">[may St.]</NOTE> not fle;</L>
<L>and ech of vs (without&euml; blame)</L>
<L>Shal declar&euml; the his name.'</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>[Sekenesse:]</HEAD>
<L>The first&euml;<NOTE PLACE="marg">[first C., St.]</NOTE> to me dede expresse:</L>
<L N="24196">quod she, 'my name is Sek&euml;nesse.</L>
<L>helthe and I, but litel space<MILESTONE N="299b" UNIT="folio"><NOTE PLACE="marg">[St. &amp; C.]</NOTE></L>
<L>May abiden in O place.</L>
<L>we wrastlen ofte (as men may se);</L>
<L N="24200">som whil&euml; she venquyssheth me,</L>
<L>and, som tym&euml;,<NOTE PLACE="marg">[some tym St.]</NOTE> in certeyn,</L>
<L>I over-throw&euml; hir ageyn,</L>
<L>make hir forto bowe hir chyne.</L>
<L N="24204">and, ne wer&euml;<NOTE PLACE="marg">[ware St., wer C.]</NOTE> that medicyne</L>
<L>ys caus&euml; that she doth releve,</L>
<L>my sayllyng shold hir often greve.</L>
<L>but, maugre hir potac&iuml;ouns</L>
<L N="24208">&aacute;nd dyuerse confecc&iuml;ouns,</L>
<L>and other sondry lettuaryes</L>
<L>Mak&euml;d at the potycaryes,&mdash;</L>
<L>bothe emplastres drye and moystes,</L>
<L N="24212">and oynement&euml;s put in boystes,&mdash;</L>
<L>yet deth and I (who lyst espye)</L>
<L>Haue, at the last&euml;,<NOTE PLACE="marg">[last C., St.]</NOTE> the maystrye.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>'first I souke vp (for the nones)
<PB REF="00000757.tif" N="649"></L>
<L N="24216">'the mary clos&euml;d in the bones,</L>
<L>and (wher that it be bad or good,)</L>
<L>waste<NOTE PLACE="marg">[wast St., baste C.]</NOTE> the flessh, and drynke the blood;</L>
<L>And thus my silf, I c&oacute;nsume al</L>
<L N="24220">the vertu that called is<NOTE PLACE="marg">[ys cally St.]</NOTE> 'vital';</L>
<L>and at the last (who list knowe,)</L>
<L>ley hym in a bed ful lowe,</L>
<L>That deth may (withouten stryf)</L>
<L N="24224">a-noon bereve hym of his lyf.'</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>Pilgrim:<NOTE PLACE="marg">[St., <I>om</I>. C.]</NOTE></HEAD>
<L>"Sothly, thou art no massagere,<NOTE PLACE="marg">[messenger St.]</NOTE></L>
<L>to whom men shold&euml;<NOTE PLACE="marg">[shold C., shuld St.]</NOTE> mak&euml; chere."</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>Secnes:<NOTE PLACE="marg">[St., <I>om</I>. C.]</NOTE></HEAD>
<L>'ffor soth&euml;, yis,<NOTE PLACE="marg">[this St.]</NOTE> (who taketh hede,)</L>
<L N="24228">folk ar holde to me in dede;</L>
<L>for, sik&euml; folk&euml;s to avaunce,</L>
<L>I make hem to ha r&eacute;pentaunce</L>
<L>Whan she was put out of mynde,<MILESTONE N="300a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="24232">and therby, a men&euml; fynde,</L>
<L>that folk&euml;s, by contric&iuml;oun,</L>
<L>may come to their savac&iuml;oun;</L>
<L>for proudest folkes, (as I gesse,)</L>
<L N="24236">I chastys&euml; with Seknesse.<NOTE PLACE="marg">[sycknesse St.]</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>'and first, I hau&euml; gret delit,<MILESTONE UNIT="Stowe folio" N="374a"></L>
<L>from hem to take their appetit;</L>
<L>their .v. witt&euml;s and Resoun,<NOTE PLACE="marg">[fiv&euml;]</NOTE></L>
<L N="24240">I be-reve hem, vp and doun,</L>
<L>make (as thou shalt vnderstonde,)</L>
<L>folk so feble, thei may not stonde.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>'and we be com&euml; to th&egrave; blyve,</L>
<L N="24244">with th&egrave; to wrastlen and to stryve.'</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>Pilgrim:<NOTE PLACE="marg">[St., <I>om</I>. C.]</NOTE></HEAD>
<L>"Or ye to me don eny shame,</L>
<L>let me first knowen the name</L>
<L>of the tother massager,<NOTE PLACE="marg">[messenger St.]</NOTE></L>
<L N="24248">That loketh with so fel a cher."</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>Sicknes:<NOTE PLACE="marg">[St., <I>om</I>. C.]</NOTE></HEAD>
<L>'I graunt&euml; wel she shal the telle,</L>
<L>yef thou wilt a whil&euml;<NOTE PLACE="marg">[whil C., whill St.]</NOTE> duelle.'</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>Age:<NOTE PLACE="marg">[St., <I>om</I>. C.]</NOTE>
</HEAD>
<PB REF="00000758.tif" N="650">
<L>Quod she, 'of folk&euml;s that ben sage,</L>
<L N="24252">I am of custom call&euml;d 'Age,'</L>
<L>Contrar&iuml;ous (as it is kouth)</L>
<L>to hir that is ycalled Youth,</L>
<L>which whilom had (thou myghtest<NOTE PLACE="marg">[mayst St.]</NOTE> se)</L>
<L N="24256">fressh&euml; fetheres forto fle.</L>
<L>but Age hath plukked hem away,</L>
<L>that vnneth&euml;<NOTE PLACE="marg">[vnneth C., vnnethe St.]</NOTE> gon I may;</L>
<L>my fet be now (who taketh hede)</L>
<L N="24260">hevy as they were of lede;</L>
<L>I may not gon, but with labour,</L>
<L>and yet of Deth I am corour,</L>
<L>knowe<NOTE PLACE="marg">[knowne St.]</NOTE> in Countres fer and ner.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>'And<NOTE PLACE="marg">[St.]</NOTE> who that is a massager,<MILESTONE N="300b" UNIT="folio"><NOTE PLACE="marg">[messenger St.]</NOTE></L>
<L N="24265">Wher he holdeth his pass&aacute;ge,</L>
<L>mut do truely his mass&aacute;ge,<NOTE PLACE="marg">[message St.]</NOTE></L>
<L>and the trouth&euml;<NOTE PLACE="marg">[trouth C., truthe St.]</NOTE> telle of ryght.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="24268">'I am vnweldy, &aacute;nd not lyght;</L>
<L>and (to speke in word&euml;s fewe,)</L>
<L>myn empty skyn doth wel shewe</L>
<L>what that I am; and ouer more,</L>
<L N="24272">thou mayst se, by my lokk&euml;s hore,</L>
<L>and by ryv&eacute;ls of<NOTE PLACE="marg">[in St.]</NOTE> my vis&aacute;ge,</L>
<L>How that I am called 'Age,'</L>
<L>of whom, folk&euml;s that<NOTE PLACE="marg">[folk that C., folke that St.]</NOTE> discerne,</L>
<L N="24276">may ful many thyng&euml;s lerne.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>'though that wasted be my blood,</L>
<L>I ha seyn bothe evel and good;</L>
<L>Preved (if I shal not feyne)</L>
<L N="24280">ende and gynnyng of bothe tweyne.</L>
<L>age, in konnyng doth excelle;</L>
<L>who much&euml; seth, can much&euml; telle:</L>
<L N="24283">no man in konnyng (this, the chef,)</L>
<L>without&euml;<NOTE PLACE="marg">[without C., withe out St.]</NOTE> syght may ha no pref.'</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>Pilgrim:<NOTE PLACE="marg">[St., <I>om</I>. C.]</NOTE></HEAD>
<L>"To her&euml; now, myn entent is,<MILESTONE UNIT="Stowe folio" N="374b"></L>
<L>what betokne thi patent&euml;s;</L>
<L>and after that, make no delay,</L>
<L N="24288">but take thy leve, and go thy way."</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>Age:<NOTE PLACE="marg">[St., <I>om</I>. C.]</NOTE>
</HEAD>
<PB REF="00000759.tif" N="651">
<L>'wher-so it like the, or displese,</L>
<L>I wil abiden at myn eese,</L>
<L>And fro this plac&euml; not retourne,</L>
<L>but euere in on with th&egrave;<NOTE PLACE="marg">[the <I>om</I>. C., the St.]</NOTE> soiourne.</L>
<L N="24293">I may not parte lyghtly a-way,</L>
<L>as Youth&euml; dede this other day.</L>
<L>She th&egrave;<NOTE PLACE="marg">[the <I>om</I>. St.]</NOTE> forsook (in verray dede)</L>
<L N="24296">whan thou haddest to hir most nede;</L>
<L>she went hir way, and took hir flyght,</L>
<L>and fled a-noon out of thy syght;<MILESTONE N="301a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>caste hir neuere to come ageyn:</L>
<L N="24300">to looken after, wer but veyn.</L>
<L>but I, be leyser mut abyde,</L>
<L>t&oacute;ward dethe<NOTE PLACE="marg">[towardeth C., toward deathe St.]</NOTE> to be thy guyde;</L>
<L>for, til deth come, I vndertake</L>
<L N="24304">that I shal the not forsake.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>'I haue doon my besy peyne.</L>
<L>to bryng&euml; th&eacute; patent&euml;s<NOTE PLACE="marg">[patents C., St.]</NOTE> tweyne,</L>
<L>oonly of fauour, for<NOTE PLACE="marg">[to St.]</NOTE> thy best;</L>
<L N="24308">ther-vp-on that thou mayst reste,</L>
<L>and of noon entenc&iuml;oun</L>
<L>to tak&euml; fro the thy bordoun:</L>
<L>to the, both&euml; may availle.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="24312">'and, for mor suer sowpewaille,<NOTE PLACE="marg">[supewayle St.]</NOTE></L>
<L>to the bordoun spiritual,</L>
<L>a staf is nedful, temporal:</L>
<L>Euerych of hem with-out&euml;<NOTE PLACE="marg">[out C., St.]</NOTE> wene,</L>
<L N="24316">the tother must of ryght sustene;</L>
<L>for whan the t&oacute; part doun doth falle,</L>
<L>help of the tother he must calle,</L>
<L>yef hym list hym-self assure.</L>
<L N="24320">but thou ne shalt not<NOTE PLACE="marg">[not, <I>om</I>. C., St.]</NOTE> wel endure</L>
<L>the felle assaut&euml;s of vs tweyne;</L>
<L>for, we ne shal no lenger feyne,</L>
<L>but (for short conclus&iuml;oun)</L>
<L N="24324">ber th&egrave; to the Erthe a-doun.'</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>Pilgrim:<NOTE PLACE="marg">[St., <I>om</I>. C.]</NOTE></HEAD>
<L>And both&euml; tweyn&euml;, with a brayd,</L>
<L>vpon a bed they ha me layd,</L>
<L>for they wolde not of me faille,
<PB REF="00000760.tif" N="652"></L>
<L N="24328">ther tabyde, til deth assaille.</L>
<L>And<NOTE PLACE="marg">[St.]</NOTE> in distresse and gret affray,<MILESTONE N="301b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>vpon the bed whil I thus lay,</L>
<L>I myght&euml;<NOTE PLACE="marg">[myght St., C.]</NOTE> tho no ferther gon,<MILESTONE UNIT="Stowe folio" N="375a"></L>
<L N="24332">to me a lady cam a-noon,</L>
<L>with ful many noble signe,</L>
<L>of cher and lok, ful benigne,</L>
<L>(I dar ryght wel record,)</L>
<L N="24336">Whos nam&euml; was 'Myserycord;</L>
<L>oon of hir brest&euml;s opon was,</L>
<L>to yeve me mylk in such a caas.</L>
<L>And also (as I was war,)</L>
<L N="24340">me sempt&euml; that a corde she bar,</L>
<L>to bynden hay (so thought&euml;<NOTE PLACE="marg">[thought C., St.]</NOTE> me).</L>
<L>and, of mercy and pyte,</L>
<L>to me that lay, like a wrecche,</L>
<L N="24344">She gan hir corde abrood to strecche;<NOTE PLACE="inter">[Blank in MS. for an Illumination.]</NOTE></L>
<L>And ful goodly, with that sygne,</L>
<L>to me she sayd with cher benygne:</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>Mysericord:<NOTE PLACE="marg">[St., <I>om</I>. C.]</NOTE></HEAD>
<L>'Rys a-noon, and su&euml; me,</L>
<L N="24348">for by thy cher, I do wel se</L>
<L>that thou art feblyd<NOTE PLACE="marg">[feble St.]</NOTE> of thy myght,</L>
<L>and thou list not her a-ryght;</L>
<L>Wherfore I wil the fostre and guye,</L>
<L N="24352">and lede the to the fermerye.'</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>Pilgrim:<NOTE PLACE="marg">[St., <I>om</I>. C.]</NOTE></HEAD>
<L>Quod I, "that were ful glad to me.</L>
<L>But, for I wot not what ye be,</L>
<L>I pray you with ful humble cher,</L>
<L N="24356">your nam&euml;, that ye wil me lere."</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>Misericord:<NOTE PLACE="marg">[St., <I>om</I>. C.]</NOTE></HEAD>
<L>'My nam&euml;, yef it be conceyved,<MILESTONE N="302a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>I ought wel to ben receyued,</L>
<L>for, whan Iuges, for offence</L>
<L N="24360">han yov&euml;d<NOTE PLACE="marg">[have gyven C.]</NOTE> hir sentence,</L>
<L>I do my peyne and my labour,</L>
<L>of Iustice and of Rigour</L>
<L>forto do remiss&iuml;oun,
<PB REF="00000761.tif" N="653"></L>
<L N="24364">'and make a mittigac&iuml;oun</L>
<L>(as folk&euml;s may ful wel discerne).</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>'for whan the kyng that is eterne,<NOTE PLACE="marg">[eterne St., sterne C.]</NOTE></L>
<L>had yoven<NOTE PLACE="marg">[yove C., gyven St.]</NOTE> in sent&euml;ment</L>
<L N="24368">a ful dredful Iug&euml;ment</L>
<L>of Adam and<NOTE PLACE="marg">[and St., on C.]</NOTE> the lynage,</L>
<L>forto deye for their outrage,</L>
<L>I cam to hym ful humblely,</L>
<L N="24372">and prayed hym ful benygn&euml;ly,</L>
<L>the myghty kyng celestial,</L>
<L>not forto distruyen al;</L>
<L>but that he wold, in his grevaunce,</L>
<L N="24376">modefyen his vengeaunce,</L>
<L>and to with-drawe his Iug&euml;ment.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>'and his bow&euml; that was bent,</L>
<L>I made hym draw&euml; of the corde,</L>
<L N="24380">and, for sygn&euml;s<NOTE PLACE="marg">[sygns C., sygne St.]</NOTE> of concorde,</L>
<L>Sette it in the heven alofte;</L>
<L>and (as men may se ful ofte)</L>
<L>In tookne of pes, and not of wrak,</L>
<L>from vs he tourned hath his bak,<MILESTONE UNIT="Stowe folio" N="375b"></L>
<L N="24385">that, of his mercy&aacute;ble lawe,</L>
<L>he may not the bow&euml; drawe,</L>
<L>whan of mercy (as it is knowe)</L>
<L N="24388">toward hym-self he drough the bowe.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>'whan he, for our Inyquyte,</L>
<L>dyed vpon the rod&euml; tre,</L>
<L>he bought our gilt so sore.<NOTE PLACE="marg">[6-<I>syllable line</I>]</NOTE></L>
<L N="24392">and vnderstond, ouer more,<MILESTONE N="302b" UNIT="folio"><NOTE PLACE="marg">[St. &amp; C.]</NOTE></L>
<L>vp nor doun (who lok&euml; wel)</L>
<L>he may not drawe it neuer a del.</L>
<L>for, of the bow&euml; the discord,</L>
<L N="24396">vnderstond&euml; by the cord:</L>
<L>I made hem so forto acorde,</L>
<L>that called am 'Misericorde.'</L>
<L>for (yef thou dost<NOTE PLACE="marg">[canst St.]</NOTE> wel vnderstond)</L>
<L N="24400">the stryng therof is in myn hond:</L>
<L>thou mayst behold it wel, and se;</L>
<L>for, of mercy and of pyte,</L>
<L>I drawe out wrecches from her charge,
<PB REF="00000762.tif" N="654"></L>
<L N="24404">'and mak&euml; hem go loos at large.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>'therfore folk&euml;s alle acorde</L>
<L>to call&euml; me 'Mis&eacute;ricorde';</L>
<L>of which (by declarac&iuml;oun)</L>
<L N="24408">to make an exposic&iuml;oun,</L>
<L>Misericord&euml;, tru&euml;ly</L>
<L>ys, on wrecches to han mercy.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>'thus my nam&euml;<NOTE PLACE="marg">[this nam St.]</NOTE> thou shalt knowe;</L>
<L N="24412">I drawe hem vp, whan they ben lowe.</L>
<L>the cordeler that waf<NOTE PLACE="marg">[wave St.]</NOTE> the corde</L>
<L>of pes, vnyte, and concorde,</L>
<L>only on wrecches to han pyte,</L>
<L N="24416">hyr name was called 'Charyte.'</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>'and yef the corde wer broke a-sondre,</L>
<L>ther is n&oacute; man, (her nor yondre,)</L>
<L>though he euere dide his peyne,</L>
<L N="24420">that myght&euml;<NOTE PLACE="marg">[myght C., St.]</NOTE> to the heven atteyne;</L>
<L>for, by this corde (as I the told)</L>
<L>all&euml; Synners must hem hold,</L>
<L>and playnly clymben vp therby,</L>
<L N="24424">oonly of pyte and mercy.'</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>Pilgrim:<NOTE PLACE="marg">[St., <I>om</I>. C.]</NOTE></HEAD>
<L>"lady, put me out of doute,</L>
<L>why ha ye now drawen oute</L>
<L>Oon of your brest&euml;s fayr and whyte<MILESTONE N="303a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="24428">(which to behold, I me delyte,)</L>
<L>like as ye wold&euml; be my bote,</L>
<L>wasshe me with your mylk most sote?"</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>Misericord:<NOTE PLACE="marg">[St., <I>om</I>. C.]</NOTE></HEAD>
<L>'Truely,' quod she '(yef ye take hede,)</L>
<L N="24432">of my mylk thou hast mor nede</L>
<L>(yef the trouthe be iustly told)</L>
<L>than outher of siluer, outher<NOTE PLACE="marg">[or St.]</NOTE> of gold,</L>
<L>or of any precious ston,</L>
<L N="24436">forto rekne hem euerychon.</L>
<L>for this mylk which thou dost se,<MILESTONE UNIT="Stowe folio" N="376a"></L>
<L>ys called Mercy and Pyte,</L>
<L>all&euml; Synners to sustene;</L>
<L N="24440">and to releve hem in their tene,</L>
<L>it<NOTE PLACE="marg">[it St., a C.]</NOTE> bryngeth hem in rest and<NOTE PLACE="marg">[&amp; St., <I>om</I>. C.]</NOTE> pees.
<PB REF="00000763.tif" N="655"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>'And, like as Aristotiles</L>
<L>writte, that mylk is nothyng elles</L>
<L N="24444">(as all&euml; Philesophres telles)</L>
<L>but blood, by transmutac&iuml;oun</L>
<L>thorugh hete and lent<NOTE PLACE="marg">[lyte St.]</NOTE> decocc&iuml;oun,</L>
<L>tourned away from his rednesse</L>
<L N="24448">to perfectioun of whytenesse;</L>
<L>and (to speke in word&euml;s playn)</L>
<L>this nomor&euml; forto sayn,</L>
<L>that a man that ys irous,</L>
<L N="24452">froward and malencolious,</L>
<L>hath but red blood: and that rednesse</L>
<L>may neuere tourn&euml; to whitenesse</L>
<L>(as clerk&euml;s sayn,) but yef so be</L>
<L N="24456">it be decoct by charyte,</L>
<L>that his malicious appetit</L>
<L>be itourned into whit,</L>
<L>thorugh perfect&iuml;oun of hete</L>
<L N="24460">of charyte, that ys most swete,</L>
<L>Than the smoke of fals envye,</L>
<L>the fume eke of mal&eacute;ncolye,<MILESTONE N="303b" UNIT="folio"><NOTE PLACE="marg">[St. &amp; C.]</NOTE></L>
<L>fleth away, in rednesse,<NOTE PLACE="marg">[6-<I>syllable line</I></NOTE><NOTE PLACE="marg">[St. &amp; C.]</NOTE></L>
<L N="24464">chaunged clene into whitenesse.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>'and who that drynketh of this mylk&mdash;</L>
<L>mor sote and softe than any<NOTE PLACE="marg">[tha any C., than St.]</NOTE> silk&mdash;</L>
<L>foryeveth (in a litel space)</L>
<L N="24468">ech offenc&euml; and trespace</L>
<L>that men ha gilt hym in his live;<NOTE PLACE="marg">[C. &amp; St.]</NOTE></L>
<L>hym list no more ageyn to stryve.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>'of such mylk, most of vertu,</L>
<L N="24472">gret plente hadd&euml; crist ihesu;</L>
<L>Shewed his brestis of pyte</L>
<L>whan he was hanged on a tre.</L>
<L>he suffred tho (it is no doute,)</L>
<L N="24476">the likour for to Renne aboute,</L>
<L>and for to shede it out yffere</L>
<L>than he was stonken<NOTE PLACE="marg">[stongen St.]</NOTE> with a spere,</L>
<L>the syde of his humanyte,</L>
<L N="24480">on alle synful to ha pyte,</L>
<L>for to wasshe away our vyce.
<PB REF="00000764.tif" N="656"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>'was neuere moder nor noryce</L>
<L>that gaf such mylk&euml;<NOTE PLACE="marg">[mylke St., mylk C.]</NOTE> her-to-fore</L>
<L N="24484">to hir child, whan it was bore.</L>
<L>his brestes, that be most fair and whyte,</L>
<L>most holy, and fresshest of delyte,</L>
<L>arn euere open to folk&euml;s alle.</L>
<L N="24488">his voyc&euml;,<NOTE PLACE="marg">[voyce St., voys C.]</NOTE> synners doth ek calle,</L>
<L>and bit hem in their hert&euml; thenke,</L>
<L>of his soot&euml; mylk to drynke:<MILESTONE N="376b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>'for blod of ire is noon in me,</L>
<L N="24492">but mylk of mercy and pyte,'</L>
<L>which wassheth away al vengeaunce:</L>
<L>who hath this mylk, hath suffisaunce.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>'The Red&euml; blood (as folk<NOTE PLACE="marg">[men St.]</NOTE> may se)</L>
<L N="24496">y-chaunged is, by charyte,</L>
<L>Into whyte mylk, hoolsom and good,</L>
<L>shaad for mankynd<NOTE PLACE="marg">[mankyng C., mankynd St.]</NOTE> vpon the rood;<MILESTONE N="304a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>with the which, I fostred and fede</L>
<L N="24500">all&euml; folk&euml;s that ha nede,<NOTE PLACE="marg">[fedd . . nedde St.]</NOTE></L>
<L>such as list, by on acorde,</L>
<L>for to be<NOTE PLACE="marg">[be St., <I>om</I>. C.]</NOTE> draw&euml; with my corde,</L>
<L>to alle I am so mercyable,</L>
<L N="24504">to my fader, R&eacute;semblable,</L>
<L>and to my moder Charyte.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>'for whan that I may any se</L>
<L>In myschief, hunger, outher thurst,</L>
<L N="24508">hem to fede, it is my lust.</L>
<L>naked and nedy, that ben lothe,</L>
<L>I haue in custom hem to clothe;</L>
<L>And, gretly I me delyte,</L>
<L N="24512">folk in prisoun to visyte;</L>
<L>and led&euml;, with a glad visage,</L>
<L>pore folk to their herbegage;</L>
<L>And thei that deye in<NOTE PLACE="marg">[en C., in St.]</NOTE> pouerte,</L>
<L N="24516">to burye hem, I d&eacute;lite me:</L>
<L>to such&euml;<NOTE PLACE="marg">[such C., suche St.]</NOTE> labour I entende;</L>
<L>al thyng amys, I do amende;</L>
<L>folk&euml;s sike and vnweldy,</L>
<L N="24520">of pyte only and mercy,</L>
<L>I serve hem in humylite.
<PB REF="00000765.tif" N="657"></L>
<L>'And now I am ycome to the,</L>
<L>In al my best&euml;<NOTE PLACE="marg">[best C., St.]</NOTE> feythful wyse,</L>
<L N="24524">forto profre my seruyse.'</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>Pilgrim:<NOTE PLACE="marg">[St., <I>om.</I> C.]</NOTE></HEAD>
<L>"Ma dame," quod I, "as it is due,</L>
<L>my lust is gretly you to sue;</L>
<L>but, for my gret&euml; febilnesse,</L>
<L N="24528">which me restreyneth by distresse,</L>
<L>And, &thorn;ees massagers<NOTE PLACE="marg">[messengers St.]</NOTE> also</L>
<L>Causen that I may not go.</L>
<L>And if ye wold, of your goodnesse,</L>
<L N="24532">Doon your gret&euml; besynesse</L>
<L>Thes massagers<NOTE PLACE="marg">[thes messengers St.]</NOTE> to putte away,<MILESTONE N="304b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>I wolde (without&euml;<NOTE PLACE="marg">[without C., St.]</NOTE> mor delay)</L>
<L>folwe, in al my best entent,</L>
<L N="24536">to gon at your comand&euml;ment."</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>Misericord:<NOTE PLACE="marg">[St., <I>om.</I> C.]</NOTE></HEAD>
<L>'Truely (nouther nygh nor ferre)</L>
<L>I may not voyd&euml; nor differre</L>
<L>the massagers<NOTE PLACE="marg">[messengers St.]</NOTE> from thy presence;</L>
<L N="24540">but I shal do my diligence,</L>
<L>with my cord&euml;, th&egrave; tenbrace,</L>
<L>and to lede th&egrave; to the place<MILESTONE UNIT="Stowe folio" N="377a"></L>
<L>which called is the Fermerye.</L>
<L N="24544">the massagers<NOTE PLACE="marg">[St., <I>om.</I> C.]</NOTE> her fast&euml; by,</L>
<L>I ha no myght hem to coharte,</L>
<L>to maken hem fro th&egrave; departe.</L>
<L>til that deth hym-silf assaille,</L>
<L N="24548">tabiden on the, they wil not faylle.'</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>Pilgrim:<NOTE PLACE="marg">[St., <I>om</I>. C.]</NOTE></HEAD>
<L>Than anoon Myserycorde</L>
<L>gan tenbrace me in hir corde.</L>
<L>and the old&euml;, both&euml; tweyne,</L>
<L N="24552">Were present, and dide her peyne</L>
<L>to brynge me to my bed anoon,</L>
<L>and list not from me fer<NOTE PLACE="marg">[for St.]</NOTE> to goon.</L>
<L>and therwith-al, &aacute;noon ryght</L>
<L N="24556">I gan to feblen of my myght</L>
<L>mor and mor, erly and late,</L>
<L>til the porter at the gate
<PB REF="00000766.tif" N="658"></L>
<L>brought&euml; me two massagers,<NOTE PLACE="marg">[brought C. &amp; St., messengers St.]</NOTE></L>
<L N="24560">benygne and goodly of her chers.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>[The Porter:] <NOTE PLACE="inter">[6 <I>lines blank for an Illumination</I>.]</NOTE></HEAD>
<L>Quod the porter anoon to me:<MILESTONE N="305a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>'I ha th&egrave; brought (yef thou lyst se)</L>
<L>two massagers<NOTE PLACE="marg">[brought C. &amp; St., messengers St.]</NOTE> (it is no nay)</L>
<L N="24564">which shal the teche the ryght&euml;<NOTE PLACE="marg">[ryght C., St.]</NOTE> way</L>
<L>to Ierusalem the cite;</L>
<L>for (bi tooknes that I se,)</L>
<L>I conceyve (on euery syde)</L>
<L N="24568">thou mayst her, no while abyde.</L>
<L>wherfore, to mak&euml; thy passage,</L>
<L>Send hem toforne, on thy massage,<NOTE PLACE="marg">[message St.]</NOTE></L>
<L>that thou mayst, by thy sendyng,</L>
<L N="24572">be bet receyved at thi comyng,</L>
<L>withouten eny spot of blame.</L>
<L>and mak&euml; to hem, in thi name,</L>
<L>a maner of commyss&iuml;oun,</L>
<L N="24576">and ek a procurac&iuml;oun,</L>
<L>that they may, thorugh their werkyng,</L>
<L>be receyu&euml;d of the kyng</L>
<L>thorugh fauour of their langage,</L>
<L N="24580">to taken vp their herbergage</L>
<L>In that cyte clestial,</L>
<L>wher the kyng is &eacute;ternal.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>'thes ladyes nam&euml;s to expresse,</L>
<L N="24584">they ben Prayer and Almesse;</L>
<L>And they ben redy, both&euml; tweyne,</L>
<L>In this caas to done her peyne.'</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>[The Pilgrim:]</HEAD>
<L>"Truely," quod I to the porter,</L>
<L N="24588">"I wolde, with al myn hert entier,</L>
<L>don alm&euml;s of entenc&iuml;oun;</L>
<L>but I ha noo pocess&iuml;oun,</L>
<L>nor nothyng in propurte,</L>
<L N="24592">but al thyng in communyte.</L>
<L>al propurte, I ha forsake,</L>
<L>And to pouerte me take,</L>
<L>Of myn<NOTE PLACE="marg">[St., C. <I>burnt</I>]</NOTE> ordre, in sothfastnesse.<MILESTONE N="305b" UNIT="folio"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>"Wherfore, touchyng such almesse,<MILESTONE UNIT="Stowe folio" N="377b">
<PB REF="00000767.tif" N="659"></L>
<L N="24597">"I ha sothly no powere</L>
<L>to make of hir a massagere,</L>
<L>to tak&euml; herbergage for me</L>
<L N="24600">In that hevenly, chef cyte.</L>
<L>alm&euml;s, and al such oother thynges,</L>
<L>mot ben of lord&euml;s and of kynges</L>
<L>Sent to-forn to that cyte,</L>
<L N="24604">Yef they wil wel receyved be,</L>
<L>ther to make her purveaunce,</L>
<L>terberwe<NOTE PLACE="marg">[to harbour, lodge]</NOTE> hem to their plesaunce.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>"for (who-so list the trouth&euml; lere)</L>
<L N="24608">alle estates in this world here&mdash;</L>
<L>kyng&euml;s, prynces, both&euml; two,</L>
<L>Duk&euml;s, lord&euml;s ek also,&mdash;</L>
<L>Reekne hem all&euml;, by and by,</L>
<L N="24612">and thei be pilgrym&euml;s as I:</L>
<L>let hem toforn pourvey&euml; wel</L>
<L>forto take vp their hostel,</L>
<L>Sende her massagers<NOTE PLACE="marg">[theyr mesengars St.]</NOTE> to se</L>
<L N="24616">their herbergage in that cyte,</L>
<L>that, for lak of providence,</L>
<L>through slouth, or through necligence,</L>
<L>they be dispurveyed, at her comyng,</L>
<L N="24620">as Barlam telleth of a kyng,</L>
<L>which, of custom synguler,</L>
<L>Reyned neuere but a<NOTE PLACE="marg">[one St.]</NOTE> yer</L>
<L>In a lond; and this the ende,</L>
<L N="24624">than of forc&euml; he must wende</L>
<L>Into an Ilond (in certeyn)</L>
<L>that was of vitaille ful bareyn;</L>
<L>and thus this kyng cam to meschaunce,</L>
<L N="24628">for laak oonly of pourveyaunce,</L>
<L>that he toforn, for his availle,</L>
<L>lyst to send&euml; no vitaille.</L>
<L>Ther was noon other men&euml; wey;<MILESTONE N="306a" UNIT="folio"><NOTE PLACE="marg">[C. &amp; St.]</NOTE></L>
<L N="24632">for hunger, he must ned&euml; deye.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>"after whom, thus stood the cas,</L>
<L>that a-nother kyng ther was,</L>
<L>which shuld&euml;<NOTE PLACE="marg">[shuld C., St.]</NOTE> for a yer succede;</L>
<L N="24636">but he was wys, and took good hede,
<PB REF="00000768.tif" N="660"></L>
<L>"whil he stood in h&aacute;boundaunce,</L>
<L>forto make his purveyaunce,</L>
<L>to send&euml;, in the sam&euml; while,</L>
<L N="24640">vitaille into that bareyn Ile.</L>
<L>he was prudent, aforn to se,</L>
<L>to provide that Scarsete</L>
<L>sholde sodeynly hym not assaille:</L>
<L N="24644">wherfore, h&eacute; sent his vitaille</L>
<L>Into that yle that bareyn was.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>"wherfore, let ech man in such caas,</L>
<L>sen aforn, in his resoun,<MILESTONE UNIT="Stowe folio" N="378a"></L>
<L N="24648">while he stant in pocess&iuml;oun</L>
<L>of his Rewme, by good avys</L>
<L>to sende aforn to paradys,</L>
<L>to taken vp, in that cyte,</L>
<L N="24652">herbergage lik his degre;</L>
<L>as whilom ded&euml;<NOTE PLACE="marg">[dyd St.]</NOTE> seynt Lowys,</L>
<L>the holy kyng that was so wys:</L>
<L>Whil he hadde domynac&iuml;oun</L>
<L N="24656">thorugh-out al his Reg&iuml;oun,</L>
<L>he ne was not necligent,</L>
<L>but sent aforn, of good entent,</L>
<L>his massagers<NOTE PLACE="marg">[messengers St.]</NOTE> and his corrours,</L>
<L N="24660">his vitaillers,<NOTE PLACE="marg">[vitilars St.]</NOTE> his pourveyours,</L>
<L>only for his &aacute;vauntage,</L>
<L>to taken vp his herbergage</L>
<L>In that ilk&euml; noble Rewm,<NOTE PLACE="marg">[reme St.]</NOTE></L>
<L N="24664">called hevenly Ieurusalem;</L>
<L>wher he was, for a mem&oacute;rye,</L>
<L>Receyved forto regne in glorye,</L>
<L>that holy<NOTE PLACE="marg">[St., C. <I>burnt</I>]</NOTE> kyng contemplatif,<MILESTONE N="306b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="24668">for the vertues of his lif,</L>
<L>his prayours and his orysouns,</L>
<L>his fastynges and deuoc&iuml;ouns,</L>
<L>his mercy meynt with ryghtwesnesse,</L>
<L N="24672">his compassiouns, his almesse,</L>
<L>of cherches his foundac&iuml;ouns,</L>
<L>and other dyuers mans&iuml;ouns</L>
<L>y-mad for folk&euml;s pore and blynde,</L>
<L N="24676">Which, neu&eacute;re, shal<NOTE PLACE="marg">[shall nevar St.]</NOTE> out of mynde:
<PB REF="00000769.tif" N="661"></L>
<L>"alle thes vertues (in substaunce)</L>
<L>made aforn hym pourveyaunce;</L>
<L>took vp a paleys most Royal</L>
<L N="24680">In that cyte celestial,</L>
<L>for kyng Lowys, that holy man,</L>
<L>as his lif reherc&euml; can,</L>
<L>wel bet than I can expresse.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="24684">"and for my part, touchyng almesse,</L>
<L>I may not make hir (fer nor ner)</L>
<L>forto be my massager:<NOTE PLACE="marg">[sessenger (!) St.]</NOTE></L>
<L>She nys not pertynent to me,</L>
<L N="24688">which ha no thyng in propurte,</L>
<L>but by licence (in certeyn)</L>
<L>oonly of my souuereyn.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>"wherfore (of entenc&iuml;oun)</L>
<L N="24692">I shal make a commyss&iuml;oun</L>
<L>to oon that is prudent and sage,</L>
<L>to taken vp myn herbergage:</L>
<L>the name of whom is Prayer,</L>
<L N="24696">to go toforn as massager."<NOTE PLACE="marg">[messenger St.]</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>Prayer:<NOTE PLACE="marg">[St., <I>om</I>. C.]</NOTE></HEAD>
<L>Quod Prayer, 'for thy best,</L>
<L>I wil fulfill&euml; thy requeste</L>
<L>as forforth<NOTE PLACE="marg">[farforthe St.]</NOTE> as I ha myght,</L>
<L N="24700">and as toforn<NOTE PLACE="marg">[reason St.]</NOTE> I ha behyght.'<MILESTONE UNIT="Stowe folio" N="378b"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>[The Pilgrim]:</HEAD>
<L>And with that word, anoon Siknesese</L>
<L>bad hir hast&euml; fast, and dresse,<MILESTONE N="307a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>withouten eny mor delay,</L>
<L N="24704">forto spede hir on hir way;</L>
<L>and without eny longer space,</L>
<L>for tavoyden anoon the place.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>[Siknesse]:</HEAD>
<L>Quod she, 'it is now no sesoun</L>
<L N="24708">to maken a comyss&iuml;oun,</L>
<L>at this tym&euml;, to prayere;</L>
<L>for, playnly (who list to lere,)</L>
<L>bothe at complyn and at pryme,</L>
<L N="24712">it hath be mad afore this tyme;</L>
<L>or ell&euml;s, herbergage to wynne,
<PB REF="00000770.tif" N="662"></L>
<L>'It were to late now to begynne.'</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>Pilgrim:<NOTE PLACE="marg">[St., <I>om</I>. C.]</NOTE></HEAD>
<L>"God me<NOTE PLACE="marg">[me St., <I>om</I>. C.]</NOTE> graunt&euml; grace and mynde,</L>
<L N="24716">good herbergag&euml; forto fynde;</L>
<L>for now I haue ynowh to do,</L>
<L>of veray c&oacute;nstreynt and of wo,</L>
<L>to remembre on<NOTE PLACE="marg">[oon C., on St.]</NOTE> my siknesse."</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="24720">and with that word, ther gan in dresse</L>
<L>oon vpon my bed anoon,</L>
<L>the cruelist of al my foon;</L>
<L>of whom in soth, whan I took hede,</L>
<L N="24724">I lost&euml; speche, of veray drede:</L>
<L>I myght&euml;<NOTE PLACE="marg">[myght C., St.]</NOTE> make no quest&iuml;oun</L>
<L>to axen hir condic&iuml;oun,</L>
<L>she was so dredful of hir chere:</L>
<L N="24728">a sithe she bar, and ek a bere;</L>
<L>sette hir foot vpon my brest,</L>
<L>for to maken on me arest.<NOTE PLACE="inter">[Blank in MS. for an Illumination.]</NOTE></L>
<L>but than<NOTE PLACE="marg">[St., C. <I>burnt</I>.]</NOTE> a lady of gret vertu,<MILESTONE N="307b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="24732">that was called Grac&euml; dieu,</L>
<L>bad hir a wyl&euml; let&euml; be,</L>
<L>whil that<NOTE PLACE="marg">[that St., tha C.]</NOTE> she spak a word to me.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>Deathe:<NOTE PLACE="marg">[St., <I>om</I>. C.]</NOTE><NOTE PLACE="head">[<I>See the French on p.</I> 665.]</NOTE></HEAD>
<L>'Sey on, and tarye neuer a del;</L>
<L N="24736">for I may not abiden wel.</L>
<L>I haate soothly al taryyng;</L>
<L>and I ne love non &aacute;bidyng.</L>
<L>the cause is this, (who taketh hede)</L>
<L N="24740">I ha mo thyng&euml;s forto spede,</L>
<L>In other places mo than oon;</L>
<L>wherfore telle on, for I mot goon.'</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>[Grace Dieu]:<NOTE PLACE="marg">[Pilgrim St., <I>om</I>. C.]</NOTE></HEAD>
<L>Grac&euml; dieu, hir look she layde</L>
<L N="24744">Vp-on me, and thus she sayde:</L>
<L>'thou stanst vpon a streyt pass&aacute;ge,</L>
<L>now as in thy pilgrem&aacute;ge.</L>
<L>Deth is present, as thou maist se,</L>
<L N="24748">fro the which, no man may fle.</L>
<L>she is of contynaunce odyble,<MILESTONE UNIT="Stowe folio" N="379a">
<PB REF="00000771.tif" N="663"></L>
<L>'and of thyng&euml;s most terryble;</L>
<L>she is the ende of euery thyng;</L>
<L N="24752">and now she cast, at hir commyng,</L>
<L>thy lif<NOTE PLACE="marg">[selfe St., ta vie DeG.]</NOTE> playnly, as thou shalt knowe,</L>
<L>with hir sith&euml; vp to mowe:</L>
<L>And afterward, this the fyn,</L>
<L N="24756">to putt&euml; th&egrave; in hir coffyn;</L>
<L>and after, of entenc&iuml;oun,</L>
<L>to yeve th&egrave; in pocess&iuml;oun</L>
<L>to worm&euml;s (as thou shalt ek knowe,)</L>
<L N="24760">that liggen in the erth&euml; lowe;</L>
<L>the which (as I wel tell&euml; can)</L>
<L>Is comm&oacute;n to euery man.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>'ther may no man, of no degre,</L>
<L N="24764">hygh nor lowh, his power fle.</L>
<L>ffor, lych as herb&euml;s and as floures,<MILESTONE N="308a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>that spryngen with soot&euml;<NOTE PLACE="marg">[soot C., St.]</NOTE> shoures</L>
<L>bothe in Aprill and in May,</L>
<L N="24768">and afterward (it is no nay,)</L>
<L>with a sythe (who list to knowe,)</L>
<L>they ben on erth&euml; leyd ful lowe,</L>
<L>and far-wel then al their fresshnesse!</L>
<L N="24772">farwel her colour and grenesse!</L>
<L>It not appereth, her nor there,</L>
<L>the hoot&euml; Sonne maketh hem Sere;<NOTE PLACE="inter">[Blank in MS. for an Illumination.]</NOTE></L>
<L>Ther colours and their fressh aray,</L>
<L N="24776">al ys tourned into hay.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>'and, thou, that so long&euml; be</L>
<L>Grene and lusty forto se,</L>
<L>Deth (his power for to kythe,)</L>
<L N="24780">wil abatyn with his sythe</L>
<L>thy grenesse, and ek also</L>
<L>parten th&egrave; on<NOTE PLACE="marg">[in St.]</NOTE> peces two,</L>
<L>The soule, the body, her and yonder,</L>
<L N="24784">and maken hem to parte assondre.</L>
<L>for, playnly, as thou shalt lere,</L>
<L>they may, as now, not gon yfere;</L>
<L>the soul&euml; must&euml;<NOTE PLACE="marg">[must C., St.]</NOTE> go tofore,</L>
<L N="24788">and the body shal be bore,
<PB REF="00000772.tif" N="664"></L>
<L>'In erthe to haue his mans&iuml;oun,</L>
<L>and tourn&euml; to corrupc&iuml;oun;</L>
<L>and afterward, be wel certeyn,</L>
<L N="24792">Ioyned with the soule ageyn,</L>
<L>and ben to-gidre eternally.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>'Now loke that thou be ful redy;</L>
<L>for yf<NOTE PLACE="marg">[St., C. <I>burnt</I>]</NOTE> ther be no lak in the,<MILESTONE N="308b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="24796">thou shalt go streyht to the<NOTE PLACE="marg">[that St.]</NOTE> cyte</L>
<L>Of the kyngdom and the Rewm</L>
<L>that called ys Ierusalem,</L>
<L>to which thy pilgremage was sette.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="24800">'thou art come to the wyket</L>
<L>(Which is gynnyng of thy labour,)</L>
<L>thow<NOTE PLACE="marg">[thow St., C. <I>burnt</I>]</NOTE> beheld in a myrrour,</L>
<L>whan thow were ful tendre of age,<NOTE PLACE="marg">[St. &amp; C.]</NOTE></L>
<L N="24804">at gynnyng of thy pilgrymage;<NOTE PLACE="marg">[St. &amp; C.]</NOTE></L>
<L>and therfor<NOTE PLACE="marg">[St., C. <I>burnt</I>]</NOTE> now thou art sette</L>
<L>at the boundes of the wyket,</L>
<L>I consaille the, first to crye</L>
<L N="24808">Vnto my Fadre for mercye,</L>
<L>behotyng the lady dame Penaunce,</L>
<L>yef thou ha not in suffisaunce</L>
<L>Don to her, whil thou wer here,</L>
<L N="24812">Iustly and truely thy devere;</L>
<L>thou art in wil, at thy partyng,</L>
<L>thorugh grace and mercy of the kyng,</L>
<L>that Regneth eternally in glorye,</L>
<L N="24816">It to fulfille in purgatorye;<NOTE PLACE="marg">[St. &amp; C.]</NOTE></L>
<L>ther tabiden in that place,<NOTE PLACE="marg">[St. &amp; C.]</NOTE></L>
<L>tyll the lord wil do th&egrave; grace,<NOTE PLACE="marg">[St. &amp; C.]</NOTE></L>
<L>of his mercy, at the laste.'</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="24820">And, for the tym&euml; cam on faste,</L>
<L>and my spech&euml; gan to faille,</L>
<L>I thoughte it<NOTE PLACE="marg">[it St., a C.]</NOTE> fooly for tasaille</L>
<L>Grac&euml; dieu with quest&iuml;ouns,</L>
<L N="24824">with demand&euml;s or<NOTE PLACE="marg">[and St.]</NOTE> resouns.</L>
<L>And (as I coude ek wel discerne)</L>
<L>Deth abood at the posterne,</L>
<L>and gan to let&euml; goon his sythe,</L>
<L N="24828">his cruel myght on me to kythe,
<PB REF="00000773.tif" N="665"></L>
<L>And gan so streytly me coharte,</L>
<L>That the soul&euml; mot departe.</L>
<L>And, such a feer anoon me took,<MILESTONE N="309a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="24832">Out of my slep that I a-wook.<NOTE PLACE="end">The last sayings of Death, Grace Dieu, and the Pilgrim are, in De Guileville's French (Petit's edition, Foeillets xcj. 4&mdash;xcij. 2):&mdash;<Q><LG TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>LA MORT.</HEAD>
<L>OR dictes tost donc / ce dist elle,<NOTE PLACE="marg">[Corresponds to English line] 24735</NOTE></L>
<L>Car moult ie he longue vielle:<NOTE PLACE="marg">[Corresponds to English line] 24737</NOTE></L>
<L>Prestement me vueil deliurer,</L>
<L>Car autre part me fault aler.<NOTE PLACE="marg">[Corresponds to English line] 24741</NOTE></L>
</LG><LG TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>LE PELERIN.</HEAD>
<L>&para; Adonc vint grace dieu a moy,<NOTE PLACE="marg">[Corresponds to English line] 24743</NOTE></L>
<L>Et me dist doulcement, Or voy.<NOTE PLACE="marg">[Corresponds to English line] 24744</NOTE></L>
</LG><LG TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>GRACE DIEU.</HEAD>
<L>&para; Je voy bien, qu'&agrave; l'estroit passaige</L>
<L>Tu es de ton p&egrave;lerinaige.<NOTE PLACE="marg">[Corresponds to English line] 24746</NOTE></L>
<L>Voicy la Mort, qui de pres t'est,<NOTE PLACE="marg">[Corresponds to English line] 24747</NOTE></L>
<L>Qui, des choses terribles est<NOTE PLACE="marg">[Corresponds to English line] 24750</NOTE></L>
<L>La fin / et le terminement.<NOTE PLACE="marg">[Corresponds to English line] 24751</NOTE></L>
<L><MILESTONE UNIT="Petit folio" N="xcij">Ta vie, tantost faulcher entent,<NOTE PLACE="marg">[Corresponds to English line] 24753</NOTE></L>
<L>Et la mectre du tout &agrave; fin;</L>
<L>Et puis ton corps en vng cofin<NOTE PLACE="marg">[Corresponds to English line] 24756</NOTE></L>
<L>Elle mectra, pour le bailler<NOTE PLACE="marg">[Corresponds to English line] 24758</NOTE></L>
<L>Aux vers puans, pour le manger.<NOTE PLACE="marg">[Corresponds to English line] 24759</NOTE></L>
<L>Ceste chose est toute commune<NOTE PLACE="marg">[Corresponds to English line] 24761</NOTE></L>
<L>A tout chascun et a chascune:<NOTE PLACE="marg">[Corresponds to English line] 24762</NOTE></L>
<L>Homme, en ce monde, est expos&eacute;</L>
<L>A la mort, comme l'herbe au pr&eacute;<NOTE PLACE="marg">[Corresponds to English line] 24765</NOTE></L>
<L>Est a la faulx / aussi est feyn,<NOTE PLACE="marg">[Corresponds to English line] 24769</NOTE></L>
<L>Qui huy est verd / et sec demain;</L>
<L>Or as est&eacute; verd vng long temps,<NOTE PLACE="marg">[Corresponds to English line] 24772</NOTE></L>
<L>Et si as receu pluyes et vens;<NOTE PLACE="marg">[Corresponds to English line] 24766</NOTE></L>
<L>Mais fault maintenant te faulchier,<NOTE PLACE="marg">[Corresponds to English line] 24780</NOTE></L>
<L>Et en deux pieces despiecer.<NOTE PLACE="marg">[Corresponds to English line] 24782</NOTE></L>
<L>L'huys est estroit / l'ame / et la cher<NOTE PLACE="marg">[Corresponds to English line] 24783</NOTE></L>
<L>Ne pourroient ensemble passer.<NOTE PLACE="marg">[Corresponds to English line] 24786</NOTE></L>
<L>L'ame premiere passera,<NOTE PLACE="marg">[Corresponds to English line] 24787</NOTE></L>
<L>Et puis apres la chair yra.<NOTE PLACE="marg">[Corresponds to English line] 24788</NOTE></L>
<L>Mais si tost ne sera ce mie;</L>
<L>Auant sera la chair pourrie,<NOTE PLACE="marg">[Corresponds to English line] 24790</NOTE></L>
<L>Et autre fois regener&eacute;e<NOTE PLACE="marg">[Corresponds to English line] 24792</NOTE></L>
<L>En la grant commune assembl&eacute;e.</L>
<L>Doncques regarde se apoinctey<NOTE PLACE="marg">[Corresponds to English line] 24794</NOTE></L>
<L>Deuement tu es, et appareilley.</L>
<L>S'&agrave; toy ne tient, tantost verras<NOTE PLACE="marg">[Corresponds to English line] 24795</NOTE></L>
<L>La grant cit&eacute; ou tendu as.<NOTE PLACE="marg">[Corresponds to English line] 24796</NOTE></L>
<L>Tu es au guichet et &agrave; l'huys<NOTE PLACE="marg">[Corresponds to English line] 24800</NOTE></L>
<L>Que ou mirouer piec&agrave; tu vis.<NOTE PLACE="marg">[Corresponds to English line] 24802</NOTE></L>
<L>Se tu es despoill&eacute; et nuz,</L>
<L>Dedans tantost seras receuz.</L>
<L>Celle entr&eacute;e tu auoies moult chier,</L>
<L>Lors quant tu la vis au premier;</L>
<L>Et toutesfois, tant ie te dy,<NOTE PLACE="marg">[Corresponds to English line] 24807</NOTE></L>
<L>Qu'&agrave; mon p&egrave;re tu cryes mercy,<NOTE PLACE="marg">[Corresponds to English line] 24808</NOTE></L>
<L>En prometant &agrave; penitence,<NOTE PLACE="marg">[Corresponds to English line] 24809</NOTE></L>
<L>Que, se n'en as &agrave; souffisance<NOTE PLACE="marg">[Corresponds to English line] 24810</NOTE></L>
<L>Fait / volentiers tu la feras<NOTE PLACE="marg">[Corresponds to English line] 24813</NOTE></L>
<L>En purgatoire, ou tu iras.<NOTE PLACE="marg">[Corresponds to English line] 24816</NOTE></L>
</LG><LG TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>LE PELERIN.</HEAD>
<L>OR vous dy ie / que lors se i'eusse</L>
<L>Peu bien parler / que ie luy eusse<NOTE PLACE="marg">[Corresponds to English line] 24821</NOTE></L>
<L>Fait des demandes dont i'auoye<NOTE PLACE="marg">[Corresponds to English line] 24824</NOTE></L>
<L>Grant doubte / et que pas ne sauoie,</L>
<L><MILESTONE UNIT="Petit folio" N="xcij:2">Folie est d'actendre au besoing,<NOTE PLACE="marg">[Corresponds to English line] 24822</NOTE></L>
<L>Car souuent on cuide que loing</L>
<L>Soit la mort; qu'elle est aux postis,<NOTE PLACE="marg">[Corresponds to English line] 24826</NOTE></L>
<L>Bien ie le sceu / ie fuz soubzpris.</L>
<L>La mort laissa sa faulx courir,<NOTE PLACE="marg">[Corresponds to English line] 24827</NOTE></L>
<L>Et me fist du corps departir.<NOTE PLACE="marg">[Corresponds to English line] 24830</NOTE></L>
<L>Ce me sembla en ce moment,</L>
<L>Si que, de l'espouentement</L>
<L>Esueill&eacute; et desdormy fu,<NOTE PLACE="marg">[Corresponds to English line] 24832</NOTE></L>
<L>Et me trouuay si esperdu,<NOTE PLACE="marg">[not englisht]</NOTE></L>
<L>Qu'auiser ie ne me pouoie</L>
<L>Se ia mort ou en vie i'estoie,</L>
<L>Jusqu'&agrave; tant que i'ouy sonner</L>
<L>L'orologe de nuyt, pour leuer:</L>
<L>Et aussi lors chantoient les cocqs;</L>
<L>Pour quoy, leuer me cuiday lors;</L>
<L>Mais ne peu / car fuz retenu</L>
<L>De la grant pens&eacute;e ou ie fu</L>
<L>Pour le myen aduentureux songe,</L>
<L>Ou quel, se quelque vne mensonge</L>
<L>Estoit mesl&eacute;e ou contenue,</L>
<L>Ou qui fust de peu de value.</L>
<L>Nul esmerueiller ne s'en doit,</L>
<L>Car iamais froment on ne voit</L>
<L>Croistre / qu'entour paille n'y aye,</L>
<L>Jusques que dehors on l'en traye;</L>
<L>Par quoy, s'en mon songe y a grain,</L>
<L>Et auecques paille ou estrain</L>
<L>y ait / ce qu'est bon / soit gard&eacute;;</L>
<L>Ce que n'est bon, soit hors venn&eacute;.</L>
<L>Que ne dy pas tant seulement</L>
<L>Pour ce premier liure present,</L>
<L>Dont cy endroit ie feray fin,</L>
<L>Pour me reposer en chemin,</L>
<L>Mais aussi pour ce que s'ensuit,</L>
<L>Ou tout le grain en paille gist,</L>
<L>Que recommande aux bons venneurs,</L>
<L>Qui sceuent hors venner erreurs.</L>
</LG></Q></NOTE></L>
</LG>
<TRAILER>&para; La fin du premier p&egrave;lerinaige De l'homme durant qu'est En vie. Deo gratias.</TRAILER>
